抵抗军队的入侵；根本就无力抵抗思想的入侵。

（人们可以抵挡军队的入侵，但抵挡不住思想的入侵。）

-维克多·雨果

On résiste à l’invasion des armées; on ne résiste pas à l’invasion des idées.

(One withstands the invasion of armies; one does not withstand the invasion of ideas.)

—VICTOR HUGO

关于作者

About the Author

第1章

CHAPTER 1

创世纪

GENESIS

-

每走一步，我的新鞋都会陷进我的脚后跟。我手里抓着一个深蓝色的活页夹，里面装满了按彩色标签分类的文件。我对自己所处的位置感到敬畏，也对自己要去的地方感到不安，我集中精力注意着脚步声。一名助手提醒我们要快速行动，以免被人发现。我们走过穿制服的警卫，走进中庭，然后拐进走廊。助手推开一扇门，我们冲下楼梯，进入一条看起来和上一条一模一样的走廊——大理石地板、高高的天花板、木门，偶尔会挂上美国国旗。我们一共七个人，我们的脚步声在走廊里回荡。我们快到了；然后我被抓住了。一名国会议员发现了我，挥手向我打招呼。又回来了？几个记者从新闻发布会上走了出来。他们看到我电光石色的头发，知道我是谁。

With each step, my new shoes dig into my heels. I clutch a dark-blue binder, filled with documents organized by colored tabs. Awestruck by where I’ve found myself, and apprehensive of where I’m heading, I focus on the sounds of our footsteps. An aide reminds us to move quickly so we won’t be seen. We walk past uniformed guards, into an atrium, and turn down a corridor. The aide pushes open a door and we rush down some stairs and into a hallway that looks exactly like the last one—marble floors, high ceilings, wooden doors with the occasional American flag. There are seven of us, and our footsteps echo through the hall. We are close; then I’m caught. A congressman spots me and waves hello. Back again already? A handful of journalists wanders out of a press conference. They clock my electric pink hair and know who I am.

两名摄影师跑到我前面开始拍摄，一边走一边倒着拍摄。人群开始聚集，问题开始涌来——怀利先生，NBC 的问题！ CNN 的问题！你为什么在这里？——我的一位律师提醒我闭嘴。助手指着电梯，警告记者们保持距离，我们挤了进去。电梯门关上时，摄像机不停地拍摄。

Two cameramen run in front of me and start filming, walking backward as they do. A scrum forms, the questions start coming—Mr. Wylie, a question from NBC! A question from CNN! Why are you here?—and one of my lawyers reminds me to keep my mouth shut. The aide points me to an elevator, warning the journalists to keep their distance, and we pile in. The cameras keep snapping as the doors close.

我被挤在电梯后部，周围都是西装​​革履的人。电梯开始下降，坠入地下深处。下行过程中，每个人都保持安静。我脑子里浮现出我和律师所做的所有准备工作——美国哪些法律被违反了，谁违反了，作为非美国公民，我有哪些权利，哪些权利被禁止，如何冷静地应对指控，如果我随后被捕会怎样。我不知道会发生什么。没有人知道。

I’m jammed in the back of the elevator, surrounded by people in suits. We start to descend, dropping deep underground. Everyone stays quiet on the way down. My mind is swimming with all of the prep work I’ve done with my lawyers—what U.S. laws were broken and by whom, what rights I do and don’t have as a non-citizen visiting America, how to calmly respond to accusations, what happens if I am arrested afterward. I have no idea what to expect. No one does.

我们停了下来，电梯门滑开了。下面除了另一扇门什么也没有，门上有一个很大的红色标志，上面用白色字母写着“禁区” 。禁止公众或媒体进入。我们位于华盛顿特区美国国会大厦地下三层

We come to a stop and the elevator doors glide open. There’s nothing down here except another door, with a large red sign that reads RESTRICTED AREA in white lettering. NO PUBLIC OR MEDIA ACCESS. We’re three floors beneath the U.S. Capitol, in Washington, D.C.

门外是铺着毛绒栗色地毯的地板。穿制服的警卫没收了我们的手机和其他电子产品，把它们放在桌子后面一个有编号的架子上，每个人一个，并给我们每个人一张编号的票。他们告诉我们，过了这个点，我们只能带铅笔和纸。在出去的路上，他们警告我们，如果确定我们记下了任何敏感内容，我们的文件可能会被没收。

Beyond the door, the floors are covered in a plush maroon carpet. Uniformed guards confiscate our phones and other electronics, placing them on a numbered shelf behind the desk, one to a person, and giving us each a numbered ticket. They tell us we can have only pencils and paper beyond this point. And on the way out, they warn us, our papers could be confiscated if it’s determined that we’ve taken notes on anything of a sensitive nature.

两名警卫推开一扇巨大的钢门。其中一人示意我们进去，我们一个接一个地走进一条长长的走廊，走廊被荧光灯照得昏暗。墙壁上镶着深色木板，走廊两旁竖着一排排美国国旗。它闻起来像一栋老建筑，陈旧发霉，还带着一丝清洁剂的味道。警卫领着我们穿过走廊，左转，继续来到另一扇门前。门上方有一个木印，上面刻着一只巨大的鹰，爪中抓着箭，正盯着我们。我们到达了目的地：美国众议院情报常设委员会的敏感隔离信息设施 (SCIF)，也是国会机密简报会的举办地。

Two guards push open a massive steel door. One of them gestures us through, and one by one we step into a long hallway dimly illuminated by fluorescent lights. The walls are paneled in dark wood, and the corridor is lined with long rows of American flags on stands. It smells like an old building, stale and musty, with hints of cleaning fluid. The guards lead us down the hall, turning left and continuing to yet another door. Above, a wooden seal emblazoned with a giant eagle, arrows clutched in its talons, stares down at us. We have arrived at our destination: the Sensitive Compartmentalized Information Facility (SCIF) of the United States House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence—the same room where classified congressional briefings are held.

走进大楼，荧光灯的强光刺眼，我的眼睛需要时间适应。这个空间毫无特色，墙壁是空白的米色，会议桌周围摆放着椅子。它可能是华盛顿众多平淡无奇的联邦大楼中的任何一间房间，但 SCIF 的寂静令我震惊。它是隔音的，墙壁是多层的，因此无法被监视。据说这座建筑是防爆的。这是一个安全的空间，是美国机密的秘密之地。

Inside, hit by the glare of fluorescent lights, my eyes need time to adjust. The space is thoroughly nondescript, with blank beige walls and a conference table surrounded by chairs. It could be any room in any of the numerous bland federal buildings scattered across Washington, but I’m struck by the silence of the SCIF. It is soundproof, built with multilayer walls that make it impervious to surveillance. The architecture is said to be blast-proof. This is a secure space, a place for America’s secrets.

我们一入座，国会议员就开始陆续入座。助手们将列表文件放在每个委员会成员面前的桌子上——民主党资深成员、加州众议员亚当·希夫 (Adam Schiff) 就坐在我对面，他左边坐着国会女议员特丽·塞维尔 (Terri Sewell)，埃里克·斯瓦尔韦尔 (Eric Swalwell) 和华金·卡斯特罗 (Joaquin Castro) 则聚集在远处。我的两侧是我的律师和朋友沙米尔·桑尼 (Shahmir Sanni)，他也是举报人。我们给共和党人几分钟时间到场。但他们从来没到场。

Once we’ve taken our seats, the members of Congress begin filing in. Aides place tabulated binders on the table in front of each committee member—the Democrats’ ranking member, California congressman Adam Schiff, sits directly across from me, and to his left sits Congresswoman Terri Sewell, with Eric Swalwell and Joaquin Castro clustered together at the far end. I’m flanked by my lawyers and my friend Shahmir Sanni, a fellow whistleblower. We give the Republicans a few minutes to show up. They never do.

2018 年 6 月，我来到华盛顿，向美国国会作证，讨论剑桥分析公司，一家我曾经工作过的军事承包商和心理战公司，以及一个涉及 Facebook、俄罗斯、维基解密、特朗普竞选团队和英国脱欧公投的复杂网络。作为前研究主管，我带来了 Facebook 数据如何被该公司武器化的证据，以及他们建立的系统如何让数百万美国人容易受到敌对外国宣传行动的攻击。希夫主持了质询。作为前联邦检察官，他的调查思路敏锐而精确，他很快就抓住了问题的核心。

It’s June 2018, and I’m in Washington to testify to the U.S. Congress about Cambridge Analytica, a military contractor and psychological warfare firm where I used to work, and a complex web involving Facebook, Russia, WikiLeaks, the Trump campaign, and the Brexit referendum. As the former director of research, I’ve brought with me evidence of how Facebook’s data was weaponized by the firm, and how the systems they built left millions of Americans vulnerable to the propaganda operations of hostile foreign states. Schiff leads the questioning. A former federal prosecutor, he is sharp and precise with his lines of inquiry, and he wastes no time getting to the heart of the matter.

你和史蒂夫·班农合作过吗？是的。

Did you work with Steve Bannon? Yes.

剑桥分析公司是否与潜在的俄罗斯特工有过联系？是的。

Did Cambridge Analytica have any contacts with potential Russian agents? Yes.

您是否相信这些数据被用来影响美国选民选举美国总统？是的。

Do you believe that this data was used to sway the American electorate to elect the president of the United States? Yes.

一个小时过去了，两个小时，三个小时过去了。我自愿选择来到这里，回答这些问题：一个自由派、同性恋的 24 岁加拿大人如何成为英国军事承包商的一员，为美国另类右翼开发心理战工具。大学毕业后，我在伦敦一家名为 SCL Group 的公司找到了一份工作，该公司为英国国防部和北约军队提供信息作战方面的专业知识。在西方军队努力应对网络极端主义之后，该公司希望我帮助组建一个数据科学家团队，以创建新的工具来识别和打击网络极端主义。这既令人着迷，又充满挑战，又令人兴奋。我们即将为英国、美国及其盟友的网络防御开辟新天地，并通过数据、算法和有针对性的网络叙事来对抗激进极端主义的叛乱。但通过 2014 年发生的一系列事件，一位亿万富翁收购了我们的项目，以便在美国建立自己的激进叛乱组织。剑桥分析公司 (Cambridge Analytica)，一家很少有人听说过的公司，一家将心理分析研究武器化的公司，成功地颠覆了世界。

An hour goes by, then two, then three. I chose to come here of my own accord and to answer these questions about how a liberal, gay twenty-four-year-old Canadian found himself part of a British military contractor developing psychological warfare tools for the American alt-right. Fresh out of university, I had taken a job at a London firm called SCL Group, which was supplying the U.K. Ministry of Defence and NATO armies with expertise in information operations. After Western militaries were grappling with how to tackle radicalization online, the firm wanted me to help build a team of data scientists to create new tools to identify and combat extremism online. It was fascinating, challenging, and exciting all at once. We were about to break new ground for the cyber defenses of Britain, America, and their allies and confront bubbling insurgencies of radical extremism with data, algorithms, and targeted narratives online. But through a chain of events that unfolded in 2014, a billionaire acquired our project in order to build his own radicalized insurgency in America. Cambridge Analytica, a company few had ever heard of, a company that weaponized research in psychological profiling, managed to turn the world upside down.

在军队中，当武器落入坏人之手时，他们称之为反噬。看起来，这种反噬在白宫本身就已引爆。我无法继续从事如此腐蚀社会的事业，所以我揭发了此事，向当局报告了整个事件，并与记者合作，向公众警告正在发生的事情。坐在这个小组面前，前一天刚坐过一次跨大西洋航班，时差还没好，随着问题变得越来越尖锐，我仍然不禁感到身临其境。但有几次，我试图解释公司运作的复杂性，却让每个人都一脸困惑，所以我只是拿出一个活页夹，把它塞给国会议员。我想，管他呢。我已经走到这一步了，所以我还不如把我身上的所有东西都给他们。没有休息，身后的门一直关着。我被锁在地下深处一个闷热、没有窗户的房间里，除了直视国会议员的眼睛外，无处可看，他们都在试图弄清楚他们的国家到底发生了什么。

In the military, when weapons fall into the wrong hands, they call it blowback. It looked as if this blowback had detonated in the White House itself. I could not continue working on something so corrosive to our societies, so I blew the whistle, reported the whole thing to the authorities, and worked with journalists to warn the public about what was going on. Sitting before this panel, jet-lagged from a transatlantic flight the day before, I still cannot help but feel on the spot as the questions grow more pointed. But several times, my attempts to explain the intricacies of the company’s operations leave everyone with puzzled faces, so I simply pull out a binder and slide it to the congressmen. What the hell, I think. I’ve come this far, so I might as well give them everything I have with me. There is no break, and the door behind me remains closed the entire time. I’m locked in a stuffy, windowless room deep underground, with nowhere to look except straight into the eyes of these members of Congress as they all try to figure out what the hell just happened to their country.

—

三个月前，也就是2018年3月17日，《 卫报》、 《 纽约时报》和英国第四频道新闻台同时公布了一项为期一年的联合调查结果。此次调查的起因是我决定揭露剑桥分析公司和脸书内部的真相。我的告密行为引发了历史上最大规模的数据犯罪调查。在英国，国家犯罪局（NCA）、英国国内情报机构军情五处（MI5）、信息专员办公室、选举委员会和伦敦警察厅都参与其中。在美国，联邦调查局、司法部、证券交易委员会（SEC）和联邦贸易委员会（FTC）也参与其中。

THREE MONTHS BEFORE THIS, on March 17, 2018, The Guardian, The New York Times, and Britain’s Channel 4 News had simultaneously published the results of a yearlong joint investigation, spurred by my decision to reveal the truth about what was happening inside Cambridge Analytica and Facebook. My coming out as a whistleblower prompted the largest data crime investigation in history. In Britain, the National Crime Agency (NCA), MI5 (the U.K.’s domestic intelligence agency), the Information Commissioner’s Office, the Electoral Commission, and London’s Metropolitan Police Service all got involved. In the United States, the FBI, the Department of Justice, the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC), and the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) jumped in.

在第一则报道发表之前的几周，特别检察官罗伯特·穆勒的调查一直在升温。2 月，穆勒起诉了 13 名俄罗斯公民和 3 家俄罗斯公司，指控他们犯有两项共谋罪。一周后，前特朗普竞选经理保罗·马纳福特和他的副手里克·盖茨也被起诉。3 月 16 日，司法部长杰夫·塞申斯解雇了联邦调查局副局长安德鲁·麦凯布，而此时距离他即将退休领取养老金仅剩 24 小时多一点。人们迫切想知道特朗普竞选团队和俄罗斯之间发生了什么，但没有人能够把这些联系在一起。我提供了将剑桥分析公司与唐纳德·特朗普、Facebook、俄罗斯情报机构、国际黑客和英国脱欧联系起来的证据。这些证据揭示了一个鲜为人知的外国承包商如何从事非法活动，以及特朗普和英国脱欧竞选团队如何利用同一个外国承包商。我带来的电子邮件链、内部备忘录、发票、银行转账记录和项目文件表明，特朗普和英国脱欧部署了相同的策略，采用相同的技术，由相同的许多人指挥——所有这些都是在俄罗斯秘密参与的阴影下进行的。

In the weeks before that first story, the investigation by special counsel Robert Mueller had been heating up. In February, Mueller indicted thirteen Russian citizens and three Russian companies, charging them with two separate counts of conspiracy. A week later came indictments of former Trump campaign manager Paul Manafort and his deputy, Rick Gates. On March 16, Attorney General Jeff Sessions fired FBI deputy director Andrew McCabe, just a little more than twenty-four hours before he was to retire with a pension. People were desperate for information about what had happened between the Trump campaign and Russia, but no one had been able to connect the dots. I provided evidence tying Cambridge Analytica to Donald Trump, Facebook, Russian intelligence, international hackers, and Brexit. This evidence revealed how both an obscure foreign contractor engaged in illegal activity and the same foreign contractor had been used by the winning Trump and Brexit campaigns. The email chains, internal memos, invoices, bank transfer records, and project documentation I brought demonstrated that Trump and Brexit had deployed the same strategies, powered by the same technologies, directed by many of the same people—all under the specter of covert Russian involvement.

报道发布两天后，英国议会主厅被提出一个紧急问题。在罕见的团结时刻，政府部长和议会高级反对党成员齐声谴责 Facebook 的疏忽，未能阻止其平台成为选举的敌对宣传网络，以及对西方民主国家的影响。下一波报道聚焦英国脱欧，公投的公正性受到质疑。我向执法部门提供的一系列文件显示，脱欧派曾利用剑桥分析公司的秘密子公司，花费黑钱在 Facebook 和谷歌广告网络上传播虚假信息。英国选举委员会认定此举违法，该计划最终成为英国历史上规模最大、后果最严重的竞选财务法违规行为之一。随着脱欧派作弊证据的出现，英国首相办公室唐宁街 10 号陷入了沟通危机。 NCA 和 MI5 后来获得了俄罗斯大使馆与英国脱欧公投期间支持脱欧运动的最大资助者有直接关系的证据。一周后，Facebook 股价暴跌 18%，估值损失 800 亿美元。动荡持续，最终导致股价跌幅创下美国公司历史上单日跌幅最大的纪录。

Two days after the story’s release, an urgent question was brought to the main chamber of the British Parliament. In a rare moment of solidarity, government ministers and senior opposition members of Parliament sang as a unified chorus about Facebook’s negligence in failing to prevent its platform from becoming a hostile propaganda network for elections and the implications for Western democracies. The next wave of stories focused on Brexit, with the integrity of the referendum vote called into question. A collection of documents I provided to law enforcement revealed that the Vote Leave campaign had used secret Cambridge Analytica subsidiaries to spend dark money to propagate disinformation on Facebook and Google ad networks. This was determined to be illegal by the U.K.’s Electoral Commission, with the scheme ending up as one of the largest and most consequential breaches of campaign finance law in British history. The office of the U.K.’s prime minister, 10 Downing Street, descended into communication crisis as the evidence of Vote Leave’s cheating emerged. The NCA and MI5 were later handed evidence of the Russian embassy’s direct relationship with the largest funders of pro-Brexit campaigns during the referendum. A week later, Facebook’s stock plummeted 18 percent, amounting to an $80 billion loss in valuation. The turbulence would continue, culminating in what still stands as the largest single-day loss in share value in U.S. corporate history.

2018 年 3 月 27 日，我被传唤到议会参加一场现场公开听证会——在接下来的几个月里，我已经习惯了这样的听证会。我们讨论了从剑桥分析公司对黑客和贿赂的依赖到 Facebook 的数据泄露再到俄罗斯情报行动等方方面面的问题。听证会结束后，联邦调查局、司法部、证券交易委员会和联邦贸易委员会展开了调查。美国众议院情报委员会、众议院司法委员会、参议院情报委员会和参议院司法委员会都想和我谈谈。几周之内，欧盟和 20 多个国家开始对 Facebook、社交媒体和虚假信息展开调查。

On March 27, 2018, I was called before Parliament for a live public hearing—something I’d get quite used to over the next several months. We covered everything from Cambridge Analytica’s reliance on hackers and bribes to Facebook’s data breach to Russian intelligence operations. After the hearing, the FBI, DOJ, SEC, and FTC launched investigations. The U.S. House Intelligence Committee, House Judiciary Committee, Senate Intelligence Committee, and Senate Judiciary Committee all wanted to talk to me. Within weeks, the European Union and more than twenty countries had opened up inquiries into Facebook, social media, and disinformation.

我向全世界讲述了我的故事，现在每个屏幕都像一面镜子，将我的故事反射回来。连续两个星期，我的生活一片混乱。每天早上 6 点，我都会出现在英国早间节目和欧洲电视网，然后继续接受美国电视网的采访，直到午夜。记者们到处跟着我。我开始收到威胁。由于担心我的安全，我不得不雇佣保镖在公开活动中保护我。我的父母都是医生，由于记者们疯狂提问和吓唬病人，他们不得不暂时关闭他们的诊所。在接下来的几个月里，我的生活变得几乎无法控制，但我知道我必须不断敲响警钟。

I told my story to the world, and now every screen was a mirror reflecting it back at me. For two weeks straight, my life was chaos. Days would start with appearances on British breakfast shows and European networks at 6 A.M. London time, continuing with interviews on U.S. networks until midnight. Reporters followed me everywhere. I started to receive threats. Fearing for my safety, I had to hire bodyguards to protect me at public events. My parents, both physicians, had to temporarily close their medical clinic due to a frenzy of journalists asking questions and scaring patients. In the months that followed, my life became almost unmanageable, but I knew I had to keep sounding the alarm.

剑桥分析公司的故事表明，我们的身份和行为在高风险数据交易中已成为商品。控制信息流的公司是世界上最强大的公司之一；他们秘密设计的算法正在以过去无法想象的方式影响美国和其他地方的思想。无论你最关心什么问题——枪支暴力、移民、言论自由、宗教自由——你都无法逃离硅谷，这是美国认知危机的新中心。我在剑桥分析公司的工作揭露了技术创新的阴暗面。我们创新了。另类右翼创新了。俄罗斯创新了。而 Facebook，也就是你分享派对邀请和婴儿照片的网站，让这些创新得以释放。

The story of Cambridge Analytica shows how our identities and behavior have become commodities in the high-stakes data trade. The companies that control the flow of information are among the most powerful in the world; the algorithms they’ve designed in secret are shaping minds in the United States and elsewhere in ways previously unimaginable. No matter what issue you care about most—gun violence, immigration, free speech, religious freedom—you can’t escape Silicon Valley, the new epicenter of America’s crisis of perception. My work with Cambridge Analytica exposed the dark side of tech innovation. We innovated. The alt-right innovated. Russia innovated. And Facebook, that same site where you share your party invites and baby pictures, allowed those innovations to be unleashed.

—

我怀疑，如果我生来就是另一个人，我肯定不会对科技感兴趣，也不会进入剑桥分析公司。我选择电脑，因为像我这样的孩子没有太多其他选择。我在不列颠哥伦比亚省西海岸的温哥华岛长大，周围是海洋、森林和农田。我的父母都是医生，我是他们的长子，接下来是我的两个妹妹，杰米和劳伦。当我十一岁的时候，我开始注意到我的腿变得越来越僵硬。我不能像其他孩子那样跑得快，而且我开始走路很奇怪，这当然让我成为欺凌的对象。我被诊断出患有两种相对罕见的疾病，症状包括严重的神经性疼痛、肌肉无力以及视力和听力障碍。十二岁时，我坐在轮椅上——正好赶上青春期的开始——我在剩下的学生时代都是坐在那把椅子上度过的。

I SUSPECT I WOULDN’T have been interested in technology, or ended up at Cambridge Analytica, had I been born into a different body. I defaulted to computers because there was not much else available to a kid like me. I grew up on Vancouver Island, on the west coast of British Columbia, surrounded by oceans, forests, and farmland. My parents were both physicians, and I was their eldest, followed by my two baby sisters, Jaimie and Lauren. When I was eleven, I started to notice that my legs were becoming stiffer and stiffer. I couldn’t run as fast as the other kids, and I started to walk funny, which of course made me a target for bullies. I was diagnosed with two relatively rare conditions, whose symptoms included severe neuropathic pain, muscle weakness, and vision and hearing impairment. By twelve I was in a wheelchair—just in time for the onset of adolescence—and I used that chair for the rest of my school days.

当你坐在轮椅上时，人们对待你的方式会有所不同。有时你会觉得自己更像是一个物体而不是一个人——你的出行方式是人们理解和定义你的方式。你必须以不同的方式接近建筑物和结构——我可以从哪些入口进入？我如何避免走楼梯而到达目的地？你要学会寻找别人从未注意到的东西。

When you are in a wheelchair, people treat you differently. You can sometimes feel more like an object than a person—your means of getting around is how people come to understand and define you. You have to approach buildings and structures differently—What entrances can I go in? How do I reach my destination while avoiding stairs? You learn to look for things that other people never notice.

我发现计算机实验室后不久，它就成了学校里唯一一个让我感觉不被疏远的教室。在外面，要么是欺凌者，要么是居高临下的工作人员。即使老师们引导其他孩子和我互动，他们也总是出于义务，这比被忽视更令人恼火。相反，我会去计算机实验室。

Not long after I discovered the computer lab, it became the one room at school where I didn’t feel alienated. Outside, there were either bullies or patronizing staff. Even when teachers shepherded other kids to interact with me, it was always done out of obligation, which became even more annoying than being ignored. Instead I’d go to the computer lab.

我大约在十三岁开始制作网页。我的第一个网站是一个 Flash 动画，内容是粉红豹被笨手笨脚的克鲁索探长追赶。不久之后，我看到了一个关于用 JavaScript 编程井字游戏的视频，觉得这是有史以来最酷的东西。这个游戏看起来很简单，直到你开始分解所有的逻辑。你不能让计算机随机选择一个方框，因为那会很无聊。你必须用规则来指导计算机，比如把一个X放在另一个X相邻的方框里——也就是说，除非该行或列中已经有一个O。那么对角线X呢——我们如何解释它们？

I started making webpages around age thirteen. My first website was a Flash animation of the Pink Panther being chased by a bumbling Inspector Clouseau. Soon after, I saw a video about programming tic-tac-toe in JavaScript and thought it was the coolest thing ever. The game seems simple enough until you start having to break down all of the logic. You can’t just let the computer randomly select a box, as that would be boring. You have to guide the computer with rules, like putting an X in a box adjacent to another X—that is, unless there is an O already in that row or column. And what about diagonal Xs—how do we explain them?

最终，我拼凑出了数百行意大利面条式的代码。我仍然记得自己做出一个动作，然后看着我的小作品回放的感觉。我觉得自己就像一个魔术师。我练习咒语越多，我的魔法就越强大。

Eventually I strung together hundreds of lines of spaghetti code. I still remember the feeling of making a move and then watching my little creation play back. I felt like a conjurer. And the more I practiced my incantations, the more powerful my magic could become.

除了计算机实验室，学校教育我什么都不能做、什么都不被允许做，我不能成为什么样的人。我的父母鼓励我继续努力寻找一个适合我的地方，所以当我 15 岁的时候，2005 年夏天，我寄宿在 Lester B. Pearson 联合世界学院，这是维多利亚的一所国际学校，以诺贝尔和平奖获得者加拿大总理的名字命名，他在 20 世纪 50 年代苏伊士危机期间构想了世界上第一支联合国维和部队。与来自世界各地的学生共度如此多的时间让我着迷，我第一次真正对课程和同学们说的话感兴趣。我和卢旺达种族大屠杀的一名幸存者成为了朋友，一天晚上，当我们在宿舍里熬夜时，他告诉我他的家人是如何被谋杀的，以及他小时候独自走到乌干达难民营的感受。

Outside of computer lab, school remained an education in what I wasn’t able or allowed to do, and who I could not be. My parents encouraged me to keep trying to find a place where I could fit in, so when I was fifteen, I spent the summer of 2005 boarding at Lester B. Pearson United World College, an international school in Victoria named after the Nobel Peace Prize–winning Canadian prime minister who conceptualized the world’s first U.N. peacekeeping force during the 1950s Suez Crisis. Spending so much time with students from every part of the world was enthralling, and for the first time, I was actually interested in the lessons and what my peers had to say. I became friends with a survivor of the Rwandan genocide, who told me one evening when we were up late in our residence hall about how his family was murdered and what it was like walking alone all the way to a refugee camp in Uganda when he was just a child.

但直到有一天晚上，在餐厅里，巴勒斯坦和阿拉伯学生与以色列学生坐在一起，激烈地争论着祖国的未来，我才真正开始意识到周围的世界。我意识到我对正在发生的事情知之甚少——但我想了解——所以我很快就对政治产生了兴趣。第二学年，我开始逃课，参加当地议会成员的市政厅活动。在学校，我很少和任何人说话，但在这些活动中，我可以自由地表达自己。在教室里，你坐在后面，老师告诉你如何思考和思考什么。有课程，有思维处方。但在市政厅，我发现情况正好相反。当然，政客站在前面，但观众——我们——可以告诉他或她我们的想法。这种反转对我来说非常有吸引力，每当国会议员宣布活动时，我都会出现，问问题，甚至告诉他们我的想法。

But it was after sitting at a dinner one evening in the dining hall where Palestinian and Arab students sat directly across from Israeli students, forcefully debating the future of their homelands, that I really started to wake up to the world around me. I realized how much I didn’t know about what was happening—but I wanted to—and so I very quickly developed an interest in politics. The following school year, I began skipping class to attend town hall events with local members of Parliament. At school, I rarely talked to anyone, but at these events I felt free to express myself. In a classroom, you sit in the back while the teacher tells you how and what to think. There is a curriculum, a prescription of thought. But in a town hall, I discovered the opposite. Sure, the politician stands up front, but it is the people in the audience—us—who get to tell him or her what we think. That inversion was so incredibly appealing to me, and whenever members of Parliament would announce an event, I’d show up, ask questions, and even tell them what I thought.

找到自己的声音让我感到自由。像任何青少年一样，我在探索自己是谁，但对于一个坐在轮椅上的同性恋者来说，这是一个更大的挑战。当我开始参加这些公共论坛时，我开始意识到我所经历的很多事情不仅仅是个人问题——它们也是政治问题。我的挑战是政治的。我的生活是政治的。我的存在本身就是政治的。所以我决定从政。一位议员的顾问、前软件工程师杰夫·西尔维斯特 (Jeff Silvester) 注意到了这个直言不讳、总是出现的孩子。他提出帮我在加拿大自由党 (LPC) 找一个职位，当时该党正在寻找技术人员。很快我们就同意了：在那个夏天结束时，我将开始我的第一份真正的工作，在渥太华议会担任政治助理。

It was liberating to find my voice. Like any teenager, I was exploring who I was, but for someone gay and in a wheelchair, this was an even bigger challenge. When I started attending these public forums, I began to realize that many of the things I was living through were not simply personal issues—they were also political issues. My challenges were political. My life was political. My mere existence was political. And so I decided to become political. An adviser to one of the MPs, a former software engineer named Jeff Silvester, took notice of this outspoken kid who always showed up. He offered to help me find a role in the Liberal Party of Canada (LPC), which was looking for tech help. Soon it was agreed: At the end of that summer I would start my first real job, as a political assistant at Parliament in Ottawa.

2007 年夏天，我在蒙特利尔度过，经常在法裔加拿大技术无政府主义者经常光顾的黑客空间里闲逛。他们往往聚集在改建的工业建筑里，这些建筑有水泥地板和胶合板墙，房间里装饰着 Apple II 和 Commodore 64 等复古科技。那时，经过治疗，我不用轮椅就能四处走动了。（我的病情一直在好转，但我作为告密者的经历考验了我的身体极限。就在剑桥分析公司的第一篇报道发表之前，我癫痫发作，昏倒在伦敦南部的人行道上，不省人事，然后在大学学院医院醒来，护士在我手臂上插入静脉注射针头时，我感到一阵剧痛。）大多数黑客根本不在乎你长什么样，也不在乎你走路的姿势是否怪异。他们和你一样热爱这门手艺，想帮助你做得更好。

I spent the summer of 2007 in Montréal, hanging out in hacker spaces frequented by French Canadian techno-anarchists. They tended to gather in converted industrial buildings with concrete floors and plywood walls, in rooms decorated with retro tech like Apple IIs and Commodore 64s. By then, with treatment, I could shuffle around without a wheelchair. (I have continued to improve, but my physical limits were tested by my experience as a whistleblower. Just before the first Cambridge Analytica story was published, I had a seizure and collapsed, unconscious, on a South London sidewalk before waking up at University College Hospital to the sharp pain of a nurse inserting an IV needle into my arm.) Most hackers couldn’t care less what you look like or if you walk funny. They share your love of the craft and want to help you get better at it.

我短暂地接触过黑客社区，这给我留下了深刻的印象。你会发现没有哪个系统是绝对的。没有什么是坚不可摧的，障碍是一种挑战。黑客哲学告诉我，如果你改变对任何系统的看法——一台计算机、一个网络，甚至一个社会——你都可能发现缺陷和漏洞。作为一个坐在轮椅上的同性恋孩子，我很早就了解了权力体系。但作为一名黑客，我了解到每个系统都有等待被利用的弱点。

My brief exposure to hacking communities left a permanent impression. You learn that no system is absolute. Nothing is impenetrable, and barriers are a dare. The hacker philosophy taught me that if you shift your perspective on any system—a computer, a network, even society—you may discover flaws and vulnerabilities. As a gay kid in a wheelchair, I came to understand systems of power early on in life. But as a hacker, I learned that every system has weaknesses waiting to be exploited.

—

在我刚开始在加拿大议会任职后不久，自由党就对南方发生的事情产生了兴趣。当时，Facebook 刚刚成为主流，Twitter 也刚刚开始发展；没有人知道如何使用社交媒体进行竞选，因为社交媒体还处于起步阶段。但美国总统政治中一颗冉冉升起的新星即将加速发展。

SHORTLY AFTER I STARTED my job at the Canadian Parliament, the Liberal Party took an interest in what was happening down south. At that time, Facebook was just becoming mainstream, and Twitter had just started gaining momentum; no one had any concept of how to use social media to campaign, because social media was in its infancy. But a rising star in U.S. presidential politics was about to hit the accelerator.

当其他候选人还在无所事事地摸索互联网时，巴拉克·奥巴马的团队建立了 My.BarackObama.com，并发起了一场草根革命。当其他网站（如希拉里·克林顿的网站）专注于发布标准的政治广告时，奥巴马的网站则专注于为草根组织提供组织和执行拉票活动的平台。他的网站让这位伊利诺伊州参议员更加兴奋，他比他的对手年轻得多，也更精通技术。奥巴马给人的感觉就像一个领导者。在我成长的岁月里，我被告知自己的极限，但他用“是的，我们可以！”这个简单的信息灌输给我的坚定乐观精神打动了我。奥巴马和他的团队正在改变政治，所以当我十八岁的时候，我和自由党派往美国的几个人一起观察他的竞选活动的不同方面，并找出可以带回加拿大进行进步竞选的新策略。

While other candidates were twiddling their thumbs trying to figure out the Internet, Barack Obama’s team set up My.BarackObama.com and started a grassroots revolution. While other sites (like Hillary Clinton’s) focused on putting up standard political advertisements, Obama’s website centered on providing a platform for grassroots organizations to organize and execute get-out-the-vote campaigns. His website ratcheted up excitement around the Illinois senator, who was much younger and more tech savvy than his opponents. Obama felt like what a leader is supposed to be. And after spending my formative years being told about my limits, the defiant optimism he instilled in that simple message of Yes, we can! spoke to me. Obama and his team were transforming politics, so when I was eighteen, I was among several people sent to the United States by the Liberal Party to observe different facets of his campaign and identify new tactics that could be transported back for progressive campaigns in Canada.

一开始，我巡视了几个初选早期的州，从新罕布什尔州开始，在那里我花时间与选民交谈，近距离了解美国文化的真实面貌。这既有趣又令人大开眼界；作为来自加拿大的我，我们的感受是如此不同，这让我感到震惊。第一次有美国人告诉我，他坚决反对“社会化医疗”，而我在国内几乎每个月都会享受这种公共医疗，我很震惊居然有人会这样想。但到了第 100 次，我却不那么惊讶了。

At first, I toured a couple of early primary states, starting with New Hampshire, where I spent time talking to voters and seeing up close what American culture was really like. This was both fun and eye-opening; coming from Canada, I was struck by how different our sensibilities were. The first time an American told me he was dead set against “socialized medicine,” the same kind of public healthcare I accessed almost every month back home, I was shocked that someone could even think this way. The hundredth time, not so much.

我喜欢四处游荡并与人交谈，所以当需要将注意力转移到数据组时，我并不十分热衷于此。但后来有人向我介绍了奥巴马的国家目标定位总监肯·斯特拉斯玛，他很快就改变了我的想法。

I liked roaming around and talking with people, so when it was time to switch focus to the data group, I wasn’t terribly excited to do it. But then I was introduced to Obama’s national director of targeting, Ken Strasma, who quickly changed my mind.

奥巴马竞选活动的亮点在于其品牌宣传和对 YouTube 等新媒体的使用。这是很酷的东西，是以前没有人使用过的视觉策略，因为 YouTube 当时还很新。这正是我想看到的，直到肯打断了我。他告诉我，忘掉视频吧。我需要更深入地了解竞选技术策略的核心。他说，我们所做的一切都是基于确切了解我们需要与谁交谈以及谈论哪些问题。

The sexy part of the Obama campaign was its branding and use of new media like YouTube. This was the cool stuff, the visual strategy nobody had used before because YouTube was still so new. That was what I wanted to see, until Ken stopped me short. Forget the videos, he told me. I needed to go deeper, into the heart of the campaign’s tech strategy. Everything we do, he said, is predicated on understanding exactly who we need to talk to, and on which issues.

换句话说，奥巴马竞选活动的支柱是数据。斯特拉斯玛团队最重要的工作是他们用来分析和理解数据的模型，这使他们能够将数据转化为应用——通过人工智能确定现实世界的沟通策略。等等——竞选活动的人工智能？这看起来非常具有未来感，就好像他们正在建造一个机器人，可以吞噬大量有关选民的信息，然后吐出目标标准。这些信息随后一路传到竞选活动的高层，在那里被用来确定奥巴马的关键信息和品牌。

In other words, the backbone of the Obama campaign was data. And the most important work Strasma’s team produced was the modeling they used to analyze and understand that data, which allowed them to translate it into an applied fit—to determine a real-world communications strategy through…artificial intelligence. Wait—AI for campaigns? It seemed vividly futuristic, as if they were building a robot that could devour reams of information about voters, then spit out targeting criteria. That information then traveled all the way up to the senior levels of the campaign, where it was used to determine key messages and branding for Obama.

处理所有这些数据的基础设施来自当时名为选民激活网络公司 (VAN) 的公司，该公司由来自波士顿地区的一对同性恋夫妇马克·沙利文和吉姆·圣乔治经营。到 2008 年竞选结束时，多亏了 VAN，民主党全国委员会掌握的选民数据比 2004 年竞选后多了十倍。如此大量的数据以及组织和操纵这些数据的工具使民主党在推动选民投票方面具有明显优势。

The infrastructure for processing all this data came from a company then called the Voter Activation Network, Inc. (VAN), which was run by a fabulous gay couple from the Boston area, Mark Sullivan and Jim St. George. By the end of the 2008 campaign, thanks to VAN, the Democratic National Committee would have ten times more data on voters than it had after the 2004 campaign. This volume of data, and the tools to organize and manipulate it, gave Democrats a clear advantage in driving voters to the polls.

我对奥巴马机器了解得越多，就越着迷。后来，我向马克和吉姆问了所有我想问的问题，因为他们似乎觉得这个年轻的加拿大人来到美国学习数据和政治很有趣。在看到肯、马克和吉姆在做什么之前，我还没有想过用数学和人工智能来推动政治竞选。事实上，当我第一次看到人们在奥巴马总部的电脑前排队时，我想，信息和情感，而不是电脑和数字，才是赢得竞选的关键。但我了解到，正是这些数字——以及他们创建的预测算法——让奥巴马与之前任何一位总统竞选者脱颖而出。

The more I learned about the Obama machine, the more fascinated I was. And I later got to ask all the questions I wanted of Mark and Jim, as they seemed to find it amusing that this young Canadian had come to America to learn about data and politics. Before I saw what Ken, Mark, and Jim were doing, I hadn’t thought about using math and AI to power a political campaign. In fact, when I first saw people lined up at computers at the Obama headquarters, I thought, Messages and emotions, not computers and numbers, are what create a winning campaign. But I learned that it was those numbers—and the predictive algorithms they created—that separated Obama from anyone who had ever run for president before.

当我意识到奥巴马竞选团队使用算法传递信息有多么有效时，我就开始研究如何自己创建算法。我自学了如何使用 MATLAB 和 SPSS 等基本软件包，这些软件包让我可以随意处理数据。我没有依赖教科书，而是从鸢尾花数据集（学习统计学的经典数据集）开始，并通过反复试验来学习。能够操纵数据（包括使用鸢尾花的不同特征，如花瓣长度和颜色）来预测花的种类）绝对令人着迷。

As soon as I realized how effectively the Obama campaign was using algorithms to deliver its messages, I started studying how to create them on my own. I taught myself how to use basic software packages like MATLAB and SPSS, which let me mess around with data. Instead of relying on a textbook, I started by playing with the Iris data set—the classic data set for learning statistics—and learned by trial and error. Being able to manipulate the data, which involved using the different features of irises, like petal length and color, to predict species of flowers, was absolutely absorbing.

了解了基本知识后，我便从花瓣转向人。VAN 中充满了关于年龄、性别、收入、种族、房屋所有权的信息，甚至还有杂志订阅和航空里程。输入正确的数据后，你就可以开始预测人们会投票给民主党还是共和党。你可以识别和分离出对他们来说可能最重要的问题。你可以开始编写更有可能影响他们意见的信息。

Once I understood the basics, I switched from petals to people. VAN was filled with information on age, gender, income, race, homeownership—even magazine subscriptions and airline miles. With the right data inputs, you could start to predict whether people would vote for Democrats or Republicans. You could identify and isolate the issues that were likely to be most important to them. You could begin to craft messages that would have a greater chance of swaying their opinions.

对我来说，这是理解选举的全新方式。数据是一股向善的力量，推动了这场变革运动。它被用来吸引首次投票者，接触那些感到被忽视的人。我越深入研究，就越觉得数据将成为政治的救星。我迫不及待地想回到加拿大，与自由党分享我从美国下一任总统那里学到的东西。

For me, this was a wholly new way of understanding elections. Data was a force for good, powering this campaign of change. It was being used to produce first-time voters, to reach people who felt left out. The deeper I got into it, the more I thought that data would be the savior of politics. I couldn’t wait to get back to Canada and share with the Liberal Party what I’d learned from the next president of the United States.

11 月，奥巴马击败约翰·麦凯恩，取得了决定性胜利。两个月后，在竞选团队的朋友邀请我参加就职典礼后，我飞往华盛顿与民主党获胜者一起聚会。（首先在门口发生了轻微的骚动，当时工作人员惊慌失措，不让我这个 21 岁以下的人参加开放式酒吧活动。）我度过了一个难忘的夜晚，与詹妮弗·洛佩兹和马克·安东尼聊天，看着巴拉克和米歇尔·奥巴马作为第一夫妇享受他们的第一支舞。一个新时代已经到来，现在有机会庆祝当合适的人了解如何使用数据赢得现代选举时会发生什么。

In November, Obama achieved a decisive victory over John McCain. Two months later, after friends in the campaign extended an invitation to the inauguration, I flew to Washington to party with the Democratic victors. (First came a slight kerfuffle at the door, when staff freaked out about letting the under-twenty-one me into the open-bar event.) I had an incredible evening, chatting with Jennifer Lopez and Marc Anthony, watching Barack and Michelle Obama enjoy their first dance as the First Couple. A new era had dawned, and now came a chance to celebrate what could happen when the right people understood how to use data to win modern elections.

—

但是，通过直接向特定选民传达特定信息，奥巴马竞选团队的微目标定位开启了美国公共话语私有化的征程。尽管直邮早已成为美国竞选活动的一部分，但数据驱动的微目标定位让竞选活动能够将无数的细粒度叙述与选民群体相匹配——你的邻居可能收到与你完全不同的信息，而你们双方都不知道。当竞选活动私下进行时，可以避免辩论和宣传的审查。城镇广场是美国民主的基础，正逐渐被在线广告网络取代。而且，没有任何审查，竞选信息甚至不再需要看起来像竞选信息。社交媒体创造了一个新的环境，正如奥巴马竞选活动试行的那样，竞选活动现在可以看起来像是你的朋友给你发信息，而你却不知道该联系的来源或意图。竞选活动可能看起来像新闻网站、大学或公共机构。随着社交媒体的崛起，我们不得不相信政治竞选活动是诚实的，因为如果有人撒谎，我们可能永远不会注意到。私人广告网络内部没有人可以纠正记录。

BUT BY DIRECTLY COMMUNICATING select messages to select voters, the microtargeting of the Obama campaign had started a journey toward the privatization of public discourse in America. Although direct mail had long been part of American campaigns, data-driven microtargeting allowed campaigns to match a myriad of granular narratives to granular universes of voters—your neighbor might receive a wholly different message than you did, with neither of you being the wiser. When campaigns were conducted in private, the scrutiny of debate and publicity could be avoided. The town square, the very foundation of American democracy, was incrementally being replaced by online ad networks. And without any scrutiny, campaign messages no longer even had to look like campaign messages. Social media created a new environment where campaigns could now appear, as Obama’s campaign piloted, as if your friend was sending you a message, without your realizing the source or calculated intent of that contact. A campaign could look like a news site, university, or public agency. With the ascendancy of social media, we have been forced to place our trust in political campaigns to be honest, because if lies are told, we may never notice. There is no one there to correct the record inside of a private ad network.

在奥巴马第一次竞选之前的几年里，硅谷的董事会会议室里出现了一种新的积累逻辑：科技公司开始利用其绘制和组织信息的能力赚钱。这种模式的核心是知识的本质不对称——机器对我们的行为了解很多，但我们对它们的行为知之甚少。为了方便起见，这些公司向人们提供信息服务，以换取更多信息——数据。数据变得越来越有价值，Facebook 平均从其 1.7 亿美国用户中每人身上赚取 30 美元。与此同时，我们却误以为这些服务是“免费的”。事实上，我们用我们的数据为这种吸引人类注意力的商业模式买单。

In the years leading up to the first Obama campaign, a new logic of accumulation emerged in the boardrooms of Silicon Valley: Tech companies began making money from their ability to map out and organize information. At the core of this model was an essential asymmetry in knowledge—the machines knew a lot about our behavior, but we knew very little about theirs. In a trade-off for convenience, these companies offered people information services in exchange for more information—data. The data has become more and more valuable, with Facebook making on average $30 from each of its 170 million American users. At the same time, we have fallen for the idea that these services are “free.” In reality, we pay with our data into a business model of extracting human attention.

更多数据带来更多利润，因此设计模式开始实施，以鼓励用户分享更多关于自己的信息。平台开始模仿赌场，创新包括无限滚动和针对大脑奖励系统的令人上瘾的功能。Gmail 等服务开始搜查我们的信件，其方式足以让传统邮政快递员入狱。实时地理跟踪曾经只用于囚犯的脚镯，现在被添加到我们的手机中，而几年前被称为窃听的功能成为无数应用程序的标准功能。

More data led to more profits, and so design patterns were implemented to encourage users to share more and more about themselves. Platforms started to mimic casinos, with innovations like the infinite scroll and addictive features aimed at the brain’s reward systems. Services such as Gmail began trawling through our correspondence in a way that would land a traditional postal courier in jail. Live geo-tracking, once reserved for convicts’ ankle bracelets, was added to our phones, and what would have been called wiretapping in years past became a standard feature of countless applications.

很快，我们就开始毫不犹豫地分享个人信息。这在一定程度上受到了新词汇的鼓励。实际上，私人拥有的监控网络变成了“社区”，这些网络用来牟利的人被称为“用户”，而令人上瘾的设计则被称为“用户体验”或“参与度”。人们的身份开始从他们的“数据废气”或“数字面包屑”中被勾勒出来。几千年来，主流经济模式一直专注于开采自然资源，并将这些原材料转化为商品。棉花被纺成织物。铁矿石被冶炼成钢铁。森林被砍伐成木材。但随着互联网的出现，我们的生活——我们的行为、我们的注意力、我们的身份——可以被创造出来成为商品。人们被加工成数据。我们将成为这个新数据工业综合体的原材料。

Soon we were sharing personal information without the slightest hesitation. This was encouraged, in part, by a new vocabulary. What were in effect privately owned surveillance networks became “communities,” the people these networks used for profit were “users,” and addictive design was promoted as “user experience” or “engagement.” People’s identities began to be profiled from their “data exhaust” or “digital breadcrumbs.” For thousands of years, dominant economic models had focused on the extraction of natural resources and the conversion of these raw materials into commodities. Cotton was spun into fabric. Iron ore was smelted into steel. Forests were cut into timber. But with the advent of the Internet, it became possible to create commodities out of our lives—our behavior, our attention, our identity. People were processed into data. We would serve as the raw material of this new data-industrial complex.

最早发现这一新现实的政治潜力的人之一是史蒂夫·班农，他是右翼网站《布赖特巴特新闻》的编辑，名不见经传。《布赖特巴特新闻》成立的目的是按照安德鲁·布赖特巴特的民族主义观点重塑美国文化。班农视自己的使命为一场文化战争，但我第一次遇到他时，他就知道自己缺少了一些东西，没有合适的武器。战地将领注重炮火力量和空中优势，而班农需要获得文化力量和信息优势——一套以数据为驱动力的武器库，适合在这个新的战场上征服人心。新成立的剑桥分析公司就是这个武器库。剑桥分析公司借鉴了军事心理战 (PSYOPS) 的技术，将史蒂夫·班农的另类右翼叛乱推向了高潮。在这场新战争中，美国选民成为混乱、操纵和欺骗的目标。真相被另类叙述和虚拟现实所取代。

One of the first people to spot the political potential of this new reality was Steve Bannon, the relatively unknown editor of right-wing website Breitbart News, which was founded to reframe American culture according to the nationalist vision of Andrew Breitbart. Bannon saw his mission as nothing short of cultural warfare, but when I first encountered him, Bannon knew that something was missing, that he didn’t have the right weapons. Whereas field generals focused on artillery power and air dominance, Bannon needed to gain cultural power and informational dominance—a data-powered arsenal suited to conquer hearts and minds in this new battlespace. The newly formed Cambridge Analytica became that arsenal. Refining techniques from military psychological operations (PSYOPS), Cambridge Analytica propelled Steve Bannon’s alt-right insurgency into its ascendancy. In this new war, the American voter became a target of confusion, manipulation, and deception. Truth was replaced by alternative narratives and virtual realities.

剑桥分析公司首先在非洲和世界各地的热带岛屿试行了这场新战争。该公司尝试了大规模的网络造谣、假新闻和大规模画像。它与俄罗斯特工合作，雇佣黑客侵入反对派候选人的电子邮件账户。很快，在远离西方媒体关注的情况下，剑桥分析公司完善了自己的手段，从煽动非洲的部落冲突转向煽动美国的部落冲突。似乎不知从何而来，美国爆发了一场起义，人们疯狂地高呼“让美国再次伟大！”和“建墙！”。总统辩论突然从政策立场转变为关于什么是真新闻、什么是假新闻的奇怪争论。美国现在正生活在首次大规模部署大规模杀伤性心理武器的后果之中。

Cambridge Analytica first piloted this new warfare in Africa and tropical islands around the world. The firm experimented with scaled online disinformation, fake news, and mass profiling. It worked with Russian agents and employed hackers to break into opposition candidates’ email accounts. Soon enough, having perfected its methods far from the attention of Western media, CA shifted from instigating tribal conflict in Africa to instigating tribal conflict in America. Seemingly out of nowhere, an uprising erupted in America with manic cries of MAGA! and Build the wall! Presidential debates suddenly shifted from policy positions into bizarre arguments about what was real news and what was fake news. America is now living in the aftermath of the first scaled deployment of a psychological weapon of mass destruction.

作为剑桥分析公司的创始人之一，我对所发生的事情负有责任，我知道我有重大的责任去纠正我过去的错误。和科技界的许多人一样，我愚蠢地陷入了 Facebook “快速行动，打破常规”的傲慢诱惑。我从来没有像现在这样后悔过。我行动迅速，创造了强大的东西，但我从未完全意识到我正在打破什么，直到为时已晚。

As one of the creators of Cambridge Analytica, I share responsibility for what happened, and I know that I have a profound obligation to right the wrongs of my past. Like so many people in technology, I stupidly fell for the hubristic allure of Facebook’s call to “move fast and break things.” I’ve never regretted something so much. I moved fast, I built things of immense power, and I never fully appreciated what I was breaking until it was too late.

—

2018 年初夏的一天，当我走向国会大厦深处的安全设施时，我对周围发生的事情感到麻木。共和党人已经在对我进行反对派调查。Facebook 正在利用公关公司抹黑批评者，其律师威胁要向联邦调查局举报我，罪名是未指明的网络犯罪。司法部现在处于特朗普政府的控制之下，而特朗普政府公然无视长期以来的法律惯例。我激怒了如此多的利益相关方，以至于我的律师们真的担心联邦调查局可能会在我做完这件事后逮捕我。我的一位律师告诉我，最安全的做法是留在欧洲。

AS I MADE MY WAY to the secure facility deep under the Capitol that day in the early summer of 2018, I felt numbed to what was happening around me. Republicans were already conducting opposition research on me. Facebook was using PR firms to smear its critics, and its lawyers had threatened to report me to the FBI for an unspecified cybercrime. The DOJ was now under the control of a Trump administration that was publicly ignoring long-held legal conventions. I had enraged so many interests that my lawyers were genuinely concerned the FBI might arrest me after I was finished. One of my lawyers told me the safest thing to do was stay in Europe.

出于安全和法律原因，我不能直接引用我在华盛顿的证词。但我可以告诉你，我走进那个房间时带了两个大文件夹，每个文件夹里都有几百页文件。第一个文件夹里有电子邮件、备忘录和文件，显示了剑桥分析公司数据收集行动的范围。这些材料表明，该公司招募了黑客，雇佣了与俄罗斯情报部门有已知联系的人员，并在世界各地的选举中参与了贿赂、勒索和造假活动。还有律师的机密法律备忘录，警告史蒂夫·班农剑桥分析公司违反了《外国代理人登记法》，还有一批文件描述了该公司如何利用 Facebook 访问超过 8700 万个私人账户，并利用这些数据压制非裔美国人的选票。

I cannot, for security and legal reasons, quote directly from my testimony in Washington. But I can tell you that I walked into that room with two large binders, each containing several hundred pages of documents. The first binder contained emails, memos, and documents showing the extent of Cambridge Analytica’s data-harvesting operation. This material demonstrated that the company had recruited hackers, hired personnel with known links to Russian intelligence, and engaged in bribery, extortion, and disinformation campaigns in elections around the world. There were confidential legal memos from lawyers warning Steve Bannon about Cambridge Analytica’s violations of the Foreign Agents Registration Act, as well as a cache of documents describing how the firm exploited Facebook to access more than eighty-seven million private accounts and used that data in efforts to suppress the votes of African Americans.

第二个文件夹更为敏感。它包含了数百页电子邮件、财务文件以及我当年早些时候在伦敦秘密获得的录音和短信记录。这些文件曾被美国情报部门寻求，并详细记录了俄罗斯驻伦敦大使馆与特朗普的同伙和英国脱欧运动领袖之间的密切关系。这份文件显示，英国另类右翼领袖在飞往特朗普竞选团队之前和之后与俄罗斯大使馆会面，其中至少有三人收到了俄罗斯矿业公司的优先投资机会，这些机会可能价值数百万美元。从这些通讯中可以清楚地看出，俄罗斯政府很早就发现了英美另类右翼网络，并且可能已经培养了其中的人物成为唐纳德·特朗普的接触代理人。它显示了 2016 年重大事件之间的联系：另类右翼的崛起、英国脱欧的意外通过以及特朗普的当选。

The second binder was more sensitive. It contained hundreds of pages of emails, financial documents, and transcripts of audio recordings and text messages that I had covertly procured in London earlier that year. These files had been sought by U.S. intelligence and detailed the close relationships between the Russian embassy in London and both Trump associates and leading Brexit campaigners. This file showed that leading British alt-right figures met with the Russian embassy before and after they flew to meet the Trump campaign, and that at least three of them were receiving offers of preferential investment opportunities in Russian mining companies potentially worth millions. What became clear in these communications was how early the Russian government had identified the Anglo-American alt-right network, and that it may have groomed figures within it to become access agents to Donald Trump. It showed the connections among the major events of 2016: the rise of the alt-right, the surprise passage of Brexit, and the election of Trump.

四个小时过去了。五个小时。我开始深入描述 Facebook 在此次事件中所扮演的角色以及应承担的责任。

Four hours went by. Five. I was deep into describing Facebook’s role in—and culpability for—what had happened.

剑桥分析公司使用的数据是否落入了潜在的俄罗斯特工手中？是的。

Did the data used by Cambridge Analytica ever get into the hands of potential Russian agents? Yes.

您是否认为 2016 年总统大选和英国脱欧运动期间，伦敦存在俄罗斯政府支持的活动？是的。

Do you believe there was a nexus of Russian state-sponsored activity in London during the 2016 presidential election and Brexit campaigns? Yes.

剑桥分析公司和维基解密之间有沟通吗？是的。

Was there communication between Cambridge Analytica and WikiLeaks? Yes.

我终于看到委员会成员眼中闪过一丝理解的光芒。我告诉他们，Facebook 不再只是一家公司。它是通往美国人民思想的大门，而马克·扎克伯格却为剑桥分析公司、俄罗斯人以及不知道有多少其他人敞开了这扇大门。Facebook 是一家垄断企业，但它的行为不仅仅是一个监管问题——它对国家安全构成了威胁。Facebook 享有的权力集中对美国民主构成了威胁。

I finally saw glimmers of understanding coming into the committee members’ eyes. Facebook is no longer just a company, I told them. It’s a doorway into the minds of the American people, and Mark Zuckerberg left that door wide open for Cambridge Analytica, the Russians, and who knows how many others. Facebook is a monopoly, but its behavior is more than a regulatory issue—it’s a threat to national security. The concentration of power that Facebook enjoys is a danger to American democracy.

我在多个司法管辖区、情报机构、立法听证会和警察当局之间跳着微妙的芭蕾舞，作了超过两百小时的宣誓证词，并移交了至少一万页的文件。我发现自己走遍了世界各地，从华盛顿到布鲁塞尔，帮助领导人不仅揭露剑桥分析公司，还揭露社交媒体对我们选举公正性的威胁。

Dancing a delicate ballet among multiple jurisdictions, intelligence agencies, legislative hearings, and police authorities, I have given more than two hundred hours of sworn testimony and handed over at least ten thousand pages of documents. I found myself traveling around the world, from Washington to Brussels, to help leaders unpack not only Cambridge Analytica but also the threats social media poses to the integrity of our elections.

然而，在我提供证词和证据的漫长时间里，我意识到警察、立法者、监管者和媒体都很难弄清楚如何处理这些信息。由于犯罪发生在网上，而非任何实际地点，警方无法就谁拥有管辖权达成一致。由于这个故事涉及软件和算法，很多人都困惑地举手投降。有一次，当我打交道的一家执法机构叫我去问话时，我不得不向那些据称是技术犯罪专家的探员解释一个基本的计算机科学概念。我在一张纸上潦草地画了一张图表，他们没收了它。从技术上讲，这是证据。但他们开玩笑说，他们需要它作为小抄来了解他们正在调查的内容。哈哈，太有趣了，伙计们。

Yet, in my many hours of giving testimony and evidence, I came to realize that the police, the legislators, the regulators, and the media were all having a difficult time figuring out what to do with this information. Because the crimes happened online, rather than in any physical location, the police could not agree on who had jurisdiction. Because the story involved software and algorithms, many people threw up their hands in confusion. Once, when one of the law enforcement agencies I was dealing with called me in for questioning, I had to explain a fundamental computer science concept to agents who were supposedly specialists in technology crime. I scribbled a diagram on a piece of paper, and they confiscated it. Technically, it was evidence. But they joked that they needed it as a crib sheet to understand what they were investigating. LOL, so funny, guys.

我们被社会化地信任我们的机构——我们的政府、我们的警察、我们的学校、我们的监管机构。就好像我们假设有个人带着一个秘密专家团队坐在办公室里制定计划，如果这个计划行不通，别担心，他有 B 计划和 C 计划——有人会负责处理。但事实上，这个人并不存在。如果我们选择等待，没有人会来。

We are socialized to place trust in our institutions—our government, our police, our schools, our regulators. It’s as if we assume there’s some guy with a secret team of experts sitting in an office with a plan, and if that plan doesn’t work, don’t worry, he’s got a plan B and a plan C—someone in charge will take care of it. But in truth, that guy doesn’t exist. If we choose to wait, nobody will come.

第2章

CHAPTER 2

失败的教训

LESSONS IN FAILURE

-

八年前，我搬到了英国，从此开始了我与剑桥分析公司纠葛的故事。我曾在加拿大政界工作过几年，但讽刺的是，我搬到伦敦是为了逃避政治。2010 年夏天，我搬进了泰晤士河南岸的一套公寓，靠近泰特现代美术馆，这座现代艺术博物馆坐落在巨大的老河岸边发电站内。在渥太华待了几年后，21 岁的我决定离开政坛，跨越大西洋去伦敦政治经济学院 (LSE) 就读法学院。离开政坛后，我摆脱了对党的旧责任。我和谁在一起不再重要，我不再需要注意我说的话，也不再需要担心谁在听。我可以自由地结识新朋友，我很高兴能开始新的生活。

It was eight years before this that I moved to England, where the story of my entanglement with Cambridge Analytica began. I’d worked in Canadian politics for a few years, but the irony is that I moved to London to escape politics. In the summer of 2010, I moved into a flat on the south bank of the River Thames, near the Tate Modern, the modern art museum housed in the colossal old Bankside Power Station. After several years in Ottawa, I had decided, at age twenty-one, to leave politics and move across the Atlantic to attend law school at the London School of Economics and Political Science (LSE). No longer in politics, I was unshackled from my old responsibilities to the party. It didn’t matter anymore who I might be seen with, and I no longer had to watch what I said or think about who might be listening. I was free to meet new people and I was excited to make a new life for myself.

我到达时还是夏天，收拾好行李后做的第一件事就是去海德公园和晒太阳的人、游客和年轻情侣们坐在一起。我充分利用了伦敦，周五和周六晚上在肖尔迪奇和达尔斯顿度过，周日则去伦敦最古老的食品市场博罗市场，那里挤满了一个露天大厅，到处都是叫卖的小贩、游客和烹饪摊位。我开始和同龄人交朋友，第一次感觉自己年轻了。

When I arrived it was still summer, and the first thing I did after unpacking was head out to sit with the sunbathers, tourists, and young couples in Hyde Park. I took full advantage of London, spending Friday and Saturday nights in Shoreditch and Dalston, and Sundays in Borough Market, London’s oldest food market, which is crammed into an outdoor hall alive with a cacophony of shouting traders, visitors, and cooking stalls. I started making friends with people my age, and for the first time, I felt young.

但抵达英国几天后，我仍因时差而感到头晕目眩，就接到一个电话，让我明白，要离开政治并不容易。四个月前，一位名叫尼克·克莱格的人成为了英国副首相。

But a few days after I arrived, still feeling fuzzy from the jet lag, I got a call that made it clear that it wouldn’t be so easy to leave politics behind. Four months earlier, a man named Nick Clegg had become the country’s deputy prime minister.

1999 年，他首次当选欧洲议会议员，并于 2007 年晋升为自由民主党领袖。当时，自由民主党是英国政坛的激进第三党——第一个支持同性婚姻，也是唯一反对伊拉克战争并呼吁放弃英国核武库的政党。在 2010 年大选中，在工党经过十多年的“第三条道路”后， “克莱格狂热”席卷了整个英国。在巅峰时期，克莱格的民意调查支持率与温斯顿·丘吉尔不相上下，他将自己定位为英国版的巴拉克·奥巴马。大选结束后，他成为联合政府的一员，保守党人戴维·卡梅伦在该政府担任首相。电话是从他的办公室打来的：他们从自由党政治中的共同关系中听说了我在加拿大和美国的数据工作，他们想了解更多信息。

First elected to the European Parliament in 1999, he worked his way up to become, in 2007, the leader of the Liberal Democrats. This was back in the days when the Lib Dems were the radical third party of British politics—the first to support same-sex marriage, and the only party to oppose the war in Iraq and call for abandoning Britain’s nuclear arsenal. In the 2010 general election, after more than a decade of Labour’s now tired “third way,” “Cleggmania” swept across Britain. At his peak, Clegg was polling as highly as Winston Churchill and positioned himself as Britain’s answer to Barack Obama. After the election, he became part of a coalition government that made the Conservative David Cameron prime minister. The call was from his office: They’d heard about my data work in Canada and America from mutual connections in liberal politics, and they wanted to know more.

到了约定的时间，我到达了自由民主党总部（LDHQ），当时它仍位于威斯敏斯特考利街 4 号。这座经过改建的新乔治亚风格豪宅距离威斯敏斯特宫只有几个街区，装饰精美，采用深红色砖砌，两侧是巨大的石制烟囱。它对于这条蜿蜒的小街来说相当大，所以我很容易就认出了它。由于它是女王陛下政府一个政党的办公室，因此伦敦警察的一支武装部队在附近守卫，在小巷里来回巡逻。按门铃后，我推开沉重的木门，走到接待处，一名实习生在那里迎接了我，并带我去开会。庄园仍然装饰着庄园原有的枝形吊灯、橡木镶板和壁炉，展现出曾经宏伟住宅的褪色优雅，这与这个曾经盛大的聚会感觉奇怪地相称。

At the appointed time, I arrived at Liberal Democratic Headquarters (LDHQ), which was then still located at No. 4 Cowley Street in Westminster. Located only a few blocks from the Palace of Westminster, the converted neo-Georgian mansion stood handsomely adorned in crimson brickwork and flanked by large stone chimneys on either side. It was rather outsize for the tiny, winding street, so I had no problem spotting it. Because it housed the offices of a party in Her Majesty’s Government, an armed unit of the Metropolitan Police stood guard nearby, strolling up and down the small side street. After being buzzed in, I heaved open the weighty wooden doors and walked up to reception, where I was greeted by an intern who would show me to the meeting. Still adorned with the manor’s original chandeliers, oak paneling, and fireplaces, the place revealed the faded elegance of a once grand residence, which felt oddly fitting for this once grand party.

考利街（Cowley Street）是人们的普遍称呼，它与我在加拿大或美国见过的任何地方都不一样。我不知道在狭窄而吱吱作响的走廊里，所有党派工作人员如何能完成工作。老旧的卧室里挤满了办公桌，连接服务器的电缆用胶带粘在墙上和门框周围。在一个改建的壁橱里，一个似乎患有睡眠呼吸暂停症的男子在地板上大声打鼾，但没有人注意到他。环顾四周，我觉得这个地方更像是一个老男孩的俱乐部，而不是一个执政党。我走上一个带有华丽雕花栏杆的大楼梯，被带进一个大会议室，那里肯定曾经是主餐厅。我等了几分钟后，一小群工作人员鱼贯而入。当例行的英国式闲聊结束时，其中一人说：“请给我们讲讲选民激活网络。”

Cowley Street, as they all called it, was unlike anything else I had seen in Canada or the United States. I wondered how all the party staffers waddling past one another in the cramped and creaking hallways could get anything done. Old bedrooms were jammed with desks, and cables connecting to servers were taped up on walls and around doorframes. In one converted closet, a man apparently with sleep apnea was snoring loudly on the floor, but no one paid him much attention. Looking around, I got the impression that this place operated more like an old boys’ clubhouse than a party in government. I walked up a large staircase with ornately carved railings and was shown into a large boardroom that must have once been the main dining room. After I’d waited several minutes, a small cadre of staffers filed in. When the obligatory British small talk concluded, one of them said, “So tell us about the Voter Activation Network.”

奥巴马 2008 年胜选后，全世界的政党都开始对这种新的“美国式竞选”感兴趣，这种竞选由国家目标数据库和大型数字运营提供支持。竞选活动的背后是新兴的微目标做法，机器学习算法会收集大量选民数据，将选民划分为狭窄的部分，并预测哪些个人选民是说服或参加选举的最佳目标。自由民主党想和我谈谈，因为他们不确定他们能否将这种新的竞选方式移植到英国的政治体系中。我与 LPC 合作的项目（建立与奥巴马竞选团队使用的相同类型的选民定位系统）对他们来说如此有趣，是因为它是美国以外第一个此类和规模如此之大的项目。加拿大和英国一样，采用同样的简单多数制“威斯敏斯特模式”选举制度，拥有多元化的政党。在这次谈话中，工作人员意识到，如果他们引进加拿大版的技术，一半的本地化工作就已经完成了。会议结束时，他们了解到这个系统能做什么后，几乎兴奋不已。离开后，我跑回学校，赶上一场关于法定解释规则的讲座的尾声，以为讲座就此结束。

After Obama’s 2008 victory, parties all over the world were becoming interested in this new “American-style campaign,” powered by national targeting databases and big digital operations. Behind the campaign was the emerging practice of microtargeting, where machine-learning algorithms ingest large amounts of voter data to divide the electorate into narrow segments and predict which individual voters are the best targets to persuade or turn out in an election. The Lib Dems wanted to talk to me because they were unsure whether they could translate this new school of campaigning into the British political system. What was so interesting for them about the project I had worked on with the LPC—setting up the same kind of voter-targeting system used by the Obama campaign—was that it was the first of its kind and scale outside the United States. And Canada, like Britain, uses the same first-past-the-post “Westminster model” electoral system and has a diverse array of political parties. In this conversation, the staffers realized that half of the localization work would have already been done if they imported the Canadian version of the technology. At the end of the meeting, they were almost giddy after learning about what the system could do. After leaving, I ran back to school to catch the tail end of a lecture on the rules of statutory interpretation and thought that was the end of it.

但第二天，自由民主党的顾问又打来电话，问我能否回来向更多的人讲述我的故事。我当时正在上课，所以一开始没有接电话，但在接到一个随机号码的四个未接电话后，我走出去看看有什么急事。那天下午有一个高级职员会议，他们问我是否可以就微目标做一个即兴演讲。所以下课后，我从伦敦政治经济学院走回考利街，背包里装满了教科书。时间这么短，我来不及换衣服，就穿着 Stüssy 的图案印花 T 恤和迷彩运动裤去见副首相的顾问。

But the Lib Dem advisers called again the next day, asking if I could come back and tell my story to a bigger group. I was in the middle of a lecture, so I didn’t pick up initially, but after four missed calls from a random number, I stepped out to see what was so urgent. There was a senior staff meeting that afternoon, and they asked if I could do an impromptu presentation on microtargeting. So after class, I walked from LSE back to Cowley Street with my backpack filled with textbooks. With such short notice, I didn’t have time to change, so I headed to meet the deputy prime minister’s advisers in a Stüssy graphic print T-shirt and camo sweatpants.

走进同一间会议室，这一次我听到的是挤满了人的嘈杂声。他们没有给我任何提示就把我领到了前面，因此，在为我略显荒谬的着装道歉之后，我就开始即兴发挥了。我告诉他们，自由民主党如何利用微目标来克服小党派的劣势。我继续说着，不禁变得更加激动。自从离开自由民主党后，我就没再谈过这件事，我的心一下子涌了出来。我告诉他们我在奥巴马竞选中看到的一切，看到这么多人第一次投票是什么感觉，看到非洲裔美国人满怀希望地参加集会是什么感觉。我告诉他们，这不仅仅是数据问题；这是关于我们如何接触那些放弃政治的人。这就是我们如何找到他们并激励他们参选的原因。但最重要的是，这是关于技术如何成为这个如今已进入权力走廊的政党用来颠覆英国政治根深蒂固的阶级制度的工具。

Walking into the same boardroom, I was met this time with the humming cacophony of a packed room. I was ushered to the front without any prompt, so, after apologizing for my slightly ridiculous attire, I proceeded to just wing it. I told them how the Lib Dems could use microtargeting to overcome the disadvantages that come with being such a small party. And as I continued, I couldn’t help but get more passionate. I hadn’t spoken about this since I left the LPC, and my heart simply poured out. I told them about what I had seen on the Obama campaign, what it was like to see so many people vote for the first time, what it was like to see African Americans at rallies filled with hope. I told them that this was not just about data; this was about how we could reach the people who had given up on politics. This was how we would find them and inspire them to turn out. But, most important, this was about how technology could be the vehicle that this party, which now found itself in the corridors of power, deployed to upend the entrenched class system that underpins so much of British politics.

几周后，自由民主党邀请我去英国为他们工作，实施一个针对选民的项目。当时我刚开始在伦敦政治经济学院学习，作为一名 21 岁的学生，我终于在伦敦站稳了脚跟。我犹豫着是否真的应该再次让自己分心于政治。但这是一个机会，可以利用同样的技术——同样的软件，本质上是同样的项目——完成我在加拿大开始的工作。但正是我在考利街的一间办公室的墙上随意看到的东西，最终吸引了我。那是一张泛黄的旧卡片，边角略微卷曲，上面有一段自由民主党的宪法摘录，上面写着：任何人都不得被贫穷、无知或顺从所奴役。

A few weeks later, the Lib Dems asked me to come work for them and implement a voter-targeting project in Britain. I was just starting my degree at LSE, and, as a twenty-one-year-old student, I was finally finding my feet in London. I hesitated about whether it was really a good idea to distract myself with politics again. But here was a chance to take the same technology—the same software, and essentially the same project—and finish what I had started in Canada. But it was what I saw hanging so casually on the wall in one of the offices at Cowley Street that finally pulled me in. It was an old yellowing card, with slightly curled corners, with an excerpt of the Liberal Democrats’ constitution that read NO ONE SHALL BE ENSLAVED BY POVERTY, IGNORANCE OR CONFORMITY.

我说是。

I said yes.

—

2008 年总统大选后，我回到渥太华，撰写了一份关于奥巴马竞选团队新技术战略的报告。这份报告轰动一时。每个人都期待着我向他们介绍竞选团队华丽的品牌宣传、图形和病毒式视频。但我却写了关于关系数据库、机器学习算法以及这些东西如何通过软件和筹款系统相互联系的文章。当我建议该党投资数据库时，人们认为我疯了。他们想要性感的答案——而不是这个。奥巴马是他们“模范”竞选的标杆，他们被高高的颧骨和撅起的嘴唇所吸引，而不是让这一切成为可能的骨架和骨干。

AFTER THE 2008 PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION, I returned to Ottawa and wrote a report about the Obama campaign’s new technology strategies. It landed with a thud. Everyone was expecting me to tell them about the campaign’s flashy branding, graphics, and viral videos. Instead I wrote about relational databases, machine-learning algorithms, and how these things connected to one another through software and fundraising systems. When I recommended that the party invest in databases, people thought I’d lost my mind. They wanted sexy answers—not this. Obama was their benchmark for a “model” campaign, and they were taken with high cheekbones and pouty lips, not the skeleton and backbone that made it all possible.

大部分竞选活动可以归结为两个核心操作：说服和投票率。投票率，或“GOTV”（争取选票），指的是那些可能支持候选人但并不总是投票的人。说服范围则相反，代表那些可能会投票但并不总是支持政党的人。那些不太可能投票或不太可能支持我们的人被放入排除范围，因为与他们接触毫无意义。那些既很可能支持候选人又很可能投票的选民是“基本”选民，他们通常被排除在联系之外，但在志愿者或捐助者招募中可能会优先考虑他们。找到合适的选民群体进行联系是游戏的名称。

Most campaigns can be boiled down to two core operations: persuasion and turnout. The turnout, or “GOTV” (get out the vote), universe is those people who likely support the candidate but do not always vote. The persuasion universe is the inverse, representing those who likely will vote but do not always support the party. People who are either very unlikely to vote or very unlikely to ever support us are put into an exclusion universe, as there is no point in engaging them. Voters who are both very likely to support the candidate and very likely to vote—these are the “base” voters, and they are typically excluded from contact, but they might be prioritized for volunteer or donor recruitment. Finding the right set of voters to contact is the name of the game.

20 世纪 90 年代，美国选民通常通过地方或州办公室提供的数据进行定位，这些数据通常包含每个选民的政党登记（如果他们有的话）和投票历史（他们参加了哪些选举）。然而，这种方法的局限性在于，并非所有州都提供这些信息，选民改变主意的频率比改变政党登记的频率要高（或者不会登记任何政党），而且这些信息不会告诉你真正激励选民的问题。微目标定位所做的是找到额外的数据集，例如有关选民抵押贷款、订阅或汽车型号的商业数据，以便为每个选民提供更多背景信息。使用这些数据，再加上民意调查和统计技术，就可以“评分”所有选民记录，从而获得更准确的信息。

In the 1990s American voters were generally targeted using data provided by local or state offices, which typically contained each voter’s party registration (if they had one) and their voting history (which elections they came out to vote in). However, the limitation to this approach is that not all states provide this information, voters change their mind more frequently than they change their party registration (or would not register a party), and this information would tell you nothing about the issues that actually motivate the voter. What microtargeting did was find extra data sets, such as commercial data about a voter’s mortgage, subscriptions, or car model, to provide more context to each voter. Using this data, along with polling and the statistical techniques, it’s possible to “score” all of the voter records, yielding far more accurate information.

奥巴马的竞选团队将这一策略主流化，并将其置于竞选活动的核心。这一点很重要，因为竞选活动的有序混乱通常不是电视上看到的那种，比如演讲或集会。相反，它是志愿者拉票人通过直接邮寄的方式与全国各地的选民进行数以百万计的直接接触。虽然它不如精心准备的演讲或令人惊叹的品牌宣传那么吸引人，但正是这种看不见的机制为现代总统竞选提供了关键的动力。当其他人都专注于竞选活动的公众形象时，战略家们则专注于部署和扩大这种隐藏的机制。

What Obama’s campaign did was mainstream this technique and put it at the heart of its campaign operations. This is important because the organized chaos of campaign activity is typically not what one sees on TV, such as speeches or rallies. Rather, it is the millions upon millions of direct contacts made by volunteer canvassers or via direct mail to individual voters throughout the country. Although less sexy than a beautifully crafted speech or amazing branding, it is this unseen machinery that provides the critical horsepower of a modern presidential campaign. When everyone else is focused on the public persona of the campaign, strategists are focused on deploying and scaling this hidden machinery.

最终，我在议会工作的反对党领袖办公室的一些人意识到，如果我们为领导人与选民和公民的互动创建一个议会版的选民激活网络，我们可以向党派展示选民激活网络将有多么有用。该党不愿意为新数据库这样奢侈的东西买单，但我们意识到领导人的官方议会预算中有足够的空间。唯一的问题是，这些资金在技术上是公共资金，我们创建的任何试点数据库都不能用于政治目的。但我们并不太担心。议会版将包含联系过领导人的选民和公民的记录，由于选民只是戴着不同帽子的选民，因此它可以让我们向党派强调所有相同的功能，而无需他们花费任何费用。当然，在亲眼目睹这样的系统后，加拿大自由党将开始了解数据的潜力。我们问马克·沙利文和吉姆·圣乔治，他们是否曾考虑过将 VAN 扩展到国际——加拿大。当时他们还没有在美国以外做过任何大型项目，但他们抓住了与我们合作的机会。在 Sullivan 和 St. George 的帮助下，我们在六个月内创建了加拿大版的 VAN 基础设施。令他们高兴的是，VAN 甚至支持英语和法语。只有一个问题：没有数据来真正为系统提供动力。

Eventually some of us in the Opposition Leader’s Office, where I was working in Parliament, realized we could show the party how useful the Voter Activation Network would be if we created a parliamentary version of it for the leader’s interactions with constituents and citizens. The party was unwilling to foot the bill for something so extravagant as a new database, but we realized we had room for it in the leader’s official parliamentary budget. The only problem was that these were technically public funds, and any pilot database we created could not be used for political purposes. But we were not too concerned. A parliamentary version would contain the records of constituents and citizens who had contacted the leader, and since constituents are simply voters with a different hat on, it would allow us to highlight all the same functionalities to the party without needing them to spend anything. Surely, after seeing such a system firsthand, the Liberal Party of Canada would begin to understand the potential of data. We asked Mark Sullivan and Jim St. George if they’d ever thought about expanding VAN internationally—to Canada. They hadn’t done any big projects outside the United States at that point, but they jumped at the chance to work with us. With the help of Sullivan and St. George, we were able to create a Canadianized VAN infrastructure in six months. To the party’s delight, VAN even worked in both English and French. There was only one problem: There was no data to actually fuel the system.

计算机模型并不是能够预测世界的魔法咒语——只有当有足够的数据作为预测依据时，它们才能做出预测。如果系统中没有数据，那么就没有模型或目标。这就像买了一辆赛车却省了汽油——无论这辆车的工程多么复杂，它就是发动不起来。所以下一步是为 VAN 采购数据。但数据需要花钱，而且由于数据将用于竞选活动，根据法律，必须由政党而不是领导人的议会办公室支付费用。但几乎立刻就遭到了该党的强烈反对，他们并不急于改变。我求助于最先带我进入政界的议员基思·马丁 (Keith Martin)。我在学校的时候，他给了我第一个实习机会，后来又给了我第一份真正的工作，即加拿大议会。马丁经常被称为加拿大政界的“特立独行者”，他的办公室里也都是特立独行的人。对我来说，他是一个完美的人选。马丁接受过急诊医生培训，早期的医疗生涯都在非洲冲突地区度过，治疗从地雷伤到营养不良等各种疾病。这家伙很酷，在从政之前过着精彩的生活——办公室墙上挂着他身穿卡其色外套、与豹子坐在一起的照片，看起来像印第安纳琼斯。作为一名急诊医生，他接受过不浪费时间的培训，但在政治上，你只能浪费时间才能生存。他曾经对议会的机械程序感到非常愤怒，以至于在辩论中，他拿起了“权杖”——我们从英国继承下来的镀金中世纪武器，放在下议院的过道里。

Computer models are not magical incantations that can predict the world—they can make predictions only when there is an ample amount of data to base a prediction upon. If there was no data in the system, then there could be no models or targeting. It would be like buying a race car but skimping on gasoline—no matter the car’s sophisticated engineering, it just wouldn’t start. So the next step was to procure data for VAN. But data was going to cost money, and because it would be used for campaigns, by law the party had to pay for it, not the leader’s parliamentary office. But almost immediately there was hard pushback from the party, which was not eager for change. I turned to the MP who first brought me into politics, Keith Martin. He had given me my first internship when I was still in school, and later my first real job, in the Canadian Parliament. Martin was often called the “maverick” of Canadian politics, and he staffed his office with mavericks, too. For me, he was a perfect fit. Martin trained as an ER doctor and spent his early medical career in African conflict zones, treating everything from land-mine injuries to malnutrition. This guy was legit cool and lived an amazing life before politics—on the wall in his office he had photos of himself looking like Indiana Jones in a khaki overshirt, sitting with leopards. As an ER medic, he was trained to not waste time, but in politics you survive by wasting time. He was once so incensed at the mechanistic procedures of Parliament that, mid-debate, he picked up “the Mace”—the gold-plated medieval weapon we inherited from Britain that lies in the aisle of the House of Commons.

2009 年，马丁的高级顾问杰夫·西尔维斯特 (Jeff Silvester) 是党内少数几个理解我所做之事的人之一。杰夫曾是一名软件工程师，后来将注意力转向了政治。在我担任议员期间，他一直是我的导师和坚强后盾。我解释说，尽管党内没有授权我推进数据定位计划，但我们必须这样做。这意味着我们需要资金。在马丁的同意下，杰夫同意帮助我筹集资金，但不告诉党内全国办公室。我们开始举办秘密活动，我可以向潜在捐助者解释，如果 LPC 希望在 21 世纪具有竞争力，我们就需要这个项目。我们暗中做这一切，趁党内工作人员不注意的时候说服基层民众捐款。很快，我们就筹集了数十万加元，足以启动该计划。由于对国家办公室不满，不列颠哥伦比亚省的党派同意成为我们实验的实验鼠。

In 2009, Jeff Silvester, Martin’s senior adviser, a former software engineer who’d turned his attention to politics, was one of the few people in the party who understood what I was trying to do. He was my mentor and my rock throughout my time at Parliament. I explained that even though the party hadn’t authorized me to move forward with the data targeting program, we needed to do it. And that meant we needed funding. With Martin’s approval, Jeff agreed to help me raise money without telling the party’s national office about it. We started holding secret events where I could explain to would-be donors that we needed this program if the LPC had any hope of being competitive in the twenty-first century. We did all this on the down-low, persuading people on the ground to put in money while the party staff weren’t paying us any attention. In short order, we raised several hundred thousand Canadian dollars, which was enough to get the program started. Dissatisfied with the national office, the British Columbia wing of the party agreed to be the guinea pigs in our experiment.

尚不清楚这些方法是否可行。在美国，只有两个主要政党，而在加拿大有五个。这意味着，你预测的维度不再是二元的（民主党或共和党），而是多元的（自由党、保守党、新民主党、绿党或魁北克政团）。有了更多的选择，你就会得到许多不同类型的摇摆选民（例如，自由保守党 vs. 自由新民主党 vs. 自由绿党等），他们可以将自己的支持转向多个方向。加拿大和欧洲的消费者数据市场也远不发达，因此美国的许多标准数据集要么不可用，要么必须从多个来源拼凑起来。最后，其他国家的政党通常有严格的捐赠或支出上限。很多人怀疑微目标定位甚至可以在美国以外的地方部署，但我还是想尝试一下。

It was not clear whether any of this would work. In the United States, there are only two major parties, whereas in Canada there are five. This means that the dimensionality of what you are predicting for is no longer binary (Democrat or Republican) but multivariate (Liberal, Conservative, New Democratic Party, Green, or Bloc Québécois). With more options, you get many different kinds of swing voters (e.g., Lib-Con vs. Lib-NDP vs. Lib-Green, etc.) who can float their support around in many directions. There was also a far less developed market for consumer data in Canada and Europe, so many of the standard data sets in the USA either were not available or had to be pieced together from many sources. Finally, parties in other countries often have strict donor or spending caps. A lot of people were skeptical that microtargeting could even be deployed outside of America, but I wanted to try nonetheless.

我打电话给肯·斯特拉斯玛，他曾负责奥巴马 2008 年的选拔活动，问他是否愿意帮助我们在加拿大建立一个项目。斯特拉斯玛在华盛顿特区的团队随后建立了模型。温哥华的卑诗省办事处拼凑了一些有用的数据集，例如旧的民意调查和拉票数据，斯特拉斯玛则研究了如何处理多党政治的额外复杂性。全省各地的志愿者要么获得了这些新的拉票名单来试用，要么获得了旧名单作为对照。结果出来后，卑诗省党的工作人员松了一口气。与许多竞选活动一样，该党使用说服拉票来接触那些尚未决定支持哪个政党的选民。通过比较旧名单的成功转化率（之前犹豫不决的选民宣布支持你的政党）和新的微目标名单的成功转化率，卑诗省行动能够确定新的选拔方法具有更高的转化率。这非常令人兴奋。我们证明了奥巴马在美国取得的成就在世界不同政治体制下也是有可能实现的。但当渥太华的全国性政党发现我们所做的一切时，他们反对这个全国性项目。他们想像奥巴马那样开展竞选活动，但当有人告诉他们如何做时，他们拒绝了。

I called up Ken Strasma, who ran Obama’s targeting operation in 2008, and asked if he’d be willing to help us set up a program in Canada. Strasma’s team in Washington, D.C., then built the models. The B.C. office in Vancouver pieced together useful data sets, such as old polling and canvassing data, and Strasma worked out how to deal with the additional complexities of multi-party politics. Volunteers all over the province were given either these new canvass lists to try out or old lists that would serve as controls. A sigh of relief came to the B.C. party staff as the results came in. As with many campaigns, the party uses persuasion canvasses to reach out to voters who have not yet made up their minds which party they will be supporting. By comparing the successful conversion rates (where a previously undecided voter declares support for your party) of the old lists with those of the new microtargeting lists, the B.C. operation was able to establish that the new targeting approaches had higher conversion rates. It was very exciting. We proved that what Obama accomplished in America would be possible in different political systems around the world. But when the national party in Ottawa found out what we had done, they objected to a national project. They wanted to run campaigns like Obama’s, but when shown how to do it, they refused.

我之所以对政治感兴趣，是因为它似乎是一种改变世界的方式，但经过一年多的苦苦挣扎，我又觉得这有什么意义呢？然后有人介入了。自由党的许多秘书人员来自一群年长的魁北克妇女，她们在政坛待了很长时间，知道政治可以改变一个人。她们带我去渥太华河对岸的法国区加蒂诺吃午饭。点燃香烟后，她们用沙哑的口音说：“听着， 不要变成我们那样的人。”她们告诉我，她们把一生都献给了党，党除了“腰围变粗和几次离婚”之外没有给她们任何回报。“去吧，年轻点，”她们说。“赶快离开这里，否则它会把你困住。”我意识到她们是对的。我才二十岁，就已经面临中年危机了。

I’d been drawn to politics because it seemed like a way to make a difference in the world, but after more than a year of banging my head against the wall, what was the point? Then came an intervention. In the Liberal Party, many of the secretarial staff came from a gaggle of older Québécois ladies, who had been around long enough to see how politics can transform someone. They took me to lunch in Gatineau, the French part of town just across the Ottawa River. After lighting up their cigarettes, they said, in their raspy, accented voices, “Listen, don’t become like us.” They told me they’d given their lives to the party, that the party had given them nothing in return except for “expanded waistlines and several divorces.” “Go, be young,” they said. “Get the hell out of here before it traps you.” And I realized they were right. At just twenty years old, I was already a midlife crisis waiting to happen.

我决定就读伦敦政治经济学院的法律系，因为伦敦离渥太华可能足够远——3300 英里，横跨大西洋 5 个时区。后来我了解到，加拿大自由党的一些领导人有相互冲突的动机。该党仍将其许多广告、咨询和印刷合同授予资深党员或其朋友拥有和经营的公司。一种新的以数据为中心的方法可能意味着党内的“朋友和家人”会失去利益。2011 年，也就是我离开渥太华一年后，自由党在联邦选举中被加拿大保守党击败，保守党在其外来的共和党顾问的要求下投资了复杂的数据系统。自由党有史以来第一次被降级到第三位，在议会中只有 34 个席位。这是一次历史性的失败。

I decided on the law school at the London School of Economics, as London was probably far enough from Ottawa—3,300 miles and five time zones across the Atlantic. I later learned that some of Canada’s party leadership had conflicted motives. The party still awarded many of its advertising, consulting, and printing contracts to firms owned and operated by senior party members or their friends. A new, data-centric approach might mean that “friends and family” in the party would lose out. In 2011, one year after I left Ottawa, the LPC was devastated in the federal election by the Conservative Party of Canada, which had invested in sophisticated data systems at the behest of its imported Republican advisers. For the first time ever, the Liberal Party was relegated to third place, with only thirty-four seats in Parliament. It was an historic defeat.

—

当我开始在伦敦为自由民主党工作时，每周只有几个小时，在伦敦政治经济学院上课期间。但我几乎马上就意识到，与奥巴马竞选团队甚至伦敦自由民主党相比，自由民主党是一个彻头彻尾的烂党派。办公室更像是一个陈旧的古玩店，而不是政治机器的心脏。自由民主党总部的工作人员大多是留着胡子、穿着西装和凉鞋的男士，他们花更多的时间闲聊老辉格党，而不是做任何动员他们的竞选活动的事情。我要求查看他们的数据系统，有人告诉我 EARS，即选举代理人记录系统。“哇，好吧。这看起来……很老派，”我说。“这是 80 年代制作的吗？”这就像要求看图形演示，却被展示那些老乒乓球游戏一样。有人告诉我，其中一个系统是在越南战争期间设计的。

WHEN I BEGAN WORKING for the Liberal Democrats in London, it was for only a few hours a week, in between my classes at LSE. But almost right away I realized that, compared with the Obama campaign or even the LPC, the Lib Dems were a complete train wreck of a party. The office operated more like a stale curiosity shop than the heart of a political machine. The LDHQ staff were mostly bearded men in suits and sandals who spent more time chitchatting about the old Whigs than doing anything to mobilize their campaign. I asked to see their data systems, and someone told me about EARS, which stood for Electoral Agents Record System. “Wow, okay. This looks…old-school,” I said. “Was this made in the eighties?” It was like asking for a graphics demo and being shown one of those old Pong games. Someone told me that one of the systems had been designed during the Vietnam War.

党内许多人很快意识到 VAN 比其他任何系统都更优越，党内最终批准与 VAN 签订合同，建立数据基础设施。但现在我们需要数据——运行法拉利的燃料。这是该项目在加拿大出错的地方，在英国的流程也同样不顺利。英国没有全国选民登记册——一切都由镇议会处理——所以我们必须联系英国各地数百个不同的议会来获取他们的选民数据。我会打电话给西萨默塞特的艾格尼丝，她大概 105 岁了，可能从女性获得选举权以来就一直在管理选民名册，我会问她：“你有登记册的数字副本吗？”她会说没有，因为她一直把记录保存在纸质版上，但我可以在当地市政厅的一本装订好的书中看到一份副本。有时当地官员同意给我们数据，有时则不同意。有时是电子版，有时是 PDF 文件，有时只是一叠纸，需要我们放入光学扫描仪中。Excel 文件通常会通过电子邮件发送，无需密码——因为谁会想窃取选民数据呢？

It soon became clear to many in the party how superior VAN was to anything else available, and the party finally approved a contract with VAN to set up the data infrastructure. But now we needed data—the fuel to run the Ferrari. This was the step where the project had gone wrong in Canada, and the process went no more smoothly in the U.K. There is no national electoral register in the U.K.—it’s all handled by town councils—so we had to approach hundreds of different councils all across Britain to get their voter data. I’d be on the phone to Agnes in West Somerset, who would be like 105 years old and had probably been managing the voter rolls since women got the vote, asking her, “Do you have a digital copy of the register?” No, she’d say, because she kept the records as they’d always been kept, on paper, but I could see a copy in a bound book in the local town hall. Sometimes the local officials agreed to give us the data, sometimes not. Sometimes it was in electronic form, sometimes it was a PDF file, and sometimes it was just reams of paper that we had to feed into an optical scanner. Excel files would usually be emailed without a password—because why would anyone want to steal voter data?

英国的选举制度还停留在 19 世纪 50 年代，我很快发现，自由民主党的策略也是如此。不难理解为什么该党及其前身自由党自二战以来一直连败不休。领导人已经忘记了如何取胜，完全沉迷于散发传单。这些传单被称为“焦点”，通常抱怨地方性的“地方问题”，如路面坑洼或垃圾收集。自由民主党认为这是一种巧妙的方式，可以将他们的信息“悄悄地”植入看起来像地方报纸的东西中。但自由民主党的廉价《真理报》有一个问题：没有人真正读过它。他们心目中的选民是那些周末翻阅邮购目录和政治文献的人——政治工作人员往往对社交一无所知，他们忘记了普通人也有自己的生活。尽管自由民主党是三大政党中规模最小的一个，但它拥有最多的志愿者，因为他们无论晴天雨天都会坚决地向人们分发传单。他们甚至在决定传单内容之前，就已经决定要分发多少传单。

The British electoral system was stuck in the 1850s, and, as I soon found out, so were the Lib Dems’ tactics. It wasn’t hard to understand why the party and its old Liberal Party predecessor had been on a losing streak since World War II. Leaders had lost touch with how to win and were utterly obsessed with handing out leaflets. These leaflets were called “Focus” and usually complained about parochial “local issues” like potholes or rubbish collection. The Lib Dems thought this was a clever way of “slipping in” their messaging to something that looked like a local newspaper. But there was a problem with the Lib Dems’ dollar-store Pravda: no one actually read it. Their idea of a voter was someone who spent their weekends flipping through mail order catalogs and political literature—political staffers are often so socially clueless, they forget that regular people have lives. Despite being the smallest of the three main parties, the Lib Dems had the most volunteers, because they were absolutely militant about shoving leaflets through doors, rain or shine. They would decide how many leaflets to deliver before even deciding what they should say in them.
