在黑客的世界里，“暴力破解”一词指的是随机尝试所有可能的选项，直到找到正确的选项。它不涉及战略制定——只是把所有东西都扔到墙上，看看哪些能粘住。这基本上就是自由民主党所做的，他们花费大量资金散发传单，却没有针对特定的选民。暴力破解是一种不成熟的黑客手段，效率低得可笑，但偶尔也能成功。当然，还有更有效的方法来赢得选举。然而，当我试图提出替代方案，而不是用他们的上层中产阶级宣传材料（包括 MS Word 剪贴画）向选民发送垃圾邮件时，我得到的却是一场关于“自由民主党如何获胜”的讲座，以及 1990 年传说中的伊斯特本补选——这是自 1988 年社会民主党与自由党合并以来，第一位以自由民主党身份获胜的议员的意外胜利——他们显然在这次补选中散发了大量传单。质疑伊斯特本就像是异端邪说。边缘宗教要求顺从，自由民主党也不例外。该党是一个散发传单的邪教组织。

In the world of hacking, the term “brute force” refers to randomly trying every possible option until you hit on the correct one. It doesn’t involve strategizing—it’s simply throwing everything at the wall to see what sticks. That’s essentially what the Lib Dems were doing, spending tons of money on leaflets without targeting particular voters. Brute force is an unsophisticated hack, comically inefficient yet occasionally successful. There were certainly more effective ways to win elections. Yet when I tried to present alternatives to spamming voters with their upper-middle-class propaganda, complete with MS Word clip art, I would get a lecture on “how Lib Dems win” and the fabled Eastbourne by-election, in 1990—the surprise victory of the first MP to win as a Lib Dem since the 1988 SDP-Liberal merger—where they had apparently delivered a lot of leaflets. To question Eastbourne was like heresy. Fringe religions demand conformity, and the Lib Dems were no different. The party was a leafleting cult.

补选是不定期的特别选举，例如投票更换已故的国会议员。自由民主党对此非常痴迷。不知为何，每当该党赢得补选时，党员们就会举起横幅，宣称“自由民主党在这里获胜”，就好像他们征服了英国一样！但作为研究的一部分，我决定记录自 1990 年以来的每一次选举和补选，发现该党输掉了绝大多数选举。“但你们所做的并没有帮助你们获胜。它只会让你输。这是数据，”我告诉他们。“这些都是事实。”

By-elections are irregular special elections, such as a vote to replace a member of Parliament who’s died. The Lib Dems were obsessed with them. For some reason, whenever the party won a by-election, members acted as if they’d conquered Britain with banners that proclaimed LIB DEMS WINNING HERE! But as part of my research, I decided to catalog every election and by-election since 1990 and found that the party had lost the overwhelming majority of them. “But what you are doing doesn’t help you win. It helps you lose. Here is the data,” I told them. “These are facts.”

一些党内领导听了这些，但大多数人似乎很生气。他们有自己的小生意，为党内忠实的选民充当“选举大师”，他们不希望新人走进来告诉他们如何修复他们的制度。这不是一个好兆头。

Some of the party leadership listened, but most just seemed pissed off. They had their own cottage industry of being “election gurus” for the party faithful and weren’t keen on a newcomer strolling in and telling them how to fix their system. This did not bode well.

与此同时，我开始研究我们从 Experian 等数据供应商那里收集到的选民数据。我试验了不同类型的沙盒模型，类似于我在加拿大所做的。但奇怪的事情不断发生。无论我如何设计模型，我都无法建立一个能够可靠地预测自由民主党选民的模型。我可以毫无困难地为保守党或工党做到这一点。住在绿树成荫的乡村小镇的上流社会人士？保守党。住在曼彻斯特的政府住宅区？工党。但自由民主党是这些介于两者之间的怪人，无法用任何简洁的描述来形容。他们中的一些人看起来像工党，一些人看起来像保守党。呃，我遗漏了什么？我想知道是否有潜在变量在起作用。在社会科学中，“潜在变量”是影响结果的因素，但您尚未观察或测量它——一个漂浮在视线之外的隐藏结构。那么这里的隐藏结构是什么？

In the meantime, I started playing around with the voter data we had been able to collect from data vendors like Experian. I experimented with different types of sandbox models, similar to what I’d done in Canada. And something strange kept happening. No matter how I designed the models, I couldn’t build one that reliably predicted Lib Dem voters. I had no trouble doing it for Tories or Labour. Posh dude in some leafy rural township? Tory. Live on a council estate in Manchester? Labour. But Lib Dems were these in-between weirdos who resisted any neat description. Some of them looked Labour-ish and some of them looked Tory-ish. Ugh, what am I missing? I wondered if there was a latent variable at work. In social sciences, a “latent variable” is an element that is influencing a result, but one you haven’t yet observed or measured—a hidden construct that’s floating just out of view. So what is the hidden construct here?

一个问题是，从根本上讲，我无法想象自由民主党的选民。我可以想象保守党，他们——从最普遍的意义上来说——要么是上流社会、富有的唐顿庄园类型，要么是工人阶级、反移民类型。工党选民是北方人、工会成员、议会住宅居民或公共部门类型。但自由民主党是谁？如果我不能想象谁会和我们一起走上这条道路，我就无法想象一条通往胜利的道路。

One problem was that, at a basic level, I couldn’t visualize a Lib Dem voter. I could visualize Tories, who—in the most general sense—were either posh, rich, Downton Abbey types or working-class, anti-immigrant types. Labour voters were northerners, union members, council estate dwellers, or public-sector types. But who were the Lib Dems? I couldn’t imagine a path to victory if I couldn’t imagine who’d be marching with us on that path.

于是，在 2011 年春末，我开始游历英国，以寻找答案。几个月来，我早上去伦敦政治经济学院上课，下午乘火车前往斯肯索普、西布罗姆维奇和斯托昂泽沃尔德等名字好听的地方。我的目的是进行选民访谈和焦点小组讨论，但不是通常的那种。我不会问准备好的、照本宣科的问题，而是进行非结构化的对话，这样人们就可以告诉我他们的生活和对他们来说重要的事情。我本可以直接进行民意调查，但我意识到我提出的任何问题都会受到我（提问者）认为最相关的问题的影响。当然，我会得到我添加到民意调查中的问题的答案，但如果它们是错误的问题怎么办？我去和人们交谈，因为我知道我已经有偏见，并受到我自己经历的影响。我不知道住在纽卡斯尔政府公屋的英国老人和布莱切利三个孩子的单亲妈妈的生活到底是怎样的。我希望他们用自己的语言和方式告诉我他们想让我知道的关于他们的生活。所以我请当地选区政党和民意调查公司帮忙随机挑选一些对象进行采访。

So, in the late spring of 2011, I started traveling around Britain to find out. For several months, I’d go to my classes at LSE in the morning, and then in the afternoon I’d hop on a train to places with delightful names like Scunthorpe and West Bromwich and Stow-on-the-Wold. My intent was to do voter interviews and focus groups, but not the usual kind. Instead of asking prepared, scripted questions, I’d have unstructured conversations, so people could tell me about their lives and what was important to them. I could have jumped directly to polling, but I realized that any questions I asked would be biased by what I, the questioner, thought was the most relevant thing to ask. Sure, I would get answers to the questions I added to the poll, but what if they were the wrong questions? I went to speak to people because I knew I was already biased and colored by my own experiences. I did not know what life was really like for an older British man living on a council estate in Newcastle, or a single mother of three in Bletchley. I wanted them to tell me what they wanted me to know about their lives, in their own words and on their own terms. So I got local constituency parties and polling firms to help randomly select people to speak to.

对于小村庄的焦点小组，通常没有地址。我到达后会被告知，“我们在山上的小屋里开会。只要走过酒吧，穿过那些长满水仙花的田野，过一会儿你就会看到它。”镇上的居民会随机出现，也许当地的酒保克莱夫或绅士农民希林汉姆勋爵会漫步而过。有时我会去村里的酒吧和那里的人聊天。英国人异想天开、细腻，而且聊天通常很有趣，焦点小组让我想起了我在不列颠哥伦比亚省非常喜欢的市政厅。人们会说话，我只是听着并记下他们说的话。

For the focus groups in smaller villages, there were often no addresses. I’d show up and be told, “We’re meeting in the cottage up on the hill. Just walk past the pub, through those fields with the daffodils, and after a while you’ll see it.” Random townspeople would show up, and perhaps Clive the local barman or Lord Hillingham the gentleman farmer would amble by. Sometimes I would just go to the village pub and chat with people there. British people were whimsical, nuanced, and often fun to chat with, and the focus groups reminded me of the town halls I had loved so much back in B.C. People would talk, and I’d just listen and take notes on what they had to say.

在这么多的谈话中，我都是一个人走的，因为党内人士对我所做的事情并不十分感兴趣，但我开始拼凑出自由民主党的随机性。很快我就发现，他们过着如​​此不同的生活。他们是诺福克郡戴着格子呢帽子的农民。他们是肖尔迪奇的艺术潮人。他们是曼布尔斯或兰菲汉格尔-克雷丁的老威尔士妇女。他们是苏荷区的同性恋者。他们是 12 年没有梳头的剑桥教授。自由民主党的选民是一个奇怪的、不拘一格的组合。

Through these many conversations I traveled alone, as the party was not terribly interested in what I was up to, but I started to piece together the randomness of the Liberal Democrats. What quickly became apparent was that they lived so many different lives. They were farmers in Norfolk in tartan hats. Hipsters being artsy in Shoreditch. Old Welsh ladies in the Mumbles or Llanfihangel-y-Creuddyn. Gays in Soho. Professors at Cambridge who hadn’t brushed their hair in twelve years. Lib Dem voters were an odd, eclectic mix.

他们可能看起来各不相同，但我注意到他们确实有一个共同点。工党选民会说“我是工党”。保守党会说“我是保守党”。但自由民主党几乎从来不会说“我是自由民主党”。相反，他们会说“我投票给自由民主党”。这是一个细微但最终重要的区别。我花了一些时间才弄清楚，这可能与该党的历史有关。该党直到 1988 年才正式成立，由两个小党合并而成，这意味着该党当前的许多选民最初来自历史上的保守党或工党家庭。这意味着在他们生命中的某个时刻，他们必须主动决定从旧政党转向这个新政党。对他们来说，支持自由民主党是一种行为，而不是一种身份。

They may have all looked different, but I noticed that they did have one common trait. Labour Party voters would say, “I’m Labour.” And the Conservatives would say, “I’m Tory.” But the Liberal Democrats would almost never say, “I’m Lib Dem.” Instead they would say, “I vote Lib Dem.” This was a slight but ultimately important distinction. It took me some thinking to figure out that it might have to do with the party’s history. The party wasn’t officially formed, in its modern incarnation, until 1988, after the merger of two smaller parties, which meant that many of its current voters originally came from historically Tory or Labour families. This meant that at some point in their lives, they’d had to make an active decision to switch from an old party to this new party. For them, supporting the Lib Dems was an act, not an identity.

—

吸引我去伦敦的人之一是马克·盖特森 (Mark Gettleson)，他很快成为了我最好的朋友之一。我第一次见到盖特森是在德克萨斯州。2007 年，当我刚刚开始在 LPC 工作时，他们派我去达拉斯参加民主党活动，进行社交。我正和数百人在一个大舞厅里闲逛，对所有的斯泰森帽感到惊叹不已，这时我身后一个简短的英国口音说：“你们不是本地人。”我转过身，看到一个穿着森林绿色裤子和印花 Liberty 衬衫的家伙笑得像柴郡猫一样。我漂白的铂金色头发，配上经典的 2000 年代中期刘海，他穿着时髦的服装，我们就像蛾类大会上的两只蝴蝶一样紧密相连。

ONE OF THE PEOPLE who drew me to London was Mark Gettleson, who quickly became one of my best friends. I had first met Gettleson in, of all places, Texas. Back in 2007, when I was just starting out at the LPC, they sent me to a Democratic Party event in Dallas to do some networking. I was milling about with hundreds of people in a giant ballroom, marveling at all the Stetson hats, when a clipped British voice behind me said, “Youuuu are not from here.” I turned around to see a bloke grinning like the Cheshire cat in forest-green trousers and a floral Liberty-print shirt. Between my bleached platinum-blond hair, complete with a classic mid-noughties fringe, and his dandified manner of dress, we were drawn together like two butterflies at a moth convention.

盖特森出生在伦敦波多贝罗路的一个犹太古董商家庭，他举止优雅、性格古怪、做作，说话方式让人想起演员斯蒂芬·弗莱。在其他时代，他可能是十八世纪伦敦沙龙里的花花公子。他博学多识，在谈话中，他可以轻而易举地将 20 世纪 90 年代早期的嘻哈音乐与普法战争联系起来。那天晚上，盖特森和我相处得很融洽，在接下来的几年里，我在美国或英国的各种政治集会上见到了他。在我决定搬到英国后，我们立即开始一起出去玩，有时我们会去一座老教堂下面的改建地下室，他不知怎么把这个地下室变成了一个漂亮的公寓，到处都是奇异的古董微型模型和艺术品，乱糟糟的，但不知怎么的，却很和谐。“我不搞极简主义，克里斯。我是个极繁主义者， ”当我看着他所有的物品时，他会这样说。

The son of a family of Jewish antique dealers on London’s Portobello Road, Gettleson is posh, eccentric, and delightfully camp and speaks with a delivery reminiscent of the actor Stephen Fry. In another time, he would have been a dandy in the salons of eighteenth-century London. He’s a polymath of the highest order. In conversation, he can draw connections between early-1990s hip-hop and the Franco-Prussian War without taking a breath. Gettleson and I vibed that night, and over the next couple of years I’d see him at various political gatherings in America or Britain. After I decided to move to the U.K., we immediately started to hang out, sometimes in the converted crypt underneath an old church that he’d somehow turned into a fabulous flat with bizarre antique miniatures and art lying around everywhere in a chaos that somehow worked. “I don’t do minimalism, Chris. I’m a maximalist,” he would say as I looked through all his objects.

—

我在伦敦过得很滋润，很快就交到了很多朋友。虽然我在伦敦政治经济学院学习法律，在议会工作，但我的朋友大多是一群夜店青年、舞者、皇后、华丽的创意人士和中央圣马丁学院的设计系学生。中央圣马丁学院是世界上最著名的设计和时尚学院之一，曾培养出亚历山大·麦昆、约翰·加利亚诺和斯特拉·麦卡特尼等毕业生。盖特森与众不同之处在于，他和我一样，能无缝地穿梭于所有这些不同的世界。当时，他在宾州、舒恩和伯兰公司伦敦办事处工作，这家著名的民主党民意调查公司最出名的是曾与克林顿夫妇有联系。他是我认识的唯一一个能陪我参加在议会大厦露台亭举行的正式招待会的人，周围都是内阁部长，然后晚上晚些时候，他又和我一起化着浓妆，戴着假发，在 Sink the Pink 华丽舞会上，在一群皇后中翩翩起舞。盖特森很有魅力，我所有的朋友都崇拜他。他既温柔又热情，在晚上外出时，他像牧羊犬牧羊羔一样牧养着年轻人。他们会完全被他自发使用芭比娃娃和角色声音来解释为什么内维尔·张伯伦的绥靖政策失败所吸引——在凌晨4 点……在热闹的家庭聚会的高潮。

I FLOURISHED IN LONDON and quickly gained a wide circle of friends. Although I was studying law at LSE and working at Parliament, most of my friends were a gaggle of club kids, dancers, queens, flamboyant creatives, and design students from Central Saint Martins, one of the world’s preeminent design and fashion schools, which had produced graduates like Alexander McQueen, John Galliano, and Stella McCartney. The thing that was different about Gettleson was that, like me, he seamlessly floated between all these different worlds. At the time, he was working for the London office of Penn, Schoen and Berland, the well-known Democratic polling firm that had most famously once been affiliated with the Clintons. He was the only person I knew who could join me for a formal reception on the Terrace Pavilion at Parliament, surrounded by cabinet ministers, and then end up with me later in the night decked out in makeup, glitter, and wigs, voguing among a heaving cavalcade of queens at a Sink the Pink glam ball. Gettleson was magnetic and all my friends adored him. As gentle as he was exuberant, he shepherded twinks on nights out like a collie shepherds lambs. They would find themselves completely mesmerized by his spontaneous use of Barbie dolls and character voices to explain why Neville Chamberlain’s policy of appeasement failed—at 4 A.M. at the height of a thumping house party.

盖特森也是少数几个能理解我使用数据做什么的人之一。一天下午，当我抱怨自己在构建自由民主党投票行为模型方面遇到的困难时，我告诉他我正考虑向剑桥的几位教授请教。他帮我联系了布伦特·克里克德，他正在剑桥攻读实验心理学博士学位，也许可以介绍我认识那里的一些教授。克里克德不仅仅是剑桥的沟通渠道。和盖特森一样，他也是个花花公子，是那种穿着粗花呢衣服、总是带着干净的佩斯利花纹口袋巾的人。虽然他来自一个富裕的中西部美国家庭，但他说话时却带着一种令人愉快的中大西洋口音，就像他在扮演《卡萨布兰卡》中的角色一样。在决定搬到英国之前，他曾是洛杉矶芭蕾舞团的舞蹈演员。

Gettleson was also one of the few people who understood what I was trying to do with data. One afternoon, as I was complaining about my difficulties in constructing a model for Lib Dems’ voting behavior, I told him I was thinking of asking some Cambridge profs about it. He connected me with Brent Clickard, who was completing his Ph.D. in experimental psychology at Cambridge and might be able to introduce me to some professors there. Clickard turned out to be so much more than simply a conduit to Cambridge. Like Gettleson, he was a dandy, the kind of guy who dresses in tweed and always has a crisp paisley pocket square. Though he came from a wealthy Midwestern American family, he spoke with a delightfully affected mid-Atlantic accent that he somehow picked up, as if he were playing a character in Casablanca. He’d been a dancer with the Los Angeles Ballet before deciding to move to England.

在几次醉酒的谈话中，克里克德建议我更深入地研究性格对投票行为的影响。具体来说，他向我介绍了性格的五因素模型，该模型将性格表示为五个量表上的一组评级：开放性、尽责性、外向性、亲和性和神经质。随着时间的推移和测试，这五个特征的测量已被证明可以有效预测人们生活的许多方面。例如，在尽责性方面得分高的人更有可能在学校表现出色。神经质得分较高的人更容易患上抑郁症。艺术家和创意人士往往在开放性方面得分较高。那些不太开放、更尽责的人往往是共和党人。这听起来很简单，但五大模型可以成为预测选民行为的极其有用的工具。在政治话语中，你会发现许多用来描述候选人、政策或政党的短语都与性格有关。奥巴马竞选时提出了变革、 希望和进步——换句话说，是一个对新思想持开放态度的平台。另一方面，共和党人倾向于注重稳定、 独立和传统——实际上，这是一个尽职尽责的平台。

In the course of several boozy conversations, Clickard suggested I look more deeply into personality as a factor in voting behavior. Specifically, he pointed me to the five-factor model of personality, which represents personality as a set of ratings on five scales: openness, conscientiousness, extraversion, agreeableness, and neuroticism. With time and testing, the measurement of these five traits has proven to be a powerful predictor of many aspects of people’s lives. A person scoring high in conscientiousness, for example, is more likely to do well in school. A person scoring higher in neuroticism is more likely to develop depression. Artists and creative people tend to score high in openness. Those who are less open and more conscientious tend to be Republicans. This sounds simple, but the Big Five model can be an immensely useful tool in predicting voters’ behavior. In political discourse, you find that many of the phrases used to describe candidates, policies, or parties align with personality. Obama ran on change, hope, and progress—in other words, a platform of openness to new ideas. Republicans, on the other hand, tend to focus on stability, independence, and tradition—in effect, a platform of conscientiousness.

半夜在公寓里看书时，我终于意识到了一件事。也许自由民主党没有地理或人口基础；也许他们是心理基础的产物。我进行了一项初步研究，发现自由民主党在“开放性”方面的得分往往高于工党或保守党选民，而在“亲和性”方面的得分则较低。我意识到这些自由民主党人往往像我一样，开放、好奇、古怪、固执，有时还有点暴躁。这就是为什么东伦敦的一位艺术家、剑桥的一位教授和诺福克的一位农民尽管过着截然不同的生活，却都能以自己的方式团结在这个政党周围。

Reading in my flat in the middle of the night, I finally realized something. Maybe the Lib Dems didn’t have a geographic or demographic base; maybe they were a product of a psychological base. I put together a pilot study and found that Lib Dems tended to score higher on “openness” and lower on “agreeableness” than Labour or Tory voters. I realized that these Lib Dems tended to be, like me, open, curious, eccentric, stubborn, and a bit bitchy at times. This is how an artist in East London, a professor at Cambridge, and a farmer in Norfolk could all coalesce around this party in their own way, despite living very different lives.

五因素模型是破解自由民主党密码的关键，最终也为后来的剑桥分析公司提供了核心思想。五因素模型帮助我以一种新的方式理解人们。民意调查员经常谈论单一的选民群体——女性选民、工薪阶层选民、同性恋选民。虽然这些因素对于人们的身份和经历来说无疑是重要的因素，但女性选民、拉丁裔选民或任何其他标签并不存在。想想看：如果你在街上随机抓取一百名女性，她们都是同一个人吗？一百名非裔美国人呢？他们都一样吗？我们真的能根据肤色和阴道说这些人是克隆人吗？他们都有不同的经历、奋斗和梦想。

The five-factor model was the key that cracked the Lib Dems code—and, in the end, provided the central idea behind what became Cambridge Analytica. The five-factor model helped me understand people in a new way. Pollsters often talk about monolithic groups of voters—women voters, working-class voters, gay voters. Although certainly important factors to people’s identities and experiences, there is no such thing as a woman voter or a Latino voter or any of these other labels. Think about it: If you randomly grab a hundred women off the street, will they all be the same person? What about a hundred African Americans? Are they all the same? Can we really say that these people are clones by virtue of their skin color and vaginas? They all have different experiences, struggles, and dreams.

探索身份和性格的细微差别开始帮助我解答为什么尽管政客们一直在做民意调查，但他们似乎仍然脱离实际。这是因为他们的很多民意调查员都脱离了现实。民意调查公司影响政客们对选民身份的看法，而这些看法通常被过分简单化或完全错误。身份从来都不是一个单一的东西；它由许多不同的方面组成。大多数人从来不把自己当作“选民”，更不用说围绕他们的世界观与税收政策的关系来塑造身份。当一个人去购物时，他们不太可能在自我意识清醒的时刻停下来，放下手里的东西，然后在商店中途突然意识到自己其实是摇摆州一个受过大学教育的郊区白人女性。每当我进行焦点小组调查时，人们往往会谈论他们的成长经历、他们的职业、他们的家庭、他们喜欢的音乐、他们讨厌的事情以及他们的个性——这些都是第一次约会时谈论的话题。你能想象如果只允许你问标准的民意调查问题，相亲会有多糟糕吗？是的，就是这样。

Exploring the nuances of identity and personality started to help me unpack why, despite the fact that politicians do polling all the time, they still seem horrendously out of touch. This is because so many of their pollsters are out of touch. Polling firms influence politicians’ ideas of what makes up voter identity, which are usually horrendously oversimplified or just plain wrong. Identity isn’t ever a single thing; it’s made up of many different facets. Most people do not ever think of themselves as a “voter,” let alone curate an identity around how their worldview relates to tax policy. When a person goes grocery shopping, they are unlikely to stop, drop their shopping in a moment of blinding self-awareness, and suddenly realize in the middle of the store that they are, in fact, a university-educated white suburban female in a swing state. Whenever I was doing focus groups, people tended to talk about how they grew up, what they do, their families, what music they like, their pet peeves, and their personality—the kinds of things you talk about on a first date. Can you imagine how terrible a blind date would go if you were allowed to ask only the standard polling questions? Yeah, exactly.

—

2011 年末，我向尼克·克莱格的团队透露，我认为自由民主党已经深陷困境。我解释说，数据显示，自由民主党选民具有意识形态倾向，他们固执己见，讨厌妥协。但当该党与保守党组成联合政府时，它就成为了这些属性的对立面。该党由不妥协的支持者组成，但它却在一个以妥协其原则为基础的政府中运作。这种妥协是对自由民主党选民理想的背叛，它必然会将人们赶出该党。

IN LATE 2011, I broke the news to Nick Clegg’s team that I thought the party was in deep trouble. I explained that the data showed that Lib Dem voters were ideological, they were stubborn, and they hated compromise. But the party had become the antithesis of these attributes when it joined a coalition government with the Tories. The party was composed of uncompromising supporters, and yet it was operating in a government birthed out of compromising its principles. This type of compromise was a betrayal of Lib Dem voters’ ideals, and it was bound to drive people out of the party.

我制作了幻灯片，并在议会一个古老的木板委员会会议室里向自由民主党领导人做了一次演讲。他们被召集在一起听取我的临时更新报告，并很高兴听到这项新技术的发现。但他们的笑容很快就消失了，因为这一切都非常悲观，详细描述了该党战略中的战术缺陷。我制作了一张幻灯片，显示工党和保守党都对投票人口进行了广泛的数据覆盖，这意味着他们记录了每个选民的大量数据，而自由民主党只覆盖了不到 2%。这份报告令人震惊和尴尬，没有人愿意与它有任何关系——或者最终，没有人愿意与我有任何关系。公平地说，我有时会有点直言不讳，而且有惹恼别人的倾向。我有点像 Marmite，一种英国人涂在面包上的咸棕色酵母提取物。人们要么喜欢它，要么讨厌它，但没有人会对 Marmite 感到厌烦。可以说，党内坚定派并不热衷于让某个看起来像实习生的加拿大人大摇大摆地走进来，告诉他们他们做的一切都是错的。

I put together slides and gave a presentation to Lib Dem leaders in an old wood-paneled committee room at Parliament. They’d been called together to hear an interim update on what I was finding and were excited to hear about what all this new technology was discovering. But their smiles quickly evaporated, as it was all very doom-and-gloom, describing in detail the tactical deficiencies in the party’s strategy. I created one slide showing that both Labour and the Tories had extensive data coverage of the voting population, meaning that they had quite a bit of data recorded for each voter, whereas the Lib Dems covered less than 2 percent of it. The report was damning and embarrassing, and no one wanted anything to do with it—or, ultimately, with me. It’s fair to note here that I can be a bit blunt at times and have a tendency to piss people off. I’m a bit like Marmite, the salty brown yeast extract British people smear on toast. People either love it or hate it, but no one is ever blasé about Marmite. Suffice it to say that the party stalwarts were not keen on having some random Canadian who looks like an intern sashaying in and telling them they’re doing everything wrong.

唯一听取我意见的自由民主党人是首席党鞭阿利斯泰尔·卡迈克尔。卡迈克尔是典型的苏格兰人，来自内赫布里底群岛最南端的艾莱岛。卡迈克尔是土生土长的苏格兰人，在学校里讲盖尔语，说话带有苏格兰高地口音，还带有他在担任皇家检察官的早期学到的更“正宗”的爱丁堡口音。他健谈而热情，当我去他的办公室时，他总是邀请我和他一起喝一杯他储藏丰富的酒柜里的威士忌。作为一名政府党鞭，他是一位铁石心肠的政治阴谋家，他随和的举止掩盖了对权力杠杆的深刻理解。作为首席党鞭，他见多识广，所以我向他寻求建议，如何摆脱我在党内所经历的僵局。我总是觉得我可以坦率地和卡迈克尔说话，作为一个敢于直言的人，他尊重我的想法。他试图说服党内工作人员听取我的意见，但不幸的是没有成功。

The one Lib Dem who listened was the chief whip, Alistair Carmichael. Carmichael is as Scottish as they come, hailing from Islay, the southernmost island of the Inner Hebrides. A native Scot who grew up speaking Gaelic in school, Carmichael talks with a Highlander brogue mixed with a more “proper” Edinburgh accent he picked up in his early years as a crown prosecutor. He is chatty and warm, and when I visited his office, he always invited me to join him in a tipple of whisky from his well-stocked cabinet. As a government whip, he was a hardened political machinator whose easy manner belied a profound understanding of the levers of power. His position as chief whip meant he’d seen and heard everything, so I turned to him for advice on how to move beyond the impasse I was experiencing in the party. I always felt like I could speak frankly to Carmichael, which he, as a man who did not have a fear of speaking his mind, respected. And he tried, unfortunately to little avail, to persuade the party staff to heed what I was saying.

所有这些都令人沮丧不已。我向他们展示了数据，并辅以同行评议的文献。我向他们展示了科学。而他们却说我悲观、有问题、不善于团队合作。最后一根稻草是，有人泄露了我的幻灯片，显然是想让我难堪。结果适得其反，一位记者赞同我的论点，指出自由民主党遭受“严重的传单问题”，在数据收集和研究方面远远落后于保守党和工党。当你花费大量时间研究选民并出去与他们会面时，你会与他们越来越亲近。我觉得我的工作不仅仅是赢得选举；它还涉及了解人们的真实生活。它是关于向当权者表达和重申被贫穷、无知或顺从所困的感受。

All of this was beyond frustrating. I was showing them data, supplemented by peer-reviewed literature. I was showing them science. And they were responding by calling me pessimistic, problematic, not a team player. The last straw came when someone leaked my slides, apparently in an attempt to embarrass me. It backfired when a journalist wrote approvingly of my arguments, noting that the Lib Dems suffered from “the great leafletting problem” and were far behind the Tories and Labour in data collection and research. When you spend so much time researching voters and going out and meeting them, you grow more and more connected to them. I felt like my work was not just about winning an election; it was also about understanding what the lives of people were really like. It was about expressing and reiterating to those in power what it was like to be trapped by poverty, ignorance, or conformity.

两年后，即 2014 年，自由民主党失去了 310 个议会席位，并失去了 12 个欧洲议会席位中的 1 个。2015 年 5 月，该党遭遇了致命一击，失去了 57 个议会席位中的 49 个。由于只有 8 名自由民主党议员连任，他们的整个议会党团成员可以舒适地塞进一辆马自达 Bongo 露营车里。

Two years later, in 2014, the Liberal Democrats lost 310 council seats and all but one of their twelve seats in the European Parliament. The coup de grâce then came in May 2015, when the party was eviscerated, losing forty-nine of its fifty-seven seats in Parliament. With only eight Lib Dem MPs being reelected, their entire parliamentary caucus could have comfortably fit into a Mazda Bongo camper van.

第3章

CHAPTER 3

我们在普拉达打击恐怖主义

WE FIGHT TERROR IN PRADA

-

伦敦的梅菲尔区是一个财富与权力的聚集地，有着帝国的厚爱。走在老街上，可以看到数十块蓝色的圆形匾额遍布在建筑上，纪念着曾经居住在这里的一些著名剧作家、作家、政治家和建筑师。圣詹姆斯广场坐落在梅菲尔区的东南角，距离唐宁街 10 号不远，广场两旁排列着古老的乔治亚式联排别墅。广场北端是查塔姆研究所，皇家国际事务研究所所在地。广场东端是世界上最大的石油公司之一英国石油公司（BP）的总部，以及诺福克大厦，二战期间美国将军艾森豪威尔和盟军远征军最高司令部的办公室就在这里。广场上分布着几家私人俱乐部，包括殖民时代的东印度俱乐部和陆军和海军俱乐部。广场中央是一个小花园，四周环绕着装饰性铁栅栏。公园中央矗立着威廉三世骑马雕像，面朝建筑物。中心花园周围环绕着灌木丛和修剪整齐的花坛。圣詹姆斯广场是英国殖民主义全球统治的活生生的纪念碑。

London’s Mayfair neighborhood is a place of exceptional wealth and power, with an unabashed legacy of empire. Walking down its old streets, one can see dozens of blue circular plaques dotting the buildings, commemorating the famous playwrights, authors, politicians, and architects who once inhabited this place. Sitting in Mayfair’s southeastern corner, not far from 10 Downing Street, is St. James’s Square, which is lined with grand old Georgian row houses. On the square’s north end sits Chatham House, the location of the Royal Institute of International Affairs. On the east end sits the headquarters of British Petroleum, or BP, one of the largest oil companies in the world, and Norfolk House, which during World War II served as the offices for U.S. general Dwight D. Eisenhower and the Supreme Headquarters Allied Expeditionary Force. Several private clubs dot the square, including the colonial-era East India Club and the Army and Navy Club. At the center of the square is a small garden encircled by sections of decorative iron fencing. And standing in the middle of the park is an equestrian statue of William III looking out toward the buildings. The center garden is surrounded by shrubbery and tidily groomed flower beds. St. James’s Square is a living monument to the global dominance of British colonialism.

BP 南侧广场东端有一栋建于 1770 年的几层楼高的建筑。它由光滑的灰色砂岩建成，配以亚麻色砖块，入口两侧有一对石制爱奥尼亚柱。外面立着一个红色的皇家邮政邮箱。2013 年初，这里是 SCL 集团的总部。该公司最初名为战略通信实验室，由奈杰尔·奥克斯领导，自 1990 年以来以各种形式存在。SCL 经英国政府批准可以访问“机密”级信息，其董事会成员包括撒切尔时代的前内阁部长和退休军事指挥官，以及教授和外国政客。该公司主要为军队工作，在世界各地开展心理和影响行动，例如巴基斯坦的圣战招募缓解、南苏丹的战斗人员解除武装和复员以及拉丁美洲的禁毒和打击人口贩运行动。

South of BP, on the east end of the square, there is a building, several stories high, that dates to 1770. It’s built of smooth gray sandstone, with flaxen brick and a pair of stone Ionic pillars that flank the entrance. A red Royal Mail postbox stands outside. This, in early 2013, was the headquarters of the SCL Group. Originally known as Strategic Communication Laboratories, the firm was led by Nigel Oakes and had existed in various forms since 1990. SCL was cleared by the British government to access “Secret”-level information, and its board included Thatcher-era former cabinet ministers and retired military commanders, as well as professors and foreign politicians. The firm worked primarily for militaries, conducting psychological and influence operations around the world, such as jihadist recruitment mitigation in Pakistan, combatant disarmament and demobilization in South Sudan, and counternarcotics and counter–human trafficking operations in Latin America.

2013 年春天，我离开自由民主党几个月后，我听说了这家公司。当时，一位与我一直保持联系的党内顾问打电话告诉我有空缺职位。他说他之所以想到我，是因为这家公司正在寻找“涉及军方的行为研究项目的数据人员”。我从未想过要从事国防项目，但在加拿大和英国的政党工作两次失败后，我准备尝试一些新的东西。

I heard about them in the spring of 2013, a few months after I left the Liberal Democrats, when a party adviser I kept in touch with called to tell me about an opening. He said he thought of me because this firm was looking for “data people for some behavior research project” involving the military. It never occurred to me to work on defense projects, but after two failures with political parties, in both Canada and Britain, I was ready to try something new.

我从前门走进去，进入了大厅，大厅里铺着黑白格纹大理石地板，挂着水晶吊灯，奶油色墙壁上装饰着华丽的石膏流苏。办公室保留了大楼的许多原始细节，几个房间围绕着一个大理石壁炉。地板上铺着紧密编织的绿色地毯，上面有红白相间的圆形小褶边。然后我被带到一个小房间，被告知要在那里等候一个名叫亚历山大·尼克斯的人，他是 SCL 集团的董事之一。我记得当时非常热，好像暖气开得很大，尽管当时是春末。（我后来才知道，这么热是故意的——这是一种在开会前调侃别人的方式。）我坐在那个狭小的汗蒸室里大约十分钟，直到一个男人进来。我注意到的第一件事是他那套剪裁完美的萨维尔街西装，衬衫上绣着他的名字首字母。他的眼睛是蓝宝石色的，与他苍白如纸的皮肤形成鲜明对比。

Walking in through the front door, I entered a lobby with checked black-and-white marble floors, a crystal chandelier, and ornate plaster fringes on the cream-colored walls. The offices have kept many of the original details of the building, with several rooms centered around a marble fireplace. Tightly woven green carpets with tiny red-and-white circular frills lined the floors. I was then shown to a small room where I was told to wait for a man named Alexander Nix, who was one of the directors of the SCL Group. I remember it being exceptionally hot, as if the heating had been left on high even though it was late spring. (I learned later that the heat was intentional—a way to mess with people before a meeting.) I sat in that tiny sweatbox of a room for about ten minutes, until a man entered. The first thing I noticed was his impeccably tailored Savile Row suit, over a shirt embroidered with his initials. His eyes were sapphire, in striking contrast to his pale, paperlike skin.

这是我结识亚历山大·尼克斯的完美场合。他出生于英国上流社会，就读于伊顿公学。皇室子女就读伊顿公学，其制服上仍保留着领子和燕尾服。大多数英国贵族都带有一种做作的气质，尼克斯也继承了这一传统。他的口音非常浓重。他戴着黑框眼镜，松软的草莓金色头发故意随意地卷曲着。他邀请我坐在一堆纸和盒子中间——他告诉我，这些都是最近完成的项目留下的残渣。他们计划很快搬到更大的办公室。

It was the perfect setting for my introduction to Alexander Nix, who was born into the British upper classes and schooled at Eton, an institution where the royals send their children and whose uniform still includes collars and tails. Most English aristocrats have an air of camp to them, and in this tradition, Nix did not disappoint. His accent was as rich as they come. He wore black-rimmed glasses, and his floppy strawberry-blond hair had a deliberately casual little flip to it. He invited me to sit down amid piles of paper and boxes—detritus from a recently finished project, he told me. They planned to move soon to a larger office.

没过多久，尼克斯就开始向我介绍 SCL 的业务细节。他让我签署了一份保密协议，然后告诉我，该公司的大部分工作都是为军事和情报机构服务，这些项目是政府无法正式承担的。“我们在那里赢得了人心……你知道，不管怎样。”他指着一张相框里的照片，照片上是一个似乎是非洲某个国家的集会。

It didn’t take long before Nix was describing the ins and outs of SCL’s business. He got me to sign an NDA and proceeded to tell me that most of the firm’s work was for military and intelligence agencies, on projects that governments couldn’t officially undertake themselves. “We win hearts and minds over there…you know, however that needs to happen.” He pointed to a framed photo of a rally in what appeared to be a country somewhere in Africa.

当我询问细节时，他拿出了几份报告。当我翻阅这些报告时，他开始解释 TAA，即目标受众分析。他说，这是信息运营项目的第一步——分析和细分。但当我浏览这些报告时，我简直不敢相信这种方法竟如此粗糙——我毫不避讳地说出来。

When I asked for details, he produced a few reports. As I flipped through them, he started to explain TAA, or target audience analysis. This is the first step in an information operations project, he said—analysis and segmentation. But as I skimmed the reports, I couldn’t believe how crude the methodology was—and I wasn’t shy about saying so.

“这可以做得更好，”我告诉他。我很快就知道，尼克斯可能会在向他天生的优越感发出挑战的那一刻发脾气。现在，他只是怒发冲冠。

“This could be done so much better,” I told him. As I’d soon learn, Nix could lose his temper in the moment it took to register a challenge to his inborn sense of superiority. For now, he merely bristled.

他说：“我们是这方面做得最好的公司。”

“We,” he said, “are the best firm at doing this.”

“当然，”我说，“但你们可以做得更好。看起来军队实际上是在从飞机上撒传单。如果军队有激光制导导弹，为什么你们要这样宣传呢？”这是一个严厉的回答——尤其是在一次潜在的工作面试中——尼克斯大吃一惊。他似乎在想，我才是说话的人。谈话突然结束，当我走出去时，我想，真是浪费时间。

“Sure,” I said, “but you could be doing a lot better job of targeting. It looks like the army is literally dumping leaflets out of a plane. If the army has laser-guided missiles, why are you doing this with propaganda?” It was a harsh response—especially in a potential job interview—and Nix was taken aback. I’m the one who does the talking, he seemed to be thinking. The conversation ended abruptly, and as I headed out, I thought, What a massive waste of time.

但事实并非如此。尼克斯很快就打电话问我是否愿意再聊一会儿，解释一下我认为 SCL 做错了什么以及他们可能会如何解决。

But it wasn’t. Nix called soon after to ask if I’d be willing to talk some more, to explain what I thought SCL was doing wrong and how they might fix it.

—

心理战的世界自人类开始发动战争以来就一直存在，SCL 就是其中的一员。公元前六世纪，波斯阿契美尼德王朝的波斯人知道埃及人崇拜猫神巴斯特，于是在盾牌上画上猫的图案，这样埃及人就不会在战斗中瞄准它们。亚历山大大帝并没有简单地摧毁和掠夺敌方城市，而是采取了积极的心理战术，留下军队传播希腊文化，将战败者融入他的庞大帝国。在中世纪，帖木儿和成吉思汗将恐怖作为心理武器，斩首敌人，并将他们的头颅挂在长矛上游行。在俄罗斯，伊凡雷帝在红场上架起巨型煎锅，将敌人活活烤死，以此恐吓民众，迫使他们屈服。第二次世界大战期间，英国人通过假入侵、使用假坦克，甚至在名为“肉馅行动”的奇异行动中将假作战计划植入装扮成阵亡士兵的尸体，从而完美地误导敌人。精心设计的信息和虚假信息的使用是获得战场战术优势的最有效方法之一。

THE WORLD OF PSYCHOLOGICAL warfare of which SCL was a part has been around for as long as humans have waged war. In the sixth century B.C., Persians of the Achaemenid, knowing that Egyptians worshipped the cat god Bastet, drew images of cats on their shields so the Egyptians would be reluctant to take aim at them in battle. Rather than simply destroy and pillage enemy cities, Alexander the Great used positive psychological tactics, leaving troops behind to spread Greek culture and assimilate the defeated into his vast empire. During the Middle Ages, Tamerlane and Genghis Khan used terror as a psychological weapon, decapitating foes and parading their severed heads around on pikes. And in Russia, Ivan the Terrible cowed the masses into submission by setting up giant frying pans on Red Square and roasting his enemies alive. During World War II, the British perfected the art of misdirecting the enemy by staging fake invasions, using dummy tanks, and even planting fake battle plans on a corpse dressed as a dead soldier in the fantastically named Operation Mincemeat. The well-designed use of information—and disinformation—is one of the most effective ways of gaining tactical advantage on the battlefield.

在设计信息武器时，考虑任何武器系统的基本方面会很有帮助：有效载荷、运载系统和瞄准系统。对于导弹来说，有效载荷是炸药，运载系统是火箭推进的机身，瞄准系统是卫星或热寻的激光器。对于信息武器，它们具有相同的组成部分。但有一个关键的区别：你使用的力量是非动能的。换句话说，你不会炸毁东西。在信息作战中，有效载荷通常是一个故事——一个用来欺骗将军的谣言或一个旨在平息村庄的文化叙事。而且，正如军方投资化学来指导炸弹制造一样，它也会试图研究哪种叙事会产生最大影响。

In devising an informational weapon, it’s helpful to think of the basic aspects of any weapon system: the payload, delivery system, and targeting system. For a missile, the payload is an explosive, the delivery system is a rocket-propelled fuselage, and the targeting system is a satellite or a heat-seeking laser. With informational weapons, the same components are present. But there is one key difference: The force you are using is non-kinetic. In other words, you don’t blow stuff up. In informational combat, the payload is often a story—a rumor deployed to trick a general or a cultural narrative intended to pacify a village. And just as the military invests in chemistry to inform bomb building, it also tries to research what kinds of narratives will yield the biggest impact.

从历史上看，美国领导人低估了信息作战，因为美国在导弹、坦克、轰炸机、舰船和枪支方面拥有巨大优势。美国已经开展了一些信息作战，尽管大多数都是古老的纸质传单。在朝鲜战争中，美军使用扩音器进行宣传，而飞机则在敌方防线上散布传单。在越南战争期间，专门的心理战营策划了类似的宣传攻势，旨在赢得尽可能多的“民心”。但在无与伦比的国防预算的支持下，美国军队已成为一群拿着玩具的男孩，其力量放大是物理和动能的。

Historically, U.S. leaders have undervalued information operations, thanks to a robust advantage in missiles, tanks, bombers, ships, and guns. The United States has undertaken some information operations, though mostly of the age-old paper-leafletting variety. In the Korean War, U.S. troops used loudspeakers to blare propaganda, while aircraft scattered leaflets across enemy lines. During the Vietnam War, specialized PSYOPS battalions planned similar propaganda blitzes, aiming to win as many of the “hearts and minds” as possible. But bolstered by an unmatched defense budget, the American military has become a gang of boys with toys, where force amplification is physical and kinetic.

坦克和掩体炸弹在病毒式宣传和网络极端主义的面前毫无作用。ISIS 不仅发射导弹，还会散布谣言。俄罗斯用“混合攻击方式”弥补其老化的军事装备，首先是对目标人群进行意识形态操纵。恐怖组织利用社交媒体招募新成员，然后使用枪支和炸弹实现其目的。这些威胁并不因为非传统而变得不那么危险，西方国家对此难以应对。你无法向互联网发射导弹，而传统的美国军事文化由喜欢发号施令的异性恋白人男性主导，对可能引入更微妙、技术增强的反击的不守规矩的新兵怀有敌意。

Tanks and bunker busters are useless against viral propaganda and Web-fueled radicalization. ISIS doesn’t just launch missiles; it also launches narratives. Russia compensates for its aging military equipment with “hybrid approaches” of attack, beginning with the ideological manipulation of target populations. Terror groups use social media to recruit new members, who then use guns and bombs to achieve their ends. These threats are no less dangerous for being nonconventional, and Western powers have struggled to respond. You can’t shoot a missile at the Internet, and traditional American military culture, dominated by straight white men who like to give and take orders, is hostile to the kind of nonconformist recruit who might introduce more nuanced, tech-enhanced counterattacks.

美国军方的国防高级研究计划局 (DARPA) 一直试图应对这些新的恐怖和冲突现实。DARPA 过去开展的项目（如“叙事网络”和“战略传播中的社交媒体”）的既定目标之一是“尝试追踪思想和概念以分析模式和文化叙事”和“开发定量分析工具来研究叙事及其对安全环境中人类行为的影响”。美国军方还开展了一项名为“人类社会文化行为建模计划”的项目，旨在创建“用于现场用户进行社会文化分析和预测的工具”。换句话说，许多此类计划的目的是获得针对威胁的完全 信息不对称——获得如此多的数据，以便我们能够完全压倒并控制目标周围的信息空间。这是尼克斯瞄准的利润丰厚的利基市场，他希望以此赢得 SCL 的新合同。

The U.S. military’s Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) has tried to grapple with these new realities of terror and conflict. Among the stated goals of past DARPA-run programs—with names like Narrative Networks and Social Media in Strategic Communications—has been to “attempt to track ideas and concepts to analyze patterns and cultural narratives” and “develop quantitative analytic tools to study narratives and their effects on human behavior in security contexts.” The U.S. military also ran a program called the Human Social Culture Behavior Modeling Program, which aimed to create “tools for sociocultural analysis and forecasting to users in the field.” In other words, the point of many of these programs is to gain total informational asymmetry against threats—to have so much data that we would be able to completely overwhelm and dominate the information space surrounding our targets. This was the lucrative niche Nix had his eye on to win new contracts for SCL.

—

NIX 最初为我提供了一份为期三个月的合同，基本上可以做任何我想做的事情。“我甚至不打算写一份工作描述，”他说。“因为坦率地说，我不知道我会写些什么。”在经历了与 LPC 和自由民主党打交道的痛苦之后，能够自由发挥对我来说非常诱人。所以在 2013 年 6 月，我开始与 SCL 合作。

NIX INITIALLY OFFERED ME a three-month contract to do, essentially, whatever I wanted. “I’m not even going to create a job description,” he said. “Because, frankly, I don’t know what I would put in it.” After all the agonies of dealing with the LPC and the Lib Dems, it was incredibly enticing to be given free rein. So in June 2013, I started working with SCL.

和大多数人一样，我从未关注过军事战略，除了偶尔在午夜狂看历史频道。由于学习难度很大，我需要快速了解公司当前的项目。问题是什么？没人回答我的问题。事实上，我的新同事们都懒得关上笔记本电脑。他们会说：“你为什么需要知道？”或者“我需要确认一下是否可以和你谈谈这件事。”这种保密性将使我很难弄清楚我应该做什么。当我向尼克斯抱怨这件事时，他故意翻了个白眼，然后把办公室柜子的钥匙递给我。在里面我发现了旧报告的活页夹。

Like most people, I had never paid much attention to military strategy, save for the occasional midnight binge watch of the History Channel. With such a daunting learning curve, I needed to quickly get up to speed on the firm’s current projects. The problem? No one would answer my questions. In fact, my new colleagues couldn’t close their laptops fast enough. “Why do you need to know?” they’d say, or “I need to check on whether I can talk to you about that.” The secrecy was going to make it difficult to figure out how to do whatever I was supposed to be doing. When I complained about this to Nix, he elaborately rolled his eyes and simply handed me the keys to a cabinet in his office. Inside I found binders of old reports.

这些文件描述了 SCL 为其老客户（包括英国国防部和美国政府）开展的项目。它正在东欧为北约开展反俄宣传活动。其中一个项目是拉丁美洲国家的禁毒计划，军事客户在那里传播虚假信息，让当地古柯种植者反抗毒枭。其他项目详细介绍了墨西哥和肯尼亚的心理战计划。正如尼克斯之前所说，这些是政府机构不想正式承担的项目。相反，他们会雇佣承包商以“市场研究公司”或某种虚假商业掩护的身份进入该地区。

The documents described projects SCL had undertaken for its old clients, which included the British Ministry of Defence and the U.S. government. It was working in Eastern Europe for NATO on counter–Russian propaganda initiatives. One was for a counter-narcotics program in a Latin American country, where a military client spread disinformation to turn local coca farmers against drug lords. Others detailed PSYOPS programs in Mexico and Kenya. As Nix had said before, these were projects that government agencies did not want to officially undertake themselves. Rather, they would hire contractors to enter the region as a “market research firm” or under some kind of faux-business cover.

一份引起我注意的报告描述了国防部的一个项目，该项目利用信息行动来影响巴基斯坦的不同目标群体。该报告收集了有关地区领导人和影响者的信息，并为每个目标受众提出了文化接触点和可能的激励因素的建议。但这种方法漏洞百出。SCL 曾尝试使用现场调查员在各地区进行民意调查，但他们使用的农村地图不完整，而且对这些新来者征求意见持怀疑态度的人的回复率很低。这导致数据太不完整或有偏见，不可靠。国防部为此支付了巨额费用，而如果他们只是雇佣几个当地人去村庄询问问题，他们就会得到更好的信息。

One report that caught my eye described a Ministry of Defence project for using information operations to influence different target groups in Pakistan. The report captured information about regional leaders and influencers and made suggestions for cultural touch points and possible motivators for each target audience. But the methodology was full of holes. SCL had attempted to do polling in regions using live enumerators, but the maps of rural areas they had used were incomplete, and response rates were low from people skeptical of these newcomers asking for their opinions. This produced data too incomplete or biased to be reliable. The MOD had paid some ludicrously huge sum for this, when they’d have gotten better information if they’d just hired a few locals to go into villages and ask questions.

第二个问题是军方选择传播宣传的方式。在一些项目中，他们制作传单，然后将其投放到整个地区。更多的该死的传单？英国军队就像自由民主党一样。当全国范围内的移动电话网络不断扩大时，为什么会这样做呢？事实上，有趣的是，这些国家中的一些国家即使在冲突期间也保持着联系。没有固定电话或广播电视的地区正在建造手机信号塔。我不明白为什么西方国家会忽视这一发展。

The second problem was the way the military had chosen to disseminate its propaganda. In some projects, they had created leaflets, then dropped them all over a region. More goddamn leaflets? The British Army was just like the Lib Dems. And why, exactly, when there were expanding mobile phone networks throughout the country? Indeed, it was interesting how connected some of these countries were, even amid conflict. Regions without landline telephones or broadcast TV were building cell towers. I couldn’t understand why Western powers were ignoring this development.

更重要的是，我想帮助尼克斯理解，如果你要做的只是把你的信息从天上掉下来，那么一层花哨的心理分析完全是浪费。我告诉他，如果 SCL 的项目专注于获取更准确的数据、构建算法、根据这些算法针对特定人群，并使用不同于传单或广播的媒体形式，那么它们的效率会高得多。尼克斯若有所思地听着，他双手合十，反复敲着嘴，思考着我所说的话。

More to the point, I wanted to help Nix understand that a fancy layer of psychological analysis is a complete waste if all you’re going to do is dump your info out of the sky. I told him that SCL’s projects would be far more effective if they focused on getting more accurate data, building algorithms, targeting specific people based on those algorithms, and using different forms of media than a leaflet or radio. Nix listened pensively, his steepled hands repeatedly tapping his mouth as he thought about what I was saying.

我也开始意识到为什么英国和美国军队在赢得民心方面如此糟糕。这些关于当地民众的文化和态度信息都是各自为政，通常是在承包商主导的辅助项目中收集的，这些项目直到主要目标确定后才被纳入军事战略——换句话说，当地民众的文化和经历是规划者事后才考虑的事情，人员和设备的重要性高于一切。这种情况需要改变。

I also started to realize why the British and American militaries were so bad at winning the proverbial hearts and minds. This cultural and attitudinal information about the population was gathered in silos, often in contractor-led ancillary projects that were not integrated into military strategy until after primary objectives were set—in other words, the culture and experiences of local populations were an afterthought for planners, trumped by personnel and equipment. That needed to change.

—

当我思考DARPA 及其英国同行国防科学技术实验室 (DSTL) 试图通过其新的社交网络和数字研究项目开展什么时，我的思绪转到了一个出乎意料但并不陌生的地方：时尚。这两个领域并不像看上去那么不同。当一个社会陷入极端主义时，它的时尚也会随之而来。想想毛派、纳粹、三K党成员和圣战分子——他们有什么共同点？外表。极端主义始于人们的外表和社会的感受。有时，它会创造出真正的制服：带有红星的橄榄色束腰外衣和帽子、红色臂章、白色尖头兜帽、马球衫和提基火炬、MAGA 帽子。反过来，这些制服融入了穿着者的身份，将他们的思维从“这是我所相信的”转变为“这就是我”。极端主义运动之所以会抓住美学不放，是因为极端主义很大程度上就是为了改变社会的美学。很多时候，极端主义所承诺的并不是任何切实的政策，而是一个地方或文化的新面貌和新感觉。

AS I PONDERED WHAT DARPA and its British equivalent, the Defence Science and Technology Laboratory (DSTL), were trying to develop with their new social network and digital research programs, my mind wandered to an unexpected but not unfamiliar place for me: fashion. The two fields are not as disparate as it might seem. When a society jerks into extremism, so does its fashion. Think about Maoists, Nazis, Klansmen, and jihadists—what do they all have in common? A look. Extremism starts with how people look and how society feels. Sometimes it creates literal uniforms: Olive tunics and caps with red stars, red armbands, white pointed hoods, polo shirts and tiki torches, MAGA hats. These uniforms, in turn, are incorporated into the wearer’s identity, transforming their thinking from This is what I believe into This is who I am. Extremist movements latch on to aesthetics because so much of extremism is about changing the aesthetics of society. Oftentimes much of what is promised is not about any tangible policies, but rather a new look and feel for a place or culture.

十六岁那年，有一天我把头发染成了深紫色。选择这种颜色并没有什么特别的原因，只是因为它很吸引人而且我喜欢它。但同时，我也因为违反学校的着装规定被校长办公室开除。我一点也不生气或害怕，反而非常放松。最后，我和校长谈了“残疾人便利”以外的其他事情。他们告诉我，我需要把头发改回“正常”的颜色。我拒绝了。校长很不高兴，我的头发问题一直持续到我离开学校。当我还在使用轮椅时，我花了很多时间考虑如何穿得合身——如何进门、如何融入同龄人、如何找到合身的衣服。我对电脑很感兴趣，但时尚也成为了我的另一爱好，原因不止一个。这在一定程度上是为了融入其中。但也是为了被人看到。当我坐在齐腰处，注视着同学衣服上的纽扣、切口、褶皱、凸起和褶皱时，我感觉自己在他们眼中是隐形的。有了紫色的头发，我才被人看见。然后，当校长要求我恢复“正常”的头发时，他命令我再次变得隐形。那时我才明白外表的力量和揭示力。

When I was sixteen, I dyed my hair one day to a mulberry shade of purple. There was no particular reason for choosing the color aside from the fact it was eye-catching and I liked it. It also landed me in the principal’s office, for violating the school dress code. Far from being upset or intimidated, I was totally at ease. Finally, I was talking to the principal about something other than “disability accommodations.” I was told that I needed to change my hair back to a “normal” color. I refused. The principal was not happy, and the tension over my hair persisted until I left school. When I was still using a wheelchair, I spent a lot of time thinking about fit—fitting through doors, fitting in with my peers, finding clothes that fit. Computers were one passion, but fashion became another, for more than one reason. It was partly about feeling included. But it was also about being seen. As I sat at waist level, noticing the buttons, the cuts, the creases, the bulges, and the folds in the clothes of classmates, I felt invisible to them. With purple hair, I was seen. And then, when the principal asked that I go back to “normal” hair, he was ordering me to become invisible again. That was when I understood how powerful—and revealing—a look can be.

当我为自由民主党研究五因素人格模型时，我开始更深入地思考人格作为一种构造。我意识到，政治和时尚建立在同一基础上，它们都基于人们如何看待自己与他人的关系这一微妙构造。时尚是了解个性的理想窗口，因为选择穿什么（或不穿什么）是我们每天都要做出的决定。所有文化中的人都会选择如何装饰自己的身体，从平凡到奢华。我们都关心自己穿什么——即使是明尼苏达州的直率老人，他从不穿灰色 T 恤和牛仔裤。他认为他不在乎衣服穿起来怎么样，直到你给他一件和服或一件达西基。

As I worked with the five-factor model of personality for the Lib Dems, I started to think more deeply about personality as a construct. Politics and fashion were built on the same foundation, I realized, in that they were both based on nuanced constructs of how people see themselves in relation to others. Fashion is an ideal window into personality, as choosing what to wear (or not) is a decision we all make on a daily basis. People in all cultures make choices about how to adorn their bodies, from the mundane to the extravagant. We all care about what we wear—even the straight old man from Minnesota who never wears anything but a gray T-shirt and jeans. He doesn’t think he cares about how his clothes look, until you offer him a kimono or a dashiki.

我清楚地记得我与伦敦政治经济学院的大学导师的最后一次会面，当时他问我下一步打算做什么。毫无疑问，他以为我会继续从政，或者申请一家高级企业律师事务所。但我告诉他我要去时装学校。沉默。他扬起眉毛，显然很失望，下意识地摇了摇头。时尚？衣服？你真的想学衣服？但对我来说，时尚和政治本质上都是关于文化和身份的循环。在我看来，它们本质上是同一种现象的两种表现形式——这一信念将成为我们在剑桥分析公司创造的核心。

I distinctly remember the final meeting I had with my university tutor at LSE, when he asked what I planned to do next. No doubt he expected to hear that I was continuing in politics or applying to a fancy corporate law firm. Instead I told him I was going to fashion school. Silence. Eyebrows raised and clearly disappointed, he unconsciously shook his head. Fashion? As in clothes? You really want to study clothes? But to me, fashion and politics are both, at their core, about cycles of culture and identity. To my mind, they’re essentially two manifestations of the same phenomenon—a conviction that would become central to what we created at Cambridge Analytica.

时尚一直在我生活中扮演着重要的角色，它确实让我对自己更加满意。当我离开学校搬到蒙特利尔时，我越来越多地离开轮椅，但那种不吸引人或不受欢迎的感觉一直伴随着我。一个周末，我在一家古董书店闲逛，在一堆旧杂志中发现了一本破旧的九年前的《Dazed & Confused》。这是 1998 年的一期，封面上写着“时尚可行？”，上面画着一个装着两条假肢的模特。这是 Alexander McQueen 的客座编辑，里面是一些精彩的照片，照片中的身材看起来各不相同，但都很美丽。看完那一期后，我开始尝试穿衣服，也更多地外出。蒙特利尔是那种如果你愿意的话会改变你的地方。我发现自己被变装酒吧吸引，欣赏一种既华丽又奢华的服装形式，同时嘲讽和颠覆了人们对美丽、身体和性别的传统观念。变装颠覆了我的思维。它告诉我如何不仅要反抗这些社会规范，还要嘲笑它们，并按照自己的方式成为自己想成为的人。

Fashion has always played a role in my life, and it really was the thing that let me become more comfortable with myself. When I left school and relocated to Montréal, I was moving more and more outside of a wheelchair, but that sense of not being attractive or desirable stayed with me. Wandering around one weekend, I found myself in a vintage book shop and discovered a frayed nine-year-old issue of Dazed & Confused in a stack of old magazines. It was a 1998 issue, with the cover line FASHION ABLE? and showing a model with two prosthetic legs. It was guest-edited by Alexander McQueen, and inside were brilliant pictures of bodies that looked different but beautiful. After looking through that issue, I started experimenting with clothes and going out more. Montréal is the sort of place that will change you if you let it. I found myself drawn to the drag bars and admiring a form of dress that can be glam and sumptuous while mocking and upending conventional notions of beauty, bodies, and gender. Drag inverted my thinking. It showed me how to not just defy these social norms, but to laugh at them and simply be who you want to be on your own terms.

我在伦敦的早期，很多朋友都是中央圣马丁学院的时尚系学生，该学院是伦敦艺术大学的组成学院之一。我最初在伦敦艺术大学就读，最后在 Carolyn Mair 的指导下工作，她拥有认知心理学和机器学习背景。Mair 博士不是典型的时尚教授，但这种匹配很合理，因为我不是典型的时尚系学生。在我向她解释我想开始研究另一种时尚“模型”——神经网络、计算机视觉和自动编码器后，她说服了大学的研究生研究委员会允许我攻读机器学习而不是设计博士学位。大约在这个时候，我也开始了在 SCL 集团的新工作，所以我的日常生活在时装模特和网络战之间波动。我渴望深入研究文化趋势的学术研究，所以我告诉 Nix，我不想全职为 SCL 工作，如果 SCL 想要我，他们必须接受我继续攻读博士学位。同时开展他们的项目。Nix 同意了这一安排，SCL 最终同意承担我的学费，这对我来说简直是天赐之物，因为作为一名国际学生，我必须支付最高的学费。

In my early years in London, many of my friends were fashion students at Central Saint Martins, which is one of the constituent colleges of the University of the Arts London. I started as a student at UAL and ended up working under the supervision of Carolyn Mair, who had a background in cognitive psychology and machine learning. Dr. Mair wasn’t a typical fashion professor, but the match made sense, as I wasn’t a typical fashion student. After I explained to her that I wanted to start researching fashion “models” of another kind—neural networks, computer vision, and autoencoders—she convinced the university’s postgraduate research committee to allow me to commence a Ph.D. in machine learning rather than in design. It was around this time that I also began my new job at SCL Group, so my days fluctuated between fashion models and cyberwarfare. I was keen to dive into my academic research on cultural trends, so I told Nix that I did not want to work for SCL full-time, and that if SCL wanted me, they would have to accept that I would be continuing my Ph.D. in parallel to their projects. Nix agreed to this arrangement and SCL eventually agreed to cover my tuition fees, which felt like a godsend for me, since as an international student I had to pay the highest rate of tuition.

这两个领域相辅相成，因为了解文化比单纯观察极端主义运动所宣称的意识形态更能让你了解极端主义运动的动态。在 SCL，我们观看了无数激进圣战宣传视频，我们注意到，除了新闻中出现的暴力片段外，他们的内容风格还具有丰富而清晰的美感。视频中展示了酷车，还有音乐。他们理想中的英雄有着明显的男性化外表，有些视频看起来几乎像真人秀节目的片段。讽刺的是，他们试图将他们落后的意识形态定位为某种现代或未来主义，这与意大利老未来主义者对未来法西斯主义的宣传相呼应——这是通往现代化的最便捷途径。这些电影宣扬了一种可怕的暴力和仇恨崇拜，但除此之外，它们也是他们文化的一部分。他们的风格自我放纵，天真浪漫，近乎媚俗。甚至恐怖分子也有流行文化。

These two domains serve each other well, as understanding culture can equip you to unpack the dynamics of extremist movements more than purely looking at their professed ideologies can. At SCL we would watch countless numbers of radical jihadist propaganda videos, and we noticed that, beyond the violence of the clips that make it onto the news, there was a rich and well-articulated aesthetic to their style of content. Cool cars were showcased. There would be music. There was a defined masculine look to their idealized heroes, and some of the videos looked almost like clips from reality TV. The irony was that they tried to position their backward ideology as somehow modern or futuristic in a way that echoed the old Italian Futurists’ promotion of a fascism for tomorrow—that it was the most expedient gateway to modernity. These films were propagating a grotesque cult of violence and hate, but beyond that, they also formed part of their culture. Their style was self-indulgent and naïvely romantic, and it bordered on kitsch. Even terrorists have pop culture.

大约在这个时候，也就是 2013 年 9 月，我清楚地记得自己当时在想，这有多酷？我从事文化工作，但不只是为了某人的品牌宣传活动。我从事文化工作是为了保卫我们的民主。军方只是使用了不同的术语 -建模影响归因或观察到的目标概况的协同作用。但在时尚界，我们称之为趋势。协同着装。协同使用主题标签。协同聆听。协同去听音乐会。文化精神本身就是人们的协同作用。我确信，这些趋势可以在数据中辨别出来。通过在线观察和分析，我们想要尝试预测这些运动的采用生命周期、早期采用者、传播率和峰值。

Around this time, in September 2013, I distinctly remember thinking, How cool is this? I get to work in culture, but not just for someone’s branding campaign. I get to work in culture for the defense of our democracy. The military just used different terms—modeled influence attribution or target profiles observed acting in concert. But in fashion, we just call that a trend. Dressing in concert. Hashtagging in concert. Listening in concert. Going to a concert in concert. The cultural zeitgeist itself is just people acting in concert. And these kinds of trends, I was sure, could be discerned in the data. Through online observation and profiling, we wanted to try to forecast these movements’ adoption life cycles, their early adopters, their diffusion rates, their peaks.

在 SCL 工作的最初几周，我开始研究如何数字化和改变传统的信息作战策略。这是该公司当时最感兴趣的，因为它意识到许多北约军队存在一个关键的能力缺口，如果开发出将宣传与广告技术相结合的新方法，它可以填补这一缺口（并从中获利）。这涉及探索我们可以借鉴哪些研究来规划这个新的数字领域，例如从点击流中获取新的信息来源，并通过分析和机器学习提高叙事针对目标接收者的定位。将信息武器化显然存在固有的复杂性。无论他们是谁或在哪里，枪支和炸弹都会杀死人——物理学的特性是全球性的。但信息武器必须根据多种因素进行量身定制：语言、文化、位置、历史、人口多样性。如果你正在制造一种用于大规模透视杀伤的非动能武器——主动解构和操纵大众的看法——你首先必须深刻理解人们的动机。

In my first weeks at SCL, I began looking into how to digitize and transform the traditional tactics of information operations. This was what the firm was most interested in at the time, as it realized that there was a critical capacity gap in many NATO militaries that it could fill (and profit from) if it developed new ways of merging propaganda with ad tech. This involved exploration of what research we could draw upon about mapping out this new digital domain, such as acquiring new information sources from clickstreams and improving the targeting of narratives at their intended recipients through profiling and machine learning. There are obvious inherent complications in weaponizing information. Guns and bombs kill people no matter who or where they are—the properties of physics are global. But an information weapon has to be tailored according to multiple factors: language, culture, location, history, population diversity. If you’re building a non-kinetic weapon designed for scaled perspecticide—the active deconstruction and manipulation of popular perception—you first have to understand on a deep level what motivates people.

叛乱本质上是不对称的，因为少数人就能造成巨大影响。因此，要在交战方组织内煽动叛乱，首先需要将资源集中在几个关键目标群体上。通过良好的分析和识别既容易接受新思维方式又有足够人脉将我们的反叙事注入其社交网络的人，可以实现最佳效果。

Insurgencies, by nature, are asymmetric, in that a few people can cause large effects. So catalyzing an insurgency within the belligerent’s organization requires first concentrating resources on a few key target groups. This is optimized by good profiling and identifying the types of people who are both susceptible to new ways of thinking and connected enough to inject our counternarrative into their social network.

最有效的视角灭绝是首先改变自我概念。从这个角度来看，操纵者试图从目标那里“窃取”自我概念，用自己的概念取而代之。这通常始于试图扼杀对手的叙述，然后控制目标周围的信息环境。这通常涉及在几个月内逐渐打破所谓的心理弹性因素。这些计划旨在在目标中产生不切实际的看法，导致混乱并损害自我效能。鼓励目标开始对小事件或想象中的事件进行灾难化，反叙事试图消除意义，给人留下混乱或毫无意义的印象。反叙事还试图培养不信任，以减轻与可能阻碍目标进化的其他人的沟通。当你开始认为自己被以某种不公平的方式利用，或者当事情看起来毫无意义或毫无目的时，对现有等级制度或团体保持忠诚就变得更加困难。你变得不太愿意接受挫折、冒险或服从命令。

The most effective form of perspecticide is one that first mutates the concept of self. In this light, the manipulator attempts to “steal” the concept of self from his target, replacing it with his own. This usually starts with attempting to smother the opponent’s narratives and then dominating the informational environment around the target. Often this involves gradually breaking down what are called psychological resilience factors over several months. Programs are designed to create unrealistic perceptions in the targets that result in confusion and damage self-efficacy. Targets are encouraged to begin catastrophizing about minor or imagined events, and counternarratives attempt to remove meaning, creating an impression of confusing or senseless events. Counternarratives also attempt to foster distrust in order to mitigate communication with others who might hamper the target’s evolution. It is much harder to stay loyal to an existing hierarchy or group when you begin to think that you are being used in some unfair way, or when events seem senseless or purposeless. You become less willing to accept setbacks, take risks, or comply with commands.

但仅仅降低士气往往是不够的。最终目的是引发与冲动、古怪或强迫行为相关的负面情绪和思维过程。这使目标从轻度或消极抵抗（例如，生产力下降、承担更少的风险、谣言等）转变为更具破坏性的行为（例如，争吵、不服从、叛变等）。例如，在南美洲，这种方法被用来挑起毒品行动成员之间的不团结，增加信息泄露、叛变或破坏供应链的内部冲突的可能性。最容易受到影响的目标通常是那些表现出神经质或自恋特征的人，因为他们往往在心理上对压力叙述的抵抗力较弱。这是因为神经质会使人更容易产生偏执的想法，因为他们往往会经历更多的焦虑和冲动，并且更多地依赖直觉而不是深思熟虑。自恋程度高的人更容易受到影响，因为他们更容易产生嫉妒和权利感，而这些是破坏规则和违反等级制度行为的强大动机。这意味着这些目标更有可能产生对骚扰、迫害、受害者或不公平待遇的夸大怀疑。这是发起颠覆大型组织的“唾手可得的果实”。后来，这一学习将成为剑桥分析公司在美国催化另类右翼叛乱的基础之一。

But simply degrading morale is often not enough. The ultimate aim is to trigger negative emotions and thought processes associated with impulsive, erratic, or compulsive behavior. This moves a target from mild or passive resistance (e.g., less productivity, taking fewer risks, rumors, etc.) into a realm of more disruptive behaviors (e.g., arguing, insubordination, mutiny, etc.). This approach has been taken in South America, for example, to provoke disunity among members of narcotics operations, increasing the likelihood of information leaks, defections, or internal conflicts that erode a supply chain. The most susceptible targets are typically the ones who exhibit neurotic or narcissistic traits, as they tend to be less psychologically resilient to stressing narratives. This is because neuroticism can make a person more prone to paranoid ideation, as they tend to experience more anxiety and impulsiveness and place more reliance on intuitive rather than deliberative thinking. People high on the narcissism scale are susceptible because they are more prone to feelings of envy and entitlement, which are strong motivators of rule-breaking and hierarchy-defying behavior. This means these targets will be more likely to develop an exaggerated suspicion of harassment, persecution, victimhood, or unfair treatment. This is the “low-hanging fruit” for initiating the subversion of a larger organization. Later, this learning would serve as one of the foundations for Cambridge Analytica’s work catalyzing an alt-right insurgency in America.

让我们明确一点：这些行动不是某种治疗咨询；它们是一种心理攻击。重要的是要记住，在军事背景下，目标的个人行为或同意并不重要。目标是敌人。军队的选择通常是派遣无人机焚烧敌人，或者扰乱敌人的部队，使他们开始自相残杀，或者变得马虎，犯下可以被利用的错误。如果你是一名军事指挥官或情报官员，心理操纵是一种“轻触式”方法。

Let’s be clear: These operations are not some kind of therapeutic counseling; they are a form of psychological attack. It’s important to remember that, in a military context, the target’s personal agency or consent is not a concern. The target is the enemy. The choice for the military is often either to send in a drone to incinerate the enemy or to mess with the enemy’s unit to such an extent that they begin to fight among themselves or get sloppy and make exploitable mistakes. If you are a military commander or an intelligence officer, psychological manipulation is the “light touch” approach.

随着社交媒体的出现，军事和安全机构突然可以直接了解世界各地犯罪和恐怖组织的警卫、办事员、女友和跑腿人员的思想和生活。社交数据提供的是一系列详细的个人信息，以前需要几个月的仔细观察才能收集到这些信息。这些目标实际上是在用丰富的数据创建自己的档案，可以加快心理学家对他们性格的评估。这引发了大量心理分析研究，这些研究可以通过机器学习算法实现自动化。这些算法将允许机构通过自动化扩大他们的网络，达到老式传单投放的规模，但精确度却达到目标信息的水平。2011 年，DARPA 开始资助对社交媒体用户的心理分析、反政府信息的传播方式，甚至网络欺骗的研究。Facebook、雅虎和 IBM 的工程师都参与了 DARPA 资助的研究项目，以评估信息的消费和传播方式。俄罗斯和中国政府也启动了自己的社交媒体研究项目。

With the advent of social media, suddenly military and security agencies had direct access to the minds and lives of guards, clerks, girlfriends, and runners of criminal and terrorist organizations all around the world. What the social data offered was a trail of detailed personal information that previously would have taken months of careful observation to gather. The targets were in effect creating their own dossiers with rich data that could quicken a psychologist’s assessment of their disposition. This spurred a host of research into psychological profiling that could be automated with machine-learning algorithms. These algorithms would allow agencies to widen their net through automation and reach the scale of an old-school leaflet drop, but with the precision of targeted messages. In 2011, DARPA began funding research into psychological profiling of social media users, how anti-government messages spread, and even online deception. Engineers at Facebook, Yahoo, and IBM all participated in DARPA-funded research projects to assess how information is consumed and spread. The Russian and Chinese governments also launched their own social media research programs.

我在 SCL 的第一天，尼克斯就问我是否听说过一家叫 Palantir 的公司。他是从一位人脉广泛的 SCL 实习生索菲·施密特那里听说这家公司的。索菲是亿万富翁埃里克·施密特的女儿，埃里克·施密特当时担任谷歌执行董事长。几个月前，在她结束实习时，她把亚历山大介绍给了 Palantir 的一些高管。Palantir 的联合创始人是硅谷著名风险投资家彼得·泰尔，他也是 Facebook 的独立董事。Palantir 是一家由风险投资公司资助的大型公司，为美国中央情报局、美国国家安全局（其任务是分析信号情报和数据以用于国家安全目的）和英国政府通信总部 (GCHQ) 进行信息操作。尼克斯对这家公司非常着迷。他希望 SCL 能做 Palantir 正在做的事情。

On my very first day at SCL, Nix asked whether I’d heard of a company called Palantir. He’d learned about it from an unusually well-connected SCL intern named Sophie Schmidt—the daughter of Eric Schmidt, a billionaire and then executive chairman of Google. A few months earlier, as she was finishing up her internship, she’d introduced Alexander to some of the executives at Palantir. Co-founded by Peter Thiel, a well-known venture capitalist in Silicon Valley who was also an independent director of Facebook, Palantir was a massive venture-capital-funded company that undertook information operations for the CIA, the National Security Agency, whose mission is to analyze signals intelligence and data for national security purposes, and the Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), the British counterpart to the NSA. Nix was obsessed. He wanted SCL to do what Palantir was doing.

在最初的几个月里，我与剑桥的心理学家布伦特·克里克德和他的朋友塔达斯·尤西卡斯一起在不同的国家开展了小型试点项目。我第一次见到尤西卡斯是在皇家汽车俱乐部，这是一家私人会员制场所，有酒吧、壁球场和台球室，上流社会人士会去那里社交和做生意。它成立于 1897 年，当时开车是一项昂贵的爱好，至今仍保留着奢华优雅的气息。当我走进有柱廊的俱乐部时，我看到尤西卡斯站在大厅里，旁边是一辆鲜红色的古董赛车，他的眼睛藏在玳瑁色太阳镜后面。他穿着一件剪裁精美的人字形夹克，配着一条干净利落的口袋巾。这一切都太过分了，但我很喜欢。

In my first few months, I worked on small pilot projects in various countries with Brent Clickard, the Cambridge-based psychologist, and a friend of his named Tadas Jucikas. I first met Jucikas at the Royal Automobile Club, a private members’ establishment with bars, squash courts, and billiard rooms, where the upper crust go to socialize and do business. It was founded back in 1897, when driving a car was an exorbitantly expensive hobby, and has retained its air of lavish elegance. When I walked up to the colonnaded clubhouse, I saw Jucikas standing in the lobby beside a bright-red antique racing car, his eyes hidden behind tortoiseshell sunglasses. He was wearing a beautifully cut herringbone jacket with a crisp pocket square. It was all so extra, but I was into it.

他领着我走进俱乐部，我们喝了几杯酒，然后走到阳台上抽雪茄。Jucikas 在立陶宛农村长大，小时候他曾看着苏联坦克驶过他的城镇。他显然很聪明。当我们坐在阳台上，一边品尝雪茄，一边讨论人工智能和数据管道时，Jucikas 打开一个挎包，拿出一张他绘制的图表。Clickard 告诉了他一些项目的范围，因此 Jucikas 绘制了一条拟议的数据科学管道，说明如何从在线个人资料中获取、清理、处理和部署数据。他一直在做博士研究，研究如何建模和预测秀丽隐杆线虫的行为，他说他只是把线虫换成了人。 Jucikas 建议通过构建自动数据收集实用程序来获取各种各样的数据，使用算法估算将不同的数据源整合为每个人的统一身份，然后使用深度学习神经网络来预测我们期望的行为。他说，我们仍然需要一个心理学家团队来创建改变行为所需的叙述，但他的流程是目标系统的第一个草图。但我最喜欢的是他用颜色编码使旅程看起来像伦敦地铁地图。随着他的解释，很明显他非常适合这份工作。

He led me inside the club, where we drank a couple of boulevardiers before moving to the balcony to smoke cigars. Jucikas had grown up in rural Lithuania, where he watched Soviet tanks roll through his town as a boy. He was obviously brilliant. As we sat on the balcony, savoring our cigars and discussing artificial intelligence and data pipelines, Jucikas opened a satchel and pulled out a diagram he’d created. Clickard had told him about the scope of some of the projects, so Jucikas had mapped out a proposed data science pipeline on how to ingest, cleanse, process, and deploy data from online profiles of people. He had been doing his Ph.D. research on modeling and predicting the behavior of C. elegans roundworms and said that he simply swapped out the worms for people. Jucikas proposed pulling a wide variety of data by building automated data-harvesting utilities, using algorithmic imputations to consolidate different data sources into a single unified identity for each individual, and then using deep-learning neural networks to predict our desired behaviors. We would still need a team of psychologists, he said, to create the narratives needed to change behaviors, but his pipeline served as the first sketch of the targeting system. But what I loved most was that he color-coded it to make the journey look like the London tube map. As he went through his explanation, it was clear that he was perfect for the job.

就这样，我和 Clickard、Jucikas 开始合作，最后我说服 Mark Gettleson 也加入进来。突然间，我被一群衣着讲究、聪明绝顶、古怪无比的人包围了。Nix 是头目，他是个咧嘴大笑、没有灵魂的推销员，他根本不了解我们在做什么，但却不失时机地向他认为可能付钱的人快速而卖力地推销。他用傲慢的宣言和粗俗的性笑话统治着办公室。

So it was that Clickard, Jucikas, and I began working together, and I eventually persuaded Mark Gettleson to join as well. Suddenly I was surrounded by a team of impeccably dressed, blazingly smart, impossibly quirky individuals. And Nix was the ringleader, the grinning, soulless salesman who didn’t understand anything we were doing but wasted no time selling it fast and hard to anyone he thought might pay. He ruled the office with haughty proclamations and crude sexual jokes.

SCL 的氛围是“无所不能”，在我们入职几个月后，这种氛围完美地体现了出来。通常我穿 T 恤和连帽衫，但一天下午，参加完伦敦时装周活动后，我走进办公室，穿着一件鲜艳的酒红色 Prada 夹克，搭配高腰裤和奶油色的 Dr. Martens 鞋，上面印着骷髅和玫瑰，风格类似纹身闪光。Nix 看了一眼，说：“Chris，你穿的是什么鬼？”

There was an “anything goes” atmosphere at SCL, perfectly crystallized in a moment that took place a couple of months after we all started. Normally I dress in T-shirts and hoodies, but one afternoon I came into the office after a London Fashion Week event wearing a vibrant burgundy Prada jacket with matching high-waisted trousers and cream-colored Dr. Martens shoes printed with skulls and roses in the style of tattoo flashes. Nix took one look and said, “Chris, what the fuck are you wearing?”

布伦特回答说：“我们在普拉达打击恐怖主义。”

To which Brent answered, “We fight terror in Prada.”

—

获取构建 Jucikas 设想的定位系统所需的数据并不容易，但由于某些发展中国家的历史偶然因素，这并非不可能。尽管传统电信基础设施严重欠发达，这主要源于腐败和殖民政府的疏忽遗留问题，但一些世界上最贫穷的国家已经跨越了几代技术，在移动网络方面取得了令人瞩目的进步。

GETTING THE REQUIRED DATA to build Jucikas’s envisioned targeting system would not be easy, but it was possible, due to a fluke of history in some parts of the developing world. Although there was substantial underdevelopment of traditional telecommunications infrastructure, largely stemming from corruption and the neglectful legacies of colonial administrations, some of the world’s poorest countries had leapfrogged generations of technology, achieving impressive advances in mobile networks.

例如，在肯尼亚，当地法律和习俗使得一些人难以获得银行账户，这导致肯尼亚人使用现金购买手机信用额度，然后将其作为一种数字货币进行交易。事实上，我们发现，许多较贫穷国家的人们不信任银行，因为他们经历过经济危机、恶性通货膨胀和银行倒闭，因此使用相同的手机解决方法。这种设置意味着每个人都需要一部手机，而且手机必须运行良好，因此在其他贫穷的国家，人们迅速投资建设了相对不错的移动基础设施。

In Kenya, for example, local laws and customs made it difficult for some people to get a bank account, leading to a system in which Kenyans used cash to buy mobile phone credits, which could then be traded as a kind of digital currency. In fact, we found that people in many poorer nations distrusted banks, having lived through economic crises, hyperinflation, and bank collapses, and used the same mobile workaround. This setup meant that everybody needed a phone, and that it needed to work well, so that in otherwise impoverished nations, there’d been rapid investment in relatively decent mobile infrastructure.

大量公民通过移动电话网络连接的一个意想不到的后果是，每个人都可以被追踪、跟踪、分析和交流。伊斯兰国、阿拉伯半岛基地组织和博科圣地等圣战网络已经掌握了这一点，利用了轻松获取未来征服者思想的优势。这颠覆了战争规则。

One unintended consequence of having large pluralities of citizens connected via mobile phone networks was that everybody could be traced, tracked, profiled, and communicated with. Jihadist networks such as ISIS, AQAP, and Boko Haram had already figured this out, taking advantage of easy access to the minds of future conquests. And that turned the rules of warfare upside down.

接下来，我们需要一个案例研究——一个可以扩展到民族国家层面的地点，向潜在的军事客户展示我们的能力。特立尼达和多巴哥拥有 130 万人口，完全符合这个条件。它是一个岛国，自给自足，但文化多样。这里有非洲裔加勒比人、印度裔加勒比人以及少数白人，创造了一种有趣的文化张力，值得探索。这是一个理想的实验室，可以让我们大规模地进行实验。

Next we needed a case study—a location where we could scale to a nation-state level, to show potential military clients what we were capable of doing. Trinidad and Tobago, with 1.3 million people, fit the bill perfectly. It was an island nation, self-contained yet with a variety of cultures. There was an Afro-Caribbean population, an Indo-Caribbean population, and a smattering of white people, creating an interesting cultural tension to explore. It was an ideal laboratory in which to run our experiments at scale.

特立尼达国家安全部想知道是否有可能利用数据来识别更有可能犯罪的特立尼达人——除此之外，是否有可能预测他们何时以及如何犯罪。SCL 在加勒比海的各个微型国家开展业务已有很长的历史，在帮助选定的政客上台后，该公司通常会收回其在政府合同中的投资。在 SCL，我们开始将此称为“少数派报告”项目，以菲利普·K·迪克的故事（由史蒂文·斯皮尔伯格改编成电影）命名，故事中，一个未来主义的预防犯罪部门在人们犯罪之前就将他们逮捕。但事实是，特立尼达政府不仅对减少犯罪感兴趣。他们知道，如果我们建立了一个预测行为的工具，他们可以在选举中使用它。他们不仅关注未来的罪犯；他们还想瞄准​​未来的政治支持者。

The Trinidad Ministry of National Security wanted to know whether it was possible to use data to identify Trinidadians who were more likely to commit crimes—and, beyond that, whether it was possible to predict when and how they might do it. SCL had a long history of operating throughout the various micronations of the Caribbean, and after it helped selected politicians get into power, the firm would often recoup its investment in government contracts. At SCL, we started referring to this as the Minority Report Project, after the Philip K. Dick story (adapted for film by Steven Spielberg) in which a futuristic PreCrime Division arrests people before they’re able to commit crimes. But the truth was, the Trinidadian government wasn’t interested only in reducing crime. They knew that if we built a tool to forecast behavior, they could use it in elections. They weren’t just focused on future criminals; they also wanted to zero in on future political supporters.

该团队预计会获取大量数据，因为特立尼达政府高层联系人向 SCL 提供了未经删改、匿名化的人口普查数据——在发展中国家，隐私通常是富人关心的问题。从本质上讲，特立尼达政府一举侵犯了所有公民的隐私。

The team anticipated vast swaths of data, because senior Trinidad government contacts were offering SCL access to the unredacted, de-anonymized census—in the developing world, privacy is a concern usually reserved for the rich. Essentially the Trinidadian government was violating the privacy of all its citizens in one swoop.

原始人口普查数据显然对该项目有用，但这并不是发达国家可以获取的资源。SCL 需要探索使用互联网收集相关数据，以创建一种跨文化和跨国适用的工具。因此，SCL 的下一步是派人到加勒比电信公司实地考察，询问 SCL 是否能够实时利用他们的数据“消防水带”。令我惊讶的是，这是可能的。

The raw census data would obviously be useful for the project, but it wasn’t a resource we could expect to have available to us in developed countries. SCL needed to explore using the Internet to collect relevant data, to create a tool that would be cross-culturally and cross-nationally applicable. So SCL’s next step was to send people on the ground to Caribbean telecom companies, to ask if SCL could tap into their data “firehose” in real time. To my surprise, this was possible.

通过与一组承包商合作，SCL 能够接入电信消防水带，选择一个 IP 地址，然后坐下来观察特立尼达岛的某人当时在互联网上浏览什么。毫不奇怪，他们浏览了大量色情内容。人们浏览着一切可以想象到的内容，包括特定文化的“特立尼达色情内容”。我记得有一天晚上坐在电脑前，看着有人在查找芭蕉食谱和观看色情内容之间切换，而尼克斯则嘲笑他们。那是一种令人作呕的轻浮笑声，几乎是幼稚的。他查找了 IP 地址，然后打开谷歌地图卫星视图，查看这个人住的街区。

Working with a set of contractors, SCL was able to tap into the telecom firehose, pick an IP address, and then sit and watch what a person in Trinidad was browsing on the Internet at that very moment. Not surprisingly, it was a lot of porn. People were browsing everything imaginable, including the culturally specific “Trini Porn.” I can remember sitting around the computer one evening and watching as someone toggled between looking up plantain recipes and watching porn, all while Nix laughed at them. It was a revoltingly giddy laugh, almost infantile. He looked up the IP address and then opened up Google Maps satellite view to see the neighborhood this person lived in.

尼克斯看着屏幕，我开始观察他，他从嘲笑和利用他人的机会中获得如此深刻、卑鄙的快感。这是典型的尼克斯——或者用他那些傲慢的同龄人的话说就是“伯蒂”。和许多老伊顿人一样，他擅长调情、调情和娱乐。SCL 的董事们指派他领导公司的副业，即在非洲、加勒比海和南亚等被遗忘的国家操纵选举。尼克斯在与微型国家的内阁部长打交道时完全得心应手。他扮演着英国绅士的角色，让这些政客有机会在古老的帝国首都伦敦获得他们想要的任何东西——王室和首相经常光顾的著名俱乐部、独家派对的邀请，或者，如果愿意的话，与优雅而开明的女性私人相处。

As Nix watched the screen, I began to watch him, taking such deep, nasty pleasure in the chance to ridicule and exploit others. It was classic Nix—or “Bertie,” as his pompous peers called him. Like many Old Etonians, he excelled at banter, flirtation, and entertainment. The directors of SCL assigned him to lead the firm’s side business of rigging elections in forgotten countries of Africa, the Caribbean, and South Asia. It was with cabinet ministers of micronations that Nix was completely in his element. Performing the role of the English gentleman, he would give these politicians access to anything they wanted in the old imperial capital of London—the prestigious clubs frequented by royals and prime ministers, invitations to exclusive parties, or, if desired, the private company of elegant and open-minded women.

尼克斯利用了帝国统治者对殖民的迷恋和不安全感。一旦他赢得了他们的信任，他就会为寻求认可和女人的部长和寻求利用腐败商业机会不被人注意地旅行的商人之间进行交易。尼克斯了解到，主权是一种极其宝贵的商品。即使是最小、最不为人知的岛国也能提供两件非常有价值的东西：护照和免税。他继承了数千万英镑，从来不需要工作。他本可以将自己的一生献给高尚的追求，或者只是安于闲适的生活，靠信托基金生活。但他却选择了 SCL。尼克斯无法控制自己——他沉迷于权力。他出生太晚，无法在旧大英帝国扮演殖民统治者，他把 SCL 视为现代的殖民统治者。正如尼克斯在我们的一次会议上所说的那样，他可以“扮演白人”。他曾在一封电子邮件中对一位同事说，“他们只是黑鬼”，指的是巴巴多斯的黑人政客。

Nix preyed upon the colonial fetishes and insecurities of the men who ran the nations of the empire. Once he gained their trust, he would then broker deals between ministers who were looking for validation and women, and businessmen who were looking to exploit corrupt business opportunities and travel unnoticed. Sovereignty, Nix learned, was an extremely valuable commodity. Even the smallest and most obscure island nation could offer two things of exceptional value: passports and tax immunity. He had inherited tens of millions of pounds and never needed to work. He could have dedicated his life to noble pursuits or simply settled into a life of leisure, sponging off his trust fund. But instead he chose SCL. Nix couldn’t help himself—he was intoxicated by power. Born too late to play colonial master in the old British Empire, he treated SCL as the modern equivalent. As Nix put it in one of our meetings, he got to “play the white man.” “They [are] just niggers,” he once said to a colleague in an email, referring to black politicians in Barbados.

我们纯粹是在特立尼达领导人的掩护下从事间谍活动。观察一个遥远小岛上人们的所见所闻，感觉很奇怪，很不真实，这更像是在玩电子游戏，而不是在侵犯真实人民的私生活。即使今天回想起来，特立尼达更像是一场梦，而不是我们真正做过的事情。

We were spying, pure and simple, with cover from Trinidadian leaders. It felt bizarre—unreal—to be observing what people were watching on a tiny, faraway island, somehow more like we were playing a video game than intruding on the private lives of actual people. Even today, thinking back on it, Trinidad seems more like a dream than something we actually did.

但我们确实做到了。特立尼达项目是我第一次陷入这种极不道德的境地，坦率地说，它让我陷入了一种否认状态。当我观看那些直播时，我不允许自己真正想象人类的猎物，这些人不知道他们的私人行为正在取悦半个地球之外的邪恶观众。特立尼达项目是我第一次体验到这一波新的数字殖民主义。我们带着优越的技术和道德漠视不请自来，不请自来，和国王的军队没什么两样。只是这一次，与过去的征服者不同，我们是完全隐形的。

But we did do it. The Trinidad project was the first time I got sucked into a situation that was grossly unethical, and, frankly, it triggered in me a state of denial. As I watched those livestreams, I didn’t allow myself to actually picture the human prey, people who had no idea that their private behavior was delighting sinister audiences half a world away. The Trinidad project was my first taste of this new wave of digital colonialism. We arrived unannounced with our superior technology and moral disregard, no better than the king’s armies. Except this time, unlike the conquerors of old, we were completely invisible.

—

在我与尼克斯共事的最初几个月里，我就已经发现他没有真正的商业道德，或者说个人道德。为了赢得一个项目，他似乎愿意不惜一切代价，在办公室里炫耀这笔交易或那笔交易。他把一切都描述成性征服：在谈判的早期阶段，双方“互相抚摸”或“把手指伸进去”。当一笔交易达成时，他会大喊：“现在我们做爱了！”

ALREADY, IN MY EARLY months of working with Nix, it had become clear that he had no real business ethics—or personal ethics, for that matter. He seemed willing to go to any lengths to win a project, and he’d peacock around the office bragging about this deal or that deal. He described everything in terms of sexual conquest: in the early stages of negotiations, the two sides were “feeling each other up” or “slipping in a finger.” When a deal closed, he’d exclaim, “Now we’re fucking!”

2013 年 8 月，拉巴大屠杀发生后不久，埃及政府代表来到伦敦开会。这是早期运动之一，社交媒体和移动应用上的即时通讯在动员中发挥了重要作用。我们遇到的埃及人有兴趣使用我们的信息计划来打击他们所谓的“政治极端分子”。我们讨论了如何在运动中制造混乱的几种方案，包括通过移动信息传播谣言，或者通过安插同盟者激怒人群并逮捕抗议者。这不是我期望 SCL 承担的项目，而且我在道义上反对他们要求我们做的事情。正是在这里，我面对了反极端主义的非常主观的含义。一方面挫败巴基斯坦等地的圣战组织，另一方面又帮助埃及一个专制的、受伊斯兰主义支持的政权建立自己的人民暴政，这似乎完全是虚伪的。但尼克斯不在乎。生意就是生意；他只是想达成交易。

In August 2013, not long after the Rabaa massacre, representatives of the Egyptian government came to London for meetings. This was one of the early movements where social media and instant messaging on mobile apps played a significant role in mobilization. The Egyptians we met were interested in using our information programs to combat what they called “political extremists.” Several scenarios were discussed about how to create havoc within the movement, including starting rumors to spread through mobile messaging or riling up crowds with planted confederates and arresting protestors. This wasn’t the kind of project I’d expected SCL to take on, and I felt morally opposed to what they were asking us to do. It was here that I was confronted with the very subjective meaning of counter-extremism. It seemed entirely hypocritical to, on the one hand, frustrate jihadist groups in places like Pakistan and then, on the other, assist an autocratic and Islamist-backed regime in Egypt in creating its own tyranny of people. But Nix didn’t care. Business was business; he just wanted to clinch the deal.

对于我和 SCL 不断壮大的心理学家和数据科学家团队来说，主要挑战在于极端主义本身的客观实质。极端主义者意味着什么？极端主义究竟是什么？如何对其进行建模？这些都是主观定义，显然埃及政府有一个想法，而我们有另一个想法。但是，如果你想要量化和预测一种特征，你必须能够为其创建定义。我们反复讨论这个问题，从理论上讨论，但现实令人警醒：极端主义就是你想让它变成的任何东西。最后，SCL 没有承担这个项目，所以我只是将我的担忧分开，继续工作。

The main challenge for me and the growing team of psychologists and data scientists at SCL was in the objective substance of extremism itself. What does it mean to be an extremist? What exactly is extremism, and how can you model it? These were subjective definitions, and clearly the Egyptian government had one idea, while we had another. But if you want to be able to quantify and predict a trait, you have to be able to create a definition of it.
