We went around and around, discussing the question in theoretical terms, but the reality of it felt sobering: Extremism is whatever you want it to be. In the end, SCL didn’t undertake the project, so I just compartmentalized my concerns and kept working.

我开始在办公室里尽量避开尼克斯——每个人都这么做，因为他的行为太令人反感了。他试图把我纳入他的羽翼之下——按照他的形象重塑我——但失败了。首先，我们的背景太不一样了。即使我不觉得尼克斯的傲慢和势利令人震惊，我也永远无法伪装成一个“受人尊敬的”伊顿老校友，而他不断的恐吓——穿什么衣服、怎么说话等等——只会让我更加害羞。我们偶尔会因为对好威士忌的共同喜爱而建立联系，但大多数时候我都保持距离。

I began trying to avoid Nix at the office—everyone did, because he behaved so repulsively. His efforts to take me under his wing—to remake me in his image—were a dismal failure. Our backgrounds were too different, for starters. Even if I didn’t find Nix’s arrogance and snobbery appalling, I never could have disguised myself as a “respectable” Old Etonian, and his constant hectoring—what to wear, how to speak, etc.—only made me more self-conscious. We did occasionally bond over a mutual fondness for good whisky, but mostly I kept my distance.

最吸引我的项目是那些对世界有益的项目，比如在中东消除被军方亲切地称为 YUM（年轻未婚男性）的激进主义，以及根除圣战行为的项目。我找到了留下来的理由，理由是，即使尼克斯显然是个坏人，SCL 仍然有很多好人。我决定埋头苦干，继续工作。

The projects that most engaged me were those that were doing some good in the world, such as programs to de-radicalize what the military affectionately called the YUMs—young unmarried males—in the Middle East and root out jihadist behavior. I found ways to justify staying, reasoning that even if Nix was obviously a villain, there were still lots of good people working for SCL. I decided just to keep my head down and keep working.

2013 年末，我被邀请参加与非洲某国潜在客户的会面。他们告诉我，这是一个政治项目，涉及在即将到来的选举前锁定选民。我对这个国家不太了解，但我认为我们可以通过移动网络或公共资源获得必要的数据，所以我答应了。我们在伦敦一家昂贵的餐厅与这位客户见面，他后来成为该国的卫生部长。

In late 2013, I was asked to join a meeting with a potential client in an African nation. This would be a political project, I was told, involving targeting voters ahead of an upcoming election. I didn’t know much about the country, but I assumed we could get hold of the necessary data through mobile networks or public sources, so I said “Sure.” We met with the client, who turned out to be the country’s minister of health, at an expensive restaurant in London.

一开始，讨论进展得差不多和我预料的一样。我们讨论了客户需要什么服务，以及 SCL 如何提供这些服务。然后，话题转到如何为项目筹集资金，该公司提出了一个建议：客户可以利用该国卫生部现有的数百万美元项目，而 SCL 将悄悄地成为分包商，动用该项目的预算进行政治研究。之后，另一名工作人员发来一封电子邮件：“一项更大规模调查的健康部分将作为竞选活动的前奏”，并指出，“政治部分也已获批准。”电子邮件继续解释说，卫生部的调查将包括有关投票行为和对现任政府的支持的问题。当然，将卫生部的纳税人资金用于政治竞选是违法的。

At first, the discussion ran more or less as I’d expected. We talked about what services the client needed and how SCL could provide them. Then the conversation turned to how the project could be funded, and the firm made a proposal: The client could leverage an existing multi-million-dollar project for the country’s ministry of health, and SCL would quietly be added as a subcontractor, dipping into the project’s budget to conduct political research. Afterward, another staff member followed up with an email: “The health component of a larger survey will act as a prelude to an election campaign,” and noted, “the political component has also been approved.” The email went on to explain that the ministry of health survey would include questions about voting behavior and support for the current administration. Of course, using taxpayer funds from the ministry of health for political campaigns is unlawful.

会议期间我什么都没说，但之后我去见了亚历山大。“这不合法，”我告诉他。他回答说：“你不能指望这些人能做任何合法的事情。这里是非洲。”

I said nothing during the meeting, but afterward I went to see Alexander. “This can’t be legal,” I told him. To which he replied, “You can’t expect anything legal with these people. It’s Africa.”

尼克斯非常擅长让人们怀疑自己，在 SCL 工作期间，我一直上当。其他时候，他没那么有说服力。有一次，他带我到新邦德街新办公室的屋顶上，进行“一对一”谈话，如果我能帮助赢得一个项目，他会给我一匹马。显然，他有很多马。我说我不想要。“哦，对了，”他说。“那就给你一匹小马吧。”和他交谈后，我常常不确定自己应该有什么感觉——是被他说的话冒犯了，还是为我的天真感到尴尬。

Nix was extremely good at getting people to doubt themselves, and throughout my time at SCL, I kept falling for it. Other times, he was less convincing. One time he took me onto the roof, high above our new offices on New Bond Street, for a “man-to-man,” where he offered me a horse if I helped win a project. He had lots of horses, apparently. I said I didn’t want one. “Oh, right,” he said. “A pony for you, then.” After speaking to him, I often wasn’t sure what I was supposed to be feeling—offended by what he’d said or embarrassed at my naïveté.

我简直不敢相信非洲项目会按计划进行，但事实确实如此。SCL 起草了一份分包计划，并提交给卫生部审批。在几个月的时间里，随着卫生相关项目的推进，部分资金（数百万美元）实际上并未流向卫生部项目。这些资金被部长的政治竞选活动和 SCL 瓜分，SCL 的分成则装在该国大使馆的外交邮袋中，这样他们就可以绕过任何边境检查或申报。我很早就退出了这个项目，因为我意识到这在道德和法律上都是不可接受的。

I couldn’t believe that the African project would play out as planned, but it did. SCL created a proposal for a subcontract and submitted it for approval with the ministry of health. Over a period of many months, as the health-related projects proceeded, some of the money—millions of dollars—did not actually go to ministry of health programs. It was split between the minister’s political campaign and SCL, with SCL’s cut arriving from the country’s embassy in diplomatic bags so that they could bypass any border inspection or declaration. I removed myself from the project early on, recognizing that it was morally and legally beyond the pale.

随着我对 SCL 项目的了解越来越深入，办公室文化似乎越发影响了我的判断。随着时间的推移，我开始适应他们的腐败和道德漠视。每个人都对我们正在取得的发现感到兴奋，但我们愿意为这个新的研究领域走多远？是否会有人最终说够了？我不知道，说实话，我不想去想这个问题。就在那时，尼克斯给我发了一封电子邮件：“我想让你见见来自美国的史蒂夫。”

The deeper I got into SCL’s projects, the more the office culture seemed to be clouding my judgment. Over time, I was acclimatizing to their corruption and moral disregard. Everyone was excited about the discoveries we were making, but how far were we willing to go in the name of this new field of research? Was there a point at which someone would finally say Enough is enough? I didn’t know, and in truth, I didn’t want to think about it. And that was when Nix sent me an email: “I’d like you to meet Steve from America.”

第四章

CHAPTER 4

来自美国的史蒂夫

STEVE FROM AMERICA

-

我肯定是打瞌睡了，因为列车员的广播吓了我一跳：“下车前往剑桥！”那是 2013 年 10 月，我早上 5 点起床，赶上 6 点 40 分从伦敦维多利亚车站出发的火车。为了省下 5 英镑，尼克斯给我订了早班车。我从座位上跳起来，不小心撞到了旁边的一位老太太。她只是怒目而视，紧紧抓着钱包，就像英国人一样。我跑出去，回头说对不起，却被绊倒了。“小心空隙！”太迟了。

I must have dozed off, because the conductor’s announcement startled me: “Alight here for Cambridge!” It was October 2013, and I’d woken up that morning at 5:00 to make the 6:40 train out of London’s Victoria Station. Nix had booked me on the early one to save himself five pounds. I jumped out of my seat and accidentally knocked into the elderly lady beside me. She just glared, clutching her purse, as English people do. I was running out, looking back to say sorry, when I tripped. “Mind the gap!” Too late.

我站起来，才意识到不知怎么把钱包放错了地方，然后惊恐地看着火车缓缓驶出车站。哎。没有现金也没有卡，我打电话给尼克斯，让他预订一辆预付费出租车。“步行过去，”他说。“你应该更小心一点。”我太累了，没法争论，他显然心情不好，所以我按照尼克斯说的做了——我走着，走出车站，走进十月清晨的薄雾和细雨中。剑桥才刚刚开始苏醒。

I stood up, only to realize that I’d somehow misplaced my wallet, and then watched in dread as the train slowly pulled out of the station. Ugh. Without cash or cards, I called Nix and asked him to book a prepaid taxi. “Walk there,” he said. “You should have been more careful.” I was too tired to argue, and he was clearly in a mood, so I did as Nix said—I walked, departing the station into the mist and drizzle of an early October morning. Cambridge was just starting to wake up.

距离预约还有几个小时，我漫步穿过帕克公园，这是一片小小的公共绿地，学生运动员们在树林中教堂尖塔的映衬下开始晨练。从那里，我穿过小镇蜿蜒的中世纪石板街，经过小商店和英国第二古老大学高耸的城墙，这所大学的历史可以追溯到 1209 年。继续前往康河附近的汤普森巷后，我来到了规模虽小但价格昂贵的大学酒店。

With several hours to kill before my appointment, I meandered through Parker’s Piece, a small common green, as student-athletes began a morning practice against a backdrop of a church steeple peeking through the trees. From there, I walked through the town’s winding medieval stone streets, past small shops and the towering walls of England’s second-oldest university, dating back to the year 1209. After continuing to Thompson’s Lane, near the River Cam, I arrived at the small but clearly expensive Varsity Hotel.

在与军事承包商合作的过程中，我遇到了各种各样奇怪的人，他们中的大多数人都强烈渴望“绝对保密”——在第一次见面之前不知道一个人的完整身份一点也不奇怪。前一天，尼克斯走进办公室，看起来有点焦躁不安，他立刻走到我面前，双手放在我的桌子上，靠近我的脸。“我需要你明天在剑桥见一个人，”他说。“我无法了解他的想法，但我认为你可以。”

Working with a military contractor, I met all sorts of bizarre characters, most of whom had a strong desire for “absolute discretion”—it wasn’t the least bit unusual to not know the full identity of a person before the first meeting. The day before, Nix had come into the office looking slightly agitated and walked immediately over to me, where he put both his hands on my desk and leaned into my face. “I need you to meet someone tomorrow in Cambridge,” he said. “I can’t get into his head, but I think you can.”

我问将会见谁。

I asked who I’d be meeting.

“我稍后会通过电子邮件向您发送详细信息。”

“I’ll email you the details later.”

在这种情况下，我从尼克斯那里得到的极其无用的指示只是去见“来自美国的史蒂夫”，除了要求我“携带数据”之外没有提供任何详细信息。

In this case, the extremely unhelpful instruction I got from Nix was simply to meet “Steve from America,” with no details beyond a request that I “bring data.”

我独自在酒店大堂坐了一个小时，然后给尼克斯发短信，问史蒂夫的电话号码。他读了短信，但没有回复。又过了十五分钟，这个粗鲁的人走过来打量着我。

I sat alone in the hotel lobby for an hour before texting Nix, asking for Steve’s number. He read the text but didn’t respond. After another fifteen minutes, this gruff character walked up and looked me over.

“你就是那个人？”他问道。

“You the guy?” he asked.

“是的，”我回答道。根据 SCL 通常的客户，我以为是政府或机构类型的人。但事实并非如此，我看到的是一个衣冠不整的男人，穿着两件有领衬衫，好像他忘了脱掉一件再穿上一件。他胡子拉碴，头发油腻，还有一层横跨大西洋飞行后留下的污垢。他的眼睛里有几块鲜红色的斑点，与他皮肤上的红斑相得益彰。总之，他给人的感觉介于二手车推销员和疯子之间。他看起来很累或茫然；我想这只是时差反应。

“Yeah, I am,” I replied. Based on the clients SCL normally had, I’d expected some government or agency type. Instead I found myself looking at a disheveled man wearing two collared shirts, as if he’d forgotten to take one off before putting the next one on. He was unshaven, with greasy hair and that layer of grime you get from a transatlantic flight. His eyes showed flecks of bright red that matched the web of rosacea on his skin. In all, the vibe he gave off fell somewhere between used-car salesman and madman. He looked tired or dazed; I assumed it was just jet lag.

电梯是典型的英式设计，几乎容不下两个人，这意味着我必须努力不碰到这个家伙。我穿着单色的 Dries Van Noten 服装——深蓝色西装裤搭配同色外套，就像一件斜裁的毛派连体衣。

The elevator was a classic English setup that barely had room for two, meaning I had to work hard not to touch this guy. I was wearing monochromatic Dries Van Noten—dark navy suit trousers with a matching overshirt that blended like an obliquely cut Maoist jumpsuit.

“你和我想象的不一样，”他半开玩笑地说。是的，你自己也不是那么漂亮，亲爱的……

“You weren’t what I’d imagined,” he half joked. Yeah, you aren’t such a looker yourself, hun…

他住在顶楼的一间套房里。除了重点墙上的大胆壁纸外，装饰简约而现代，与下面中世纪城市的全景形成鲜明对比。没有行李似乎很奇怪，但不值得细想。然后我犹豫了。哦，等等，我和一个老家伙单独住在一间豪华酒店房间里。我看了看特大号床，然后注意到旁边的桌子上有一小瓶护手霜。操，操，操——尼克斯是在用我当诱饵吗？

He was staying in a suite on the top floor. Save for the bold wallpaper on an accent wall, the décor was minimal and modernist, which made for a stark contrast with the panoramic view of the medieval city below. The absence of luggage seemed weird, but not worth dwelling on. Then I hesitated. Oh, wait, I’m alone in a posh hotel room with some old guy. I looked over at the king bed, then noticed a little bottle of hand lotion on the table next to it. Fuck, fuck, fuck—was Nix using me as bait?

我紧紧抓住包，希望里面的笔记本电脑足够重，可以有效打击我。就在这时，史蒂夫·班农走到床边的大沙发上，让我坐下。令我大为欣慰的是，他自己拉了一把椅子，问我要不要喝点水。他坐下时，肚子已经快要溢出腰围了。

I clutched my bag, hoping the laptop inside was heavy enough to land an effective blow. At that moment, Steve Bannon walked over to the large sofa adjacent to the bed and offered me a seat. To my extreme relief, he grabbed a chair for himself and asked if I wanted some water. As he sat down, his stomach spilled over his waistline.

“尼克斯告诉我你正在做文化变迁研究，”他说。“跟我说说这个吧。”

“Nix tells me you’re doing research on cultural change,” he said. “Tell me about that.”

我告诉他，我们正在使用计算机量化文化趋势，并预测这些趋势在极端主义高发地区将如何演变。“我们试图一窥文化的命运，”我说，旨在提炼数十年来计算和社会理论的价值。班农翻了个白眼。“是啊，是啊，是啊。你别胡说了，告诉我你到底在做什么。”

I told him we were using computers to quantify cultural trends and predict how they will evolve in places at risk for extremism. “We try to glimpse into the destiny of cultures,” I said, aiming to distill decades’ worth of computational and social theory. Bannon rolled his eyes. “Yeah, yeah, yeah. You can cut the bullshit and tell me what it is you actually do.”

我们聊了四个小时——不仅谈论政治，还谈论时尚和文化、福柯、第三波女权主义者朱迪斯·巴特勒以及破碎自我的本质。从表面上看，班农似乎完全可以预测——又是一个老直男白人——但他说话时有一种我完全没有预料到的觉醒。事实上，我很快就觉得他很酷。当我们开始交换衡量文化的想法时，我提出向他展示一些我们的数据。我打开了一个 Tableau 工作簿，调出了特立尼达的地图。我点击了一个按钮，一层霓虹黄色的圆点开始填充地图。“顺便说一句，这些都是真实的人，”我说。“我们有他们的人口统计数据……性别、年龄、种族。”

We talked for four hours—not only about politics but about fashion and culture, Foucault, the third-wave feminist Judith Butler, and the nature of the fractured self. On the surface, Bannon seemed utterly predictable—another old, straight white guy—but he spoke with a certain wokeness I hadn’t expected at all. In fact, I quickly decided he was kind of cool. As we started trading ideas on measuring culture, I offered to show him some of our data. I opened a Tableau workbook and called up a map of Trinidad. I clicked a button and a layer of neon-yellow dots began to populate the map. “Those are real people, by the way,” I said. “They are the ones we have demographic data on…gender, age, ethnicity.”

我再次点击，又出现了更多的点。“现在我们添加了在线足迹——就像互联网浏览一样。”

I clicked again and more dots appeared. “And now we are adding in online footprinting—like Internet browsing.”

我再次点击。“这些是包含人口普查信息的记录……现在还有社交媒体资料。”我继续添加图层，他俯身靠近。地图越来越亮，一簇簇小点向外扩展，直到最后一次点击后，地图变得令人眼花缭乱，色彩缤纷。他问是谁付钱的，但我告诉他我说不出来。当我开始概述 DARPA 资助的社交媒体网络研究类型时，他问美国是否可以进行类似研究。

I clicked again. “And here are records with census information…and now social media profiles.” I continued to add layers and he leaned in. The map lit up more and more, with little clusters of dots growing outward until, after the final click, the map was dazzling, in a multitude of colors. He asked who had paid for it, but I told him I couldn’t say. As I started to outline the types of research into social media networks that DARPA was funding, he asked if something similar could be carried out in America.

“我不明白为什么不行，”我说。

“I don’t see why not,” I said.

—

史蒂夫·班农于 20 世纪 50 年代初出生于弗吉尼亚州一个爱尔兰裔工薪阶层天主教家庭。他在一所天主教军事高中就读，毕业于弗吉尼亚理工大学，获得城市事务学位，随后在海军担任水面作战军官，之后在五角大楼任职，负责撰写有关美国海军全球舰队状况的报告。20 世纪 80 年代，他的人生发生了学术转变——1983 年获得乔治城大学国家安全研究硕士学位，1985 年获得哈佛商学院工商管理硕士学位。在投资银行工作一段时间后，班农开始在好莱坞拍电影，担任执行制片人、导演和编剧。他参与了 30 多部电影的制作，包括一部关于罗纳德·里根的纪录片。2005 年，班农加入总部位于香港的互联网游戏娱乐公司 (IGE)，一年后他获得了 6000 万美元的投资，其中一半来自他的前雇主高盛。该公司最终更名为 Affinity Media Holdings，班农继续帮助运营该公司，直到 2012 年加入 Breitbart。接下来，班农与他人共同创立了政府问责研究所，该研究所最终出版了Breitbart News 特约编辑彼得·施魏策尔 (Peter Schweizer) 撰写的《克林顿现金》一书。

STEVE BANNON WAS BORN in Virginia in the early 1950s to a working-class Irish Catholic family. He went to a Catholic military high school and graduated with a degree in urban affairs from Virginia Tech, then served in the Navy as a surface warfare officer before a post at the Pentagon writing reports on the status of the U.S. Navy fleet worldwide. In the 1980s, his life took an academic turn—a 1983 master’s in national security studies from Georgetown University, a 1985 M.B.A. from Harvard Business School. After a tour in investment banking, Bannon moved on to making films in Hollywood as an executive producer, director, and writer. He worked on more than thirty films, including a documentary about Ronald Reagan. In 2005, Bannon joined the Hong Kong–based Internet Gaming Entertainment (IGE), and a year later he brought in a $60 million investment, half of which came from his former employer Goldman Sachs. The company eventually rebranded as Affinity Media Holdings, and Bannon continued to help run it until 2012, when he joined Breitbart. Next, Bannon co-founded the Government Accountability Institute, which eventually published the book Clinton Cash, by Breitbart News editor at large Peter Schweizer.

2005 年，右翼评论员安德鲁·布赖特巴特创办了在线新闻聚合网站 Breitbart.com，到 2007 年，该网站已发展成为以 Breitbart News 的名义发布原创内容的网站。该网站以布赖特巴特的个人哲学为底线，这种哲学被称为“布赖特巴特主义”：政治源于文化，如果保守派想要成功遏制美国的进步思想，他们就必须首先挑战文化。因此，布赖特巴特的成立不仅是为了成为一个媒体平台，也是为了成为扭转美国文化潮流的工具。

In 2005, the right-wing commentator Andrew Breitbart began Breitbart.com, an online news aggregator, and by 2007 it had grown to publish original content as Breitbart News. The site ran on the undercurrent of Breitbart’s personal philosophy, which has been referred to as the Breitbart Doctrine: Politics flows from culture, and if conservatives wanted to successfully dam up progressive ideas in America, they would have to first challenge the culture. And so Breitbart was founded to be not only a media platform but also a tool for reversing the flow of American culture.

2012 年，安德鲁·布莱巴特（Andrew Breitbart，他曾把默瑟夫妇介绍给班农）突然去世，班农接替他担任高级编辑，并接受了他的理念。我们第一次见面时，他是布莱巴特的执行主席，来到剑桥寻找有前途的年轻保守派和候选人来为他的伦敦新分社工作。正如我们后来在英国脱欧时了解到的那样，这样做的逻辑是，英国是美国人的重要文化象征。班农后来告诉我，赢得英国人的支持，美国就会倒下，因为好莱坞的神话和比喻塑造了英国是一个受过良好教育、理性、有品位的国家。但他有一个问题。尽管该网站引起了轩然大波，但它却被归类为无法找到性爱的年轻异性恋白人男性的聚集地。玩家门事件是他们文化战争中最早、最公开的事件之一：当几名女性试图揭露游戏行业中严重的厌女症时，她们遭到了跟踪、人肉搜索，甚至收到了无数死亡威胁，而这场大规模的运动就是针对那些将“女权主义意识形态”强加于游戏文化的“进步人士”。

When Andrew Breitbart (who had introduced the Mercers to Bannon) died suddenly in 2012, Bannon took his place as senior editor, and assumed his philosophy. At our first meeting, he was the executive chair of Breitbart and had come to Cambridge in search of promising young conservatives and candidates to staff his new London bureau. The logic, as we later learned with Brexit, was that Britain served as an important cultural signifier for Americans. Win the Brits, and so falls America, Bannon later told me, as the mythologies and tropes of Hollywood had crafted an image of Britain as a country of educated, rational, and classy people. He had a problem, though. For all the site’s sound and fury, it became pigeonholed as a place for young, straight white guys who couldn’t get laid. Gamergate was one of the first, most public instances of their culture war: When several women tried to bring to light the gross misogyny within the gaming industry, they were hounded, doxed, and sent numerous death threats in a massive campaign against the “progressives” imposing their “feminist ideology” onto gaming culture.

Gamergate 事件并非由 Breitbart 煽动，但它对 Bannon 来说是一个信号，他看到愤怒、孤独的白人男性在感到自己的生活方式受到威胁时会变得异常活跃。Bannon 意识到培养性欲旺盛的处男厌女情绪的力量。他们虚无主义的愤怒和“beta 起义”的言论在互联网的深处酝酿。但培养一支“非自愿独身者”大军并不足以实现他所幻想的运动。他需要找到一种新的方法。

Gamergate was not instigated by Breitbart, but it was a sign to Bannon, who saw that angry, lonely white men could become incredibly mobilized when they felt that their way of life was threatened. Bannon realized the power of cultivating the misogyny of horny virgins. Their nihilistic anger and talks of “beta uprisings” simmered in the recesses of the Internet. But growing an army of “incels” (involuntary celibates) would not be sufficient for the movement he fantasized about. He needed to find a new approach.

这是剑桥分析公司传奇中最为奇怪的时刻之一——飞机上的随机对话改变了历史。在我遇到班农的几个月前，两名共和党顾问马克·布洛克和琳达·汉森碰巧坐在一位前军官旁边，这位军官曾是一家在选举中使用“网络战”公司的分包商。布洛克在飞机上睡着了，但汉森和她的邻座开始聊天，那位男士告诉了她 SCL 在信息战方面的项目。飞机降落后，汉森告诉布洛克，他们需要联系尼克斯。布洛克曾担任赫尔曼·凯恩的竞选经理，与共和党圈子的边缘分子关系密切。他认识班农，并立即意识到 SCL 对他有吸引力。于是布洛克把班农介绍给了尼克斯，我最终在这间酒店套房里见到了后来大规模操纵美国人心理的那个人。

This is one of the odder moments in the Cambridge Analytica saga—the random airplane conversation that changed history. Several months before I met Bannon, two Republican consultants, Mark Block and Linda Hansen, happened to be sitting next to an ex–military officer who had worked as a subcontractor for a company that utilized “cyberwarfare” in elections. Block fell asleep on the flight, but Hansen and her seatmate started chatting, and the man told her about SCL’s projects in information warfare. When the flight landed, Hansen told Block they needed to contact Nix. Block, who had been the campaign manager for Herman Cain, was well connected to the fringe elements of Republican circles. He knew Bannon and understood immediately that SCL would be of interest to him. So Block connected Bannon with Nix, and I wound up in this hotel suite meeting the man who would later stage a mass manipulation of the American psyche.

当我走进 Varsity 酒店大门时，尼克斯已经在纽约与班农见过几次面。但当尼克斯试图解释我们的项目时，他遇到了一个问题——他实际上并不了解我们在做什么。他与班农处于完全陌生的领域，班农更关心研究的细节，而不是研究人员的出身。在 SCL 内部，尼克斯通常被其他董事降职，去处理“不太严肃”的客户。尼克斯的父亲是 SCL 的大股东，2007 年去世后，尼克斯在公司中变得更加活跃。他以平均成绩毕业于曼彻斯特大学艺术史专业，但比起画廊或图书馆，他更喜欢富有的朋友和家人的各种企业。

By the time I walked through the doors of the Varsity Hotel, Nix had already met with Bannon several times in New York. But when Nix tried to explain our projects, he ran into a problem—he didn’t actually understand what we were working on. He was in deeply unfamiliar territory with Bannon, who cared more about the details of the research than the pedigree of the researchers. Inside SCL, Nix was typically relegated by the other directors to deal with their “less serious” clients. Nix became more active in the company after his father, who was a large shareholder, died in 2007. He had graduated with average marks in art history from the University of Manchester but preferred the various enterprises of wealthy friends and family to galleries or libraries.

班农不是尼克斯的典型客户，尼克斯更习惯于与英国旧帝国的发展中国家的部长或商人打交道。班农不需要热带国家的第二本护照。他不想在伦敦扮演殖民者，也不关心尼克斯的发音或他定制西装的剪裁。班农想要真实的东西。对于一个习惯于用衣着暴露的乌克兰女人和伊顿公学式的醉醺醺的玩笑来勾引部长的人来说，这让他非常困惑。

Bannon was not a typical client for Nix, who was far more used to dealing with ministers or businessmen from the developing nations of Britain’s old empire. Bannon did not need a second passport from a tropical nation. He was not looking for colonial cosplay in London, and he did not care how Nix pronounced his words or about the tailoring of his bespoke suit. Bannon wanted real things. It was deeply disorienting for a man accustomed to seducing ministers with scantily clad Ukrainian women and inebriated Etonian banter.

最初，尼克斯向班农建议我们在伦敦的蓓尔美尔街见面，这条街两旁都是宏伟的石头建筑。蓓尔美尔街位于白金汉宫以北几个街区，始于特拉法加广场，止于圣詹姆斯宫，后者是几位皇室成员在 16 世纪的住所。该地区是英国一些最独特的私人绅士俱乐部的所在地，在这里，黑色领带很常见，尼克斯与他的同龄人交往，在奢华的环境中喝酒。尼克斯曾想象在卡尔顿俱乐部的私人餐厅里享用一顿丰盛的晚餐，精心策划菜单和服务人员，但在最后一刻被拒绝了。

Originally, Nix suggested to Bannon that we meet somewhere on London’s Pall Mall, a street lined with grand stone buildings. A couple of blocks north of Buckingham Palace, Pall Mall begins at Trafalgar Square and ends at St. James’s Palace, the sixteenth-century residence of several members of the royal family. The area is home to some of Britain’s most exclusive private gentlemen’s clubs, where black tie is common and Nix socialized with his peers, sucking down drinks in opulent surroundings. Nix had imagined an elaborate dinner in a private dining room at the Carlton Club, meticulously planning the menu and serving staff, only to be rebuffed at the last minute.

尽管如此，尼克斯知道，包括班农在内的每个人都渴望实现一个未实现的秘密自我。他意识到，美国人正懒洋洋地待在英国古老的大学里，扮演一个角色——当班农照镜子时，他看到的是一位哲学家。为了赢得他的信任，尼克斯需要帮助他实现成为伟大思想家的梦想。所以我的“学术”气质正是他引诱班农参与角色扮演所需要的。

Still, Nix knew that everyone, including Bannon, suffers the yearning of an unfulfilled secret self. He realized that the American was lounging in the ancient universities of England to play out a role—when Bannon looked in the mirror, he saw a philosopher. To win him over, Nix would need to help him achieve his fantasy of becoming a thinker of big thoughts. And so my “academic” vibe became just what he needed to lure Bannon into role-play.

如今，班农已声名远扬，但 2013 年秋天，当我们坐在那间酒店房间里时，我对这位来自美国的史蒂夫几乎一无所知。即便如此，我很快意识到我们是志趣相投的人。我们最终都从事政治，但我们共同的热情是文化，他志在电影，而我志在时尚。他纵容我对解构趋势的兴趣，并同意我们的许多社会规范可以归结为美学。我们都看到了科技和网络空间的蓬勃发展。他谈到了游戏玩家、表情包和 MMORPG——像《魔兽世界》这样拥有大量玩家的网络游戏。他在一句话中使用了“pwned”这个词，这是一个游戏玩家的表达方式，暗示着对对手的支配或羞辱。我们在所有让我们感到奇怪的事情上都产生了共鸣。当我们坐在一起聊天时，我发现自己出乎意料地对他感到自在。他不是政治黑客，而是一个被允许自由发言的书呆子。

Today Bannon is famous, but as we sat in that hotel room in the autumn of 2013, I knew virtually nothing about Steve from America. Even so, I quickly realized we were kindred spirits. We had ended up in politics, but our shared passion was culture, with his ambitions in film and mine in fashion. He indulged my interest in deconstructing trends and agreed that many of our social norms could be boiled down to aesthetics. And we both saw what was bubbling in tech and online spaces. He talked about gamers, memes, and MMORPGs—online games like World of Warcraft with huge numbers of players. He used the word “pwned” in a sentence, which is a gamer expression that implies domination or humiliation of a rival. We connected on all the things that made us weird. As we sat talking together, I found myself growing unexpectedly comfortable with him. He was no political hack, but a fellow nerd given permission to speak freely.

当班农说他对改变文化感兴趣时，我问他如何定义文化。他沉默了很久。我告诉他，如果你不能定义某样东西，你就无法衡量它，如果你无法衡量它，你就无法知道你是否在改变它。

When Bannon said he was interested in changing culture, I asked him how he defined culture. There was a long pause. I told him that if you can’t define something, you can’t measure it, and if you can’t measure it, you can’t know if you are changing it.

我没有深入理论，而是用文化刻板印象给班农提供了一个极其简化的文化示例。意大利人以比其他人更热情和外向而闻名。（我曾经和一位意大利人约会过，可以证明这种名声背后的事实。）虽然很明显并非所有意大利人都热情洋溢，但如果你去意大利，你可能会发现比你去德国或新加坡等国家时，意大利人性格外向的程度要高。这可以看作是一种常态——外向性或热情的钟形分布曲线上的峰值。也许意大利的峰值比其他国家高一点。

Rather than dive deep into theory, I gave Bannon a grossly simplified example of what culture is by using cultural stereotypes. Italians have a reputation for being more passionate and extroverted than other people. (Having dated one, I can testify to the grain of truth behind this reputation.) And while it’s obvious that not all Italians are loud and brimming with passion, if you visit Italy, you’ll probably find more people who are extroverted in their presentation than if you visit, say, Germany or Singapore. This can be thought of as a norm—the peak on a bell-shaped distribution curve of extroversion or loudness. And perhaps Italy peaks a bit further up the scale than other countries.

当我们描述文化时，我们使用个性的语言和词汇。我们用同样的词语来描述人和民族。一方面，我们不能在个人层面上形成刻板印象，因为每个人都是不同的。但另一方面，我们可以说，从更广泛的意义上讲，意大利文化可能比许多其他文化更外向一些。

When we describe cultures, we use the language and vocabulary of personality. We use the same words to describe both people and peoples. On the one hand, we can’t stereotype at the individual level, because every person is different. But on the other hand, we can say that, in a broader sense, Italian culture can be characterized as probably a bit more outgoing than many other cultures.

如果我们可以使用个人数据来衡量或推断个人的某些特征，然后使用这些特征来描述一种文化，我们就可以绘制出分布图，为该文化创建一个近似的指标。这个框架使我们能够提出如何使用在社交媒体、点击流或数据供应商处找到的个人数据来识别，例如，通过他们作为个人消费者和用户的行为模式，确定最外向的意大利人是谁。然后，如果有人想改变文化，使其外向程度略有降低，这些数据会给我们一份实际命名的意大利人名单，按他们的外向程度排序，我们可以随着时间的推移跟踪和定位他们，试图逐渐削弱他们的外向性。换句话说，文化变革可以被认为是推动文化分布曲线向上或向下移动。数据使我们能够将文化分解为个人，个人成为社会中可移动的单位。

If we can measure or infer certain traits in individuals using personal data, and then use those same traits to describe a culture, we can chart a distribution, creating an approximate metric for that culture. This framework made it possible for us to propose how we could use personal data found on social media, in clickstreams, or from data vendors to identify, for example, who the most extroverted Italian people are through their patterns of behavior as individual consumers and users. Then, if one wants to shift the culture to make it slightly less extroverted, this data gives us a list of actual named Italians, ordered by their degree of extroversion, whom we could track and target over time, trying to chip away at their extroversion. In other words, culture change can be thought of as nudging the distribution curve of culture up or down. What the data allowed us to do was to disaggregate that culture into individuals, who became movable units of that society.

班农是个喜欢说话的人，但当我谈到他感兴趣的话题时，他很安静，甚至很恭敬。但他也渴望回到应用上。要理解如何将这一运动变成一项实际行动，可以想想公共卫生。当一种传染病威胁到人群时，你首先要对某些媒介进行免疫——通常是婴儿和老人，因为他们最容易受到感染。然后是护士和医生、老师和公交车司机，因为他们最有可能通过广泛的社交互动传播传染病，即使他们自己没有感染这种疾病。同样的策略可以帮助你改变文化。例如，为了让一个群体更能抵御极端主义，你首先要确定哪些人容易受到武器化信息的攻击，确定使他们容易受到传染病叙事影响的特征，然后用接种反叙事来针对他们，努力改变他们的行为。当然，从理论上讲，同样的策略可以反过来使用——助长极端主义——但我甚至没有考虑过这一点。

Bannon was someone who liked to talk, but when I got into a subject that interested him, he was quiet and even deferential. But he was also eager to get back to applications. To understand how this might become a practical campaign, think of public health. When a communicable disease threatens a population, you immunize certain vectors first—usually babies and old people, as they are most susceptible to infection. Then nurses and doctors, teachers and bus drivers, as they are most likely to spread a contagion through wide social interaction, even if they do not succumb to the disease themselves. The same type of strategy could help you change culture. To make a population more resilient to extremism, for example, you would first identify which people are susceptible to weaponized messaging, determine the traits that make them vulnerable to the contagion narrative, and then target them with an inoculating counter-narrative in an effort to change their behavior. In theory, of course, the same strategy could be used in reverse—to foster extremism—but that was not something I had even considered.

—

黑客攻击的目的是找到系统的弱点，然后利用这一弱点。在心理战中，弱点就是人们思维方式的缺陷。如果你想入侵某人的思想，你需要找出认知偏见，然后利用它们。如果你在街上随意走到一个人面前，问他“你快乐吗？”，她很可能会回答“快乐”。然而，如果你走到同一个人面前，先问他“这几年你胖了吗？”或“你的高中同学中有没有比你更成功的？”，然后再问“你快乐吗？”，那个人就不太会回答“快乐”。她的个人情况或历史实际上没有任何改变。但她对生活的看法却改变了。为什么？因为在她脑海中，有一条信息比其他信息更重要。

THE GOAL IN HACKING is to find a weak point in a system and then exploit that vulnerability. In psychological warfare, the weak points are flaws in how people think. If you’re trying to hack a person’s mind, you need to identify cognitive biases and then exploit them. If you walk up to a random person on the street and ask, “Are you happy?” the chances are high that she will say yes. If, however, you walk up to that same person and first ask, “Have you gained weight in the last few years?” or “Are any people from your high school more successful than you?” and then you ask “Are you happy?”—that same person will be less inclined to answer yes. Nothing about her personal situation or history has actually changed. But her perception of her life has. Why? Because one piece of information in her mind was weighted more than the others.

我们研究的是提问者如何权衡这些信息，进而影响她对这些信息的判断。我们让她对自己生活的心理模型产生了偏见。那么哪个是正确的呢？她快乐还是不快乐？答案取决于哪些信息被拉到了她的脑海里。在心理学中，这被称为启动效应。从本质上讲，这就是你如何将数据武器化：你要弄清楚哪些突出的信息被拉到前面来影响一个人的感受、她的信仰和她的行为。

What we played with as the questioner was how she was weighting that information, which in turn affected her judgment of that information. We biased her mental model of her life. So which is true? Is she happy or not happy? The answer depends on which information is being pulled to the front of her mind. In psychology, this is called priming. And this is, in essence, how you weaponize data: You figure out which bits of salient information to pull to the fore to affect how a person feels, what she believes, and how she behaves.

除非某人的父母是秘密的瓦肯人，否则地球上没有人是纯粹理性的思考者。我们都受到认知偏见的影响，这是我们思维中常见的错误，会导致对信息产生有缺陷的主观解释。人们带着偏见处理信息是完全正常的——事实上每个人都是这样——而且这些偏见在日常生活中往往是无害的。这些偏见在每个人身上并不是随机的。相反，它们是系统性错误，这意味着它们会在常见的非理性思维形式中形成模式。事实上，心理学领域已经发现了数以千计的认知偏见。有些偏见非常常见，看似直观，人们甚至很难意识到它们实际上是非理性的。

Unless someone’s parents are secretly Vulcan, no one on earth is a purely rational thinker. We are all affected with cognitive biases, which are the commonly occurring errors in our thinking that generate flawed subjective interpretations of information. It is completely normal for people to process information with bias—in fact, everyone does—and oftentimes these biases are harmless in day-to-day life. These biases are not random in each person. Rather, they are systematic errors, meaning they create patterns in common forms of irrational thinking. In fact, thousands of cognitive biases have been identified in the field of psychology. Some biases are so common and seemingly intuitive that it can be hard for people to even recognize that they are actually irrational.

例如，心理学家阿莫斯·特沃斯基和丹尼尔·卡尼曼进行了一项研究，他们向参与者提出了一个非常简单的问题：“假设你从英文文本中随机抽取一个单词。这个单词以k 开头的可能性更大，还是k是第三个字母的可能性更大？”大多数人回答前者，即以k开头的单词（例如kitchen、kite 或kilometer ）的可能性更大。然而，事实恰恰相反，在典型的英文文本中，第三个字母为k 的单词（如ask、like、make、joke 或take ）的概率实际上是前者的两倍。他们像这样测试了五个字母（k、l、n、r 和v ）。人们更容易通过首字母来思考单词，因为我们被教导要按首字母来组织（或按字母顺序排列）单词。然而，人们会将这种容易回忆与频率或概率混为一谈，即使这与事实相去甚远。这种认知偏差称为可用性启发法，它只是影响我们思维的众多偏差之一。这种偏见就在于，为什么当人们在新闻中看到更多暴力谋杀的报道时，他们往往会认为社会正在变得更加暴力，而事实上，在过去的二十五年里，全球谋杀率总体上一直在下降。

For example, the psychologists Amos Tversky and Daniel Kahneman conducted a study that asked participants a very simple question: “Suppose you sample a word at random from an English text. Is it more likely that the word starts with a k, or that k is the third letter?” Most people responded with the former, that words that start with k (e.g., kitchen, kite, or kilometer) are more likely. However, the opposite is true, and one is actually twice as likely in a typical English text to encounter words where the third letter is a k, such as ask, like, make, joke, or take. They tested for five letters (k, l, n, r, and v) like this. It is easier for people to think of words by first letter because we are taught to organize (or alphabetize) words by their first letter. However, people conflate this ease of recall with frequency or probability, even when this is far from the truth. This cognitive bias is called the availability heuristic, and is just one of many biases that affect our thinking. The bias is why, for example, people who see more news reports of violent murders on the news tend to think that society is becoming more violent when in fact global murder rates have been declining overall during the last quarter century.

我一直在根据自己在政治、时尚和信息战方面的经验思考这些想法。例如，政治极端主义是一种文化活动，时尚与之类似：它们都基于文化信息如何通过网络节点传播。圣战主义的兴起和 Crocs 的流行都可以被视为信息流的产物。当我开始为 SCL 的反极端主义工作研究文化信息时，我借鉴了与我在时尚预测中探索的概念、方法和工具类似的概念、方法和工具——采用周期、传播率、网络同质性等。这项工作就是试图预测人们如何内化并传播文化信息——无论是加入死亡邪教还是选择衣柜。

I had been pondering these ideas based on my experiences in politics, then fashion, and then information warfare. Political extremism, for example, is a cultural activity with parallels in fashion: They’re both based on how cultural information proliferates through the nodes of a network. The rise of jihadism and the popularity of Crocs can both be thought of as the products of information flows. When I started my research into cultural information for SCL’s counter-extremism work, I drew upon similar concepts, approaches, and tools to those I was exploring in fashion forecasting—adoption cycles, diffusion rates, network homophily, etc. The work was all about trying to anticipate how people would internalize and then spread cultural information—whether that meant in joining a death cult or in choosing a wardrobe.

班农立刻就理解了这一切，甚至告诉我，他和我一样相信政治和时尚本质上是同一现象的产物。很明显，他对情报收集的态度广泛而深入，而我从未见过许多政界人士这样做。而这正是他如此强大的原因。他阅读关于交叉女权主义或身份流动性的书籍，并不是因为他对这些思想持开放态度，而是因为他想颠覆它们——找出人们所依附的东西，然后将其武器化。那天我不知道的是，班农想要打一场文化战争，所以他找到了专门研究信息武器的人来帮助他建立武器库。

Bannon immediately grasped all of this, even telling me that he believed, as I do, that politics and fashion are essentially products of the same phenomenon. It was obvious that he treated intelligence gathering in a broad and deep way, which is not something I’ve seen many people in politics do. And that’s what makes him so powerful. He reads about intersectional feminism or the fluidity of identity not, as I later learned, because he’s open to those ideas but because he wants to invert them—to identify what people attach themselves to and then to weaponize it. What I didn’t know that day was that Bannon wanted to fight a cultural war, and so he had come to the people who specialized in informational weapons to help him build his arsenal.

我和班农显然志趣相投，那天的谈话进行得非常自然，感觉就像在调情——但实际上不是，因为那样太恶心了。但从理智上讲，我们是一对。离开那次会议时，我感到振奋，并被花时间倾听的人所认可。我第一次见到班农时，他给人的印象是一个通情达理的人——甚至可以说是友善。我可以看出他喜欢学习新思想，并对它们的可能性感到兴奋。但让我印象深刻的是，这个人是一位文化专家和技术宅男。我意识到他有点自由主义倾向，但我们并没有谈论太多政治。

Bannon and I were clearly on the same wavelength, and the conversation that day flowed so naturally, it felt as if we were flirting—but not, because that would be gross. But intellectually, we were a match. I left that meeting feeling uplifted and validated by someone who had taken the time to listen. Bannon came across as a reasonable guy when I first met him—nice, even. I could tell he appreciated learning new ideas and got excited by their possibilities. But what struck me was how this guy was a cultural maven and a tech nerd. I realized he had a bit of a libertarian streak, but we hadn’t talked that much about politics.

然后我想起我丢了钱包。我打电话给尼克斯告诉他事情进展如何——我需要一张新票。“克里斯，我很忙，你自己处理吧。”

Then I remembered I had lost my wallet. I called Nix to tell him how everything had gone—and that I needed a new ticket. “Chris, I’m busy, sort it out yourself.”

—

班农对我们工作的兴趣不仅仅是学术上的；他对 SCL 有远大的想法。他告诉尼克斯，一位主要的右翼捐助者可能会被说服投资该公司。罗伯特·默瑟是一位不寻常的亿万富翁。他在 20 世纪 70 年代初获得了计算机科学博士学位，然后在 IBM 工作了二十多年。1993 年，他加入了一家名为文艺复兴科技的对冲基金，在那里他使用数据科学和算法来指导他的投资——并因此赚了一大笔钱。默瑟不是那种疯狂买卖企业的投机取巧者。他是一位极其内向的工程师，将他的技术技能非常具体地应用于赚钱的艺术和科学上。

BANNON’S INTEREST IN OUR work wasn’t merely academic; he had big ideas for SCL. He told Nix of a major right-wing donor who might be persuaded to make an investment in the firm. Robert Mercer was unusual for a billionaire. He’d gotten a Ph.D. in computer science in the early 1970s, then went on to become a cog in the wheel at IBM for twenty-some years. In 1993, he joined a hedge fund called Renaissance Technologies, where he used data science and algorithms to inform his investments—and made a stupid amount of money doing it. Mercer wasn’t one of these wheeler-dealer types who frenetically bought and sold businesses. He was an extremely introverted engineer who applied his technical skills very specifically to the art and science of making money.

多年来，默瑟已经向保守派竞选活动捐赠了数百万美元。他还创办了默瑟家族基金会，由当时 39 岁的女儿丽贝卡管理，该基金会最初支持研究和其他慈善事业，但后来也开始向参与政治的非营利组织捐款。他的财富​​和影响力使他与科赫兄弟和谢尔登·阿德尔森一起成为共和党捐赠者。默瑟可能愿意投资 SCL 的消息让尼克斯垂涎欲滴。默瑟的形象是颠覆金融业。文艺复兴是业内表现最好的对冲基金之一——默瑟通过放弃传统金融背景，而是聘请物理学家、数学家和科学家来构建他的公司算法来建立这家公司。但默瑟似乎希望我们尝试一种更雄心勃勃的盈利颠覆版本。通过分析一个国家的每个公民，推断他们的性格和独特行为，并将这些资料放入该社会的计算机模拟中（在计算机内部创建），我们将构建人造社会的第一个原型。如果我们可以在具有与其所代表的实际人相同特征的人工代理模拟中玩弄经济或文化，我们可能就能够创建迄今为止最强大的市场情报工具。通过添加量化的文化信号，我们即将进入类似于“文化金融”的新领域。我们认为，如果我们做对了，我们就可以模拟整个社会的不同未来。忘掉做空公司吧；想想整个经济体。

Over the years, Mercer had donated millions of dollars to conservative campaigns. He also started the Mercer Family Foundation, run by his then-thirty-nine-year-old daughter, Rebekah, which originally supported research and other charities, but had begun to also donate to politically involved nonprofit groups. His wealth and influence placed him alongside the Koch brothers and Sheldon Adelson in the pantheon of Republican donors. The news that Mercer might be willing to invest in SCL made Nix salivate. Mercer’s profile was one of disrupting the financial sector. Renaissance was one of the highest-performing hedge funds in the industry—and Mercer built the firm by eschewing traditional finance backgrounds and instead hiring physicists, mathematicians, and scientists to build his firm’s algorithms. But Mercer, it seemed, wanted us to attempt an even more ambitious version of profitable disruption. By profiling every citizen in a country, imputing their personalities and unique behaviors, and placing those profiles in an in silico simulation of that society (one created inside a computer), we would be building the first prototype of the artificial society. If we could play with an economy or culture in a simulation of artificial agents with the same traits as the actual people they represented, we could just possibly create the most powerful market intelligence tool yet imagined. And by adding quantified cultural signals, we were verging on a new area of something akin to “cultural finance.” We thought that if we got it right, we could run simulations of different futures of whole societies. Forget shorting companies; think about entire economies.

事实证明，Mercer 所考虑的不仅仅是经济，但当时我们的重点是展示 SCL 的能力。经过一番深思熟虑，班农决定我们应该在弗吉尼亚州进行概念验证，弗吉尼亚州感觉就像美国的一个很好的缩影。它有点偏北，又有点偏南。它有山区和沿海地区、军事城镇、富裕的华盛顿特区郊区、农村和农场，以及富人和穷人、黑人和白人的横截面。弗吉尼亚州的实验标志着我们第一次在美国玩数据。就像我与 LPC 和自由民主党所做的那样，我们从定性研究开始——与当地人进行非结构化的开放式对话。SCL 团队中没有美国人，我们对弗吉尼亚州一无所知，对我来说，弗吉尼亚州和加纳一样陌生。显然，第一步是访问该州并与当地居民交谈，了解他们如何看待世界以及他们关心什么。除非他们以自己的方式和环境向我们介绍自己，否则我们无法提出问题。一旦我们更好地了解弗吉尼亚人关心什么以及他们如何处理事情，我们就可以构建具体问题进行定量研究。政治和文化是如此紧密地交织在一起，以至于人们通常无法只研究其中一个而忽略另一个。

It turned out that what Mercer had in mind went beyond the economy, but at the time our focus was on demonstrating what SCL was capable of doing. After some deliberation, Bannon decided that we should run a proof of concept in Virginia, which felt like a good microcosm of America. It’s a little bit northern and a little bit southern. It has mountains and coastal areas, military towns, wealthy D.C. suburbs, rural areas and farms, and a cross section of rich and poor, black and white. The Virginia experiment would mark the first time we’d played with data in the United States. As I’d done with the LPC and the Lib Dems, we started off with qualitative research—unstructured, open-ended conversations with local people. Nobody on the SCL team was American, and we didn’t know anything about Virginia, which was as foreign to me as Ghana. The obvious first step was to visit the state and talk to people, to learn how they perceived the world and what mattered to them. We couldn’t generate questions until they had introduced themselves to us, in their own way and in their own environment. Once we had a better feel for what Virginians cared about and how they approached things, we could then structure specific questions for quantitative research. Politics and culture are so intertwined that one cannot usually study one without the other.

于是，我和马克·盖特森、布伦特·克利卡德以及其他几个人一起飞往美国，于 2013 年 10 月抵达弗吉尼亚州，当时该州即将举行全州选举。我们在焦点小组中听到的一件事是对共和党州长候选人、前州检察长肯·库奇内利的担忧。他属于极右翼，曾倡导削减同性恋权利和反对环境保护的举措。弗吉尼亚州的共和党拥有庞大的福音派基督教选民群体，库奇内利要想获胜，就需要这些选民的支持。但是，正如我们在研究中发现的那样，他为了争取选民的选票而拼命争取，结果却超出了目标。

So, along with Mark Gettleson, Brent Clickard, and a few others, I flew to America, arriving in Virginia in October 2013, shortly before statewide elections there. One of the things we heard in focus groups was concern about the Republican candidate for governor, the former state attorney general Ken Cuccinelli. He was a super-right-wing type who had advocated for initiatives to roll back gay rights and fight environmental protections. The Republican Party in Virginia has an enormous bloc of evangelical Christian voters, and Cuccinelli needed them if he was going to win. But, as we discovered in our research, he went so hard after their votes, he overshot his mark.

库奇内利的举措之一是向联邦法院请愿，要求撤销对弗吉尼亚州“违反自然罪”法的裁决。该法最初于 1950 年通过，并于 2013 年被美国第四巡回上诉法院正式推翻（鉴于 2003 年美国最高法院决定将成年人之间自愿的性行为合法化），从技术上讲，该法禁止口交和肛交。库奇内利认为，该法是打击恋童癖所必需的。从纸面上看，他让我想起了我们在非洲部分地区遇到的疯狂政客，他们痴迷于同性恋和他们的卧室罪恶。但社会极端分子和怪人随处可见，即使在白人美国也是如此。

One of Cuccinelli’s initiatives was to petition a federal court to reverse its ruling on Virginia’s “Crimes Against Nature” law. Originally passed in 1950 and formally struck down in 2013 by the U.S. Fourth Circuit Court of Appeals (in light of a 2003 U.S. Supreme Court decision to decriminalize sexual activity between consenting adults), the statute technically outlawed oral and anal sex. Cuccinelli argued that the law was needed to combat pedophilia. On paper, he reminded me of crazed politicians we’d encountered in parts of Africa, obsessed with gays and their bedroom sins. But social extremists and weirdos can be found anywhere, even in white-bread America.

我们焦点小组的成员——尤其是那些直男、精力充沛的美国男人——一直在说他们认为这有多奇怪。禁止同性恋行为当然是可以的，但为什么要禁止所有非生殖性行为呢？库奇内利为什么如此反对口交？让我们面对现实吧——这不是有点奇怪吗？这些男人一直在说他们不喜欢想象库奇内利和口交，谁能责怪他们呢？我们一直听到关于这个问题的消息，所以我们决定尝试一个实验。

People in our focus groups—particularly straight, red-blooded American men—kept saying how weird they thought this was. Ban the gay stuff, sure, but why ban all non-procreative sex? Why was Cuccinelli so opposed to blow jobs? Let’s be real—isn’t that a little weird? These guys kept talking about how they didn’t like thinking about Cuccinelli and getting head, and who could blame them? We kept hearing about this issue, so we decided to try an experiment.

在五因素人格模型中，保守派往往表现出两种特征的组合：开放性较低和责任心较高。最普遍的是，共和党人不太可能寻求新奇事物或对新体验表现出好奇心（隐秘情况显然是例外）。同时，他们喜欢结构和秩序，不喜欢惊喜。民主党人更开放，但往往也不太有责任心。这在一定程度上解释了为什么政治辩论往往围绕行为和个人责任中心展开。

In the five-factor model of personality, conservatives tend to display a combination of two traits: lower openness and higher conscientiousness. In the most general way, Republicans aren’t likely to seek out novelty or to express curiosity about new experiences (with closet cases being the obvious exception). At the same time, they favor structure and order, and they don’t like surprises. Democrats are more open but also often less conscientious. This is in part why political debates often center around behavior and the locus of personal responsibility.

我们的定性研究告诉我们，除其他事项外，弗吉尼亚州共和党人对库奇内利对口交的痴迷感到反感。心理测试也告诉我们，共和党人不喜欢不可预测性。我们能否利用这两项观察结果制定一项策略，以改变人们对库奇内利的看法？

Our qualitative research told us, among many other things, that Virginia Republicans were put off by Cuccinelli’s obsession with blow jobs. And psychometric testing also told us that Republicans don’t like unpredictability. Could we create a strategy, using those two observations, to move the needle of opinion on Cuccinelli?

盖特森的才华就体现在这里。他特别着迷于阿尔法男性选民和库奇内利与他们之间的矛盾，但他也知道，在信息方面，要找到穿针引线是件很棘手的事。所以他专注于怪异因素。人们之所以不感兴趣，是因为他们认为库奇内利很奇怪。如果他的信息承认了这一点，会怎么样？我们决定测试一条信息，简单地说：“你可能不同意，但至少你知道我的立场。”这样一来，即使人们认为他的立场很疯狂，至少他可以把它变成一种可预测且有序的疯狂。

This was where Gettleson’s brilliance came into play. He was particularly fascinated by alpha-male voters and Cuccinelli’s conundrum with them, but he also knew it would be tricky to thread the needle in terms of message. So he focused on the weirdness factor. People were put off because they thought Cuccinelli was being weird. What if his messaging acknowledged that? We decided to test a message that simply stated, “You might not agree, but at least you know where I stand.” That way, even if people thought his position was crazy, at least he could turn it into a predictable and ordered kind of crazy.

我们召集了焦点小组、在线小组和数字广告测试来试用这句口号，结果它胜过我们尝试过的所有其他信息——尽管它本质上毫无意义。这是一个重大的发现：我们能够通过定制候选人的信息来匹配选民的心理测试，从而影响他们的观点。而且由于许多共和党人都表现出这些性格特征，所以这种框架——我就是我，你知道我的立场——可能对其他共和党人同样有效。这种策略在责任心得分高、对库奇内利不确定的人中效果更好。对他们来说，它将库奇内利描述为“你所认识的魔鬼”，并将他突出的“怪癖”定位为至少是一种可靠的怪癖。

We convened focus groups, online panels, and digital ad tests to try out the slogan, and it outperformed all the other messages we tried—even though it was essentially meaningless. This was a big realization: We were able to sway voters’ opinions by tailoring the candidate’s message to match their psychometric tests. And because so many Republicans display these personality traits, that framing device—I am who I am, and you know where I stand—would probably work equally well for other Republicans. This strategy performed better among high scorers in conscientiousness who had been unsure about Cuccinelli. For them, it framed Cuccinelli as “the devil you know” and positioned his salient “quirkiness” as at least a reliable quirkiness.

事实证明，共和党人可以接受一个疯狂的候选人，只要他始终疯狂。这一发现后来为剑桥分析公司所做的几乎所有工作提供了参考。当然，从这里开始，候选人就可以吹嘘说他可以站在第五大道中间开枪打死某人而不会失去支持。

It turns out that Republicans can accept a batshit insane candidate, so long as it’s consistent insanity. This finding later informed almost everything that Cambridge Analytica worked on. From there, of course, it’s a short jump to having a candidate brag that he could stand in the middle of Fifth Avenue and shoot somebody without losing support.

—

在我们的实验过程中，我们收集了大量有关弗吉尼亚州人民的个人信息。这些信息很容易获得——我们只需通过 Experian、Acxiom 等数据经纪人和拥有福音派教会、媒体公司等专家名单的利基公司购买访问权即可。甚至一些州政府也会向你出售狩猎、捕鱼或持枪许可证持有者的名单。州政府部门是否关心，甚至是否愿意询问，这些公民的数据去了哪里？没有。我们可能是骗子或外国间谍，他们不会有任何线索。

IN THE COURSE OF our experiment, we compiled reams of personal information about the people of Virginia. It was easy to get—we just bought access to it through data brokers such as Experian, Acxiom, and niche firms with specialist lists from evangelical churches, media companies, and so on. Even some state governments will sell you lists of hunting, fishing, or gun licensees. Did the state government bureaus care, or even bother to ask, where this data on their citizens was going? Nope. We could have been fraudsters or foreign spies and they wouldn’t have had a clue.

大多数人都知道 Experian 是一家消费者信用报告公司。该公司最初就是这么做的，根据各种财务因素计算人们的信用评分。该公司会从各种来源收集信息——航空公司会员、媒体公司、慈善机构，甚至游乐园。它还从政府机构收集信息，例如 DMV、钓鱼和狩猎许可证以及枪支许可证。在编制这些详细资料时，该公司意识到可以利用它们进行营销来赚取额外的收入。

Most people know Experian as a consumer credit reporting company. That’s how it started out, calculating credit scores for people based on a variety of financial factors. The company would collect information from a wide array of sources—airline memberships, media companies, charities, even amusement parks. It also gathered information from government agencies, such as the DMV, fishing and hunting licensing, and gun licensing. As it compiled these detailed profiles, the company realized it could make additional money using them for marketing.

20 世纪 90 年代，政治战略家开始购买个人信息用于竞选。想想看：如果你知道一个人开什么车或卡车、是否打猎、捐助什么慈善机构以及订阅什么杂志，你就可以开始形成这个人的形象。许多民主党人和共和党人都会看一眼。他们的外表被记录在这张数据快照中。然后你可以根据这些信息锁定潜在选民。

In the 1990s, political strategists started buying personal information to use in campaigns. Think about it: If you know what kind of car or truck a person drives, whether they hunt, what charities they give to, and what magazines they subscribe to, you can start to form a picture of that person. Many Democrats and Republicans have a look. And their look was captured in this data snapshot. You can then target potential voters based on that information.

我们还获得了人口普查数据。与隐私控制不那么严格的发展中国家不同，美国政府不会提供特定个人的原始数据，但你可以获得县或社区层面的犯罪、肥胖以及糖尿病和哮喘等疾病的信息。一个人口普查区块通常包含六百到三千人，这意味着通过结合许多数据来源，我们可以建立模型来推断个人的这些属性。例如，通过参考糖尿病的风险或保护因素，如年龄、种族、位置、收入、对健康食品的兴趣、餐馆偏好、健身房会员资格和过去使用减肥产品（所有这些都可以在大多数美国消费者档案中找到），我们可以将这些数据与有关某个地区糖尿病发病率的汇总统计数据进行匹配。然后，我们可以为给定社区中的每个人创建一个分数，衡量他们患有糖尿病等健康问题的可能性——即使人口普查或消费者档案本身从未直接提供过这些数据。

We also got access to census data. Unlike developing nations with less stringent privacy controls, the U.S. government won’t provide raw data on specific individuals, but you can get information, down to the county or neighborhood level, on crime, obesity, and illnesses such as diabetes and asthma. A census block typically contains six hundred to three thousand people, which means that by combining many sources of data, we could build models that infer those attributes about individuals. For example, by referencing risk or protective factors for diabetes, such as age, race, location, income, interest in health food, restaurant preference, gym membership, and past use of weight-loss products (all of which are available in most U.S. consumer files), we could match that data against aggregated statistics about a locality’s diabetes rates. We could then create a score for each person in a given neighborhood measuring the likelihood that they had a health issue like diabetes—even if the census or consumer file never directly provided that data on its own.

我和盖特森花了几个小时探索随机而奇怪的属性组合。有人有枪证，但也是美国公民自由联盟 (ACLU) 的成员吗？有人有交响乐季票和终身美国步枪协会会员资格吗？同性恋共和党人真的存在吗？有一天，我们发现自己想知道，反同性恋教堂的捐赠者是否也会在有机食品店购物。我们搜索了为试点项目获得的消费者数据集，发现少数人的数据显示他们同时做这两件事。

Gettleson and I spent hours exploring random and weird combinations of attributes. Were there people who had gun licenses but also belonged to the ACLU? Were there people who had season tickets to a symphony and a lifetime NRA membership? Are gay Republicans even real? One day we found ourselves wondering whether there were donors to anti-gay churches who also shopped at organic food stores. We did a search of the consumer data sets we had acquired for the pilot and found a handful of people whose data showed that they did both.

我立刻就想见见这些神秘人物中的一位，部分原因是我很好奇，但也因为我想确保我们的数据是准确的。我们把出现的名字拉出来，然后把它们送到呼叫中心，客服人员会给每个人打电话，询问他们是否愿意与研究人员见面回答一些问题。大多数人都说不，但有一位女士同意了——我迫不及待地想见见她。她的消费习惯似乎很复杂——她喜欢瑜伽，喜欢全食超市，也是一名反同性恋教会的成员和右翼慈善机构的捐助者——这让我怀疑我们的数据要么有误，要么这个人是美国最迷人的人物之一。

I instantly wanted to meet one of these mythical creatures, in part because I was curious but also because I wanted to make sure our data was accurate. We pulled the names that came up, then sent them to a call center, where agents phoned each person to ask if they’d be willing to meet with a researcher to answer some questions. Most said no, but there was one woman who agreed—and whom I couldn’t wait to meet. Her spending habits seemed all over the map—a Whole Foods shopper with an interest in yoga, but also a member of an anti-gay church and a donor to right-wing charities—which made me suspect that either our data was somehow faulty or this person was among the most fascinating characters in the United States.

这位女士的数据将我引导到费尔法克斯县郊区一栋不起眼的错层式住宅。有那么一刻，我犹豫了。“呃，这会不会很尴尬？”但我已经走了这么远，所以我走到门口按响了门铃。我听到头顶上传来风铃声。然后，一位头发蓬乱的金发女郎打开了门，几乎扑向我。“嘿！！！进来吧！”当我们进屋时，我注意到她确实穿着 Lululemon 瑜伽裤。她带我进入她的客厅，里面有香火味，有佛像和印度教象头神 Ganesh 的雕像。然后我发现墙上有一个十字架。这一切都很特别。

The woman’s data guided me to a modest split-level in the suburbs of Fairfax County. For a moment, I hesitated. “Ugh, is this going to be awkward?” But I’d come all this way, so I walked up to the door and rang the bell. I heard wind chimes just over my head. Then a perky blonde with blown-out hair opened the door and almost leapt at me. “HEYYYY!!! Come on in!” As we entered the house I noticed she was indeed wearing Lululemon yoga pants. She showed me into her living room, which smelled of incense and had statues of both Buddha and the elephant-headed Hindu god Ganesh. Then I spotted a crucifix on the wall. It was all pretty extra.

她递给我一杯自制的康普茶，我接受了。在厨房里，她打开了一个大罐子，往杯子里倒了一杯非常成熟、略带凝结的液体。

When she offered me a glass of homemade kombucha, I accepted. In the kitchen, she opened a large jar of something and poured an extremely ripe and slightly coagulated liquid into a glass.

“它确实是益生菌。”

“It’s really probiotic.”

“是的，我能看出来，”我看着玻璃杯中漂浮的块状物回答道。

“Yeah, I can tell,” I answered, looking at the floating chunks in the glass.

我们开始聊天时，她用新时代的术语说要“调和她的正能量”，毫无疑问，这是受到她书架上的狄巴克·乔布拉的启发。但当我们开始谈论道德时，她突然转向了火与硫磺的福音派观点——尤其是关于同性恋者，她知道这些人会直接下地狱（没有双关语的意思）。然而，她表达这种信念的方式也是一种奇怪的混合：她说同性恋就像是你能量中的一块障碍物——一块罪恶的障碍物。她向我传道了两个小时，而我坐在那里草草地记笔记，好像我们是某种混乱的治疗会议的参与者。

As we started talking, she spoke in New Age terms about trying to “align her positive energy,” inspired, no doubt, by the Deepak Chopra on her bookshelf. But when we started talking about morality, she shifted abruptly into fire-and-brimstone evangelical views—particularly about gay people, who she knew were going straight to hell (no pun intended). Yet even the way she expressed that belief was a strange amalgamation: She said that being gay was like a block in your energy—a sinful block. She evangelized to me for two hours as I sat there scribbling notes, as though we were participants in some kind of messed-up therapy session.

那次会面让我脑子里充满了想法。我觉得自己发现了一些重要的东西，因为民意调查员到底会如何对这个女人进行分类？这让我确信我们需要投入更多精力来了解人口统计学背后的细微差别。我曾经见过灵长类动物学家简·古道尔，她说了一句话，让我印象深刻。在一次招待会上，我问她为什么研究野生灵长类动物而不是在受控实验室中。原因很简单，她说：因为它们不生活在实验室里。人类也不。如果我们要真正了解人类，我们必须始终记住他们生活在数据集之外。

I came away from that encounter swirling with ideas. I felt like I was on to something important, because how the hell would a pollster classify this woman? This convinced me we needed to invest more in understanding the nuances behind the demographics. I once met the primatologist Jane Goodall, and she said something that always stuck with me. Mingling at a reception, I asked why she researched primates in the wild instead of in a controlled lab. It’s simple, she said: Because they don’t live in labs. And neither do humans. If we are to really understand people, we have to always remember that they live outside of data sets.

令人惊奇的是，人们很容易被自己感兴趣的东西所吸引。我们是一家英国军事承包商，致力于实现伟大的创意，我们的团队不断壮大，其中大多数是同性恋，大多数是自由派数据科学家和社会研究人员。那么，我们为什么要开始与这种由对冲基金经理、计算机科学家和一个经营小众右翼网站的人组成的不拘一格的团队合作呢？因为这个想法很棒。我们可以自由地研究文化这种抽象而流动的东西，从而进入研究社会的新领域。如果我们能把社会放进计算机，我们就可以开始量化一切，把贫困和种族暴力等问题封装在计算机中；我们可以模拟如何解决这些问题。就像那位女士没有看到她偶像中的矛盾一样，我还没有看到我所做的事情中的矛盾。

It’s amazing how easy it is to get drawn into something you are interested in. We were a British military contractor, working on big ideas, with a growing team of mostly gay and mostly liberal data scientists and social researchers. So why had we started working with this eclectic mix of hedge fund managers, computer scientists, and a guy who ran a niche right-wing website? Because the idea was a killer one. With free rein to study such an abstract and fluid thing as culture, we could be breaking into a new field of researching societies. If we could put society into a computer, we could start to quantify everything and encapsulate problems like poverty and ethnic violence in a computer; we could simulate how to fix them. And just as the woman did not see the contradictions in her idols, I did not yet see the contradiction in what I was doing.

第五章

CHAPTER 5

剑桥分析公司

CAMBRIDGE ANALYTICA

-

在 2013 年秋季的家访和焦点小组讨论中，我们发现弗吉尼亚州是美国生活的典型代表。我们从费尔法克斯出发，穿过该州中部，然后前往诺福克和弗吉尼亚海滩，在当地的酒吧和夫妻餐馆停留，我们喜欢那里的氛围和食物。事实上，你可以从人们的饮食和说话方式中学到很多东西。在我们发现甜茶和某些食物的文化意义后，它们成了我们的最爱。如果说美国南部传统上是由旧的梅森-迪克森线划定的，这条线标志着奴隶主和自由州之间的边界，那么现代弗吉尼亚州则有一条不同的分界线，北部的餐馆供应不加糖的茶，而南部的餐馆供应加糖的茶。当地人告诉我们，“真正的南部”从这里开始——甜茶线不仅在梅森-迪克森以南，而且比里士满更南。

In the course of home visits and focus groups in the autumn of 2013, we found Virginia contained a quintessential cross section of American life. We toured from Fairfax through the middle of the state, and then headed down to Norfolk and Virginia Beach, stopping in at local bars and mom-and-pop restaurants, where we welcomed the ambience as much as the sustenance. Indeed, you can learn a lot from the ways people eat, drink, and talk. Sweet tea and certain foods became pet obsessions after we discovered their cultural significance. If the American South was traditionally delineated by the old Mason-Dixon Line, which marked the border between slave owners and free states, a different divide cut through contemporary Virginia, where restaurants to the north served tea unsweetened and those to the south served it sweet. Here began the “real South,” the locals informed us—at the Sweet Tea Line, not just south of Mason-Dixon but farther south than Richmond too.

我最喜欢的活动是观察和聆听那些同意让我们与他们共度时光的美国人。我会坐在沙发上，偷听人们谈论他们的一天，或者他们在收音机里听到的内容，或者办公室政治。我会观察人们观看福克斯新闻，并注意到他们会变得多么愤怒（因为我来自一个没有福克斯新闻的国家，所以这是最有趣的事情之一）。这是一种奇怪的表现，因为他们会坐下来等待——并且期待——被“精英”当天对他们所做的一切侮辱。他们会对福克斯发火，他们的愤怒变得显而易见。有时我似乎在目睹一场治疗，比如当人们在沮丧的一周后在愤怒的房间里砸东西时。这与我通常看到的朋友偶然看到福克斯新闻时的情况形成了鲜明的对比。我清楚地记得阿利斯泰尔·卡迈克尔曾经把一个大喊大叫、脸红的福克斯新闻记者称为“被打耳光的人”。

My favorite activities were to watch and listen to the Americans who agreed to let us spend time with them. I would sit on the sofa and eavesdrop on people talking about their day, or what they heard on the radio, or office politics. I would watch people watching Fox News and notice how furious they would get (which, because I came from a country without Fox News, was one of the most interesting things to see). It was a weird performance, as they would sit down waiting—and expecting—to be insulted by whatever the “elites” had done to them that day. They would flip on Fox and their rage became palpable. Sometimes I seemed to be witnessing a therapy session, like when people smash things in a rage room after a frustrating week. This was quite the juxtaposition to what I was normally used to seeing when my friends would happen to stumble upon Fox News. I distinctly remember Alistair Carmichael once referred to a shouty, red-faced Fox News correspondent as a “slapped arse.”

一对夫妇告诉我，他们欠了数千美元的保险免赔额，有时他们会因为当月要修理汽车而省下药费。他们同意接受采访，因为他们收到的 100 美元将使他们更接近支付下个月的费用。但他们将自己的保险费用归咎于谁？不是他们雇主的糟糕健康计划或缺乏体面的薪水——他们指责奥巴马医改。他们真心认为，奥巴马医改只是为了帮助更多无证工人来到美国，这是一项自由社会工程的宏伟计划，目的是通过更多倾向于民主党的拉丁裔选民让民主党继续执政，在他们看来，这让保险和医院变得更加昂贵。

One couple told me about the thousands of dollars they owed for their insurance deductibles and how they would sometimes skimp on their prescriptions because they had to repair their car that month. They’d agreed to the interview because the $100 they received would get them closer to covering next month’s costs. But who did they blame for their insurance costs? Not their employer’s bad health plan or a lack of decent pay—they blamed Obamacare. They genuinely thought it was rolled out simply to help more undocumented workers come to America in a grand plan of liberal social engineering to keep the Democrats in power through more Democrat-leaning Latino voters, which in their minds made insurance and hospitals more expensive.

在福克斯新闻愤怒室待上一个小时后，人们会感觉一天好多了——他们可以发泄压力，事后他们在工作或家庭中遇到的问题都是别人的错。这意味着他们的挣扎可以完全外化，让他们免于面对严峻的现实：他们的雇主可能并不关心他们，不给他们生活工资。承认自己被每天见到的人利用，而不是被奥巴马医改和“非法移民”的无名敌人利用，这太痛苦了。

People would feel better about their day after an hour-long session in the Fox News rage room—they could groan out their stress, and afterward their problems at work or home were someone else’s fault. It meant that their struggles could be wholly externalized, sparing them the stark reality that maybe their employer didn’t care enough about them to give them a living wage. It would be too painful to admit that perhaps they were being taken advantage of by someone they saw every day rather than the faceless enemy of Obamacare and “illegals.”

这是我看福克斯新闻时间最长的一次，我脑子里想的都是这个电视台如何将人们的身份认同感塑造成可以当作武器的东西。福克斯用夸张的叙述激起人们的愤怒，因为愤怒会破坏人们寻求、合理化和权衡信息的能力。这导致了一种心理偏见，称为情感启发式，人们会使用受到情绪显著影响的心理捷径。正是这种偏见让人们在愤怒中说出后来后悔的话——事实上，在当时他们的想法不同。

This was my longest exposure to Fox News, and all I could think about was how the network was conditioning people’s sense of identity into something that could be weaponized. Fox fuels anger with its hyperbolic narratives because anger disrupts the ability to seek, rationalize, and weigh information. This leads to a psychological bias called affect heuristic, where people use mental shortcuts that are significantly influenced by emotion. It’s the same bias that makes people say things they later regret in a fit of anger—in the heat of the moment they are, in fact, thinking differently.

福克斯的观众放下了警惕，然后被告知他们是“普通美国人”群体的一部分。这种身份被反复强调，这就是为什么主持人多次提到“我们”并与观众直接交谈。观众被提醒，如果你真的是一个“普通美国人”，这就是你——即“我们”——的想法。这让人们开始进行身份动机推理，这是一种偏见，它本质上让人们接受或拒绝信息是基于它如何建立或威胁群体身份，而不是基于内容的优点。这种动机推理就是民主党人和共和党人为什么可以观看完全相同的新闻节目并得出相反的结论。但我开始明白福克斯之所以有效，是因为它把一种身份植入了观众的头脑中，然后观众开始把关于思想的辩论解读为对他们身份的攻击。这反过来又引发了一种反抗效应，即不同的观点实际上加强了观众对他们最初信念的决心，因为他们感觉到对他们个人自由的威胁。民主党人对福克斯的诱饵批评得越多，观众的观点就越根深蒂固，他们就越愤怒。例如，观众可以拒绝对唐纳德·特朗普发表种族主义言论的批评：他们将批评内化为对自己身份的攻击，而不是对候选人身份的攻击。这会产生一种潜在的影响，辩论越多，观众就越根深蒂固。

With their guards down, Fox’s audience is then told they are part of a group of “ordinary Americans.” This identity is hammered home over and over, which is why there are so many references to “us” and direct chatting to the audience by the moderators. The audience is reminded that if you are really an “ordinary American,” this is how you—i.e., “we”—think. This primes people for identity-motivated reasoning, which is a bias that essentially makes people accept or reject information based on how it serves to build or threaten group identity rather than on the merits of the content. This motivated reasoning is how Democrats and Republicans can watch the exact same newscast and reach the opposite conclusion. But I began to understand that Fox works because it grafts an identity onto the minds of viewers, who then begin to interpret a debate about ideas as an attack on their identity. This in turn triggers a reactance effect, whereby alternative viewpoints actually strengthen the audience’s resolve in their original belief, because they sense a threat to their personal freedom. The more Democrats criticized Fox’s bait, the more entrenched the audience’s views and the angrier they became. This is how, for example, viewers could reject criticism of Donald Trump for saying racist things: They internalized the critique as an attack on their own identity rather than that of the candidate. This has an insidious effect in which the more debate occurs, the more entrenched the audience becomes.

在进行这项研究的过程中，我也开始以不同的方式看待社会和经济上处于弱势地位的白人。很明显，种族主义和仇外情绪的部分根源是一种受到威胁的感觉，而福克斯新闻等媒体不断发出的明显“警告”则强化了这种感觉。我注意到美国有线新闻频道上的热门政治辩论存在一个问题，即在给选民贴标签时缺乏细微差别。白人选民、拉丁裔选民、女性选民、郊区选民等经常被当作单一的、单一的群体来讨论，而事实上，许多选民身份的显著方面并没有真正反映出民意调查员、分析师或顾问用来描述他们的标签。这反过来又疏远了某些人。例如，如果你是一个住在拖车里的白人，当你在电视上看到有人坚持认为白人在这个国家享有超级特权时，你可能会生气。如果你从小就使用户外厕所，那么你可能不会容忍关于跨性别者是否应该使用自己选择的厕所的大讨论。如果你属于中下阶层，看到黑人领取福利，如果你生活在一个不断削减你支持率的州，你的态度会是“好吧，我的福利怎么办？”这并不奇怪。这并不是为了捍卫这些观点，但如果我们想理解它们，我们必须对其他观点保持开放态度，即使是丑陋的观点。

Doing this research, I also began to see socially and economically deprived white people in a different way. It was clear that part of what underpins racist and xenophobic sentiment is a feeling of being threatened, reinforced through constant and salient “warnings” from sources like Fox News. One of the problems I noticed with the topical political debates on American cable news channels is the lack of nuance in labeling voter constituencies. White voters, Latino voters, women voters, suburban voters, etc., are all frequently discussed as unidimensional and monolithic groups, when in fact the salient aspects of many voters’ identities do not actually reflect the labels that pollsters, analysts, or consultants use to describe them. And this in turn alienates certain people. If you’re a white man living in a trailer, for example, you’re probably going to get angry when you are shown people on TV who are insisting that white people are super-privileged in this country. If you grew up using an outhouse, you probably don’t have much tolerance for a big discussion about whether trans people should be able to use the toilets of their choice. If you’re lower middle class and you see a black person on welfare, it’s not surprising that your attitude would be “Well, what about my welfare?” if you live in a state that has continually cut your support. This is not to defend these views, but if we want to understand them, we have to remain open to other perspectives, even ugly ones.

作为我们对美国文化的早期探索的一部分，我们研究了我们认为可能在这种社会不和谐中发挥作用的两个领域。首先，我们研究了社会身份威胁感是否助长了这些观点。第二个领域与此相关，但略有不同。人们普遍存在的一个逻辑谬误是将世界视为赢家和输家的零和游戏。这种有缺陷的逻辑延伸到这样一种观点：关注其他群体最终意味着对他们这样的人的关注减少。无论如何，少数群体似乎都是“威胁”——身份威胁或资源威胁。根据这种潜在威胁感的假设，我们想看看我们是否可以减轻其中一些感觉，我们通过尝试减少威胁感来做到这一点。在一项研究中，我们要求人们想象他们是不可战胜的超级英雄，不会被伤害或杀死。然后，我们询问他们通常认为具有威胁性的人的类型——同性恋、移民、其他种族的人——结果发现他们对这些“威胁性”刺激的反应更为温和。如果你无敌，就没有什么可以威胁到你，即使是同性恋者。这对我和团队来说非常有趣，因为我们正在探索缓解种族紧张的潜在因素的可能方法。通过每次实验，我们更多地了解如何根据人们内心深处的特质来操纵结果。

As part of our early exploration of American culture, we looked at two areas we thought might be at play in this social discord. First we looked at whether a sense of social identity threat was fueling some of these views. The second area was related but slightly different. A common logical fallacy that people have is seeing the world as a zero-sum game of winners and losers. This flawed logic extends into a perception that attention paid to other groups will ultimately mean less attention for people like them. Either way, minorities seemed to be “threats”—identity threats or threats to resources. Following this hypothesis of an underlying sense of threat, we wanted to see if we could mitigate some of these feelings, and we did so by trying to reduce the sense of threat. We would ask people in one study to imagine they were invincible superheroes who couldn’t be harmed or killed. We then asked them about types of people they ordinarily considered threatening—gays, immigrants, people of other races—and found that they had a more muted response to those “threatening” stimuli. If you are invincible, nothing can threaten you, not even the gays. This was fascinating for me and the team, as we were unpacking possible ways to mitigate underlying factors for racial tension. With each experiment, we learned more about how to manipulate outcomes according to people’s innermost traits.

我们在弗吉尼亚州的工作取得了令人鼓舞的成果。我们表明，人格特质与政治结果之间存在关联，我们不仅可以预测某些行为，还可以通过将信息语言与心理测量资料相对应来改变态度。我们知道，尽管我们在这个小沙箱中使用的数据集相当不错，但它们仍然不足以辨别人格和身份的所有细微差别。为了真正在计算机中重建社会，我们需要找到更完整的数据——更多的数据。但这是未来要解决的问题。

Our work in Virginia yielded promising results. We showed that there were relationships between personality traits and political outcomes, and that we could not only predict certain behaviors but also shift attitudes by framing the language of messages to correspond to psychometric profiles. We knew that even though the data sets we used were pretty decent in this little sandbox of pilots, they were still woefully inadequate for discerning all the nuances of personality and identity. In order to truly re-create society in silico, we would need to find even more complete data—way more data. But that was a problem to be solved in the future.

尼克斯给了我们一周时间撰写一份报告，而这份报告通常需要两个月才能完成。他急于开始行动，因为他知道这关系到什么。班农告诉他，美世可能会投资高达 2000 万美元。对于像 SCL 这样每年预算在 700 万至 1000 万美元之间的小众公司来说，这将是一笔改变游戏规则的资金。

Nix gave us a week to write a report that would normally have taken two months to do. He was anxious to get the ball rolling, because he knew what was at stake. Bannon had told him that Mercer might invest up to $20 million. For a niche firm like SCL, which had an annual budget in the range of $7 million to $10 million, this would be a game-changing amount of money.

经过通宵加班和周末加班的工作，我们在下周一将报告发给了班农，他立即明白了我们能取得的成果。他完全同意。事实上，他在阅读报告后给 SCL 办公室打了电话，几乎欣喜若狂。“伙计们，这太棒了，”他不停地说。

After pulling late nights and working through the weekend, we sent the report to Bannon the following Monday, and he immediately understood the possibilities of what we could accomplish. He was fully on board. In fact, he called the SCL office after reading the report and was almost giddy. “This is so great, guys,” he kept saying.

现在我们只需要说服罗伯特·默瑟。

Now we just had to persuade Robert Mercer.

—

几周后，2013 年 11 月下旬的一个晚上，尼克斯打电话到我家。“收拾行李，”他说。“你明天要飞往纽约。”他、塔达斯·朱西卡斯和我准备向罗伯特·默瑟和他的女儿丽贝卡汇报我们的发现。

A COUPLE OF WEEKS after this, one evening in late November 2013, Nix called me at home. “Pack a bag,” he said. “You’re flying to New York tomorrow.” He, Tadas Jucikas, and I were going to present our findings to Robert Mercer and his daughter Rebekah.

尼克斯一早就飞走了，但不知为何，他为我和朱西卡斯订了一班较晚的航班。我们下午四点左右抵达肯尼迪机场，会议定于五点开始。当我们在美国海关排队时，我的电话响了。是尼克斯打来的。“你他妈的在哪儿？”他问道。

Nix flew out first thing in the morning, but for some reason he’d booked Jucikas and me on a later flight. We landed at JFK around four in the afternoon, with our meeting scheduled to start at five. As we stood in line at U.S. customs, my phone rang. It was Nix. “Where the fuck are you?” he demanded.

“我们刚下飞机，”我告诉他。

“We just got off the plane,” I told him.

“好吧，你迟到了，”他厉声说道。“你最好快点过来。”

“Well, you’re late,” he snapped. “You’d better hurry up and get here.”

“我不能就这样挥挥手就通过护照检查！”我恼火地说。当我们在电话里争吵时，队列中的其他人都转过头去。我们继续争吵，直到一名海关官员对我大吼大叫，让我挂断电话。事情还没结束。尼克斯反复给我打电话——当我们上车时，当我们到达酒店时，当我换衣服去开会时。这是典型的尼克斯，计划不周，指望我把所有事情都解决好。我很生气，决定把手机调成静音，慢慢地做准备，主要是为了惹恼他。我和朱西卡斯打车去开会，会议地点是丽贝卡·默瑟在上西区的公寓。丽贝卡和她的丈夫，一位名叫西尔万·米罗奇尼科夫的法国金融家，在河滨大道特朗普广场的遗产区买了六套公寓，把它们合并成一套有十七间卧室的巨大住宅。该空间占据了二十三、二十四和二十五层的大部分区域，可以看到哈德逊河上下的壮丽景色，点缀着纽约的所有灯光。

“I can’t just wave myself through passport control!” I said, exasperated. As we squabbled on the phone, others in the queue turned their heads. We continued arguing until a customs official barked at me to get off the phone. And that wasn’t the end of it. Nix called me repeatedly—as we got in the car, when we arrived at the hotel, and as I changed clothes to come to the meeting. This was typical Nix, planning poorly and expecting me to fix everything. Irritated, I decided to put my phone on silent and take my time getting ready, mostly just to vex him. Jucikas and I took a cab to the meeting, which was at Rebekah Mercer’s apartment on the Upper West Side. Rebekah and her husband, a French financier named Sylvain Mirochnikoff, had bought six apartments at the Heritage at Trump Place, on Riverside Boulevard, combining them into one gigantic seventeen-bedroom home. The place took up most of the twenty-third, twenty-fourth, and twenty-fifth floors, with spectacular views up and down the Hudson, dotted with all the lights of New York.

但这也显得俗气，因为丽贝卡随意地用一些手工艺品装饰了它：陶瓷小雕像、靠垫、节日装饰品。客厅里，她有一架华丽的钢琴，钢琴上面堆满了小摆设和相框里的家庭照片。

But it was also tacky, as Rebekah had decorated it with random artsy-craftsy touches: ceramic figurines, throw pillows, holiday decorations. In the living room, she had a magnificent grand piano, and on top of it was a clusterfuck of knickknacks and framed family photos.

丽贝卡是个有趣的例子。她在斯坦福大学学习生物学和数学，并获得了运筹学和工程经济系统硕士学位。后来，她跟随父亲进入文艺复兴科技公司从事交易工作，但当她开始在家教育孩子时，她离开了。2006 年，她和姐妹们在曼哈顿买了一家面包店，所以她的生活主要围绕着孩子和巧克力块饼干。她有一种超级活泼的气质，就像某种右翼啦啦队队员。而且因为她有很多钱可以捐，所以她在共和党圈子里很有影响力。与更愤世嫉俗的共和党官员不同，她患有马克·布洛克所说的“结核病”——她是这些保守运动的忠实信徒。

Rebekah was an interesting case. She had studied biology and mathematics at Stanford and earned a master’s in operations research and engineering economic systems. She had then followed her father into trading at Renaissance Technologies but left when she began homeschooling her children. In 2006, she and her sisters bought a bakery in Manhattan, so her life became primarily about kids and chocolate chunk cookies. She had a super-perky air about her, like some kind of right-wing cheerleader. And because she had so much money to give, she was an influential person in GOP circles. Unlike more cynical Republican Party operatives, she had what Mark Block called “TB”—she was a true believer in these conservative crusades.

我走进客厅，看到丽贝卡和尼克斯坐在一张双人沙发上。他们俩有说有笑，尼克斯则展现出自己的魅力。房间里挤满了人——鲍勃·默瑟、班农、布洛克、支持英国脱欧的右翼英国独立党 (UKIP) 的几位老人，以及一群西装革履的男士，我猜他们是律师或企业顾问。还有其他几位默瑟家的人也在场，包括鲍勃的妻子戴安娜、他们的女儿詹妮弗和几个孙子孙女。这是一场家庭聚会。

I walked into the living room and saw Rebekah sitting on a loveseat with Nix. The two of them were chatting and laughing, Nix turning on the charm. The room was packed with people—Bob Mercer, Bannon, Block, a couple of old men from the pro-Brexit right-wing U.K. Independence Party (UKIP), and a collection of guys in suits who I assumed were lawyers or corporate advisers. Several other Mercers were also there, including Bob’s wife, Diana, their daughter Jennifer, and a few grandchildren. This was a family affair.

默瑟与他的女儿们完全相反，她们华而不实、喋喋不休。他很少看任何人，大部分时间只是倾听。他穿着一身朴素的灰色西装，尽管我们是在他女儿家吃晚饭。大部分谈话都是由他的女儿或随行人员进行的。他令人生畏，非常严肃，几乎完全不说话。当他说话时，他的语气很平淡。他只问与我们工作非常技术性方面相关的问题，并且总是希望我提供具体的统计数据。

Mercer was the antithesis of his daughters, who were gaudy and garrulous. He rarely looked at anyone and mostly just listened. He wore a plain gray suit, even though we were at his daughter’s house for dinner. Most of the talking was done by his daughters or his entourage. He was intimidating, deeply serious, and almost entirely nonverbal. When he did speak, his tone was flat. He asked only questions related to very technical aspects of our work and always wanted me to give specific statistics.

时间到了，尼克斯站起来，简短地介绍了 SCL 的背景、我们为军队所做的工作，以及该公司通常不会像现在这样纵容私人客户（这是谎言），但默瑟一直坚持要找他，这让他筋疲力尽。我不得不忍住不翻白眼。然后尼克斯介绍了我，并开始完全错误地描述这个项目。他显然没有读过这份长篇报告，所以就开始编造调查结果。我知道默瑟会一眼看穿他的胡说八道，所以我打断了他，描述了我们在弗吉尼亚所做的事情。尼克斯坐在丽贝卡旁边，怒视着我。在讨论这个项目时，我添加了一些更有趣的细节来吸引默瑟一家。当我提到康普茶女士，把她描述成一个热爱瑜伽和有机食品的福音派基督徒时，丽贝卡脱口而出，“这太像我了！终于有人理解我们了！”

When the time came, Nix stood up and gave a short speech about SCL’s pedigree, our work for the military, and how the firm didn’t normally indulge private clients as we were now (a lie) but how Mercer’s persistence at chasing him had worn him down. I had to stop myself from rolling my eyes. Nix then introduced me and started describing the project wholly incorrectly. He clearly had not read the long report and so just started making up findings. I knew Mercer would see right through his bullshit, so I interrupted to describe what we’d done in Virginia. Nix glared at me as he sat down beside Rebekah. In discussing the project, I added some of the more colorful details to draw the Mercers in. When I mentioned Kombucha Lady, describing her as an evangelical Christian who loved yoga and organic foods, Rebekah blurted, “That’s so me! Finally, someone understands us!”

我还谈到了 SCL 在其他地区的项目——中东、北非、加勒比地区。谈到特立尼达项目时，我看到班农在我描述用计算机复制社会的想法时点头致意。这也引起了鲍勃·默瑟的注意，因为作为一名工程师，他对这部分特别感兴趣。在我加入 SCL 之后，我意识到 DARPA 资助的信息传播研发项目只是换了个名字的文化趋势预测。收集社交媒体数据以使用算法分析用户只是开始。一旦推断出他们的行为属性，就可以运行模拟来绘制他们如何大规模地相互交流和互动。这让我想起了 1990 年代在社会学的一个叫做“人工社会”的小众领域进行的实验，其中涉及使用粗糙的多智能体系统在计算机中“培育”社会的尝试。我记得十几岁时读过艾萨克·阿西莫夫的《基地》系列，其中科学家利用有关社会的大型数据集创建了“心理史学”领域，这使得他们不仅能够预测未来，还能控制未来。

I also talked about SCL’s projects in other regions—the Middle East, North Africa, the Caribbean. When I got to the Trinidad project, I could see Bannon nodding his head as I described the idea of replicating society in silico. It also got Bob Mercer’s attention, because as an engineer he was especially interested in this part. After I started at SCL, I had realized that the information propagation R&D projects that DARPA was funding were just cultural trend forecasting by another name. Harvesting social media data to profile users with an algorithm was just the beginning. Once their behavioral attributes were inferred, simulations could be run to map out how they would communicate and interact with one another at scale. This brought to mind experiments from the 1990s in a niche field of sociology called “artificial societies,” which involved attempts by crude multi-agent systems to “grow” societies in silico. I could remember as a teenager reading Isaac Asimov’s Foundation series, where scientists used large data sets about societies to create the field of “psychohistory,” which allowed them to not only predict the future but also control it.

默瑟曾让文艺复兴科技公司的员工参与 SCL 的最初规划，鉴于尼克斯非常注重金钱，而对冲基金是该项目早期阶段的一部分，每个人都以为这会成为一项商业活动。说得粗略一点，如果我们能复制每个人的数据资料并在计算机中复制社会——就像游戏《模拟人生》一样，但使用的是真实人物的数据——我们就可以模拟和预测社会和市场会发生什么。这似乎是默瑟的目标。如果我们创造了这个人造社会，我们认为我们将即将创造出世界上最强大的市场情报工具之一。我们将进入一个新领域——文化金融和对冲基金趋势预测。

Mercer had involved people from his company Renaissance Technologies in the original scoping of SCL, and, given that Nix was so focused on money and a hedge fund was part of the early stages of this project, everyone was under the impression that this was going to become a commercial venture. To put it crudely, if we could copy everyone’s data profiles and replicate society in a computer—like the game The Sims but with real people’s data—we could simulate and forecast what would happen in society and the market. This seemed to be Mercer’s goal. If we created this artificial society, we thought we would be on the threshold of creating one of the most powerful market intelligence tools in the world. We would be venturing into a new field—cultural finance and trend forecasting for hedge funds.

计算机工程师转行做社会工程师的默瑟希望重构社会并优化其成员。他的爱好之一是建造模型火车，我感觉他认为他可以让我们为他建造一个模型社会，让他不断修改直到完美。通过量化人类行为和文化互动的许多内在方面，默瑟最终意识到他可以掌握信息战中的 Uber。而且，就像 Uber 用一个应用程序摧毁了百年历史的出租车行业一样，他的冒险也将对民主产生同样的影响。

Mercer, the computer engineer turned social engineer, wanted to re-factor society and optimize its people. One of his hobbies is building model train sets, and I got the feeling that he thought he could, in effect, get us to build him a model society for him to tinker with until it was perfect. By taking a leap at quantifying many of the intrinsic aspects of human behavior and cultural interaction, Mercer eventually realized that he could have at his disposal the Uber of information warfare. And, like Uber, which decimated the hundred-year-old taxi industry with a single app, his venture was about to do the same with democracy.

班农的目标则截然不同。他不是传统的共和党人。事实上，他讨厌米特·罗姆尼式的共和党人，认为他们奉行空洞的资本主义。他讨厌艾恩·兰德，因为她将人物化为商品。他会谈论经济需要更高的目标，有时称自己为马克思主义者，这并非出于意识形态，而是为了表明一个观点——马克思谈到人类实现目标。他自称相信佛法，这是印度教和佛教的教义，与宇宙秩序和正确、和谐的生活方式有关。他觉得自己的使命是找到美国的目标。在他看来，现在是革命的正确时机：他从金融危机和对机构信任度下降中看到了几个信号，预示着一场大清算即将来临。班农的追求是近乎宗教的，他扮演着救世主的角色。

Bannon’s goal was fundamentally different. He was no traditional Republican. In fact, he hated Mitt Romney–style Republicans for what he saw as their vapid capitalism. He loathed Ayn Rand, because she objectified people into commodities. He would talk about how an economy needed a higher purpose and sometimes referred to himself as a Marxist, less out of ideology than to make a point—that Marx talked about humans fulfilling a purpose. He claimed to believe in dharma, a tenet of Hinduism and Buddhism that has to do with order in the universe and proper, harmonious ways of living. He felt his mission was to find America’s purpose. In his mind, the time was right for a revolution: He saw several signals from the financial crisis and a decaying trust in institutions that foretold of a great reckoning looming on the horizon. Bannon’s quest was quasi-religious, with him assuming the role of messiah.

因此，和默瑟一样，班农也讨厌“大政府”，但他有自己的理由——因为他看到行政国家取代了传统和文化所扮演的角色。对他来说，欧盟是罪魁祸首，一个极端的、无趣的官僚机构取代了传统——让欧洲成为一个毫无意义的经济市场。在班农看来，西方世界似乎正在​​迷失方向，放弃其文化传统，转向毫无意义的消费主义和一个没有面孔的国家。对班农来说，这是一场全面的文化战争。作为一名自封的先知，班农想要一种工具来窥视我们社会的未来。班农称Facebook 是上帝之眼，可以观察每个公民，他可以努力为每个美国人找到佛法。这样一来，我们的研究对他来说几乎变成了精神上的。
