So, like Mercer, Bannon hated “big government,” but for his own reason—because he saw the administrative state replacing the roles played by tradition and culture. For him, the EU was a chief offender, a sterile bureaucracy replacing tradition in the extreme—leaving Europe to become an economic marketplace devoid of meaning. The Western world seemed to Bannon as if it were losing its way by abandoning its cultural traditions for meaningless consumerism and a faceless state. For Bannon, this was a full-on culture war. As a self-anointed prophet, Bannon wanted a tool to peer into the future of our societies. And with what Bannon called Facebook’s God’s-eye view of each and every citizen, he could work to find the dharma for every American. In this way our research became almost spiritual for him.

尼克斯、班农和默瑟都对彼得·蒂尔的数据挖掘公司 Palantir 非常着迷，该公司的名字来自 JRR 托尔金的《指环王》中的水晶球，即全视之眼。当时，我觉得这些人想通过投资 SCL 来创建自己的私人 Palantir。想象一下默瑟这样的投资者的潜力：预测未来人们会买什么和不买什么，以便赚更多的钱。如果你能预见到即将来临的危机，你就拥有了全视社会的球体：你可能一夜之间赚到数十亿美元。

Nix, Bannon, and Mercer were all fascinated with Palantir, Peter Thiel’s data-mining firm, whose name comes from the crystal ball, or all-seeing eye, from J.R.R. Tolkien’s Lord of the Rings. At the time, it seemed to me that these men wanted to create their own private Palantir by investing in SCL. Imagine the possibilities for an investor like Mercer: Predict the future of what people will buy and not buy, in order to make more money. If you can see a crash coming, you have the all-seeing orb for society: You might make billions overnight.

我吃完饭后，丽贝卡邀请大家到餐厅。厨房工作人员端上了一盘盘精美的菲力牛排，但丽贝卡知道我不吃肉，所以请厨师为我准备了一道特别的菜。原来是烤奶酪三明治——我想至少她尝过了。她伸手到我的盘子里拿了一个，咬了一口后，心满意足地叹了口气。“其实我要这个只是因为我想吃一个，”她吐露道。

When I finished, Rebekah invited everyone into the dining room. The kitchen staff brought out plates of filet mignon with a delicate garnish, but, knowing that I didn’t eat meat, Rebekah had asked the chef to prepare a special dish for me. It turned out to be grilled cheese sandwiches—I suppose at least she’d tried. She reached over to my plate to grab one and, after taking a bite, sighed with contentment. “I actually just asked for these because I wanted one,” she confided.

“你知道吗，”她说，“我很高兴像你这样的人能给我们机会。我们需要更多像你这样的人。”

“You know,” she said, “I’m so glad that someone like you is giving us a chance. We need more of your kind of people.”

“哦，你是什么意思？”我天真地问道。当然，我完全明白她的意思，但我希望她大声说出来。

“Oh, what do you mean?” I asked innocently. Of course, I knew exactly what she meant, but I wanted her to say it out loud.

“顺便说一句，我爱同性恋者！”

“The gays—who I love, by the way!”

我思索着她是如何做到既热爱同性恋，又支持压迫同性恋的事业的。不过话说回来，我参加过许多晚宴，人们一边大嚼牛排，一边谈论他们有多爱动物。

I pondered how she squared the mental gymnastics of both loving the gays and also supporting causes to oppress them. But then again, I’ve been to many dinners where people talk about how much they love animals as they tear into a steak.

丽贝卡希望吸引更多 LGBT 人士加入共和党，相信这会壮大共和党。然后她说她喜欢我的夹克，并建议我们什么时候一起去购物。丽贝卡很笨拙，而且被尼克斯巧妙地操纵着，我几乎为她感到难过。但并不完全如此。

Rebekah wanted to entice more LGBT people into the Republican ranks, believing it would strengthen the party. She then said she loved my jacket and suggested we go shopping together sometime. Rebekah was so awkward, and so expertly manipulated by Nix, I almost felt sorry for her. But not quite.

用餐结束后，鲍勃让所有人离开，只留下尼克斯、丽贝卡和律师。他决定投资——自掏腰包 1500 万到 2000 万美元。“我们将创造一个真正的真知晶球， ”尼克斯说。“我们将真正看到会发生什么。”

At the end of the meal, Bob asked everyone to leave except for Nix, Rebekah, and the lawyers. He had made the decision to invest—somewhere between $15 million and $20 million of his own money. “We’ll create an actual palantír,” Nix said. “We’ll literally be able to see what’s going to happen.”

—

口袋里有高达 2,000万美元的钱，尼克斯心情很激动。我们见面后的第二天晚上，他带我和 Jucikas 去 Eleven Madison Park 吃了一顿丰盛的晚餐，这是一家拥有拱形天花板的米其林星级餐厅。他大张旗鼓地翻阅酒单，然后指示服务员给我们端来一瓶拉菲罗斯柴尔德酒——一瓶价值 2,000 美元的葡萄酒。

WITH UP TO $20 million in the bag, Nix was in a giddy mood. The night after our meeting, he took Jucikas and me to a lavish dinner at Eleven Madison Park, a Michelin-star venue with vaulted ceilings. He ostentatiously flipped through the wine list, then directed the waiter to bring us the Château Lafite Rothschild—a $2,000 bottle of wine.

“随你喜欢，”他一边说，一边大手大脚地挥舞着手臂。这真是一个惊喜，因为尽管尼克斯很富有，但他却很吝啬，甚至对办公用品等最小的开支都抱怨不已。有一次，他拒绝了一笔费用报销，因为有人买了“太多”的荧光笔，他说：“你不需要超过一支。”但那天晚上，他点了几十道菜，简直是一场亚瑟王盛宴。他为自己的奢华而自豪。

“Get whatever you like,” he said, waving his arm grandly. This was a pleasant surprise, because, despite his wealth, Nix was cheap and complained about even the smallest expenses, such as office supplies. He once rejected an expense claim because someone bought “too many” highlighters, saying, “You don’t need more than one.” But on this evening he ordered what seemed like dozens of dishes, an Arthurian feast. He was flush with his own magnificence.

侍者端来了酒，他刚给我们倒满酒杯，尼克斯就挥动手臂，把酒瓶从桌子上打翻在地。酒水滴得到处都是，侍者还没来得及抽出手臂毛巾擦干净，尼克斯就喊道：“再来一杯！”我一定惊呆了，因为他眨眨眼说：“当你有 2000 万美元时，这真的不重要，不是吗？”

The waiter brought the wine, and no sooner had he filled our glasses than Nix flailed his arm in conversation and knocked the bottle off the table. Hundred-dollar droplets spewed everywhere, and before the waiter even had a chance to whip off his arm towel and clean it up, Nix exclaimed, “Bring us another!” I must have looked at him agape, because he winked and said, “When you have $20 million, it doesn’t really matter, does it?”

夜晚变成了一场狂欢。不知怎么的，几个穿着紧身裙的女人出现了，其他食客显然大吃一惊。“克里斯，你想要一个吗？”他问我，直到我提醒他我不喜欢女人，好像谁都需要提醒似的，他脱口而出，“哦，你想让我给你找个流浪汉吗？”我不知道该怎么回答，但尼克斯只是继续说。然后他给我讲了一个关于他在伊顿公​​学的时光的故事，以及那些时髦男孩似乎为了好玩而做的事情。整个场景令人无比尴尬，而且情况越来越糟。

The night turned into a full-on bacchanalia. Somehow a couple of women in tight skirts materialized, to the evident shock of other diners. “Chris, do you want one?” he asked me, until I reminded him that I was not into women, as if anyone needed reminding, and he blurted, “Oh, do you want me to find you a bum boy?” I didn’t know how to respond, but Nix just kept talking. He then told me a story about his time at Eton and what posh boys apparently do for fun. The whole scene was beyond mortifying, and it just kept getting worse.

餐厅的管理层不得不想办法处理我们。我们的账单现在已经有几万美元了，所以他们不能在我们付钱之前就把我们赶出去。Jucikas 和 Nix 已经完全不在乎了，但我坐在那里看着每个人都看着我们。然后，显然是一次有组织的行为，十几个服务员突然在房间里散开，和其他桌子上的客人低声说话。所有的客人都从桌子上站起来，走进隔壁的餐厅，而服务员则收拾吃了一半的主菜和酒瓶，巧妙地把大家从我们造成的骚动中带走。

At some point, the restaurant’s management had to figure out what to do with us. Our bill by now was in the tens of thousands of dollars, so they couldn’t just throw us out before we’d paid. Jucikas and Nix were too far gone to care, but I was sitting there watching everyone watch us. Then, in what was obviously a coordinated move, a dozen waiters suddenly fanned out in the room, whispering to the guests at the other tables. All the guests rose from their tables as one and walked into an adjoining dining room while the waiters picked up half-eaten entrees and bottles of wine and deftly resettled everyone away from the ruckus we were causing.

我开始觉得那晚有些阴暗的先见之明。后来我才知道，混乱和破坏是班农活跃意识形态的核心原则。在催化美国的佛法再平衡之前，他的运动首先需要在整个社会中引发混乱，以便出现新的秩序。他是一位计算机科学家和空谈哲学家的狂热读者，这位哲学家自称孟子·莫尔德巴格 (Mencius Moldbug)，他是另类右翼的英雄，他写长篇大论攻击民主和几乎所有关于现代社会秩序的东西。莫尔德巴格对“真相”的看法影响了班农，也影响了剑桥分析公司的发展。莫尔德巴格曾写道：“胡说八道是一种比真相更有效的组织工具”，班农也接受了这一观点。“任何人都可以相信真相，”莫尔德巴格写道。“它是政治制服。如果你有制服，你就有军队。”

I’ve come to think that there was something darkly prescient about that night. Chaos and disruption, I later learned, are central tenets of Bannon’s animating ideology. Before catalyzing America’s dharmic rebalancing, his movement would first need to instill chaos throughout society so that a new order could emerge. He was an avid reader of a computer scientist and armchair philosopher who goes by the name Mencius Moldbug, a hero of the alt-right who writes long-winded essays attacking democracy and virtually everything about how modern societies are ordered. Moldbug’s views on “truth” influenced Bannon and what Cambridge Analytica would become. Moldbug has written that “nonsense is a more effective organizing tool than the truth,” and Bannon embraced this. “Anyone can believe in the truth,” Moldbug writes. “It serves as a political uniform. And if you have a uniform, you have an army.”

默瑟的投资被用来资助 SCL 的一个分支，班农将其命名为剑桥分析公司。我只能想象，如果鲍勃和丽贝卡·默瑟看到他们的投资促成了如此令人激动的享乐主义闹剧，他们会怎么想。另一方面，史蒂夫·班农可能会喜欢它。

Mercer’s investment was used to fund an offshoot of SCL, which Bannon named Cambridge Analytica. I can only imagine what Bob and Rebekah Mercer would have thought if they had seen the pulsating hedonistic shit show their investment had enabled. Steve Bannon, on the other hand, probably would have loved it.

—

那是 2014 年春天，晚上十点，距离在纽约吃晚餐已经过去了几个月，当我们飞速穿过田纳西州的乡村时，一股冷风突然袭来，让我的头脑和肺部都清醒了。司机马克·布洛克 (Mark Block) 烟瘾很大，他开车时把车子开得热气腾腾，迫使我们不得不打开车窗。盖特森和我坐在车后座。当我们沿着荒凉的道路行驶时，一股股尼古丁的烟雾飘散在黑暗中，周围是漆黑的森林。我回到了美国，为剑桥分析公司 (Cambridge Analytica) 设立试点项目，而布洛克是我的向导。作为 SCL 介绍班农的人，布洛克对这个项目的潜力感到兴奋，尽管他无法帮助我们建立模型，但他对美国了如指掌。

IT WAS SPRING 2014 and ten o’clock at night, several months after the dinner in New York, and as we sped through rural Tennessee, a sudden rush of chilly air cleared my head and lungs. The chain-smoking driver, Mark Block, had hotboxed the car, forcing us to open the windows. In the back of the car sat Gettleson and me. Clouds of nicotine escaped into the dark as we drove along desolate roads, surrounded by inky forests. I was back in the United States, setting up pilot projects for Cambridge Analytica, and Block was my guide. As SCL’s introducer to Bannon, Block was excited about the potential of this project, and although he wasn’t able to help build our models, he knew America like the back of his hand.

“我在后面拿了些啤酒，”布洛克说。“来一杯吧。”为什么不呢？我想，于是啤酒和谈话开始流淌。布洛克是我遇到过的最迷人的另类右翼人物之一——既是一个超级友好的中西部人，脸上带着温暖的笑容，又是一个经验丰富的共和党特工，在尼克松执政期间磨练了自己的能力。

“I got some beers in the back,” Block said. “Have one.” Why not? I thought, and the beer and conversation began to flow. Block was one of the more fascinating alt-right characters I’d encountered—both a super-friendly midwesterner with a warm smile and a seasoned GOP operative who had cut his teeth in the Nixon years.

“让我告诉你为什么尼克松是我们最好的总统之一，”他突然说道。

“Let me tell you why Nixon was one of our best presidents,” he said out of the blue.

“好吧，我会咬——为什么？”

“Okay, I’ll bite—why?”

“因为他和老鼠做过爱。”

“Because he fucked rats.”

“等——什么？”

“Wait—what?”

“民主党人。他搞过很多民主党人，”他笑着说。“那时候你什么事都能逍遥法外。”

“Democrats. He fucked so many Democrats,” he laughs. “Back then you could get away with anything.”

“哦哦，是的。”

“Ohhhhh, right.”

“这就是我的公司被称为 Block RF 的原因。”

“It’s why my firm is called Block RF.”

威斯康星州选举委员会曾禁止布洛克在该州竞选，原因是在法官竞选连任期间涉嫌暗箱操作，不过后来布洛克自愿支付了 15,000 美元罚款，没有承认任何不当行为，这一问题得以解决。在担任科赫兄弟的美国繁荣组织（一个 501(c)(4)“社会福利”组织）负责人期间，他创建了一个庞大的右翼组织网络，一个监督组织将其称为“Blocktopus”。对他来说，政治与思想或政策无关——对于像丽贝卡·默瑟这样的忠实信徒来说，那都是胡说八道。对他来说，政治就是游击战，他可以扮演切·格瓦拉。

Block had once been barred by the Wisconsin State Elections Board from running campaigns in that state because of alleged shady dealings during a judge’s reelection bid, although this was later resolved through Block voluntarily paying a $15,000 fine without any admission of wrongdoing. In his years as head of the Koch brothers’ Americans for Prosperity, a 501(c)(4) “social welfare” group, he’d created a vast network of right-wing organizations that one watchdog group dubbed the “Blocktopus.” For him, politics was not about ideas or policy—that was all bullshit for the true believers like Rebekah Mercer. For him, politics was guerrilla warfare, where he could play Che.

布洛克的另一个成功之作是赫尔曼·凯恩（Herman Cain）无意中拍出的“吸烟广告”。2012 年，凯恩竞选总统时，布洛克担任他的幕僚长。在竞选广告中，他大部分时间都在喋喋不休，镜头紧紧对准他的脸。他的灰色小胡子凌乱地垂在紫色的嘴唇上，嘴唇因吸烟而焦黑。

Another of Block’s coups was Herman Cain’s accidentally brilliant “smoking ad.” As Cain’s chief of staff when he ran for president in 2012, Block appeared in a campaign spot in which he mostly just rambled, the camera zooming in tight on his face. His gray mustache fell messily over his purple lips, charred from the cigarettes he smoked.

“我真的相信赫尔曼·凯恩会把‘联合’重新带回美利坚合众国，”他摇着头说道。广告结束时，他盯着镜头，吸了一口烟，随意地吐出烟雾，背景中响起克里斯塔·布兰奇的歌曲《我是美国！》。这几乎令人震惊，因为联邦通信委员会早在 1971 年就禁止在电视和广播上播放香烟广告。但这是布洛克的个人风格，他用这种方式向政治正确性竖中指。

“I really believe that Herman Cain will put the ‘United’ back in the United States of America,” he says, shaking his head for emphasis. As the ad closes, he stares into the camera and sucks on a cigarette, casually exhaling smoke while the Krista Branch song “I Am America!” swells in the background. This was almost shocking, as the FCC had banned cigarette advertisements on TV and radio back in 1971. But it was Block’s personal touch, his way of flipping the bird to political correctness.

我喜欢和布洛克一起玩——他是个很可爱的人，总是会问你过得怎么样，尽管我也知道他会毫不犹豫地在竞选中坑你。我们聊得越多，我越觉得他并不真的相信另类右翼所代表的仇恨思想——他只是接受了反抗的美学。他喜欢自己在共和党内作为永恒反叛者的角色，我们因共同反抗建制的乐趣而结缘。

I enjoyed hanging out with Block—he was quite an endearing guy and would always ask how you were doing, though I also knew that he wouldn’t hesitate to screw you over on a campaign. The more we talked, the more it seemed to me that he didn’t really believe in the hateful ideas the alt-right stood for—he just embraced the aesthetics of revolt. He relished his role as an eternal rebel with a cause inside his niche of the Republican Party, and we bonded over our mutual enjoyment of defying the establishment.

这就是我们开始为剑桥分析公司工作的过程，这个改变历史的项目推动了英国脱欧、唐纳德·特朗普的当选以及个人隐私的消亡：我们在美国各地进行热盒攻击。

And that’s how we began our work for Cambridge Analytica, the history-changing project that would fuel Brexit, the election of Donald Trump, and the death of personal privacy: hotboxing our way across the United States.

—

2014 年初， CA 派往美国进行焦点小组研究的第一批人是社会学家和人类学家，其中没有一个是美国人。这是有意为之。美国人倾向于认为自己的国家是例外，但我们希望像研究任何国家一样研究它，使用相同的语言和社会学方法。以这种方式探索美国非常有趣，而且因为我自己不是美国人，所以我觉得我更能够打破对美国文化的固有假设，注意到美国人自己看不到的东西。当谈到其他地方发生的事情时，美国人会谈论“部落”、“政权”、“激进化”、“宗教极端分子”、“种族冲突”、“当地迷信”或“仪式”。人类学是为其他人而不是美国人而设的。美国据说是“山巅之光”，这是罗纳德·里根 (Ronald Reagan) 广为推广的术语，改编自圣经中的登山宝训。

IN EARLY 2014, the first people CA sent over to the United States to do focus groups were sociologists and anthropologists, none of whom were American. This was intentional. There’s a tendency among Americans to see their country as exceptional, but we wanted to study it like we would study any country, using the same language and sociological approaches. It was fascinating to explore America this way, and because I’m not American myself, I felt I was more able to cut through unquestioned assumptions of American culture and notice things that Americans don’t see in themselves. When it comes to what’s happening in other places, Americans will talk about “tribes,” “regimes,” “radicalization,” “religious extremists,” “ethnic conflicts,” “local superstitions,” or “rituals.” Anthropology is for other people, not Americans. America is supposedly this “shining city upon a hill,” a term Ronald Reagan famously popularized, adapting it from the biblical story of the Sermon on the Mount.

但当我看到福音传教士预言世界末日，非信徒将遭殃时，当我观看威斯特布路浸信会的示威游行时，当我看到身穿比基尼的女士手持半自动步枪的枪展时，当我听到白人谈论“黑人暴徒”和“福利女王”时，我看到一个国家深陷种族冲突、宗教极端主义和激进叛乱的阵痛之中。美国沉迷于自己的自我概念，它想成为例外。但事实并非如此。美国和其他国家一样。

But when I would see evangelists prophesying the end times and woe unto the nonbelievers, when I watched a Westboro Baptist Church demonstration, when I saw a gun show with bikini-clad ladies carrying semi-automatics, when I heard white people talk about “black thugs” and “welfare queens,” I saw a country deep in the throes of ethnic conflict, religious radicalization, and a bubbling militant insurgency. America is addicted to its own self-conception, and it wants to be exceptional. But it’s not. America is just like any other country.

美国有些地方让我感觉和我去过的任何地方一样陌生。就在默瑟夫妇决定投资 SCL 之前，尼克斯、朱西卡斯和我在弗吉尼亚州农村会见了潜在的支持者。一辆车载着我们从华盛顿特区出发，穿过富裕的郊区，最后沿着一条长路深入森林。最后，我们来到一片小空地，那里有一座农舍，远离任何其他文明的迹象。开车的人什么也没说，我们的手机不再有信号，感觉就像恐怖电影的开场一样。

There were places in the United States that felt as foreign as any place I’d been. Just before the Mercers decided to invest in SCL, Nix, Jucikas, and I met with possible backers in rural Virginia. A car took us from Washington, D.C., through the wealthy suburbs, and then finally down a long road running deep into the woods. Eventually we came to a small clearing with a farmhouse, miles from any other sign of civilization. The guy who was driving us said nothing, our phones no longer had a signal, and it felt like the opening scene of a horror film.

进入农舍后，我们被领进一间没有窗户的会议室，天花板上挂着高科技屏幕。然后一群 NRA 活动人士走了进来，像钟表一样，每个人都拿出一把枪放在桌子上。我唯一一次看到这样的事情是在波斯尼亚——但至少波斯尼亚人会把他们的枪整齐地放在架子上。这就像黑手党电影里的场景，或者阿富汗军阀会议的场景。我没有说什么，因为当一群人把枪放在桌子上时，你真的不能说，“对不起，这些枪有点咄咄逼人，让我很不舒服。”

Inside the farmhouse, we were shown into a windowless boardroom with high-tech screens that came out of the ceiling. And then a group of NRA activists came in and, like clockwork, each one pulled out a gun and laid it on the table. The only time I’d seen anything like this was in Bosnia—but at least Bosnians will put their guns neatly on a rack. This was like something out of a Mafia movie, or a meeting of warlords in Afghanistan. I didn’t say anything, because when a bunch of men put their guns on the table, you can’t really say, “Sorry, these guns are a little aggressive and making me uncomfortable.”

美国有自己的起源神话，也有自己的极端主义团体。在 SCL，我很不高兴地观看了无数 ISIS 和非洲军阀散布的宣传视频。圣战邪教成员对枪支的迷恋与 NRA 成员对枪支的迷恋并无二致。我知道，如果我们要真正研究美国，就需要像研究部落冲突一样去研究——通过绘制该国的仪式、迷信、神话和种族紧张局势。

The United States has its own origin myths, its own extremist groups. At SCL, I had the displeasure of watching countless propaganda videos disseminated by ISIS and deadbeat wannabe African warlords. The way members of jihadist cults fetishize their guns is no different from the way members of the NRA fetishize theirs. I knew that if we were going to truly study America, we needed to do it as if we were studying tribal conflict—by mapping out the country’s rituals, superstitions, mythologies, and ethnic tensions.

Gettleson 是我们派出的最有成效的研究人员之一。2014 年春夏，他走遍了美国，召集焦点小组，与人们交谈，然后将报告发回伦敦。然后，我们会提出理论和假设，以便在定量研究中进行测试。Gettleson 是一位极具魅力和机智的英国人，因此他很容易让人们谈论。他很快发现美国人和他们日常政治之间的脱节。例如，人们不由自主地谈论国会任期限制这个看似模糊的问题。他们会一遍又一遍地说，华盛顿的大问题是政客们在任时间太长，被特殊利益集团收买。在北卡罗来纳州的一个焦点小组中，有几个人使用了“抽干沼泽”这个短语，所以他也把这个短语写在了他发回的笔记中。CA 后来使用多变量测试对目标选民的在线小组研究了这句话，看看它是否引起了选民的共鸣。

Gettleson was one of the most productive researchers we sent. During the spring and summer of 2014, he went all across the United States, convening focus groups, having conversations with people, and then sending reports back to London. We would then generate theories and hypotheses to test in our quantitative research. Gettleson is an extremely charming and witty Brit, so it was easy for him to get people talking. He quickly observed a disconnect between Americans and their day-to-day politics. For example, people kept talking, unprompted, about the seemingly obscure issue of congressional term limits. They’d say over and over that the big problem in Washington is that the politicians stay in office too long and get bought by special interests. At one focus group in North Carolina, a couple of people used the phrase “Drain the swamp,” so he included that in the notes he sent back, too. CA would later study that phrase using multivariate tests on online panels of target voters, to see whether it resonated with voters.

在为期六周的时间里，盖特森访问了路易斯安那州、北卡罗来纳州、俄勒冈州和阿肯色州。在每个州，布洛克都会帮他联系愿意开车带他四处游览并帮助处理后勤事务的人。我要求他关注交叉性——特别是找到那些通常被归为一类但持有不同政治观点的人。因此，他召集了一个焦点小组，比如拉丁裔共和党人、拉丁裔民主党人和拉丁裔独立人士。和在弗吉尼亚州一样，我们利用一家市场研究公司来寻找参与者。

Over a six-week period, Gettleson visited Louisiana, North Carolina, Oregon, and Arkansas. In each state, Block connected him with people who would drive him around and help with logistics. I had asked him to focus on intersectionality—and in particular, finding people who were normally lumped into one category but had different political views. So he’d convene a focus group of, say, Latino Republicans, Latino Democrats, and Latino independents. As in Virginia, we used a market research company to find the participants.

即使是对于一个已经在美国呆了很长时间的人来说，研究结果也令人大开眼界。盖特森在路上通过电子邮件发来的实地报告描述了一个濒临精神崩溃的国家。

The results were eye-opening, even for someone who had already spent a lot of time in the United States. Gettleson’s field reports, emailed from the road, described a country nearing a nervous breakdown.

在新奥尔良举行的西班牙裔独立人士焦点小组会议上，他遇到了一位铁杆保守派人士，她宣称：“我没有登记为共和党人，因为我是真正的保守派人士。我的名字可能是拉丁裔，但我和他们一样都是美国人！”桌子另一端是一位皈依伊斯兰教的秘鲁人，她戴着头巾参加了会议。

In New Orleans, at a focus group of Hispanic independents, he met a hardcore conservative who declared, “I’m not registering as a Republican because I’m a real conservative. I may have a Latino name, but I’m as American as they come!” At the other end of the table was a Peruvian convert to Islam who had worn her hijab to the meeting.

当话题转到枪支问题时，她告诉那名男子，如果全国步枪协会的领导人是像她这样的人，他可能会改变对全国步枪协会的看法。他的回答很简单：“我会再去买一把枪。”后来，那名女子离开了人群，去找一个可以祈祷的空房间，让这位保守派超人目瞪口呆：我不知道该如何回应。我对此有意见，但我不能告诉一个人他们不能祈祷。

When the conversation shifted to guns, she told the man he might change his mind about the NRA if it were led by someone who looked like her. His answer was simple: “I’d just go and buy another gun.” Later, the woman excused herself from the group to find a spare room where she could pray, leaving the conservative superman dumbfounded: I don’t know how to respond to this. I have a problem with it, but I can’t tell a person they can’t pray.

宗教和枪支并不是盖特森在路易斯安那州遇到的唯一热点问题，由于种族多样性极其丰富，该州是研究的沃土。移民问题也引发了激烈的争论，其中不少几乎升级为斗殴。

Religion and guns were hardly the only hot-button issues Gettleson encountered in Louisiana, which was fertile ground for research, thanks to its super-varied ethnic diversity. Immigration also stoked heated debates, with more than a few almost escalating into fistfights.

一个名叫劳埃德的男子说话带有卡津口音，盖特森几乎听不懂他的口音，他大声而清楚地表达了自己对教区学校不再教授母语法语的厌恶。他对自己孙女被剥夺了学习卡津祖先“文化和传统”的机会感到愤怒。

A man named Lloyd, speaking with a Cajun accent that Gettleson found almost indecipherable, came across loud and clear in venting his disgust that the schools in his parish no longer taught his native French. He was furious that his granddaughter was being denied the chance to learn the “culture and heritage” of her Cajun forebears.

不到十五分钟，同一个人就开始对拉丁裔大发牢骚，说他们甚至在美国也不会停止说西班牙语。不知何故，小组里没有人发现其中的分歧——劳埃德可以大发牢骚指责西班牙人说西班牙语，但仍然用半法语说话，让人听不懂，并哀叹自己的传统文化的消失。

It wasn’t fifteen minutes before the same man launched into a rant about Latinos, how even in America they wouldn’t stop speaking Spanish. Somehow, no one in the group saw the disconnect—that Lloyd could rant against Spanish people for speaking Spanish but still speak incomprehensibly in semi-French and bemoan the loss of his own heritage.

种族问题也引发了其他一些不愉快的时刻。在一个焦点小组中，在听到了对奥巴马总统的抱怨后，盖特森问道：“难道没有人对总统感到失望吗？”房间里一片寂静，只有一位年轻人，直到现在，他都表现得非常有礼貌和谦恭。

Ethnicity and race fueled several other ugly moments. In one focus group, after hearing a chorus of complaints about President Obama, Gettleson asked, “Does anyone not feel disappointed by the president?” The room was silent except for a young guy who until now had come off as exceedingly polite and courteous.

他说：“我并不感到失望。”

“I don’t feel disappointed,” he said.

“为什么是这样？”

“And why is that?”

“嗯，他是第一位黑人总统，所以我没抱什么期待。”

“Well, he’s the first black president, so I wasn’t expecting nothing.”

在那个房间里，没有人眨眼，但其他焦点小组似乎戳破了党派泡沫。尽管如此，激烈的争论并不是常态；大多数参与者都努力避免冲突，即使他们明显意见不一。阿肯色州的史密斯堡有一个例外，当时一张奥巴马的照片促使一位衣着考究的女士说：“我要去我的车拿枪。”一个年轻男子厉声说：“你他妈的怎么敢！那是我们的总统。别拿这个开玩笑。”

In that room, no one batted an eye, but other focus groups seemed to puncture partisan bubbles. All the same, full-blown arguments were not the norm; most participants made an effort to avoid conflict, even when they clearly disagreed. One exception came in Fort Smith, Arkansas, when a photo of Obama prompted a well-dressed lady to say, “I’ll go to my car and get my gun.” A younger man snapped: “How fucking dare you! That is our president. Do not even joke about that.”

在盖特森看来，这个女人从来没有想过她对总统的看法可能会受到挑战。

To Gettleson’s eye, the woman had never in a million years considered that her views of the president might be challenged.

美国人对枪支的热爱屡屡被提及，甚至在俄勒冈州波特兰这样的自由主义堡垒中也是如此，在那里，一个纹身的嬉皮士可能会在递交她的进步愿望清单时停下来大声担心奥巴马政府执意要没收她的枪支。在为俄勒冈州焦点小组送餐时，盖特森难以置信地看到司机把他那把巨大的手枪放在驾驶座上，然后跑进赛百味去买三明治。“我以前从未见过手枪，”盖特森后来告诉我。“我在想，车没锁——如果有人看到枪，伸手进去拿怎么办？我应该把它收起来吗？车上似乎有一种枪架——我应该把它放进去吗？如果我不小心开火怎么办？有两分钟的时间，我真的坐在那里盯着这把枪，就好像它是车里的炸弹一样。”

America’s love affair with guns came up repeatedly, even in liberal bastions like Portland, Oregon, where a tattooed hipster might pause in delivering her progressive wish list to worry aloud that the Obama administration was hell-bent on seizing her firearms. On a food run for an Oregon focus group, Gettleson watched in disbelief as the driver left his massive handgun on the driver’s seat before running into Subway to grab their sandwiches. “I’ve never seen a handgun before,” Gettleson told me later. “I’m thinking, The car is unlocked—what if someone sees the gun, reaches in, and grabs it? Should I put it away? There seems to be a type of gun holder—should I put it in there? What if I accidentally fire it? For two minutes of my life, I literally sat there staring at this gun as if it were a bomb in the car.”

剑桥分析公司采访的许多俄勒冈人都痴迷于大政府和“大环境”。其中一位是俄勒冈共和党主席阿特·罗宾逊，他多次竞选美国众议院议员失败，但默瑟夫妇并没有因此放弃支持他的政治抱负。我去他位于俄勒冈州凯夫交界处森林深处的家拜访他，发现即使以另类右翼的标准来看，他也精神错乱。

A lot of the Oregonians Cambridge Analytica spoke to were obsessed with big government and “Big Enviro.” One of them was the chairman of the Oregon Republican Party, Art Robinson, whose multiple losing bids for the U.S. House of Representatives hadn’t discouraged the Mercers from supporting his political ambitions. I went to visit him in his home, deep in the woods of Cave Junction, Oregon, and found him to be unhinged, even by alt-right standards.

罗宾逊是一位生物化学家，曾与诺贝尔奖得主莱纳斯·鲍林共事，实验室之外，他有两个兴趣：管风琴和小便。他从世界各地的教堂和大教堂里回收废弃的十九世纪管风琴，并花上几个小时将它们拆开再重新组装。

Robinson, a biochemist who had worked with the Nobel Prize winner Linus Pauling, had two interests outside the lab: pipe organs and piss. He salvaged defunct nineteenth-century organs from churches and cathedrals all over the world and would spend hours taking them apart and reassembling them.

罗宾逊还收集了数千人的尿液，试图发现疾病和长寿的秘密。他的妻子劳雷莉在 43 岁时因一种未被发现的疾病突然去世，此后，他开始关注健康和衰老问题。在他创立并设在自己家中的俄勒冈科学与医学研究所，他用一台巨大的光谱仪分析尿液，以确定其化学成分。动物——有的死了，有的还活着——随处可见。猫、狗、羊和马在房子里漫游，而房子里的墙上挂着斑马皮、鹿头和水牛头。蜘蛛爬满了椽子，屋里弥漫着未洗过的动物的气味。房子里有几架从旧教堂和大教堂里打捞出来的组装好的管风琴。

Robinson also collected urine from thousands of people, in an effort to discover the secrets of disease and longevity. He had become fixated on health and aging after his wife, Laurelee, died suddenly of an undetected illness at age forty-three. At the Oregon Institute of Science and Medicine, which he founded and based at his home, he ran pee through a giant spectrometer to determine its chemical composition. Animals—some dead, some alive—were everywhere. Cats, dogs, sheep, and horses roamed the property, while inside, a zebra skin and the heads of a deer and a buffalo hung from the walls. Spiders had taken over the rafters and the place smelled of unwashed animals. There were several fully assembled pipe organs salvaged from old churches and cathedrals.

罗宾逊似乎已经失控了。他坚称气候变化是个骗局，认为低剂量的电离辐射对人体有益，并警告说化学尾迹正在毒害人类。想象一下，几年后，当他被考虑担任特朗普总统的科学顾问时，我的反应。

Robinson seemed to have tipped over the edge. He insisted that climate change was a hoax, argued that low doses of ionized radiation can be good for people, and warned that chemtrails were poisoning the population. Imagine my reaction when, a few years later, he was considered for the position of President Trump’s scientific adviser.

—

亿万富翁有两种：一种是永远赚不够钱的，另一种是赚够了好几辈子之后，开始关注改变世界的。Mercer 属于后者。虽然剑桥分析公司是作为一家企业成立的，但我后来才知道，它从来就不是为了赚钱。这家公司的唯一目的是蚕食共和党，重塑美国文化。当剑桥分析公司成立时，民主党在有效利用数据方面远远领先于共和党。多年来，他们一直在 VAN 中维护一个中央数据系统，全国任何民主党竞选活动都可以利用该系统。共和党没有可比性。CA 将缩小这一差距。

THERE ARE TWO TYPES of billionaires: those who can never make enough money and those who, after making enough to last multiple lifetimes, turn their attention to changing the world. Mercer was the latter. Although Cambridge Analytica was created as a business, I learned later that it was never intended to make money. The firm’s sole purpose was to cannibalize the Republican Party and remold American culture. When CA launched, the Democrats were far ahead of the Republicans in using data effectively. For years, they had maintained a central data system in VAN, which any Democratic campaign in the country could tap into. The Republicans had nothing comparable. CA would close that gap.

默瑟将赢得选举视为社会工程问题。“修复社会”的方法是创建模拟：如果我们可以在计算机内部量化社会，优化该系统，然后在计算机外部复制这种优化，我们就可以按照他的形象重塑美国。除了技术和更宏大的文化战略之外，投资 CA 是一个聪明的政治举措。当时，我被告知，由于他支持的是一家私人公司而不是 PAC，因此默瑟不必将他的支持报告为政治捐款。他将获得两全其美的结果：CA 将努力影响选举，但不受管理美国选举的任何竞选资金限制。他的巨大足迹将保持隐藏。

Mercer looked at winning elections as a social engineering problem. The way to “fix society” was by creating simulations: If we could quantify society inside a computer, optimize that system, and then replicate that optimization outside the computer, we could remake America in his image. Beyond the technology and the grander cultural strategy, investing in CA was a clever political move. At the time, I was told that because he was backing a private company rather than a PAC, Mercer wouldn’t have to report his support as a political donation. He would get the best of both worlds: CA would be working to sway elections, but without any of the campaign finance restrictions that govern U.S. elections. His giant footprints would remain hidden.

这个新实体的设立结构极其复杂，甚至让项目工作人员感到困惑，他们永远不确定自己到底为谁工作。SCL 集团仍是一家在特拉华州注册成立的新美国子公司剑桥分析公司的“母公司”。默瑟以 1500 万美元的本金投资获得了剑桥分析公司 90% 的所有权，SCL 则获得 10% 的所有权。这样的设置是为了让 CA 可以作为一家美国公司在美国运营，同时让 SCL 的国防部门保持“英国”公司的身份。因此，SCL 不必将新所有权和默瑟的参与通知英国国防部或其其他政府客户。然而，这家子公司被赋予了 SCL 工作的知识产权，这造成了一个奇怪的局面：子公司实际上拥有其“母公司”的核心资产。随后，SCL 和剑桥分析公司签署了一项独家协议，根据该协议，剑桥分析公司将把其所有合同转让给 SCL，SCL 的人员将负责实际交付服务并代表剑桥分析公司工作。然后，为了让 SCL 员工使用最初提供给剑桥分析公司的知识产权，该知识产权随后被授权回 SCL。

The structure chosen to set up this new entity was extremely convoluted, and it even confused staff working on projects, who were never sure who exactly they actually worked for. SCL Group would remain the “parent” of a new U.S. subsidiary, incorporated in Delaware, called Cambridge Analytica. For a principal investment of $15 million, Mercer took 90 percent ownership of Cambridge Analytica, and SCL would take 10 percent. This setup was so that CA could operate in the United States as an American company while keeping SCL’s defense division a “British” company. Therefore, SCL would not have to notify the U.K. Ministry of Defence or its other government clients of the new ownership and Mercer’s involvement. However, this subsidiary was bestowed the IP rights to SCL’s work, creating a bizarre situation where the subsidiary actually owned the core assets of its “parent.” SCL and Cambridge Analytica then signed an exclusivity agreement whereby Cambridge Analytica would transfer all of its contracts to SCL, and SCL’s personnel would service the actual delivery and work on behalf of Cambridge Analytica. And then, to allow SCL staff to use the IP that it originally gave to Cambridge Analytica, the IP was then licensed back to SCL.

尼克斯最初解释了这种错综复杂的设置是如何让我们在不被人注意的情况下进行操作的。默瑟在金融领域的竞争对手密切关注着他的一举一动，如果他们知道他收购了一家心理战公司，业内其他人可能会猜到他的下一步行动——开发复杂的趋势预测工具——或者挖走关键员工。我们知道班农想和《布莱巴特》合作一个项目，但这原本只是一个满足他个人爱好的副业。当然，这都是胡说八道，他们想建立一个政治武器库。我甚至不确定默瑟一开始是否知道剑桥分析公司的工具有多有效。他就像任何一家初创公司的投资者一样——把钱投给有想法的聪明、有创造力的人，希望它能变成有价值的东西。

Nix initially explained how this labyrinthine setup was to allow us to operate under the radar. Mercer’s rivals in the finance sector watched his every move, and if they knew that he had acquired a psychological warfare firm, others in the industry might figure out his next play—to develop sophisticated trend-forecasting tools—or poach key staff. We knew Bannon wanted to work on a project with Breitbart, but this was originally supposed to be a side project to satiate his personal fixations. Of course, this was all bullshit, and they wanted to build a political arsenal. I’m not even sure Mercer knew, at first, how effective Cambridge Analytica’s tools would be. He was like an investor in any startup—throwing money at smart, creative people who had an idea, in the hopes that it would turn into something valuable.

然而，很少有人知道谁成为了剑桥分析公司第一个造假目标。当班农和我第一次见面时，他拒绝去 Pall Mall 的一家私人俱乐部，而是选择在剑桥见面。尼克斯意识到了这一点，他通常讨好客户的方式——用豪华俱乐部、昂贵的葡萄酒和粗雪茄来打动他们——对班农不起作用，因为他认为自己是一名知识分子，非常适合剑桥的哥特式大厅和广阔的绿地。所以尼克斯就像某种神话中的变形者一样，为了引诱猎物，立即决定利用这一点。

What few people know, however, is the story of who became Cambridge Analytica’s very first target of disinformation. Back when Bannon and I first met, he had rejected going to a private club on Pall Mall, preferring to meet in Cambridge. Nix clocked this, realizing that his normal way of courting clients—by impressing them with fancy clubs, expensive wines, and fat cigars—wouldn’t work on Bannon, who saw himself as an intellectual, perfectly suited to the Gothic halls and sprawling greens of Cambridge. So Nix, like some kind of mythological shape-shifter transforming to lure his prey, made an instant decision to play to that.

他告诉班农，虽然 SCL 在伦敦设有办事处，但由于与剑桥大学有着密切的合作关系，我们的主要工作地点在剑桥。这完全是谎言，是临时编造的。但对于尼克斯来说，事实就是他当时认为真实的事情。他一说我们在剑桥有办事处，就开始一直提到它，并敦促班农来这里看看。

He told Bannon that while SCL had London offices, we were based primarily out of Cambridge because of our close partnership with the university. This was a total falsehood, made up on the fly. But for Nix, truth was whatever he deemed true in the moment. As soon as he’d said we had a Cambridge office, he started referring to it all the time, urging Bannon to stop by.

“亚历山大，我们没有剑桥办公室，”我对他的疯狂感到恼火。“你他妈的在说什么？”

“Alexander, we don’t have a Cambridge office,” I said, exasperated with his insanity. “What the fuck are you talking about?”

“哦，是的，我们有，只是目前还没有开放，”他说。

“Oh, yes we do, it’s just not open at the moment,” he said.

在班农下次访问英国前几天，尼克斯让伦敦办公室的员工在剑桥设立了一个假办公室，里面有租来的家具和电脑。在班农计划抵达的那天，他说：“好了，各位，我们今天在剑桥办公室工作！”然后我们都收拾好行李，准备去那里工作。尼克斯还雇佣了一些临时工和几名衣着暴露的年轻女性，为班农的访问在剑桥办公室工作。

A couple of days before Bannon’s next visit to the U.K., Nix had the London office staff set up a fake office in Cambridge, complete with rented furniture and computers. On the day Bannon was scheduled to arrive, he said, “Okay, everyone, we’re working out of our Cambridge office today!” And we all packed up to go out there and work. Nix also hired a handful of temps and several scantily clad young women to staff the would-be office for Bannon’s visit.

整个事情都让人觉得荒唐可笑。盖特森和我互相发信息，分享关于波将金村的链接，波将金村是俄罗斯在旧沙皇俄国建立的假城镇，目的是在 1783 年叶卡捷琳娜大帝到访时吸引她。我们将办公室命名为波将金遗址，并无情地嘲笑尼克斯想出了这样一个愚蠢的想法。但当我和班农一起在假办公室里走来走去时，我可以看到他眼中的光芒，两个月前，我在剑桥的一家酒店第一次见到他。他很相信它，并且享受着它的每一刻。幸运的是，他从来没有注意到有些电脑实际上没有插上电源，或者有些雇佣的女孩不会说英语。

The whole thing felt ludicrous. Gettleson and I messaged each other, sharing links about Potemkin villages, the fake Russian towns set up in old tsarist Russia to woo Catherine the Great when she visited in 1783. We christened the office the Potemkin Site and made relentless fun of Nix for coming up with such a stupid idea. But when I walked around the fake office with Bannon, two months after I first met him in a Cambridge hotel, I could see the light in his eyes. He was buying it and loving every moment of it. Fortunately, he never noticed that some of the computers weren’t actually plugged in or that some of the hired girls didn’t speak English.

每次班农来这里，尼克斯都会建立波将金网站。班农从未发现它是假的。即使他发现了，他也不介意。它符合愿景。当班农为默瑟夫妇资助的新实体命名时，他选择了剑桥分析公司——因为那是我们的总部所在地，他说。所以剑桥分析公司的第一个目标就是班农本人。波将金网站完美地体现了剑桥分析公司的灵魂，它完美地向人们展示他们想看到的东西，无论真实与否，以塑造他们的行为——这一策略非常有效，即使是史蒂夫·班农这样的人也会被亚历山大·尼克斯这样的人愚弄。

Nix set up the Potemkin Site every time Bannon came to town. Bannon never caught on that it was fake. Or if he did, he didn’t mind. It fit the vision. And when it came time to name the new entity the Mercers were funding, Bannon chose Cambridge Analytica—because that was where we were based, he said. So Cambridge Analytica’s first target was Bannon himself. The Potemkin Site perfectly encapsulated the heart and soul of Cambridge Analytica, which perfected the art of showing people what they want to see, whether real or not, to mold their behavior—a strategy that was so effective, even a man like Steve Bannon could be fooled by someone like Alexander Nix.

第六章

CHAPTER 6

特洛伊木马

TROJAN HORSES

-

“你知道 DARPA 资助了他们的一些工作，”布伦特·克里克德在从伦敦到剑桥的火车上告诉我。“如果你想扩大你的团队，这些人就是你想要的。”作为 SCL 的心理学家之一，他往返于公司和剑桥大学心理学实验室的学术工作之间。和我一样，克里克德也开始着迷于我们的研究可能带来的成果，这就是为什么他如此愿意让公司接触世界顶尖的研究心理学家。剑桥大学的心理学系在使用社交媒体数据进行心理分析方面取得了多项突破，这反过来又引起了政府研究机构的兴趣。剑桥分析公司最终成为什么样子，很大程度上取决于它以这所大学命名的学术研究成果。

“You know DARPA funds some of their work,” Brent Clickard told me on a train ride from London to Cambridge. “If you want to expand your team, these are the ones you want.” As one of SCL’s psychologists, he floated between the company and his ongoing academic work inside one of the psychology labs at the University of Cambridge. Like me, Clickard was becoming enamored with the possibilities of what our research could yield, which is why he was so willing to provide the firm access to the world’s leading research psychologists. The psychology department at Cambridge had spearheaded several breakthroughs in using social-media data for psychological profiling, which in turn prompted interest from government research agencies. What Cambridge Analytica eventually became depended in large part on the academic research published at the university it was named after.

剑桥分析公司是一家收集大量数据并利用这些数据设计和提供有针对性的内容的公司，这些内容能够大规模地影响公众舆论。然而，如果无法获得目标人群的心理档案，这一切都不可能实现——而事实证明，通过 Facebook 的松散监管许可程序，获取这些档案出奇地容易。这个故事始于我在 SCL 的早期，当时他们还没有创建剑桥分析公司这个美国衍生品牌。布伦特·克里克德带我参观了剑桥心理测量中心。在阅读了他的许多论文以及他在中心的同事的论文后，我对他们将机器学习与心理测试相结合的新策略很感兴趣。他们似乎在研究我们在 SCL 几乎相同的研究问题，尽管目的略有不同——或者我是这么认为的。

Cambridge Analytica was a company that took large amounts of data and used it to design and deliver targeted content capable of moving public opinion at scale. None of this is possible, though, without access to the psychological profiles of the target population—and this, it turned out, was surprisingly easy to acquire through Facebook, with Facebook’s loosely supervised permissioning procedures. The story of how this came to be started in my early days at SCL, before they created Cambridge Analytica as a spin-off American brand. Brent Clickard had shown me around the Psychometrics Centre at Cambridge. Having read through many of his papers, and those of his colleagues at the Centre, I was intrigued by their novel tactic of integrating machine learning with psychometric testing. It seemed like they were working on almost the same research questions we were at SCL, albeit with a slightly different purpose—or so I thought.

使用社交数据推断个人心理倾向的研究发表在一些心理学顶级学术期刊上，例如《美国国家科学院院刊》（PNAS）、 《心理科学》和《人格与社会心理学杂志》等。证据很明显：社交媒体用户的点赞、状态更新、群组、关注和点击模式都是离散的线索，当它们汇总在一起时，可以准确地揭示一个人的性格特征。Facebook 经常支持对其用户进行这种心理学研究，并为学术研究人员提供访问其用户私人数据的特权。2012 年，Facebook 申请了一项美国专利，用于“从社交网络系统通信和特征中确定用户性格特征”。Facebook的专利申请解释说，它对心理分析的兴趣是因为“推断出的性格特征与用户的个人资料一起存储，可用于定位、排名、选择产品版本以及各种其他目的。”因此，虽然 DARPA 对军事信息行动的心理分析感兴趣，但 Facebook 感兴趣的是利用它来增加在线广告的销量。

Research into using social data to infer the psychological disposition of individuals was published in some of psychology’s top academic journals, such as the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences (PNAS), Psychological Science, and the Journal of Personality and Social Psychology, among many others. The evidence was clear: The patterns of a social media user’s likes, status updates, groups, follows, and clicks all serve as discrete clues that could accurately reveal a person’s personality profile when compiled together. Facebook was frequently a supporter of this psychological research into its users and provided academic researchers with privileged access to its users’ private data. In 2012, Facebook filed for a U.S. patent for “Determining user personality characteristics from social networking system communications and characteristics.” Facebook’s patent application explained that its interest in psychological profiling was because “inferred personality characteristics are stored in connection with the user’s profile, and may be used for targeting, ranking, selecting versions of products, and various other purposes.” So while DARPA was interested in psychological profiling for military information operations, Facebook was interested in using it for increased sales of online advertising.

当我们走近唐宁站大楼时，我看到一块小牌匾，上面写着“心理实验室”。实验室内部空气浑浊，室内装饰自 20 世纪 70 年代以来就没有更新过。我们走上几层楼梯，来到一条狭窄走廊尽头的最后一间办公室，在那里，克里克德向我介绍了亚历山大·科根博士，他是剑桥大学的教授，专门研究心理特征的计算建模。科根是一个长相孩子气的男人，穿着和他的举止一样笨拙。他站在房间中央，脸上挂着得意的笑容，房间里堆满了他在香港学习期间留下的一堆堆文件和随意的装饰品。

As we approached the Downing Site building, I spotted a small plaque that read PSYCHOLOGICAL LABORATORY. Inside, the air was stale, and the décor hadn’t been updated since at least the 1970s. We walked up a few flights of stairs and then to the last office at the end of a narrow corridor, where Clickard introduced me to Dr. Aleksandr Kogan, a professor at the University of Cambridge who specialized in computational modeling of psychological traits. Kogan was a boyish-looking man and dressed as awkwardly as his manner. He stood with a simpering grin in the middle of the room, which was filled with stacks of papers and random decorations from his time studying in Hong Kong.

起初，我对科根的背景一无所知，因为他的英语带有完美的美国口音，尽管语调有些夸张。后来我才知道，他出生于苏联末期的摩尔多瓦苏维埃社会主义共和国，童年的一部分时间在莫斯科度过。苏联解体后不久，即 1991 年，他的家人移民到美国，他在加州大学伯克利分校学习，之后在香港获得心理学博士学位，并加入剑桥大学任教。

At first, I had no idea about Kogan’s background, as he spoke English with a perfect American accent, albeit with an exaggerated prosody. I later learned he was born in the Moldavian SSR during the final years of the Soviet Union and spent part of his childhood in Moscow. Not long after the Soviet Union collapsed, in 1991, his family emigrated to the United States, where he studied at the University of California, Berkeley, before completing his Ph.D. in psychology in Hong Kong and joining the faculty at the University of Cambridge.

克里克德把我介绍给了科根，因为他知道科根在剑桥实验室所做的工作对 SCL 非常有用。但是，克里克德知道尼克斯喜欢什么样的场合，于是决定在吃开胃小菜和喝葡萄酒时介绍一下我。尼克斯是个反复无常的人，他完全可以因为不喜欢别人的领带或餐厅选择而拒绝别人。所以我们都在克里克德预订的一张桌子旁见面，桌子位于国王十字火车站旁边的大北方酒店楼上的酒吧里。科根当天在伦敦游玩，在返回剑桥之前抽出时间向我们介绍了他的工作。尼克斯在晚上出去喝酒很常见，但我从未见过他被自己以外的声音陶醉。我们讨论的话题是社交媒体。

Clickard had introduced me to Kogan, as he knew the work he was doing in his lab at Cambridge could be extremely useful for SCL. But, knowing Nix’s preferred style of venue, Clickard decided that the introduction should happen over canapés and wine. Nix was fickle, and he could completely write people off because he didn’t like their tie or choice of restaurant. So we all met at a table booked by Clickard at an upstairs bar inside the Great Northern Hotel, beside Kings Cross train station. Kogan was visiting London for the day and had made time to tell us about his work before heading back to Cambridge. It was common enough for Nix to drink too much wine on a night out, but I’d never seen him intoxicated by a voice other than his own. The topic was social media.

科根告诉我们：“Facebook 比你生活中的任何人都更了解你，甚至比你的妻子还要了解你。”

“Facebook knows more about you than any other person in your life, even your wife,” Kogan told us.

尼克斯从恍惚中清醒过来，恢复了往常尴尬的样子。“有时最好的妻子不知道某些细节，”他一边喝着酒一边打趣道。“我为什么需要或想要一台电脑来提醒我——或者她？”

Nix snapped out of his trance, reverting to his usual embarrassing self. “Sometimes it’s best wives don’t know certain details,” he quipped, sipping his wine. “Why would I ever need or want a computer to remind me—or her?”

“你可能不想要它，”教授回答，“但广告商想要。”

“You might not want it,” the professor answered, “but advertisers do.”

“他很有趣，但我觉得他不像是剑桥人，”趁科根去洗手间的时候尼克斯一边喝着酒一边嘟囔道。

“He’s interesting, but he doesn’t sound like a Cambridge man to me,” mumbled Nix, drinking more wine while Kogan was in the restroom.

“因为他不是剑桥人，亚历山大。天啊……他只是在那里教书！”

“Because he’s not from Cambridge, Alexander. Jesus…He just teaches there!”

克里克德翻了个白眼。尼克斯分散了人们的注意力，使他们无法专注于更紧迫的问题。在公司研究了科根的研究后，尼克斯很想让他工作。SCL 刚刚从美世公司获得了融资，正在建立一个新的美国实体。但在尼克斯让科根接近他在美国的新大奖项目之前，他必须先在加勒比地区证明自己。当时，也就是 2014 年初，科根正在与圣彼得堡国立大学的研究人员合作开展一项由俄罗斯政府通过公共研究经费资助的心理分析项目。科根为圣彼得堡的一个团队提供咨询，该团队正在提取大量社交媒体资料数据，并利用这些数据来分析网络喷子行为。鉴于这项俄罗斯社交媒体研究侧重于适应不良和反社会特征，SCL 认为它可以应用于特立尼达项目，因为那里的国家安全部工作人员有兴趣尝试预测特立尼达公民犯罪倾向的模型。

Clickard rolled his eyes. Nix was a distraction from more pressing concerns. After the firm looked at Kogan’s research, Nix was eager to put him to work. SCL had just secured the financing from Mercer and was in the process of setting up a new American entity. But before Nix was to let Kogan near his new prize project in America, he would have to prove himself in the Caribbean first. At the time, in early 2014, Kogan was working with researchers based at St. Petersburg State University on a psychological profiling project funded by the Russian state through a public research grant. Kogan advised a team in St. Petersburg that was pulling swaths of social media profile data and using it to analyze online trolling behavior. Given that this Russian social media research focused on maladaptive and antisocial traits, SCL thought it could be applied to the Trinidad project, as Ministry of National Security staff there were interested in experimenting with predictive modeling of Trinidadian citizens’ propensity to commit crimes.

在一封发给特立尼达安全部及其国家安全委员会关于“通过拦截数据进行犯罪心理分析”的电子邮件中，SCL 的一名工作人员表示，“我们可能想进一步了解一下亚历克斯·科根为俄罗斯人所做的有趣工作，看看它是否适用。”

In an email to Trinidad’s security ministry and its National Security Council about “criminal psychographic profiling via [data] intercepts,” one SCL staffer said that “we may want to either loop in or find out a bit more about the interesting work Alex Kogan has been doing for the Russians and see how / if it applies.”

Kogan 最终签约协助 SCL 开展特立尼达项目，他提供了如何模拟一组心理结构的建议，过去的研究表明这些心理结构与反社会或越轨行为有关。Kogan 希望通过帮助规划项目来获得数据，他开始与 SCL 讨论如何访问其 130 万特立尼达人的数据集，以供他自己研究。我喜欢 Kogan 的地方在于他希望快速工作并完成任务，这对于习惯于缓慢学术生活的教授来说并不常见。他给人的印象是诚实、雄心勃勃、坦率，尽管有点天真，但他对创意和知识抱负充满热情。

Kogan eventually signed up to assist SCL on the Trinidad project, where he offered advice on how to model a set of psychological constructs that past research had identified as related to antisocial or deviant behavior. Kogan wanted data in exchange for helping to plan the project, and he started discussions with SCL about accessing its data set of 1.3 million Trinidadians for his own research. What I liked about Kogan was that he wanted to work fast and to get stuff done, which was not common for professors accustomed to the glacial pace of academic life. And he came across as honest, ambitious, and upfront, if a little bit naïve, in his excitement for ideas and intellectual ambition.

一开始我和 Kogan 相处得还不错。他和我一样对新兴的计算心理学和计算社会学领域感兴趣。我们会连续几个小时谈论行为模拟的前景，当我们讨论 SCL 时，他显然很兴奋。与此同时，Kogan 有点奇怪，我注意到他的同事会在他不在的时候对他进行讽刺。但这并没有困扰到我。如果说有什么不同的话，那就是这让我对他产生了更多的共鸣——毕竟，我自己也曾被人说过很多讽刺的话。此外，在 SCL 工作，你必须有点奇怪。

I got along quite well with Kogan in the beginning. He shared my interest in the emerging fields of computational psychology and computational sociology. We would talk for hours about the promise of behavioral simulation, and when we discussed SCL, he was palpably excited. At the same time, Kogan was slightly odd, and I noticed that his colleagues would make snide remarks about him when he wasn’t around. But it wasn’t as if this bothered me. If anything, it made me relate to him more—after all, I’d been on the receiving end of plenty of snide remarks myself. Besides, you had to be a bit weird to work at SCL.

2014 年 1 月，当 Kogan 加入 Trinidad 计划时，我们刚刚与 Bannon 启动了美国项目的早期试验阶段。根据我们的定性研究，我们有一些想要测试的理论，但现有数据不足以进行心理分析。消费者信息（来自航空公司会员、媒体公司和大型商场等来源）没有产生足够强烈的信号来预测我们正在探索的心理属性。这并不奇怪，因为例如在沃尔玛购物并不能定义你是怎样的人。我们可以推断出人口统计或财务属性，但不能推断出性格——例如，外向者和内向者都会在沃尔玛购物。我们需要的数据集不仅要覆盖美国人口的很大一部分，还要包含与心理属性显着相关的数据。我们怀疑我们需要我们在世界其他地方的其他项目中使用的那种社交数据，例如点击流或人口普查记录中观察到的变量类型，Kogan 已经注意到了这一点。

When Kogan joined the Trinidad initiative in January 2014, we were just launching the early trial phases of the America project with Bannon. Based on our qualitative studies, we had some theories we wanted to test, but the available data was insufficient for psychological profiling. Consumer information—from sources like airline memberships, media companies, and big-box stores—didn’t produce a strong enough signal to predict the psychological attributes we were exploring. This wasn’t surprising, because shopping at Walmart, for example, doesn’t define who you are as a person. We could infer demographic or financial attributes, but not personality—extroverts and introverts both shop at Walmart, for example. We needed data sets that didn’t just cover a large percentage of the American population but also contained data that was significantly related to psychological attributes. We suspected we needed the kind of social data we had used on other projects in other parts of the world, such as clickstreams or the types of variables observed in a census record, which Kogan had picked up on.

Kogan 先从特立尼达开始，但他对 SCL 在美国的工作更感兴趣。他告诉我，如果他被聘用到美国项目，我们可以与他在心理测量中心的团队合作，填补变量和数据类别的空白，以创建更可靠的模型。他开始要求访问我们的一些数据集，以查看训练集中可能缺少什么，训练集是用于“训练”模型以识别模式的样本数据集。但这并不是问题的关键。Clickard 告诉他，我们已经完成了初步建模，并拥有训练集，但我们需要大规模数据。我们找不到包含我们知道有助于预测心理特征并覆盖广泛人群的变量的数据集。这成为了一个主要的绊脚石。Kogan 说他可以为我们解决这个问题——只要他也能将数据用于他的研究。当他说如果他被聘用到美国项目，我们可以在剑桥大学建立第一个全球计算社会心理学研究所时，我立即同意了。心理学、人类学和社会学等社会科学面临的挑战之一是相对缺乏数字数据，因为衡量和量化整个社会的抽象文化或社会动态极其困难。也就是说，除非你能把每个人的虚拟克隆放入计算机并观察他们的动态。感觉就像我们掌握着开启研究社会新方式的钥匙。我怎么能拒绝呢？

Kogan started on Trinidad, but he was far more intrigued by SCL’s work in the United States. He told me that if he was brought on to the American job, we could work with his team at the Psychometrics Centre to fill gaps in the variables and data categories in order to create more reliable models. He started asking to access some of our data sets to see what might be missing in the training set, which is the sample data sets one uses to “train” a model to identify patterns. But that wasn’t quite the problem. Clickard told him that we’d done preliminary modeling and had training sets but that we needed data at scale. We couldn’t find data sets that contained variables that we knew helped predict for psychological traits and covered a wide population. It was becoming a major stumbling block. Kogan said that he could solve the problem for us—as long as he could use the data for his research too. When he said that if he was brought onto the America project, we could set up the first global institute for computational social psychology at the University of Cambridge, I was instantly on board. One of the challenges for social sciences like psychology, anthropology, and sociology is a relative lack of numerical data, since it’s extremely hard to measure and quantify the abstract cultural or social dynamics of an entire society. That is, unless you can throw a virtual clone of everyone into a computer and observe their dynamics. It felt like we were holding the keys to unlock a new way of studying society. How could I say no to that?

2014 年春天，科根把我介绍给了心理测量中心的另外几位教授。大卫·斯蒂尔韦尔博士和米卡尔·科辛斯基博士正在研究他们从 Facebook 合法获取的大量数据集。他们是社交媒体心理分析领域的先驱。2007 年，斯蒂尔韦尔创建了一款名为 myPersonality 的应用程序，该应用程序为加入该应用程序的用户提供个性档案。在向用户提供结果后，该应用程序将收集该档案并将其存储起来以用于研究。

In the spring of 2014, Kogan introduced me to a couple of other professors at the Psychometrics Centre. Dr. David Stillwell and Dr. Michal Kosinski were working with a massive data set they’d harvested legally from Facebook. They were pioneers in social-media-enabled psychological profiling. In 2007, Stillwell set up an application called myPersonality, which offered users a personality profile for joining the app. After giving the user a result, the app would harvest the profile and store it for use in research.

两位教授的第一篇关于 Facebook 的论文发表于 2012 年，并很快引起了学术界的关注。在 Kogan 为我们联系后，Kosinski 和 Stillwell 向我介绍了他们多年研究中获得的大量 Facebook 数据集。他们说，美国军方研究机构 DARPA 是他们研究的资助者之一，因此他们非常适合与军事承包商合作。Stillwell 在我们的互动中通常保持沉默，但 Kosinski 显然雄心勃勃，倾向于推动 Stillwell 继续对话。Kosinski 知道这些数据可能非常有价值，但他需要 Stillwell 同意任何数据传输。

The professors’ first paper on Facebook was published in 2012, and it quickly caught the attention of academics. After Kogan connected us, Kosinski and Stillwell told me about the huge Facebook data sets they’d acquired in their years of research. The U.S. military’s research agency, DARPA, was one of the funders of their research, they said, making them well suited to work with a military contractor. Stillwell was typically muted in our interactions, but Kosinski was clearly ambitious and tended to push Stillwell into keeping the conversation going. Kosinski knew this data could be extremely valuable, but he needed Stillwell to agree to any data transfers.

“你是怎么得到它的？”我问。

“How did you get it?” I asked.

他们告诉我，Facebook 实际上是允许他们通过教授们开发的应用程序获取数据。Facebook 希望人们在其平台上进行研究。它对用户了解得越多，就越能从中获利。当他们解释如何收集数据时，很明显 Facebook 的权限和控制非常松懈。当一个人使用他们的应用程序时，斯蒂尔韦尔和科辛斯基不仅可以收到该人的 Facebook 数据，还可以收到该人所有好友的数据。Facebook 并不要求应用程序明确同意收集应用程序用户好友的数据，因为它认为成为 Facebook 用户就足以同意获取他们的数据——即使这些好友不知道该应用程序正在收集他们的私人数据。Facebook 的平均用户好友数在 150 到 300 之间。我想到了班农和默瑟，因为我知道他们会喜欢这个想法——而尼克斯会很高兴他们喜欢这个想法。

They told me, essentially, that Facebook simply let them take it, through apps the professors had created. Facebook wants people to do research on its platform. The more it learns about its users, the more it can monetize them. It became clear when they explained how they collected data that Facebook’s permissions and controls were incredibly lax. When a person used their app, Stillwell and Kosinski could receive not only that person’s Facebook data, but the data of all of their friends as well. Facebook did not require express consent for apps to collect data from an app user’s friends, as it viewed being a user of Facebook as enough consent to take their data—even if the friends had no idea the app was harvesting their private data. The average Facebook user has somewhere between 150 and 300 friends. My mind turned to Bannon and Mercer, as I knew they would love this idea—and Nix would simply love that they loved it.

“让我把事情说清楚，”我说，“如果我开发一个 Facebook 应用，有一千人使用它，我就会得到……大约 15 万个个人资料？真的吗？Facebook 真的允许你这样做吗？ ”

“Let me get this straight,” I said. “If I create a Facebook app, and a thousand people use it, I’ll get…like 150,000 profiles? Really? Facebook actually lets you do that?”

他们说，没错。如果有几百万人下载了这款应用，我们就能获得 3 亿份个人资料，减去重叠的共同好友。这将是一个惊人的庞大数据集。到目前为止，我处理过的最大的数据集是特立尼达，我认为这个数据集相当大，有 100 万人的个人资料。但这个数据集的水平完全不同。在其他国家，我们必须获得特殊的数据访问权限，或者花费数月时间抓取和收集比这个小几个数量级的人群的数据。

That’s right, they said. And if a couple million people downloaded the app, then we’d get 300 million profiles, minus the overlapping mutual friends. This would be an astonishingly huge data set. Up to that point, the largest data set I had worked on was Trinidad, which I thought was quite large, with profiles of one million people. But this set was on an entirely different level. In other countries, we had to get special access to data or spend months scraping and harvesting for populations several orders of magnitude smaller.

“那么你如何让人们下载这个应用程序呢？”我问道。

“So how do you get people to download this app?” I asked.

“我们只是付钱给他们。”

“We just pay them.”

“多少？”

“How much?”

“一美元。有时两美元。”

“A dollar. Sometimes two.”

现在，请记住，我公司有 2000 万美元的潜在损失。而这些教授刚刚告诉我，我可以用……一百万美元左右的价格获得数千万个 Facebook 个人资料。这是一件轻而易举的事。

Now, remember, I’ve got a potential $20 million burning a hole in our firm’s pocket. And these profs have just told me that I can get tens of millions of Facebook profiles for…a million dollars, give or take. This was a no-brainer.

我问斯蒂尔威尔是否可以对他们的数据进行一些测试。我想看看我们能否复制我们在特立尼达的结果，在那里我们可以获得类似的互联网浏览数据。如果 Facebook 个人资料像我希望的那样有价值，我们不仅能够满足罗伯特·默瑟创建强大工具的愿望——更酷的是，我们可以将一个全新的学术领域推向主流：计算心理学。我们正站在行为模拟这一新科学的前沿，我对这一前景感到兴奋不已。

I asked Stillwell if I could run some tests on their data. I wanted to see if we could replicate our results from Trinidad, where we had access to similar types of Internet browsing data. If the Facebook profiles proved as valuable as I hoped, we would not only be able to fulfill Robert Mercer’s desire to create a powerful tool—what was even cooler was that we could mainstream a whole new field of academia: computational psychology. We were standing at the frontier of a new science of behavioral simulation and I was bursting with excitement at the prospect.

—

Facebook 于 2004 年推出，是一个连接大学学生和同龄人的平台。几年后，该网站发展成为世界上最大的社交网络——几乎每个人，甚至你的父母，都会在这里分享照片、发布无害的状态更新并组织聚会。在 Facebook 上，你可以“点赞”品牌或主题页面以及朋友的帖子。点赞的目的是让用户有机会塑造自己的个性并关注他们最喜欢的品牌、乐队或名人的更新。Facebook 认为这种点赞和分享现象是其所谓“社区”的基础。当然，它也认为这是其收入模式的基础，广告商可以使用 Facebook 数据优化他们的定位。该网站还推出了一个 API（应用程序编程接口），允许用户加入 Facebook 上的应用程序，然后这些应用程序将提取他们的个人资料数据以获得“更好的用户体验”。

FACEBOOK LAUNCHED IN 2004 as a platform to connect students and peers in college. In a few years, the site grew to become the largest social network in the world—a place where almost everyone, even your parents, shared photos, posted innocuous status updates, and organized parties. On Facebook, you could “like” things—pages of brands or topics, along with the posts of friends. The purpose of liking was to allow users a chance to curate their personas and follow updates from their favorite brands, bands, or celebrities. Facebook considers this phenomenon of liking and sharing the basis of what it calls a “community.” Of course, it also considers this the basis of its revenue model, where advertisers can optimize their targeting using Facebook data. The site also launched an API (application programming interface) to allow users to join apps on Facebook, which would then ingest their profile data for a “better user experience.”

2010 年代初，研究人员迅速意识到，整个群体都在一个地方整理有关自己的数据。Facebook 页面包含家庭环境中“自然”行为的数据，但不包括研究人员的指纹。每次滚动都会被跟踪，每个动作都会被跟踪，每个点赞都会被跟踪。所有信息都在那里——细微差别、兴趣、厌恶——而且都是可以量化的。这意味着来自 Facebook 的数据越来越具有生态效度，因为它不是由研究人员的问题引发的，这些问题不可避免地会带来某种偏见。换句话说，传统上用于人类学或社会学的被动定性观察的许多好处可以保留下来，但由于许多社会和文化互动现在都被记录在数字数据中，我们可以增加定量研究中实现的普遍性的好处。以前，获取此类数据的唯一途径是从银行或电话公司，而这些公司受到严格监管，以防止访问此类私人信息。但与银行或电信公司不同的是，社交媒体几乎没有任何法律来管理其对极其细化的个人数据的访问。

In the early 2010s, researchers quickly caught on that entire populations were organizing data about themselves in one place. A Facebook page contains data on “natural” behavior in the home environment, minus the fingerprints of a researcher. Every scroll is tracked, every movement is tracked, every like is tracked. It’s all there—nuance, interests, dislikes—and it’s all quantifiable. This means the data from Facebook has increasingly more ecological validity, in that it is not prompted by a researcher’s questions, which inevitably inject some kind of bias. In other words, many of the benefits of the passive qualitative observation traditionally used in anthropology or sociology could be maintained, but as many social and cultural interactions were now captured in digital data, we could add the benefits of generalizability one achieves in quantitative research. Previously, the only way one could have acquired such data would have been from your bank or phone company, which are strictly regulated to prevent access to that sort of private information. But unlike a bank or telecom company, social media operated with virtually no laws governing its access to extremely granular personal data.

尽管许多用户倾向于区分网络上发生的事情和现实生活中发生的事情，但他们使用社交媒体产生的数据（从发布对节目季终集的反应到点赞周六晚上外出的照片）都是来自互联网之外的生活。换句话说，Facebook 数据是现实生活中的数据。随着人们越来越多地使用手机和互联网生活，这种数据只会越来越多。这意味着，对于分析师来说，通常不需要提出问题：你只需创建算法来在用户自然发生的数据中找到离散模式。一旦你这样做了，系统本身就可以揭示你原本永远不会注意到的数据模式。

Although many users tend to distinguish between what happens online from what happens IRL (in real life), the data that is generated from their use of social media—from posting reactions to the season finale of a show to liking photos from Saturday night out—is generated from life outside the Internet. In other words, Facebook data is IRL data. And it is only increasing as people live their lives more and more on their phones and on the Internet. This means that, for an analyst, there’s often no need to ask questions: You simply create algorithms that find discrete patterns in a user’s naturally occurring data. And once you do that, the system itself can reveal patterns in the data that you otherwise would have never noticed.

Facebook 用户可以在单一数据表单中集中管理自己的所有信息。我们不需要连接一百万个数据集；我们不需要进行复杂的数学运算来填补缺失的数据。信息已经到位，因为每个人都在网站上提供实时自传。如果你从头开始创建一个系统来观察和研究人们，那么没有比 Facebook 更好的了。

Facebook users curate themselves all in one place in a single data form. We don’t need to connect a million data sets; we don’t have to do complicated math to fill in missing data. The information is already in place, because everyone serves up their real-time autobiography, right there on the site. If you were creating a system from scratch to watch and study people, you couldn’t do much better than Facebook.

事实上，Youyou、Kosinski 和 Stillwell 在 2015 年进行的一项研究表明，使用 Facebook 上的点赞，计算机模型在预测人类行为方面占据主导地位。通过 10 个点赞，该模型预测一个人的行为比同事更准确。如果有 150 个点赞，模型就比家庭成员更了解他。如果有 300 个点赞，模型就比自己的配偶更了解这个人。部分原因是朋友、同事、配偶和父母通常只看到你生活的一部分，而你的行为受到这段关系的影响。你的父母可能永远看不到你在凌晨 3 点 服用两剂 MDMA 后会变得多么疯狂，你的朋友可能永远看不到你在办公室里和老板在一起时是多么矜持和恭敬。他们对你的印象都略有不同。但 Facebook 可以窥视你的人际关系，通过手机跟踪你，并追踪你在网上点击和购买的内容。这就是网站数据比朋友或家人的判断更能反映你“真正是谁”的原因。在某些方面，计算机模型可以比人们自己更了解他们的习惯——这一发现迫使研究人员增加了一个警告。他们写道：“计算机在性格判断方面超越人类，在心理评估、营销和隐私领域带来了重大机遇和挑战。”

In fact, a 2015 study by Youyou, Kosinski, and Stillwell showed that, using Facebook likes, a computer model reigned supreme in predicting human behavior. With ten likes, the model predicted a person’s behavior more accurately than one of their co-workers. With 150 likes, better than a family member. And with 300 likes, the model knew the person better than their own spouse. This is in part because friends, colleagues, spouses, and parents typically see only part of your life, where your behavior is moderated by the context of that relationship. Your parents may never see how wild you can get at a 3 A.M. rave after dropping two hits of MDMA, and your friends may never see how reserved and deferential you are in the office with your boss. They all have slightly different impressions of who you are. But Facebook peers into your relationships, follows you around in your phone, and tracks what you click and buy on the Internet. This is how data from the site becomes more reflective of who you “really are” than the judgments of friends or family. In some respects, a computer model can know a person’s habits better than they even know themselves—a finding that compelled the researchers to add a warning. “Computers outpacing humans in personality judgment,” they wrote, “presents significant opportunities and challenges in the areas of psychological assessment, marketing, and privacy.”

有了足够的 Facebook 数据，我们终于可以尝试在计算机中模拟社会。其影响是惊人的：理论上，你可以模拟未来社会，制造种族紧张或贫富差距等问题，并观察它们如何发展。然后，你可以回溯并更改输入，以找出如何缓解这些问题。换句话说，你可以开始在计算机内部模拟现实世界问题的解决方案。对我来说，将社会视为游戏的整个想法非常史诗般。我对 Kogan 向我提出的研究所的想法非常着迷，并非常渴望以某种方式实现它。这不仅仅是我们的爱好；各地的教授也同样热情高涨。在哈佛开会后，Kogan 通过电子邮件向我传达了他们的反馈，他说：“关键术语是改变游戏规则并彻底改变社会科学。”起初，Stillwell 和 Kosinski 似乎也很兴奋。然后 Kogan 无意中告诉他们 CA 的预算为 2000 万美元。所有的学术友谊立刻陷入停滞。

With access to enough Facebook data, it would finally be possible to take the first stab at simulating society in silico. The implications were astonishing: You could, in theory, simulate a future society to create problems like ethnic tension or wealth disparity and watch how they play out. You could then backtrack and change inputs, to figure out how to mitigate those problems. In other words, you could actually start to model solutions to real-world issues, but inside a computer. For me, this whole idea of society as a game was super epic. I was obsessed with the idea of the institute that Kogan suggested to me, and became extremely eager to somehow make it happen. And it wasn’t just our pet obsession; professors all over were getting just as enthused. After meetings at Harvard, Kogan emailed me about their feedback, saying, “The operative term is game changing and revolutionizing social science.” And at first, it seemed like Stillwell and Kosinski were excited, too. Then Kogan let slip to them that CA had a budget of $20 million. And all the academic camaraderie ground immediately to a halt.

科辛斯基给科根发了一封电子邮件，说他们要求预付 50 万美元，外加使用 Facebook 数据的所有“版税”的 50%。我们甚至还没有证明这可以在实地试验中大规模实施，而他们已经要求巨额资金。尼克斯让我拒绝，这让科根感到恐慌，担心这个项目还没开始就会失败。所以在我们拒绝了科辛斯基的现金要求的第二天，科根说他可以自己做，按照他最初的条件——他会帮助我们获取数据，CA 会按成本支付，他可以用它进行研究。科根说他可以使用更多拥有 Facebook 相同好友收集权限的应用程序，他可以使用这些应用程序。我立刻警惕起来，认为科根可能只是计划在秘密使用斯蒂尔韦尔和科辛斯基的应用程序。但科根坚持说他已经开发了自己的应用程序。“好吧，”我说。“证明这一点。给我一份数据转储。”为了确保这些数据不是从其他应用程序中提取的，我们给了 Kogan 10,000 美元，让他用新的数据集试用他的新应用程序。他同意了，而且没有为自己要任何钱，只要他能保留一份数据副本。

Kosinski sent Kogan an email saying they wanted half a million dollars up front, plus 50 percent of all “royalties” for the use of their Facebook data. We had not even proven this could work at scale in a field trial yet, and they were already demanding huge amounts of money. Nix told me to refuse, and this made Kogan panic that the project was going to fall apart before it even began. So the day after we rejected Kosinski’s demand for cash, Kogan said he could do it on his own, on his original terms—he would help us get the data, CA would pay for it at cost, and he would get to use it for his research. Kogan said he had access to more apps that had the same friends-collection permission from Facebook and that he could use those apps. I was immediately wary, thinking that Kogan might have just been planning to use Stillwell and Kosinski’s app under the radar. But Kogan insisted to me that he’d built his own. “Okay,” I said. “Prove it. Give me a dump of data.” To make sure these were not just pulled from the other app, we gave Kogan $10,000 to pilot his new app with a new data set. He agreed and did not ask for any money for himself, so long as he could keep a copy of the data.

虽然科辛斯基当时从未告诉我这件事，但他后来表示，他打算将 Facebook 数据授权所得的资金捐给剑桥大学。然而，剑桥大学也坚决否认参与了任何 Facebook 数据项目，因此尚不清楚该大学是否知道这一潜在的财务安排，或者是否会接受这笔资金。

Although he never told me this at the time, Kosinski has since said that he intended to give the money from the licensing of the Facebook data to the University of Cambridge. However, the University of Cambridge also strongly denies that it was involved with any Facebook data projects, so it is unclear that the university was aware of this potential financial arrangement, or would have accepted the funds if offered.

接下来的一周，科根向 SCL 发送了数万份 Facebook 个人资料，我们做了一些测试，以确保这些数据的价值与我们的期望相符。结果甚至更好。它包含了数万名用户的完整个人资料——姓名、性别、年龄、位置、状态更新、喜好、朋友——一切​​。科根说他的 Facebook 应用甚至可以提取私人消息。“好的，”我告诉他。“我们开始吧。”

The following week, Kogan sent SCL tens of thousands of Facebook profiles, and we did some tests to make sure the data was as valuable as we’d hoped. It was even better. It contained complete profiles of tens of thousands of users—name, gender, age, location, status updates, likes, friends—everything. Kogan said his Facebook app could even pull private messages. “Okay,” I told him. “Let’s go.”

—

当我开始与 Kogan 合作时，我们迫切希望建立一个研究所，将我们收集的 Facebook、点击流和消费者数据存入仓库，供心理学家、人类学家、社会学家、数据科学家等任何感兴趣的学者使用。让我在 UAL 的时尚教授们高兴的是，Kogan 甚至允许我添加一些服装风格和美学项目，以便我在博士研究中进行测试。我们计划去世界各地的不同大学，继续建立数据集，以便开始在社会科学领域建模。在哈佛医学院的一些教授建议我们可以访问数百万份患者基因档案后，连我都对这个想法的发展感到惊讶。Kogan 告诉我，想象一下，一个将一个人的实时数字行为与其基因数据库联系起来的数据库的力量。Kogan 很兴奋——有了基因数据，我们可以进行强有力的实验，解开先天与后天之争。我们知道我们正处在一件大事的风口浪尖。

WHEN I STARTED WORKING with Kogan, we were eager to set up an institute that would warehouse the Facebook, clickstream, and consumer data we were collecting for use by psychologists, anthropologists, sociologists, data scientists—any academics who were interested. Much to the delight of my fashion professors at UAL, Kogan even let me add several clothing-style and aesthetic items that I could test for my Ph.D. research. We planned to go to different universities around the world, continuing to build up the data set so we could then start modeling things in the social sciences. After some professors at Harvard Medical School suggested we could access millions of their patient genetic profiles, even I was surprised at how this idea was evolving. Imagine the power, Kogan told me, of a database that linked up a person’s live digital behavior with a database of their genes. Kogan was excited—with genetic data, we could run powerful experiments unpacking the nature-vs.-nurture debate. We knew we were on the cusp of something big.

我们通过一个名为 Amazon MTurk 的微任务网站获得了第一批数据。最初，亚马逊将 MTurk 打造为一个内部工具，以支持一个图像识别项目。由于该公司需要训练算法来识别照片，因此第一步是让人类手动标记照片，这样人工智能就有一组正确识别的照片可供学习。亚马逊愿意为每个标签支付一分钱，成千上万的人报名参加这项工作。

We got our first batch of data through a micro-task site called Amazon MTurk. Originally, Amazon built MTurk as an internal tool to support an image-recognition project. Because the company needed to train algorithms to recognize photographs, the first step was to have humans label them manually, so the AI would have a set of correctly identified photos to learn from. Amazon offered to pay a penny for each label, and thousands of people signed up to do the work.

亚马逊看到了商机，于 2005 年将 MTurk 拆分成产品，称之为“人工人工智能”。现在，其他公司可以付费接触那些愿意在业余时间做一些微任务的人——比如输入收据扫描件或识别照片——只需支付少量费用。这是人类在做机器的工作，甚至 MTurk 这个名字也体现了这一点。MTurk 是“Mechanical Turk”的缩写，这是一种十八世纪的国际象棋“机器”，曾让众人惊叹不已，但实际上它是一个躲在盒子里的小人，通过特制的杠杆操纵棋子。

Seeing a business opportunity, Amazon spun out MTurk as a product in 2005, calling it “artificial artificial intelligence.” Now other companies could pay to access people who, in their spare time, were willing to do micro-tasks—such as typing in scans of receipts or identifying photographs—for small amounts of money. It was humans doing the work of machines, and even the name MTurk played on this. MTurk was short for “Mechanical Turk,” an eighteenth-century chess-playing “machine” that had amazed crowds but was actually a small man hiding in a box, manipulating the chess pieces through specially constructed levers.

心理学家和大学研究人员很快发现，MTurk 是利用大量人员填写性格测试的绝佳方式。研究人员不必费尽心思寻找愿意参加调查的本科生，因为这样做根本无法提供真正具有代表性的样本，而是可以从世界各地招募各种各样的人。他们会邀请 MTurk 成员参加一分钟的测试，并向他们支付少量费用。测试结束时，会有一个付款代码，用户可以在亚马逊页面上输入该代码，然后亚马逊会将付款转入此人的账户。

Psychologists and university researchers soon discovered that MTurk was a great way to leverage large numbers of people to fill out personality tests. Rather than have to scrounge for undergraduates willing to take surveys, which never gave a truly representative sample anyway, researchers could draw all kinds of people from all over the world. They would invite MTurk members to take a one-minute test, paying them a small fee to do so. At the end of the session, there would be a payment code, which the person could input on their Amazon page, and Amazon would transfer payment into the person’s account.

Kogan 的应用程序与 MTurk 协同工作：用户同意参加测试，并支付少量费用。但为了获得报酬，他们必须在 Facebook 上下载 Kogan 的应用程序并输入特殊代码。该应用程序会收集调查的所有回复，并将其放入一个表中。然后，它会提取用户的所有 Facebook 数据，并将其放入第二个表中。然后，它会提取该用户所有 Facebook 好友的数据，并将其放入另一个表中。

Kogan’s app worked in concert with MTurk: A person would agree to take a test in exchange for a small payment. But in order to get paid, they would have to download Kogan’s app on Facebook and input a special code. The app, in turn, would take all the responses from the survey and put those into one table. It would then pull all of the user’s Facebook data and put it into a second table. And then it would pull all the data for all the person’s Facebook friends and put that into another table.

用户会填写一系列心理测量问卷，但首先要填写的是同行评审和国际认可的性格测量问卷，即 IPIP NEO-PI，它列出了数百个条目，例如“我与他人保持距离”、“我喜欢听取新想法”和“我做事不假思索”。将这些回答与 Facebook 点赞结合起来，就可以做出可靠的推断。例如，外向的人更有可能喜欢电子音乐，开放度得分较高的人更有可能喜欢奇幻电影，而神经质的人会喜欢“我讨厌父母看我的手机”这样的页面。但我们能推断的不仅仅是性格特征。也许并不奇怪，在 Facebook 上喜欢布兰妮·斯皮尔斯、MAC 化妆品或 Lady Gaga 的美国男性是同性恋的可能性略高。虽然单独看每个点赞几乎总是太弱，无法单独预测任何事情，但当这些点赞与其他数百个点赞以及其他选民和消费者数据相结合时，就可以做出有力的预测。一旦分析算法经过训练和验证，它就会被应用到 Facebook 好友的数据库中。虽然我们没有针对好友资料进行调查，但我们可以访问他们的点赞页面，这意味着算法可以提取数据并推断出如果他们参加了调查，他们可能会如何回答每个问题。

Users would fill out a wide battery of psychometric inventories, but it always started with a peer-reviewed and internationally validated personality measure called the IPIP NEO-PI, which presented hundreds of items, like “I keep others at a distance,” “I enjoy hearing new ideas,” and “I act without thinking.” When these responses were combined with Facebook likes, reliable inferences could then be made. For example, extroverts were more likely to like electronic music and people scoring higher in openness were more likely to like fantasy films, whereas more neurotic people would like pages such as “I hate it when my parents look at my phone.” But it wasn’t simply personality traits we could infer. Perhaps not surprisingly, American men on Facebook who liked Britney Spears, MAC Cosmetics, or Lady Gaga were slightly more likely to be gay. Although each like taken in isolation was almost always too weak to predict anything on its own, when those likes were combined with hundreds of other likes, as well as other voter and consumer data, then powerful predictions could be made. Once the profiling algorithm was trained and validated, it would then be turned onto the database of Facebook friends. Although we did not have surveys for the friend profiles, we had access to their likes page, which meant that the algorithm could ingest the data and infer how they likely would have responded to each question if they had taken a survey.

随着项目在夏季的不断发展，人们探索了更多的概念，而科根的建议开始与班农想要的完全吻合。科根概述说，我们应该开始研究人们的生活满意度、公平性（公平或怀疑他人），以及一种称为“耸人听闻和极端兴趣”的概念，该概念在法医心理学中越来越多地用于理解越轨行为。这包括“军国主义”（枪支和射击、武术、弩、刀）、“暴力神秘主义”（毒品、黑魔法、异教）、“智力活动”（唱歌和创作音乐、出国旅行、环境）、“神秘轻信”（超自然现象、飞碟）和“健康兴趣”（露营、园艺、徒步旅行）。我个人最喜欢的是“对星座的信仰”的五分量表，办公室里的几个同性恋开玩笑说，我们应该将其拆分成“星座兼容性”功能，并将其链接到同性恋约会应用程序 Grindr。

As the project grew over the summer, more constructs were explored, and Kogan’s suggestions began to match exactly what Bannon wanted. Kogan outlined that we should begin examining people’s life satisfaction, fair-mindedness (fair or suspicious of others), and a construct called “sensational and extreme interests,” which has been used increasingly in forensic psychology to understand deviant behavior. This included “militarism” (guns and shooting, martial arts, crossbows, knives), “violent occultism” (drugs, black magic, paganism), “intellectual activities” (singing and making music, foreign travel, the environment), “occult credulousness” (the paranormal, flying saucers), and “wholesome interests” (camping, gardening, hiking). My personal favorite was a five-point scale for “belief in star signs,” which several of the gays in the office joked we should spin off into an “astrological compatibility” feature and link it to the gay dating app Grindr.

使用 Kogan 的应用，我们不仅得到了一个训练集，使我们能够创建一个非常好的算法（因为数据非常丰富、密集且有意义），而且我们还获得了数百个额外好友资料的额外好处。所有这些只需为每个应用安装 1 到 2 美元。我们完成了第一轮收获，还有剩余。在管理方面，他们总是说开展任何项目都有一条黄金法则：你可以便宜、快速或出色地完成一个项目。但问题是你只能选择其中两个，因为你永远无法同时获得这三个。这是我一生中第一次看到这条规则被彻底打破——因为 Kogan 创建的 Facebook 应用比我能想象到的任何东西都更快、更好、更便宜。

Using Kogan’s app, we would not only get a training set that gave us the ability to create a really good algorithm—because the data was so rich, dense, and meaningful—but we also got the extra benefit of hundreds of additional friend profiles. All for $1 to $2 per app install. We finished the first round of harvesting with money left over. In management, they always say there is a golden rule for running any project: You can get a project done cheap, fast, or well. But the catch is you can choose only two, because you’ll never get all three. For the first time in my life, I saw that rule totally broken—because the Facebook app Kogan created was faster, better, and cheaper than anything I could have imagined.

—

计划于 2014 年 6 月发布。我记得当时天气很热：尽管夏天即将来临，但尼克斯还是关掉了空调，以降低办公室账单。我们花了几个星期校准一切，确保应用程序正常运行，能够提取正确的数据，并在将数据注入内部数据库时一切都匹配。平均而言，一个人的回应会产生三百人的记录。每个人可能会有几百个赞，我们可以分析。我们需要组织和跟踪所有这些赞。整个 Facebook 上有多少可能的项目、照片、链接和页面可以点赞？数万亿。例如，俄克拉荷马州某个乐队的 Facebook 页面可能在全国范围内获得 28 个赞，但它在功能集中仍算作自己的赞。如此规模和复杂性的项目可能会出现很多问题，因此我们花了很多时间测试在规模扩大时处理数据集的最佳方法。一旦我们确信一切顺利，就该启动项目了。我们向账户中存入 10 万美元，开始通过 MTurk 招募人员，然后等待。

THE LAUNCH WAS PLANNED for June 2014. I remember it was hot: Even though the summer was coming, Nix kept the air-conditioning off to lower the office bills. We had spent several weeks calibrating everything, making sure the app worked, that it would pull in the right data, and that everything matched when it injected the data into the internal databases. One person’s response would, on average, produce the records of three hundred other people. Each of those people would have, say, a couple hundred likes that we could analyze. We needed to organize and track all of those likes. How many possible items, photos, links, and pages are there to like across all of Facebook? Trillions. A Facebook page for some random band in Oklahoma, for example, might have twenty-eight likes in the whole country, but it still counts as its own like in the feature set. A lot of things can go wrong with a project of such size and complexity, so we spent a lot of time testing the best way to process the data set for when it scaled. Once we were confident that everything worked, it was time to launch the project. We put $100,000 into the account to start recruiting people via MTurk, then waited.

我们站在电脑旁，科根在剑桥。科根启动了应用程序，有人说：“好耶。”就这样，我们开始直播了。

We were standing by the computer, and Kogan was in Cambridge. Kogan launched the app, and someone said, “Yay.” With that, we were live.

起初，这是历史上最令人失望的项目发布会。什么都没发生。五分钟、十分钟、十五分钟过去了，人们开始满怀期待地走来走去。“这他妈是什么？”尼克斯咆哮道。“我们为什么站在这里？”但我知道人们需要一点时间才能看到 MTurk 上的调查，填写调查问卷，然后安装应用程序获得报酬。尼克斯开始抱怨后不久，我们就看到了第一个成功案例。

At first, it was the most anticlimactic project launch in history. Nothing happened. Five, ten, fifteen minutes went by, and people started shuffling around in anticipation. “What the fuck is this?” Nix barked. “Why are we standing here?” But I knew that it would take a bit of time for people to see the survey on MTurk, fill it out, then install the app to get paid. Not long after Nix started complaining, we saw our first hit.

然后，数据如潮水般涌来。我们得到了第一条记录，然后是两条、二十条、一百条、一千条——所有这些都在几秒钟内完成。Jucikas 在记录计数器上添加了随机的哔哔声，主要是因为他知道 Nix 对愚蠢的音效情有独钟，他觉得用花哨的技术陈词滥调来打动 Nix 是多么容易，这很有趣。随着数字疯狂增长，Jucikas 的计算机开始发出嘟嘟嘟的声音。随着好友资料被添加到数据库中，零的增量不断增加，表格以指数级增长。这对每个人来说都很令人兴奋，但对于我们当中的数据科学家来说，这就像是注射了纯粹的肾上腺素。

Then the flood came. We got our first record, then two, then twenty, then a hundred, then a thousand—all within seconds. Jucikas added a random beeping sound to a record counter, mostly because he knew Nix had a thing for stupid sound effects, and he found it amusing how easy it was to impress Nix with gimmicky tech clichés. Jucikas’s computer started going boop-boop-boop as the numbers went insane. The increments of zeroes just kept building, growing the tables at exponential rates as friend profiles were added to the database. This was exciting for everyone, but for the data scientists among us, it was like an injection of pure adrenaline.

我们温文尔雅的首席技术官 Jucikas 拿了一瓶香槟。他总是热情洋溢，是派对的灵魂人物，他确保办公室里随时都有一箱香槟，以备不时之需。立陶宛苏维埃社会主义共和国末期，他在一个极其贫困的农场长大，多年来，他把自己打造成了剑桥精英，一个花花公子，他的座右铭似乎是今天活得开心，因为明天你可能会死。对于 Jucikas 来说，一切都是极端和夸张的。这就是为什么他为办公室买了一把拿破仑战争时期的古董军刀，他现在打算使用它。既然可以用军刀开香槟，为什么还要用正常的方式呢？

Jucikas, our suave chief technology officer, grabbed a bottle of champagne. He was always full of bonhomie, the life of the party, and he made sure we had a case of champagne in the office at all times for just such occasions. He had grown up extremely poor on a farm in the waning days of the Lithuanian SSR, and over the years he had remade himself into a Cambridge elite, a dandy whose motto seemed to be live it up today, because tomorrow you might die. With Jucikas, everything was extreme and over the top. That’s why he’d bought for the office an antique saber from the Napoleonic Wars, which he now intended to use. Why open champagne the normal way when you can use a saber?

他抓起一瓶 Perrier-Jouët Belle Epoque 香槟（他最喜欢的），松开固定软木塞的盖子，斜着拿住酒瓶，优雅地用军刀从侧面划过。整个瓶盖被完全掀开，香槟喷涌而出。我们倒满香槟杯，为我们的成功干杯，享受着当晚我们喝下的许多瓶香槟中的第一瓶。Jucikas 继续解释说，用军刀划香槟不是靠蛮力，而是要研究酒瓶，优雅而精准地击中最薄弱的地方。如果做得正确，这只需要很小的压力——基本上是让瓶子自己破裂。你破解了瓶子的设计缺陷。

He grabbed a bottle of Perrier-Jouët Belle Epoque (his favorite), loosened the cage holding the cork, held the bottle at an angle, and elegantly swiped the saber down the side. The entire top snapped clean off, and champagne gushed out. We filled the flutes and toasted our success, enjoying the first of many bottles we would drink that night. Jucikas went on to explain that sabering champagne is not about brute force; it’s about studying the bottle and hitting the weakest spot with graceful precision. Done correctly, this requires very little pressure—you essentially let the bottle break itself. You hack the bottle’s design flaw.

—

当默瑟最初投资时，我们以为我们还有几年时间让项目全面启动。但班农立即驳回了这个想法。“9 月前完成，”他说。当我说这太快时，他说，“我不在乎。我们刚刚给了你数百万美元，这是你的最后期限。自己想办法吧。”2014 年中期选举即将到来，他希望他现在开始称之为“里彭计划”的项目（以共和党成立的威斯康星州小镇命名）能够启动并运行。我们中的许多人对班农翻了白眼，他在投资后变得越来越古怪。但我们认为，我们只需安抚他狭隘的政治痴迷，就能发挥我们在科学领域创造革命性事物的潜力。我们一直告诉自己，只要目的正当，不择手段。

WHEN MERCER FIRST MADE the investment, we assumed we had a couple of years to get the project fully running. But Bannon shot that notion down right away. “Have it ready by September,” he said.
