Then, decades later, when Europe looked more economically promising than the fledgling countries emerging out of colonial rule, Britain turned its back on these nations, closed off its borders, and implemented tough new immigration rules for Commonwealth citizens. At the same time, Britain began opening up nearly unrestricted immigration to European citizens, who were overwhelmingly white.

正是出于这种深深的不公平感，很多有色人种（比如桑尼的朋友和家人，他们来自巴基斯坦）对欧盟没有好感：他们知道忍受卡夫卡式的移民制度是什么感觉，这个制度要求他们证明自己的每一点价值。他们知道生活在一个剥削他们的祖先来建设自己的国家是什么感觉，现在内政部的卡车在印度和巴基斯坦社区巡逻，上面贴着警告，比如“非法入境？回家，否则将被逮捕。发短信给家里78070”。与此同时，一个德国人或意大利人可以毫无疑问地进入英国，然后忙着找工作，而他们的祖父很可能曾对英国召集参战的印度人和尼日利亚人进行致命攻击。

It was out of this sense of deep unfairness that many people of color—people like Sanni’s friends and family, who were from Pakistan—had no affinity for the EU: They knew what it felt like to have to endure a Kafkaesque immigration system requiring them to prove every ounce of their worth. They knew what it felt like to live in a country that had exploited their ancestors to build itself up but now sent Home Office trucks roving through the neighborhoods of Indian and Pakistani communities, emblazoned with warnings like HERE ILLEGALLY? GO HOME OR FACE ARREST. TEXT HOME TO 78070. Meanwhile, a German or Italian, whose grandfather may very well have taken deadly aim on those battalions of Indians and Nigerians that Britain called into battle, could enter Britain with no questions asked, and then get busy applying for jobs.

当留欧派大肆宣扬“支持移民”的口号来捍卫欧盟时，许多有色人种看到的是这种口号中暗藏的白人色彩——它实际上意味着赋予部分移民权利。对于桑尼这样的人来说，脱欧是一个边缘化的故事，是一个英国未解决的殖民主义遗产的故事——它试图纠正拒绝移民和有色人种进入这个几个世纪以来一直掠夺他们的国家的错误。正是通过识别这种日益高涨的怨恨情绪，脱欧运动成功地在某些移民群体与希望他们全部“回家”的沙文主义脱欧派之间建立了一种违反直觉的联盟。

As the Remain campaign paraded around its “pro-immigration” messages to defend the EU, what many people of color saw was the tacit whiteness of that very message—that it really meant rights for some immigrants. For people like Sanni, Brexit was a story of marginalization and of Britain’s unaddressed legacy of colonialism—an attempt to right the wrong of denying immigrants and people of color access to the very country that had plundered them for centuries. And it was by identifying this bubbling resentment that the pro-Brexit movement managed to create a counterintuitive alliance between some sections of immigrant communities and cohorts of jingoist Brexiteers who wanted them all to “go home.”

—

帕金森给了桑尼一份无薪实习机会。2016 年春天，他以志愿者的身份开始工作。由于外联团队规模很小，他的职责很快就增加了。他的大部分工作都集中在少数族裔和同性恋社区。他会访问贫困社区，询问居民他们打算如何投票以及为什么投票。

PARKINSON GAVE SANNI AN unpaid internship. He started in the spring of 2016 as a volunteer. Because the outreach team was so small, his duties quickly multiplied. Much of his work was focused on minority and queer communities. He would visit impoverished neighborhoods to ask residents how they were planning to vote and why.

桑尼上班第一天，就注意到一个穿着绿色外套和粉色裤子的花花公子：马克·盖特森，他全身都是同性恋。桑尼和盖特森立刻开始开玩笑说，在这群保守的白人中，他们是格格不入的。盖特森于 2016 年春天加入脱欧阵营，担任顾问，他的机智、智慧和对英国自由主义者的直觉理解给员工留下了深刻印象。他立即开始为几个外联团体建立网站，其中许多团体都是他自己命名的，比如绿叶、出柜和骄傲等等。当我在自由民主党认识的 22 岁时尚专业学生达伦·格莱姆斯加入团队时，他和盖特森开始构思脱欧阵营的一个进步分支，称为 BeLeave。

On Sanni’s first day at the office, he noticed a dandy in a green blazer and pink pants: Mark Gettleson, in his full homosexual plumage. Right away, Sanni and Gettleson started joking about being the odd men out in this sea of conservative white men. Gettleson had joined Vote Leave as a consultant in the spring of 2016, impressing the staff with his wit, intelligence, and intuitive understanding of British liberals. He immediately began setting up the websites for several of the outreach groups, many of which he branded and named himself—Green Leaves, Out and Proud, and others. When Darren Grimes, the twenty-two-year-old fashion student I knew from the Lib Dems, joined the team, he and Gettleson started conceptualizing a progressive arm of Vote Leave, to be called BeLeave.

那时我已经在加拿大了，但我们都通过 Facebook 保持联系。在为 BeLeave 设计品牌的过程中，Grimes 通过 Messenger 向我发送了他的创意表。尽管我正忙于为渥太华新成立的自由党政府制定项目，但我想在他与自由民主党的艰难时期之后给他一点帮助。他的挑战之一是选择正确的颜色。脱欧公投的官方颜色是红色，所以他们需要一些不同的东西。我说：“为什么不使用 Pantone 年度流行色呢？”——2016 年恰好是宁静蓝和玫瑰石英粉。Darren 做了一个模型，我回复道：“它看起来很同性恋和千禧一代。一点也不法西斯。”

I was in Canada by then, but we all kept in touch via Facebook. In the course of designing the branding for BeLeave, Grimes sent me his idea sheet via Messenger. Even though I was preoccupied with setting up projects for the new Liberal government in Ottawa, I wanted to give him a hand after the rough time he’d had with the Lib Dems. One of his challenges was in choosing the right colors. The official color for Vote Leave was red, so they needed something different. I said, “Why not use the Pantone colors of the year?”—which in 2016 happened to be Serenity blue and Rose Quartz pink. Darren did a mock-up, and I messaged back, “It looks so gay and millennial. Not fascist at all.”

BeLeave 试图通过关注移民平等待遇、结束所谓的欧盟和非欧盟公民之间的“护照歧视”、欧盟保护主义政策对非洲农民的不公平影响以及环境保护等问题来吸引支持脱欧的较温和的一方。帕金森要求桑尼将注意力从少数族裔外联转移到 BeLeave 后，他和格莱姆斯——一对二十出头的实习生——基本上负责这项计划，偶尔会听取 Vote Leave 高级职员的意见。由于已经获得了铁杆反移民选民的支持，脱欧派只需获得一小部分更自由的选民即可获胜。数据是锁定这些选民的关键。

BeLeave attempted to appeal to the softer side of the pro-Brexit vote by focusing on issues such as parity in treatment for immigrants, ending what they termed “passport discrimination” between EU and non-EU citizens, the unfair impact protectionist EU policies had on African farmers, and environmental protections. After Parkinson asked Sanni to shift his attention from minority outreach to BeLeave, he and Grimes—a pair of interns in their early twenties—essentially ran the initiative, with occasional input from the senior staff at Vote Leave. With the hardcore anti-immigration votes already in the bag, the Leave side needed to secure only a small percentage of more liberal-minded voters to win. Data was the key to targeting those voters.

然而，脱欧派没有所需的数据，而唯一可以提供数据的公司剑桥分析公司也不在考虑范围，因为它已经与 Leave.EU 合作。如果脱欧派与剑桥分析公司合作，就会违反限制竞选活动协调的法律。后来我才知道，他们雇佣了一家公司，这家公司的起源与我在 SCL 的早期经历有交集，当时我刚刚开始组建一个技术团队。

Vote Leave didn’t have the data it needed, though, and the one company that could provide it, Cambridge Analytica, was not an option because it was already working with Leave.EU. If Vote Leave worked with Cambridge Analytica, it would run afoul of laws restricting coordination between the campaigns. What they did, I learned later, was hire a firm whose origins intersected with my early days at SCL, when I was just starting to put together a technical team.

那是 2013 年 8 月，当时我正在寻找可以提供帮助的人。我回想起在 LPC 的时光以及 Jeff Silvester 的指导，他在我还在学校时就对我产生了兴趣。Silvester 是一名受过培训的计算机软件工程师，早在他开始在 LPC 倡导新的数据战略之前，他就对企业数据系统有了扎实的了解。Silvester 是一个留着胡子的大个子——他让我想起了《公园与游憩》中的 Ron Swanson——他总是体贴周到，但他也有那种从政多年者的冷淡和愤世嫉俗的幽默感。他住在不列颠哥伦比亚省维多利亚市郊外，周末他作为当地童子军部队的领导帮助指导年轻人。我作为实习生与 Silvester 一起工作的头几个月，我帮助他处理难民和政治庇护申请的案件，他向我展示了如何真正改变人们的生活。他是我认识的最可敬的人之一。

This was back in August 2013, when I was looking for people who could help. I recalled my time at the LPC and the mentorship of Jeff Silvester, who had taken an interest in me while I was still in school. Silvester, a computer software engineer by training, had developed a solid understanding of enterprise data systems long before he started advocating for a new data strategy at the LPC. A big guy with a beard—he reminded me of Ron Swanson in Parks and Recreation—Silvester was unfailingly considerate and thoughtful, but he also had the dry and cynical sense of humor of someone who had spent years in politics. He lived outside of Victoria, British Columbia, and on weekends he helped mentor young people as leader of a local Boy Scout troop. My first few months working with Silvester as an intern involved helping him on casework for refugee and political asylum claims, and he showed me how you can really make a difference in people’s lives. He was one of the most honorable people I knew.

加入 SCL 后不久，我写信给西尔维斯特，描述了该公司的投资组合——不仅仅是为北约开展心理战项目，还包括在非洲抗击艾滋病的努力。他很快回复说：“你需要一个加拿大办事处！”当特立尼达项目出现时，他的愿望实现了。SCL 需要有人帮助建立和管理数据基础设施，而西尔维斯特正好有合适的背景。西尔维斯特挖走了另一位加拿大政治人物扎克·马辛厄姆，他是不列颠哥伦比亚省政治圈的资深人士，负责新公司（他称之为 AIQ）的项目管理。该公司在加拿大注册，法律名称为 AggregateIQ，但它签署了一份知识产权协议，授予 SCL 对其作品的权利。SCL 以及后来的剑桥分析公司经常利用以不同名称注册的离岸公司网络。与避税计划所采用的策略类似，这个遍布全球的公司网络帮助剑桥分析公司绕过了选举或数据隐私监管机构的审查。

Shortly after joining SCL, I wrote to Silvester, describing the firm’s portfolio—not just psychological warfare projects for NATO, but efforts to fight HIV in Africa. He quickly replied: “You need a Canadian office!” When the Trinidad project came up, he got his wish. SCL needed someone to help build and manage data infrastructure, and Silvester had exactly the right background. Silvester poached another Canadian political operative, Zack Massingham, a veteran of the rough world of B.C. provincial politics, to lead project management for the new company, which he called AIQ. The company was registered in Canada and was legally called AggregateIQ, but it signed an intellectual property agreement that granted SCL the rights to its work. SCL and, later, Cambridge Analytica frequently took advantage of a network of offshore companies registered under different names. Similar to the strategies employed by tax avoidance schemes, this network of companies around the world helped Cambridge Analytica bypass the scrutiny of electoral or data privacy regulators.

AIQ 的总部位于温哥华岛维多利亚潘多拉大道上的一栋砖砌建筑内，距离海边仅一个街区。SCL 和 CA 的员工都喜欢来这里办公，这里景色优美，空气清新，与伦敦的繁忙节奏相比，这里令人放松。随着 AIQ 的发展，公司招募了一支优秀且多元化的工程师团队来负责 SCL 项目。

AIQ’s headquarters was a brick building on Pandora Avenue, only a block from the ocean in Victoria, on Vancouver Island. SCL and CA employees loved to visit the office—it was scenic, breezy, and relaxed compared with the frenetic pace of London. As AIQ grew, the firm recruited a fantastic and diverse team of engineers to work on SCL projects.

AIQ 与 SCL 签订的 Trinidad 合同包括为 Facebook 数据收集、点击流数据、ISP 日志以及 IP 和用户代理与家庭住址的核对构建基础设施，这将有助于对互联网浏览数据进行去匿名化处理。随着 SCL 发展成为剑桥分析公司，AIQ 成为后端技术工程团队不可或缺的一部分。在决定将 CA 的模型加载到可以启动社交和数字广告定位的平台后，AIQ 负责构建 CA 的广告定位平台 Ripon。在 Kogan 收集 Facebook 数据后，这些数据被传递给 AIQ 以加载到 Ripon 平台，该平台允许用户根据数百种不同的心理测量和行为因素对选民群体进行细分。在 2016 年美国初选期间，AIQ 工作人员将前往南部的德克萨斯州，为参议员泰德·克鲁兹的竞选活动构建基础设施。

AIQ’s Trinidad contract with SCL included building infrastructure for Facebook data harvesting, clickstream data, ISP logs, and the reconciliation of IPs and user agents to home addresses, which would help de-anonymize Internet browsing data. As SCL grew into Cambridge Analytica, AIQ became an indispensable part of the back-end technical engineering team. Once it was decided that CA’s models would have to be loaded into a platform that could launch social and digital ad targeting, AIQ was tasked with constructing Ripon, CA’s ad-targeting platform. After Kogan harvested the Facebook data, it was passed on to AIQ for loading into the Ripon platform, which allowed a user to segment universes of voters according to hundreds of different psychometric and behavioral factors. During the 2016 U.S. primaries, AIQ staff members would travel south to Texas to build out infrastructure for Senator Ted Cruz’s campaign.

当布列塔尼·凯泽 (Brittany Kaiser) 和萨姆·帕滕 (Sam Patten) 加入剑桥分析公司并接手尼日利亚项目时，AIQ 被带去传播剑桥分析公司的选民压制和恐吓宣传。在上传了妇女被活活烧死和男子被割喉窒息的视频后，AIQ 试图将内容定位到剑桥分析公司给他们的地区和选民资料上。2015 年，当我发现西尔维斯特正在从事这个项目时，感觉真的很奇怪：我曾经的导师根本不是那种会轻率地传播酷刑受害者视频的人。多年后，我和西尔维斯特见面，问他关于尼日利亚的事。除非你把尴尬的笑声算在内，否则他没有表现出任何悔意。不知何故，他已经接受了公司作为剑桥分析公司承包商向世界散布的混乱。

When Brittany Kaiser and Sam Patten joined Cambridge Analytica and took over the Nigeria project, AIQ was brought on to distribute CA’s voter suppression and intimidation propaganda. After uploading videos of women being burned alive and men choking on their own blood as they had their throats cut, AIQ sought to target the content at regions and voter profiles that CA gave them. In 2015, when I found out that Silvester was working on this project, it felt truly bizarre: My onetime mentor was not at all the sort of person who would blithely disseminate videos of torture victims. Years later, I would meet up with Silvester and ask him about Nigeria. Unless you count uncomfortable laughter, he showed no remorse. Somehow he had made peace with the mayhem his company had spewed out into the world as a Cambridge Analytica contractor.

—

2016 年 6 月 16 日下午，支持留欧的工党议员乔·考克斯 (Jo Cox) 正步行前往西约克郡小镇伯斯托尔的图书馆。她正前往参加两周一次的“诊疗所”，这是英国的传统，议员们定期与需要帮助处理案件或想要提出问题的选民举行公开会议。但当考克斯距离图书馆门口仅几步之遥时，一名戴着棒球帽的男子向她走来，举起一把短筒猎枪，大喊“英国优先！”，近距离射杀了她。该男子随后将 41 岁的考克斯拖到两辆停着的汽车之间，开始刺杀她，向试图阻止他的震惊的旁观者挥舞着刀子。在整个袭击过程中，他不断大喊“英国优先！这是为了英国！”，最终，他重新装弹，射中考克斯的头部，结束了袭击。考克斯是两个孩子的母亲，躺在人行道上奄奄一息。

ON THE AFTERNOON OF June 16, 2016, a pro-Remain Labour MP named Jo Cox was walking to the library in the small town of Birstall, West Yorkshire. She was heading to her fortnightly “surgery,” a British tradition wherein MPs regularly host open meetings with constituents who need help with casework or want to raise an issue. But when Cox was just steps from the library door, a man wearing a baseball cap walked toward her, raised a sawed-off shotgun, shouted “Britain first!” and shot her point-blank. The man then dragged the forty-one-year-old Cox between two parked cars and began stabbing her, flailing his knife at shocked onlookers who tried to stop him. He continued to yell “Britain first! This is for Britain!” throughout the attack, which finally ended when he reloaded his gun and shot Cox in the head. Cox, the mother of two young children, lay dying on the pavement.

乔·考克斯遇刺事件在英国引起轩然大波，因为英国的枪支暴力远不及美国。议员们聚集在议会广场守夜，哀悼者留下的鲜花组成了一座临时纪念碑。很快，凶手被发现是一名白人至上主义者和纳粹同情者，这只会加剧脱欧派和留欧派之间的情绪紧张。为了平息这场风波，并向考克斯致敬，脱欧派和留欧派同意停止所有竞选活动三天，这是一个非同寻常的决定，因为距离投票仅剩一周。然而，AIQ 秘密继续为脱欧派投放数字广告，因为他们知道英国媒体无法判断他们是否继续投放在线广告。在尼日利亚传播了人们遭受酷刑和杀害的视频后，在公众悼念遇害议员期间进行一些额外的数字宣传似乎并不失礼。

The assassination of Jo Cox sent waves of genuine shock throughout Britain, where gun violence is far less common than in the United States. Fellow MPs gathered for a vigil on Parliament Square, where flowers left by mourners formed a makeshift memorial. It soon emerged that the killer was a white supremacist and Nazi sympathizer, which only served to heighten the emotional tension between Leave and Remain supporters. In an attempt to calm the storm, and in tribute to Cox, the Leave and Remain campaigns agreed to stop all campaign activities for three days, an extraordinary decision with only a week remaining until the vote. However, AIQ secretly continued deploying digital advertisements for Vote Leave, knowing that the British media would not be able to tell whether they were continuing online ads. It seemed that, after distributing videos in Nigeria of people being tortured and killed, a bit of extra digital campaigning during a period of public mourning for a murdered MP was not beneath them.

此时，英国的政治气氛已经变得极其恶劣。支持留欧和支持脱欧的议员都收到了威胁（主要是针对留欧一方），种族暴力事件急剧增加，社交媒体每天都在爆炸性增长。再也没有人对英国政坛发生的事情保持消极或漠不关心的态度了。人们已经觉醒，人们感到愤怒。非常愤怒。

By this time, the political climate in Britain had become extremely toxic. Threats were being sent to both Remain- and Leave-supporting MPs (mostly to the Remain side), there was a disproportionate increase in race-based violence, and social media was blowing up every day. No one was passive or nonchalant about what was going on in British politics anymore. People were awake and people were angry. Very angry.

脱欧派在这段时间里发布的许多信息都针对“大都市精英”（政客们这样称呼他们）以及有色人种和欧洲移民。脱欧派逃避了责任，但显然他们把种族歧视的宣传留给了 Leave.EU，后者很乐意（并自豪地）承担起这项事业。在乔·考克斯被谋杀前几天，Leave.EU 的法拉奇发布了一张竞选海报，海报上是一队棕色皮肤的移民，下面写着“临界点”几个字。这一举动让人联想到 1930 年代纳粹宣传中犹太人大批涌入欧洲的场景。

A lot of the messaging from the Leave side during this time was targeted toward “metropolitan elites,” as the politicians called them, as well as people of color and European migrants. Vote Leave eschewed responsibility, but it was apparent that they had left the race-baiting to Leave.EU, which gladly (and proudly) took up the cause. A few days before Jo Cox was murdered, Leave.EU’s Farage unveiled a campaign poster showing a caravan of brown-skinned migrants beneath the words BREAKING POINT. The move drew comparisons to Nazi propaganda from the 1930s showing lines of Jewish people flooding into Europe.

当我坐在加拿大观看这场闹剧时，我告诉自己，脱欧公投与 Leave.EU 不一样，因为我的许多朋友都在为脱欧公投工作。我认为法拉奇的竞选活动是利用剑桥分析公司进行种族主义宣传。脱欧公投不可能迎合这种言论。我错了。

As I sat in Canada watching the drama unfold, I told myself that Vote Leave was not the same as Leave.EU, as many of my friends were working for Vote Leave. Farage’s campaign is the racist one using Cambridge Analytica, I thought. Vote Leave couldn’t possibly be pandering to that kind of rhetoric. I was wrong.

到竞选活动的最后几周，脱欧派几乎花光了其 700 万英镑拨款。英国法律禁止该组织接受更多资金或与其他竞选活动合作，但卡明斯想继续花钱，并决定另辟蹊径。AIQ 一直在接受脱欧派的大部分广告支出，卡明斯对 AIQ 的数字定位能力印象深刻。AIQ 能够定位、吸引和激怒特定选民。AIQ 的许多目标都是不经常投票的选民，因此即使民意调查显示留欧派领先，这也意味着 AIQ 正在吸引新的选民群体，这些选民被系统地排除在传统竞选活动和民意调查公司之外。但 AIQ 意识到，如果要保持势头，它需要的资金将超过脱欧派合法允许的支出，而且需要尽快筹集到资金。因此，注意力转向了 BeLeave 项目。在此之前，BeLeave 一直是一个完全有机的运作，由脱欧派办公室的几名实习生管理。没有付费广告，所有创意内容都是桑尼和格莱姆斯在业余时间开发的。脱欧派会为某些事情提供指导和资金，但数额非常小——偶尔 100 英镑。

By the final weeks of the campaign, Vote Leave had spent nearly all of its allotted £7 million. British law barred it from accepting any more funds or collaborating with other campaigns, but Cummings wanted to keep spending and decided to find another way. AIQ had been receiving the bulk of Vote Leave’s ad spending, and Cummings was extremely impressed with the power of AIQ’s digital targeting capabilities. AIQ was able to target, engage, and enrage specific voters. Many of AIQ’s targets were infrequent voters, so even though public polls had Remain ahead, this meant AIQ was engaging new niches of the electorate who were systemically excluded from traditional campaigning and by polling firms. But AIQ realized that if it was to sustain its momentum, it would need more money than Vote Leave was legally allowed to spend—and it needed it fast. So attention turned to the BeLeave project. Until that point, BeLeave had been a totally organic operation run by a couple of interns in the Vote Leave office. There were no paid ads, and all the creative content was being developed by Sanni and Grimes in their spare time. Vote Leave would provide guidance and money for certain things, but only very small amounts—£100 here and there.

大约在同一时间，帕金森开始邀请桑尼下班后到他家住，因为他知道桑尼住在英国伯明翰，两人开始了一段恋情。对于 22 岁、尚未向家人公开自己性取向的桑尼来说，这一切都非常新鲜和令人困惑。他不知道该如何处理与老板之间的这种亲密关系。但他对能从一位在英国政府高层工作的高级政治顾问那里得到如此多的关注和指导感到敬畏。帕金森会带桑尼出去，告诉他他对自己的工作有多满意，如果他继续这样做，他将来可能会从事这一职业。桑尼同意保守这段婚外情的秘密。

Around the same time, Parkinson began inviting Sanni to stay after hours with him in his house because he knew that Sanni was based in Birmingham, U.K., and the two began a relationship. For Sanni, who was twenty-two and not yet out about his sexuality to his family, this was all very new and confusing. He did not know how to deal with this intimate situation he now found himself in with his boss. But he was in awe of receiving so much attention and guidance from a senior political adviser who worked at the top echelons of the British government. Parkinson would take Sanni out and tell him how pleased he was with his work, and that if he kept it up there might be a future career in it for him. Sanni agreed to keep the affair secret.

选民们也注意到了 BeLeave 的工作。Sanni 和 Grimes 创作的一些内容迅速走红，甚至超过了 Vote Leave 的付费广告。BeLeave 的图片关注“卫生棉条税”等进步问题，他们认为，如果英国人脱离欧盟，他们就不需要其他 27 个成员国同意取消这种明显具有厌恶女性色彩的税收。看来，BeLeave 的进步、觉醒和社会正义导向的欧洲怀疑主义品牌有明确的市场。6 月 23 日公投前几周，Vote Leave 的外联主管 Cleo Watson 为 Grimes 和 Sanni 安排了一次与潜在捐助者的会面。两人在 Vote Leave 总部会见了捐助者，并提出了一项提案，概述了他们的帖子有多有效——在某些情况下，他们的有机外联效果超过了 Vote Leave 的付费广告的影响。

Voters were noticing BeLeave’s work too. Some of the content that Sanni and Grimes had created went viral and even outperformed Vote Leave’s paid ads. BeLeave’s graphics focused on progressive issues such as the “tampon tax,” arguing that if Britons were out of the EU, they would not need twenty-seven other member states to agree to get rid of what was so obviously a misogynistic tax. It seemed that there was a clear market for BeLeave’s progressive, woke, and social-justice-oriented brand of Euroskepticism. Weeks before the June 23 referendum, Cleo Watson, who was head of outreach in Vote Leave, set up a meeting for Grimes and Sanni with a potential donor. The pair met the donor in the Vote Leave headquarters and made a proposal outlining how effective their posts were—their organic outreach was in some cases surpassing the impact of Vote Leave’s paid ads.

格莱姆斯给我发了这个演示文稿，询问我如何优化 Facebook 的在线定位以及他的预算应该是多少。我回复了他，指导他们应该使用哪些指标以及如何宣传。这是一个不错的演示文稿，但捐赠者最终决定不投入任何资金。在捐赠者退出后，投票脱欧组织的一位高级主管找到这两名年轻的实习生，告诉他们，他们已经找到了一种为 BeLeave 筹集资金的新方法——但他们必须先签署一些文件。在与投票脱欧组织的律师会面后，桑尼和格莱姆斯被指示成立一个独立的竞选活动，开设一个银行账户，并起草正式章程。投票脱欧组织的律师起草了新竞选活动的章程，并把文件交给实习生签署。桑尼和格莱姆斯没有意识到，由于 BeLeave 与投票脱欧组织合作如此密切，因此它不能再花钱了。脱欧阵营声称，脱欧阵营是独立组织，可以自行支出预算，这使得这些年轻的实习生面临风险，因为这个“独立”阵营会进行任何非法的竞选支出。但这两名实习生并未被告知这些，他们继续像以前一样在脱欧阵营总部工作，参加脱欧阵营活动，并帮助散发传单。

Grimes had sent me this presentation, asking my advice on how to optimize targeting online for Facebook and what his budget should be. I messaged him back, providing guidance on what metrics they should use and how they should pitch. It was a good presentation, but the donor ultimately decided against putting in any money. After the donor pulled out, one of Vote Leave’s senior directors approached the two young interns and told them that they had found a new way to get them money for BeLeave—but they would have to sign some paperwork first. After meeting with Vote Leave’s lawyers, Sanni and Grimes were instructed to set up as a separate campaign, open a bank account, and write a formal constitution. The Vote Leave lawyers drafted the new campaign’s articles of association and handed the interns paperwork to sign. What Sanni and Grimes did not realize was that it was not lawful for BeLeave to spend any more money because it was working so closely with Vote Leave. By saying that the BeLeave campaign was separate and could spend its own budget Vote Leave was putting these young interns at risk for any illegal campaign spending undertaken by this “separate” campaign. But the two interns were not told any of this, and they continued as before, working at the Vote Leave headquarters, attending Vote Leave events, and helping with leafleting.

第二周，格莱姆斯和桑尼被告知，脱欧阵营承​​诺的资金终于到位了——而且这笔钱比他们要求的还要多。事实上，还会多出数十万英镑。脱欧阵营开始组织向脱欧阵营转移 70 万英镑，这将是脱欧阵营整个竞选活动中最大的一笔开支。但格莱姆斯和桑尼必须首先同意一个条件。脱欧阵营的问题是，如果他们两人以“独立”竞选形式获得这笔钱，他们就有权利随心所欲地花这笔钱。因此，脱欧阵营告诉两名实习生，他们实际上永远不会在新的银行账户中看到这笔钱。相反，脱欧阵营会直接将钱转给 AIQ，格莱姆斯和桑尼只需在 AIQ 的发票上签字即可。桑尼感到失望，他问，这些资金是否至少能支付他的旅行和伙食费（他是财务主管和秘书），但他的脱欧派主管告诉他，这是不可能的。格莱姆斯和桑尼不知道他们刚刚同意的事情是完全违法的。他们信任脱欧派的律师和顾问，他们一直告诉他们一切都井然有序。

The next week, Grimes and Sanni were told that the money Vote Leave promised them was finally coming through—and it was going to be more than they had asked for. In fact, it was going to be hundreds of thousands of pounds more. Vote Leave began organizing the transfer of £700,000 to BeLeave, in what would be the single largest expenditure of Vote Leave’s entire campaign. But Grimes and Sanni had to first agree to one condition. The problem for Vote Leave was that if the two were to receive the money as an “independent” campaign, they would be legally entitled to spend it however they liked. So Vote Leave told the two interns they would never actually see any of the money in their new bank account. Rather, Vote Leave would transfer the money to AIQ directly, and Grimes and Sanni would simply have to sign off on a set of AIQ invoices. Disappointed, Sanni asked if he could at least have his travel and food costs covered by some of these funds (he was treasurer and secretary), but he was told by his Vote Leave supervisor that that would not be possible. Grimes and Sanni had no idea that what they’d just agreed to was completely illegal. They had trusted the lawyers and advisers of Vote Leave, who consistently told them everything was in order.

让这一骗局更加糟糕的是，脱欧派律师将这些实习生的名字写在脱欧派文件上，让格莱姆斯对最终产生的法律后果负个人责任。这在英国一些较肮脏的竞选流派中并不罕见，尤其是在保守党中，他们曾多次被发现使用这种伎俩：高级竞选顾问不想承担违反选举法的个人风险，他们会找一个没有经验的人，通常是一个热心的年轻志愿者，并提名他们为竞选活动的“代理人”，这将使该人对竞选活动负法律责任。这样一来，如果发现不法行为，就会有一个替罪羊，真正的肇事者可以逍遥法外，继续享受他们与权力的接近，而把被背叛的志愿者和破碎的生活抛在身后。

What made that deception even worse was that Vote Leave’s lawyers put these interns’ names on the BeLeave documents, making Grimes personally liable for the legal fallout that eventually came. This was not an uncommon strategy in some of the dirtier schools of British campaigning, particularly among the Tories, who have been caught several times using the scheme: Senior campaign advisers not wanting to take on the personal risk of breaking election laws would find someone inexperienced, often an eager young volunteer, and nominate them as the campaign’s “agent,” which would make that person legally liable for the campaign. That way, if and when wrongdoing was uncovered, a fall guy was in place and the true perpetrators could walk off scot-free, continuing to enjoy their proximity to power while leaving behind the betrayed volunteers and broken lives.

—

公投日终于到来了。6 月 23 日，倾盆大雨持续袭击英格兰南部，赶去投票的伦敦人最终遭遇了严重的延误，火车站关闭，地铁在晚上因洪水而停止运行。包括格莱姆斯和桑尼在内的大部分“脱欧”团队成员花了一整天时间前往关键的“脱欧”席位拉票。多佛是英国通过海路和火车进入欧洲的门户，也是英国人进入英吉利海峡前的最后一站。志愿者们在多佛花了很多时间在倾盆大雨中挨家挨户敲门。右翼小报《太阳报》的头版有一个大胆而熟悉的标题：相信英国。

FINALLY, THE DAY OF the referendum arrived. On June 23, torrential rains continued to batter the south of England, and Londoners hurrying to vote ended up facing horrendous delays, with train stations closing and the tube shutting down in the evening due to flooding. Most of the Vote Leave team, including Grimes and Sanni, spent the day going to key Leave seats to get out the vote. Dover was the gateway to Europe for the U.K. by sea and by train, and the final stop for Britons before they entered the English Channel. The volunteers spent many hours in Dover knocking on doors in heavy, torrential rain. The front page of the right-wing tabloid The Sun had a single bold and familiar headline: BELEAVE IN BRITAIN.

直到投票当晚，帕金森给我发了一张他和马辛厄姆在脱欧阵营总部的照片，照片中，他们站在雾蒙蒙的窗户前，笑容满面，身后是议会大厦的轮廓。奇怪的是，尽管我回到加拿大后见过西尔维斯特几次，也和他交谈过几次，但他从未提到过 AIQ 与脱欧阵营的关系。支出报告公布后，人们发现 AIQ 获得了脱欧阵营 40% 的预算，以及包括脱欧阵营在内的其他支持脱欧阵营的数十万英镑资金。

I had no idea AIQ was involved in the Leave campaign until the night of the vote, when Parkinson texted me a photo of himself with Massingham inside the Vote Leave headquarters—grinning in front of fogged-up windows with the outline of Parliament lingering behind them. Weirdly, even though I had seen and spoken to Silvester several times since returning to Canada, he never once mentioned AIQ’s connection to the Leave campaigns. After the spending returns were released, it was revealed that AIQ had received 40 percent of Vote Leave’s budget—and hundreds of thousands of pounds more from the other pro-Brexit campaigns, including BeLeave.

现在我明白了，卡明斯就是用这种方法来回避剑桥分析公司已经与 Leave.EU 合作的事实——他只是利用了 CA 的一家子公司，这家子公司位于另一个国家，名字无人知晓。AIQ 拥有剑桥分析公司的基础设施，处理其所有数据，并可以执行所有相同的功能，但没有标签。（Vote Leave 否认它有权访问剑桥分析公司的 Facebook 数据。）没有人愿意告诉我，因为每个人都知道我离开剑桥分析公司时关系非常不好，其他许多人也知道。西尔维斯特和马辛厄姆选择保持沉默，因为这是他们在政治上最大的演出。西尔维斯特非常乐于谈论他们在非洲或加勒比地区所做的见不得人的工作，但不会谈论英国脱欧。

Now I understood that this was how Cummings had gotten around the fact that Cambridge Analytica was already working with Leave.EU—he just used one of CA’s subsidiaries, based in a different country, with a name that no one knew. AIQ had Cambridge Analytica’s infrastructure, handled all of its data, and could perform all the same functions, but without the label. (Vote Leave denies that it had access to Cambridge Analytica’s Facebook data.) Nobody had wanted to tell me because everyone knew that I had left Cambridge Analytica on such bad terms, as had many others. Silvester and Massingham chose to stay quiet because this was their biggest gig in politics. Silvester was perfectly comfortable talking about the shady work they had done in Africa or the Caribbean, but not about Brexit.

作为一名曾参与过针对性宣传活动的人，我知道媒体谈论的大部分内容并不是个人和团体在公投期间实际看到的内容。几乎是立刻，我意识到英国正在发生一些非常险恶的事情。即便如此，72% 的选民还是投了票。几个小时内，投票结果难分胜负，但最终，脱欧派以 51.89% 的选票获胜。当时我并不知道，脱欧派已任命托马斯·博维克为该活动的首席技术官。在加入脱欧派之前，博维克曾与亚历山大·尼克斯和 SCL 合作，在加勒比海岛国开展了多个数据收集项目。（然而，没有任何迹象表明博维克参与了 SCL 在该地区的任何非法工作。）公投后，博维克透露，在公投前几周，脱欧派和 AIQ 共向目标选民传播了 100 多个不同的广告，包含 1,433 条不同的信息。卡明斯随后透露，这些广告的观看次数超过 1.69 亿次，但仅针对几百万人的一小部分选民，这导致他们的新闻推送被“脱欧”投票信息所主导。

As someone who had worked on targeted campaigns, I knew that most of the content that the media was talking about was not what individuals and groups were actually seeing during the referendum. Almost instantly, I realized something deeply sinister was happening in Britain. Even so, 72 percent of voters cast ballots. For hours, the vote was too close to call, but in the end, Leave emerged victorious with 51.89 percent of the vote. Unbeknownst to me at the time, Vote Leave had appointed Thomas Borwick to become the chief technology officer of the campaign. Before joining Vote Leave, Borwick had worked with Alexander Nix and SCL running a number of data-harvesting projects in island nations across the Caribbean. (However, there is nothing to suggest that Borwick participated in any of SCL’s unlawful work in the region.) After the referendum, Borwick revealed that Vote Leave and AIQ had together disseminated more than a hundred different ads with 1,433 different messages to their target voters in the weeks leading up to the referendum. Cummings later revealed that these ads were viewed more than 169 million times, but only targeted at a narrow segment of a few million voters, which resulted in their newsfeeds being dominated by Vote Leave messaging.

英国人民是 AIQ 部署的大规模信息行动的目标，而留欧派的问题在于，他们完全没有意识到自己所面对的是什么。正如剑桥分析公司所指出的那样，激起愤怒和愤慨会降低对充分理性解释的需求，并将选民置于更加不加区分的惩罚心态中。CA 发现，这种愤怒不仅使目标选民对经济将受到影响的想法免疫，而且如果这意味着大都市自由主义者或移民等外来群体将在此过程中受到影响——实际上，他们的选票将被用作一种惩罚形式，那么有些人会支持经济受到影响。

The people of the United Kingdom were the targets of a scaled information operation deployed by AIQ, and the problem with Remain was that they completely failed to understand what they were up against. As Cambridge Analytica identified, provoking anger and indignation reduced the need for full rational explanations and would put voters into a more indiscriminately punitive mindset. CA found that not only did this anger immunize target voters to the notion that the economy would suffer, but some people would support the economy suffering if it meant that out-groups like metropolitan liberals or immigrants would suffer in the process—that, in effect, their vote would be used as a form of punishment.

事实证明，这种方法可以有效对抗留欧派的“恐惧计划”宣传，该计划试图让选民关注脱欧可能带来的灾难性经济风险。简而言之，让愤怒的人感到恐惧要困难得多。愤怒产生的“情感偏差”会影响人们对负面结果的估计，这就是为什么愤怒的人更倾向于采取冒险行为——无论是投票还是在酒吧打架，情况都是如此。如果你曾经参加过酒吧斗殴，你就会知道，让对手三思而后行最糟糕的方法就是对他大喊威胁。这只会激怒他。

This approach proved effective against Remain’s “Project Fear” messaging, which tried to focus voters on the potentially catastrophic economic risks of exiting the European Union. In short, it is far harder to make angry people fearful. The “affect bias” arising out of anger mediates people’s estimation of negative outcomes, which is why angry people are more inclined to engage in risky behavior—the same is true whether they are voting or starting a bar fight. If you have ever been in a bar fight, you know that literally the worst way imaginable to make your opponent think twice about a rash move is to yell threats at him. It only eggs him on.

留欧派关注经济，却忽视了停下来问问人们，他们眼中的经济到底是什么。剑桥分析公司发现，许多非城市地区或社会经济地位较低的人往往将“经济”的概念外化为只有富人和大都市人才能参与的事情。“经济”不是他们在当地商店的工作，而是银行家的工作。这也是某些群体对经济风险甚至贸易战感到安心的原因，因为在他们看来，混乱将降临到“经济”中工作的人身上。他们听到的经济论点越有力，他们就越有信心，他们“实际上”听到的是畏缩的精英担心失去财富的恐惧。这让他们感到强大，而这将成为他们想要掌握的力量。

Remain’s focus on the economy also neglected to stop and ask people what they thought the economy was in the first place. Cambridge Analytica identified that many people in non-urban regions or in lower socioeconomic strata often externalized the notion of “the economy” to something that only the wealthy and metropolitan participated in. “The economy” was not their job in a local store; it was something that bankers did. This is also what made certain groups comfortable with economic risks and even trade wars, since, in their minds, that chaos would be unleashed upon the people who worked in “the economy.” And the more forceful the economic argument they heard, the more confident they would become that what they were “actually” hearing was the fears of a cowering elite worried about losing its wealth. This made them feel powerful, and it would become a power they wanted to wield.

脱欧派获胜后，英国和世界陷入震惊和恐慌。戴维·卡梅伦在唐宁街 10 号前发表一份严肃声明，称将于 10 月辞去首相一职。欧元和英镑双双暴跌，全球股市暴跌。一份要求举行第二次公投的请愿书开始流传，选举结束后 72 小时内，已有 350 多万人签署了请愿书。在美国，人们的反应大多是惊讶和困惑。当专家们试图分析英国脱欧对美国人意味着什么时，奥巴马总统采取了“保持冷静，继续前行”的态度，向所有人保证“有一件事不会改变，那就是我们两国之间的特殊关系。”

After Leave won, a wave of shock and consternation swept Britain and the world. David Cameron gave a somber statement in front of 10 Downing Street, saying he would step down as prime minister by October. Both the euro and the British pound plummeted in value, and global stock markets nosedived. A petition began circulating, asking for a second referendum, and within seventy-two hours of the election, more than three and a half million people had signed it. In the United States, the response was mostly surprise and confusion. As pundits tried to parse what Brexit would mean for Americans, President Obama adopted the Keep Calm and Carry On approach, assuring everyone that “one thing that will not change is the special relationship that exists between our two nations.”

当时，唐纳德·特朗普 (Donald Trump) 碰巧在苏格兰，参观他的特朗普坦伯利 (Trump Turnberry) 高尔夫度假村。他称脱欧胜利是“一件大事”，并表示选民们夺回了自己的祖国。

Donald Trump, then the presumptive Republican nominee, happened to be in Scotland at the time, visiting his Trump Turnberry golf resort. He called the Leave victory “a great thing,” saying that the voters had taken back their country.

“人们想要夺回自己的国家，他们想要独立，”特朗普说。“全世界的人们都很愤怒……他们对边界感到愤怒，他们对那些进入美国并占领美国的人感到愤怒，甚至没有人知道他们是谁。他们对很多事情都感到愤怒。”

“People want to take their country back, they want to have independence,” Trump said. “People are angry, all over the world…They’re angry over borders, they’re angry over people coming into the country and taking over, nobody even knows who they are. They’re angry about many, many things.”

当时世界还不知道，英国脱欧是一个犯罪现场。英国是班农多年前发起的行动的第一个受害者。英国脱欧运动的所谓“爱国者”高声呼吁将英国法律和主权从欧盟的魔爪中拯救出来，他们决定通过嘲笑这些法律来赢得选举。为此，他们在外国司法管辖区部署了与剑桥分析公司有关联的公司网络，远离负责保护我们民主完整性的机构的审查。英国脱欧失败期间出现了一个明显的模式，预示着美国即将发生的事情，此前不为人知的外国实体开始通过部署来源不明的大型数据集来影响国内选举。由于社交媒体公司没有对其平台上传播的广告活动进行任何检查，因此没有人站岗阻止敌对实体试图制造混乱并破坏我们的民主。

The world did not know it yet, but Brexit was a crime scene. Britain was the first victim of an operation Bannon had set in motion years before. The so-called “patriots” of the Brexit movement, with their loud calls to rescue British law and sovereignty from the grips of the faceless European Union, decided to win a vote by mocking those very laws. And to do so, they deployed a web of companies associated with Cambridge Analytica in foreign jurisdictions, away from the scrutiny of the agencies charged with protecting the integrity of our democracies. Foreshadowing what was to come in America, a clear pattern emerged during the Brexit debacle, where previously unknown foreign entities began exerting influence on domestic elections by deploying large data sets of unexplained origins. And with social media companies not performing any checks on the advertising campaigns spreading throughout their platforms, there was no one standing guard to stop hostile entities seeking to sow chaos and disrupt our democracies.

第十章

CHAPTER 10

学徒

THE APPRENTICE

-

“我不会撒谎，这绝对是我处理过的最奇怪的案件之一，”我的律师说，当时我们正坐在她伦敦的办公室里，阅读剑桥分析公司 2015 年 6 月的一封诉前信（虚假），信中声称我正试图成立一家竞争对手公司，以支持刚刚开始的特朗普总统竞选。几个月前，也就是 2015 年春天，唐纳德·特朗普第一次出现在我的生活里，当时马克·布洛克打电话给我，提出了一个与我为剑桥分析公司所做的工作截然不同的建议。正如布洛克所解释的那样，特朗普集团需要市场调研方面的帮助，要么是为特朗普的真人秀节目《学徒》，要么是为他的赌场。布洛克还打电话给了还在伦敦的朱西卡斯和盖特森。我们三个人谈了谈，同意与特朗普的高管见面。

“I’m not going to lie, this is certainly one of the weirder cases I’ve dealt with,” my lawyer said as we sat in her office in London reading through a June 2015 pre-action letter from Cambridge Analytica (falsely) claiming that I was attempting to set up a rival firm in aid of the nascent Trump presidential campaign. Donald Trump had first come into my life a few months before, in the spring of 2015, when Mark Block called me with a proposition refreshingly far removed from the work I’d done with Cambridge Analytica. As Block explained it, the Trump Organization needed help with market research, either for Trump’s reality TV show The Apprentice or his casinos. Block had also called Jucikas and Gettleson, who were still in London. The three of us talked, and we agreed to a meeting with the Trump executives.

在与特朗普集团的通话中，我们了解到《学徒》收视率下降，入住特朗普酒店和在赌场赌博的人数也越来越少。随着网络赌博的兴起，以及对唐纳德·特朗普性感、精明的亿万富翁形象的完全依赖，他的团队似乎开始意识到，过时的赌场系统和年迈、满脸橘色的三线明星并不能给潜在的新客户带来“性感和乐趣”。特朗普品牌正处于低迷时期，公司需要想办法振兴它。

In calls with the Trump Organization, we heard about declining ratings for The Apprentice and how fewer people were staying at Trump hotels and gambling in the casinos. With the advent of online gambling and the total dependence on Donald Trump’s public image as a sexy, savvy billionaire, it seemed his team was beginning to realize that an outdated casino system and an aging, orange-stained C-list celebrity didn’t conjure “sexy and fun” for potential new customers. The Trump brand was on a downturn, and the company needed to figure out how to give it a boost.

这个项目令人沮丧地毫无定型，高管们甚至不确定我们做了什么或我们能提供什么帮助，我开始怀疑特朗普的高管们只是在寻求免费建议。当他们提议一个月后举行一次会议时，我拒绝了，满足于让 Jucikas 和 Gettleson 从特朗普大厦汇报情况。会议在特朗普大厦的一家餐厅举行，谈话又回到了电话中结束的那个模糊的地方。我们能否利用数据来提升特朗普及其产品的形象——重振特朗普品牌？如果可以，谁会是这样一个项目的目标？

The project was frustratingly amorphous, the executives weren’t even sure what we did or how we could help, and I started to suspect that the Trump executives were just looking for free advice. When they proposed a meeting for about a month later, I declined, content to let Jucikas and Gettleson report back from Trump Tower. The meeting took place at a Trump Tower restaurant, and the conversation picked up in the same vague place the calls had left off. Could we use data to enhance the image of Trump and his products—to revive the Trump brand? And if so, who would be the targets for such a project?

当盖特森打电话告诉我发生了什么事时，他笑了起来。“你不会相信的，”他说。“特朗普正在计划竞选总统。”会议的参与者包括科里·莱万多夫斯基，他自称是特朗普的竞选经理，并向盖特森和朱西卡斯保证，特朗普确实认真考虑竞选总统。他邀请我们参加竞选活动——出于几个原因，我不想参加这个邀请。第一：这是一场政治竞选，我辞去了剑桥分析公司的工作，离开伦敦就是为了远离政治。第二：特朗普看起来是个完全荒谬的人，很可能是个失败的候选人。第三：他以共和党人的身份参选，我已经受够了为右翼政客做脏活。探索如何提高真人秀节目的收视率是一回事，帮助共和党人竞选总统则是另一回事。盖特森同意了——朱西卡斯很快就要成为共和党竞选顾问了，但他并不怎么同意——我们认为，特朗普的次要情节已经结束了。

When Gettleson called to tell me about what went down, he was laughing. “You’re not going to believe this,” he said. “Trump is planning to run for president.” The meeting had included Corey Lewandowski, who identified himself as Trump’s campaign manager and assured Gettleson and Jucikas that Trump was indeed serious about running for president. He invited us to take part in the campaign—an offer I wanted no part of, for several reasons. One: It was a political campaign, and I had quit Cambridge Analytica and left London specifically to get away from politics. Two: Trump seemed like an utterly ridiculous individual and a likely failure as a candidate. And three: He was running as a Republican, and I was finished doing dirty work for right-wing politicians. It was one thing to explore how to improve ratings for a reality TV show; it was quite another to help a Republican run for president. Gettleson agreed—Jucikas, soon to be a consultant on GOP campaigns, not so much—and the Trump subplot, we assumed, had come to an end.

但几周后，也就是 2015 年 6 月 5 日，我们得知剑桥分析公司起诉了 Gettleson、Jucikas 和我。他们声称我们违反了与该公司签署的保密协议中的禁止招揽条款。根据诉讼，我们曾招揽过剑桥分析公司的一位客户：唐纳德·特朗普。通知我们诉讼的信件给了我们两周的时间做出回应，所以尽管这个案子明显是假的，我还是决定聘请律师尽快让它消失。在我们的第一次会议上，律师们都感到很困惑。想象一下，在剑桥分析公司或史蒂夫·班农成为家喻户晓的名字之前，这样的对话有多么奇怪：“所以有一家心理战公司，”我告诉他们。“它被美国的共和党亿万富翁收购了。在我辞职后，我被邀请与唐纳德·特朗普交谈—— 《学徒》里的那个家伙？显然，他将竞选总统，他是他们的秘密客户。所以现在他们起诉我……”

But a couple of weeks later, on June 5, 2015, we learned that Cambridge Analytica was suing Gettleson, Jucikas, and me. They claimed that we had violated the non-solicitation clause in our NDAs with the firm. We had, according to the lawsuit, solicited one of Cambridge Analytica’s clients: Donald Trump. The letters informing us of the lawsuit gave us two weeks to respond, so even though the case was clearly bogus, I decided to hire a lawyer to make it go away as quickly as possible. At our first meeting, the attorneys were baffled. Imagine how strange this conversation was, long before Cambridge Analytica or Steve Bannon became household names: “So there’s this psychological warfare firm,” I told them. “And it got acquired by this Republican billionaire in the United States. And after I quit, I got invited to talk with Donald Trump—the guy from The Apprentice? Apparently, he’s going to run for president, and he’s secretly a client of theirs. And so now they’re suing me…”

到现在，剑桥分析公司已经像疾病一样在共和党内蔓延，为众议院和参议院竞选的知名候选人提供咨询，并代表右翼利益开展研究文化现象（如美国青年中的军国主义）的项目。从表面上看，剑桥分析公司非常成功。但在幕后，该公司正在欺骗共和党——尤其是默瑟家族。对我来说，这起诉讼的真正真相是，剑桥分析公司作为特朗普的秘密客户与默瑟家族有联系，同时该公司还为默瑟家族中意的总统候选人泰德·克鲁兹工作。班农不仅与默瑟家族有着不同的议程，而且他也没有兴趣支持克鲁兹，班农鄙视克鲁兹。

By now, Cambridge Analytica had spread like a disease through the Republican Party, advising prominent candidates in House and Senate races and undertaking projects to study cultural phenomena, such as militarism among U.S. youth, on behalf of right-wing interests. On the face of it, Cambridge Analytica was wildly successful. But behind the scenes, the firm was screwing the Republican Party generally—and the Mercers specifically. For me, the real revelation in the lawsuit was that Cambridge Analytica was connected with Trump as an off-book client at the same time the firm was working for the Mercers’ preferred presidential candidate, Ted Cruz. Not only did Bannon have a different agenda than the Mercers, he also had no interest in supporting Cruz, whom Bannon despised.

在我向律师解释我根本不是为特朗普工作后，他们基本上说，“好吧，别担心。公司经常会发这些信件作为严厉警告，但通常不会有什么结果。这可能是他们的主管缺乏安全感。我们可以解决这个问题。”

After I explained to the attorneys that I wasn’t even working for Trump, they essentially said, “Fine, don’t worry. Firms send these letters all the time as a stern warning, but usually nothing comes of them. It’s probably their director’s insecurity. We can take care of this.”

但代价并不便宜。事实上，剑桥分析公司明确表示，他们打算继续纠缠我，让我付出金钱和心痛，直到我屈服。我提出签署一份文件，表示我永远不会再为共和党人工作，但剑桥分析公司不想要这样。他们希望我永远不再与数据打交道，这当然是一个不可能实现的要求。我们来来回回，一连几个月。整个事情变得越来越奇怪。在法律纠纷过程中，我发现，在我和盖特森离开公司后，剑桥分析公司编造了两个虚假的员工身份——“克里斯·杨”和“马克·内特尔斯”，他们继续在他们的网站和客户面前使用这些身份。最后，我同意签署一份保密协议，这本质上是一个超级保密协议，声明我永远不会讨论我在剑桥分析公司看到和做过的事情。我不知道，我作为告密者的未来的第一个陷阱已经设好了。

But it wasn’t going to be cheap. Indeed, Cambridge Analytica made it clear that they intended to keep badgering me, costing me money and peace of mind, until I gave in. I offered to sign a document saying I would never again work for a Republican, but Cambridge Analytica didn’t want that. They wanted me to never work with data again, which of course was an impossible request. Back and forth we went, for months on end. The whole thing got more and more bizarre. In the course of the legal dispute, I discovered that after Gettleson and I left the firm, CA had invented two fake staff personas—“Chris Young” and “Mark Nettles”—that they continued to use on their site and with clients. Finally I agreed to sign a deed of confidence, which was essentially a super-non-disclosure agreement stating that I would never discuss what I had seen and done at Cambridge Analytica. Unbeknownst to me, the first trap in my future as a whistleblower had been set.

—

当我回到加拿大为特鲁多的研究团队工作时，我每天的大部分时间都在参加电话会议和会议，大多数时候我都喜欢稳定、温暖且没有敌意的工作环境，尤其是老板不会一心想对员工进行心理虐待。

WHEN I MOVED BACK to Canada to work for Trudeau’s research team, my days involved mostly conference calls and meetings, and for the most part I welcomed the stability and warmth of an environment that wasn’t hostile, particularly one in which the boss wasn’t hell-bent on psychologically abusing his staff.

2016 年 3 月，一位加拿大政府高级官员打电话给我，要求我提供一份略微超出我职权范围的简报。他想了解一下美国共和党初选的情况，当时初选正如火如荼地进行着。具体来说，他想知道唐纳德·特朗普为何在民调中一路高歌猛进。3 月 1 日，特朗普在超级星期二的 11 个州中赢得了 7 个州的共和党初选，成千上万的支持者在全国各地的集会上高声呐喊。特朗普的行为越出格，他的民调数字似乎就越高：在 3 月 3 日的总统辩论中，他与佛罗里达州参议员马可·卢比奥争论起了他的阴茎尺寸，特朗普夸口说：“我向你保证，这绝对没问题。”两周后，特朗普在一天之内赢得了六个州和领地中的四个——卢比奥退出了竞选。特鲁多的支持者并不担心——但目前还不担心——但他们很好奇，因为这位真人秀明星变身的候选人让他们觉得荒谬又怪异。他为什么会表现得这么好？美国人在想什么呢？和许多加拿大同胞一样，他们以得意洋洋地向落后的邻居摇头表示高兴。

In March 2016, a senior Canadian government official called me asking for a briefing that was slightly outside my mandate. He wanted a read on the Republican primaries in the United States, which were in full swing. Specifically, he wanted to know why Donald Trump was surging in the polls. On March 1, Trump had taken the Republican primaries in seven out of eleven of the Super Tuesday states, and thousands of screaming supporters were packing his rallies across the country. The more outrageously Trump behaved, it seemed, the higher his poll numbers rose: At the March 3 presidential debate, he tangled with Senator Marco Rubio of Florida about, of all things, the size of his penis, with Trump boasting, “I guarantee you there’s no problem.” Two weeks later, Trump won four out of six states and territories in a single day—and Rubio dropped out of the race. Trudeau’s people weren’t worried—yet—but they were curious, because the reality TV star turned candidate struck them as ridiculous and weird. Why was he doing so well? What were the Americans thinking? Like many of their fellow Canadians, they took pleasure in smugly shaking their heads at their backward neighbors.

加拿大人很难理解民粹主义，因为与美国或英国不同，加拿大从未有过鲁珀特·默多克旗下的媒体。加拿大没有福克斯新闻或《太阳报》。由于其银行系统风险意识更强，该国没有经历过房地产危机或金融危机。与经合组织其他国家不同，加拿大是爱国主义和支持移民实际上呈正相关的例外。所以我会发现自己一遍又一遍地重复同样的谈话，让困惑的加拿大人无法理解英国脱欧或特朗普当选是如何发生的。

Canadians have a hard time understanding populism because, unlike America or Britain, it has never had any Rupert Murdoch–owned media. There is no Fox News or The Sun in Canada. Because of its more risk-conscious banking system, the country did not experience a housing crisis or financial crash. And unlike the rest of the OECD, Canada is the outlier where patriotism and support for immigration actually correlate positively with each other. So I would find myself repeating the same conversation over and over to baffled Canadians who simply could not understand how Brexit or Trump were even possible.

皮埃尔·特鲁多曾于 20 世纪 60 年代末和 70 年代担任加拿大总理，他曾说过，住在离美国这么近的地方就像“和大象一起睡觉。不管这头野兽多么友好、脾气多么温和……每一次抽搐和咕噜声都会影响到你。”即使特朗普没有获胜——当时很少有人认为他会获胜——他的贸易立场也已经引起了波澜。特朗普讨厌北美自由贸易协定 (NAFTA)，并激怒了与加拿大贸易关系至关重要的州的美国选民。人们担心的不是特朗普会赢，而是他执政的时间越长，他的反北美自由贸易协定言论对这些州的州长和立法选举的影响就越大，这反过来会改变全国的贸易对话。

Pierre Trudeau, Canada’s prime minister in the late 1960s and 1970s, once said that living so close to the United States was like “sleeping with an elephant. No matter how friendly and even-tempered is the beast…one is affected by every twitch and grunt.” Even if Trump didn’t win—and few people at that point thought he would—his position on trade was already creating ripples. Trump hated the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) and was riling up the American electorate in states crucial to trade relations with Canada. The fear was not so much that Trump would win, but that the longer he lasted, the more his anti-NAFTA bombast might affect gubernatorial and legislative races in these states, which in turn would shift the national dialogue on trade.

剑桥分析公司事件尚未引起公众关注，但我的加拿大同事们都知道，我为该公司所做的工作最终被传给了某些美国政治竞选活动。随着特朗普的支持率不断上升，他们的好奇心也与日俱增。我描述了剑桥分析公司的选民操纵策略——该公司如何识别和锁定具有神经质或阴谋论倾向的人，然后传播旨在深化和强调这些特征的宣传。我解释了剑桥分析公司在从 Facebook 获取用户数据后，在某些情况下可以比他们的配偶更准确地预测他们的行为，以及该公司如何利用这些信息来煽动共和党内部的激进分子。

The Cambridge Analytica saga was not yet lodged in the public consciousness, but it was no secret among my Canadian colleagues that my work for the firm had ultimately been passed on to certain U.S. political campaigns. As Trump continued to gain ground, their curiosity grew. I described Cambridge Analytica’s tactics of voter manipulation—how the firm identified and targeted people with neurotic or conspiratorial predispositions, then disseminated propaganda designed to deepen and accentuate those traits. I explained how, after obtaining people’s data from Facebook, Cambridge Analytica could in some cases predict their behavior better than their own spouses could, and how the firm was using that information to, in effect, radicalize people inside the Republican Party.

因此，尽管特朗普显然触动了一定比例的美国选民，但剑桥分析公司却在幕后努力将他的竞选活动提升到另一个层次。他们瞄准的人群中，有一群通常不投票给共和党或根本不投票的人。他们试图通过这种方式扩大选民，同时又致力于压制选民。特别是，他们专注于脱离非裔美国人和其他少数族裔社区。他们这样做的方法之一是兜售左翼社会正义言论，将希拉里·克林顿描绘成白人至上主义的宣传者——而他们自己却为白人至上主义者工作。目的是让所有具有更左翼意识形态的人口统计数据的人投票给像吉尔·斯坦这样的第三方候选人。

So while it was obvious that Trump touched a nerve with a certain percentage of American voters, Cambridge Analytica was working behind the curtain to raise his campaign to another level. A bunch of the people they were targeting were those who typically didn’t vote Republican or didn’t vote at all. They were trying to expand the electorate through this while at the same time they were committed to voter suppression. In particular, they focused on disengaging African Americans and other minority communities. One of the ways they did this was to peddle left-wing social justice rhetoric to depict Hillary Clinton as a propagator of white supremacy—while themselves working for a white supremacist. The aim was to move people from all demographics of a more left-wing ideology to vote for a third-party candidate, like Jill Stein.

当剑桥分析公司起诉我时，我开始关注候选人特朗普，因为那时我才知道这家公司在为他工作。起初，他的竞选活动一团糟。但后来他开始重复“建墙”和“抽干沼泽”等短语，他的民意调查支持率开始上升。我打电话给盖特森说：“嗯，这听起来很熟悉，不是吗？”——因为这些正是剑桥分析公司在特朗普宣布之前测试过的短语，并包含在发送给班农的报告中。这意味着，在 2016 年春季，当剑桥分析公司据称为泰德·克鲁兹工作时，其研究成果似乎（眨眨眼！）流向了唐纳德·特朗普。

I had started paying attention to candidate Trump when Cambridge Analytica sued me, because that was when I learned that the firm was working for him. At first, his campaign was a mess. But then he began repeating phrases like “Build the wall” and “Drain the swamp,” and he started rising in the polls. I called Gettleson and said, “Well, this sounds eerily familiar, doesn’t it?”—because these were the exact phrases CA had tested and included in reports sent to Bannon well before Trump announced. Meaning that, throughout the spring of 2016, when Cambridge Analytica was supposedly working for Ted Cruz, the fruits of its research seemed to be (wink wink!) making their way to Donald Trump.

随着初选的进行，特朗普获胜的机会显然在增加，渥太华民众的态度也开始从“他疯了，哈哈”转变为“他疯了……他可能会成为我们身边大象的总统”。

As the primaries continued, it became apparent that Trump’s chances of winning were increasing, and the attitude of people in Ottawa began to shift from “He’s crazy, ha ha,” to “He’s crazy…and he might become president of the elephant next to us.”

—

随着英国脱欧迫在眉睫，特朗普的支持率也越来越高，我意识到是时候发声了。我决定联系几位在硅谷工作的朋友。其中一位——我叫她“Sheela”——认识 Andreessen Horowitz 的一位同事，这家风险投资公司由科技奇才马克·安德森 (Marc Andreessen) 联合创立。20 世纪 90 年代初，安德森与埃里克·比纳 (Eric Bina) 共同创建了 Mosaic 网络浏览器，从此改变了人们使用互联网的方式。Mosaic 更名为 Netscape，并于 1995 年首次公开募股 (IPO)，成为最早的互联网超级成功企业之一。从那时起，安德森通过投资 Skype、Twitter、Groupon、Zynga 等公司赚了数亿美元……还有 Facebook。他也是 Facebook 的董事。

AS BREXIT LOOMED AND TRUMP gained ground, I realized it was time to speak up. I decided to connect with a couple of friends who worked in Silicon Valley. One of them—I’ll call her “Sheela”—knew someone at Andreessen Horowitz, the venture capital firm co-founded by the tech wunderkind Marc Andreessen. In the early nineties, Andreessen, along with Eric Bina, had created the Mosaic Web browser, forever changing the way people used the Internet. Mosaic became Netscape, which became one of the earliest Internet super-successes with its IPO in 1995. Since then, Andreessen had made hundreds of millions of dollars investing in companies like Skype, Twitter, Groupon, Zynga…and Facebook. He also sat on Facebook’s board.

2016 年春天，我飞​​往旧金山，开始向相关方介绍我在剑桥分析公司所见所闻。Sheela 在位于门洛帕克沙丘路的 Andreessen Horowitz 办公室安排了一次会面。从外面看，这栋建筑看起来像一个稍微高档的郊区牙医诊所，但里面，大厅相当平淡，墙上挂满了昂贵的艺术品。我在会议室里会见了 Andreessen 的员工，并向他们介绍了剑桥分析公司、它盗用的数百万 Facebook 个人资料以及它利用这些个人资料干预选举的恶意方式。

I flew to San Francisco in the spring of 2016 to start briefing relevant parties on what I’d seen at Cambridge Analytica. Sheela set up a meeting at the Andreessen Horowitz offices, on Sand Hill Road in Menlo Park. From the outside, the building looked like a slightly upscale suburban dentist’s office, but inside, a rather bland lobby gave way to walls hung with fantastically expensive art. I met with Andreessen employees in a conference room and told them about Cambridge Analytica, the millions of Facebook profiles it had misappropriated, and the malicious way it was using the profiles to interfere with the election.

“伙计们，你们为大股东和董事会成员工作，”我说。“Facebook 应该意识到这种情况。”他们告诉我他们会调查此事。至于是否真的发生了，我不知道。

“Guys, you work for a major shareholder and board member,” I said. “Facebook needs to be aware that this is going on.” They told me they would look into it. Whether that actually happened, I have no idea.

现在 Facebook 的一名董事会成员似乎已经介入此案，于是我去了旧金山 Mission District 的一个聚会，Facebook 的一位副总裁预计也会是来宾之一。结果，聚会上挤满了 Facebook 的员工。他们的装扮是标准的硅谷风格——紧身的灰色 T 恤——谈话中很难不听到生酮禁食饮食的进展报告、喝 Soylent 代餐，以及为什么食物变得“被高估”。我被介绍为剑桥分析公司的负责人，很快就成了关注的焦点，因为他们都听说过很多关于这家公司的传言。当时，他们似乎都知道剑桥分析公司，后来我发现，早在 2015 年 9 月，Facebook 员工就在内部讨论过剑桥分析公司，并要求对该公司可能“抓取”数据的行为进行调查。 2015 年 12 月，员工们再次要求进行调查，后来美国证券交易委员会向 Facebook 提交的一份投诉中引用了这些员工的话，称该公司是一家“粗略的数据建模公司（至少可以这么说），但已经深入渗透了我们的市场”。但当我回答他们的问题时，很明显，他们对剑桥分析公司所取得的成就的兴趣远不及对民主的威胁。就连 Facebook 的副总裁似乎也大多不为所动。他说，如果我对剑桥分析公司有意见，那么我应该成立一家竞争对手公司——通过开发 Lyft 来回应 Uber 的宣传。我觉得这个建议很不合常理，更不用说不负责任了，因为它出自一家完全有能力采取有意义行动的公司高管之口。但我很快意识到，这就是硅谷的运作方式。对任何问题的反应，即使是像威胁到我们选举的完整性这样严重的问题，也不是“我们如何解决它？”而是“我们如何将其货币化？”他们无法看到商业机会之外的东西。我浪费了自己的时间。后来我参与的美国监管调查最终确定，至少有 30 名 Facebook 员工知道剑桥分析公司的事情——但在我举报之前，该公司并没有制定任何程序向监管机构报告此事。

With a Facebook board member now apparently on the case, I went to a party in San Francisco’s Mission District, where a Facebook VP was expected to be among the guests. As it turned out, the party was filled with Facebook employees. The look was standard-issue Silicon Valley—form-fitted gray T-shirts—and it was hard to get through a conversation without hearing a progress report on a keto fasting diet, drinking Soylent meal replacements, and why food was becoming “overrated.” Introduced as the guy from Cambridge Analytica, I quickly became the center of attention, as they’d all heard so many rumors about the company. At the time, they all seemed to be aware of Cambridge Analytica, and I later found out that as far back as September 2015, Facebook employees discussed Cambridge Analytica internally and had asked for an investigation into the possible “scraping” of data by the company. The employees reiterated their request for an investigation in December 2015, and would later be quoted in a Securities and Exchange Commission complaint filed against Facebook describing the firm as a “sketchy (to say the least) data modeling company that has penetrated our market deeply.” But as I answered their questions, it was obvious that threats to democracy didn’t interest them nearly as much as the mechanics of what Cambridge Analytica had pulled off. Even the Facebook vice president seemed mostly unfazed. If I had a problem with Cambridge Analytica, he said, then I should create a rival firm—respond to the Uber of propaganda by developing the Lyft. This suggestion struck me as perverse—not to mention irresponsible—coming from an executive at a company well positioned to take meaningful action. But that was how Silicon Valley operated, I soon realized. The reaction to any problem, even one as serious as a threat to the integrity of our elections, is not “How can we fix it?” Rather, it’s “How can we monetize it?” They were incapable of seeing beyond the business opportunity. I had wasted my time. The U.S. regulatory investigation that I later took part in eventually determined that at least thirty Facebook employees knew about Cambridge Analytica—but prior to the story being made public by my whistleblowing, the company did not put into place any procedures to report this to regulators.

后来，我被安德森·霍洛维茨的员工邀请加入一个名为“未来世界”的私人 Facebook 聊天群，硅谷各大公司的高管们正在讨论科技行业面临的问题，包括我提出的问题。安德森还开始与硅谷的其他高管讨论他们的平台可能被滥用的情况。他邀请了其他几位硅谷知名人士到他家聚餐，他们开始把这个聚餐称为“军政府” ——指的是掌权后统治一个国家的独裁团体。

Later, I was invited by Andreessen Horowitz staff to a private Facebook chat group called “Futureworld,” where executives from major Silicon Valley companies were discussing problems facing the tech sector, including issues I had raised. Andreessen also started talking to other executives in Silicon Valley about how their platforms were potentially being misused. He welcomed several other Silicon Valley notables to his house for a dinner group they began to refer to as “the Junta”—a reference to authoritarian groups that rule a country after taking power.

一名小组成员在给安德森的电子邮件中说：“如果我们的通信被政府注意到，是因为我们对‘军政府’一词的讽刺性使用触发了他们的算法，那真是太讽刺了。”

“It’ll sure be ironic if the reason our correspondence lands on the government’s radar,” one group member emailed Andreessen, was because “their algorithms were triggered by our sarcastic use of the word ‘junta.’ ”

—

2016 年初夏，俄罗斯事件开始发酵。6 月中旬，Guccifer 2.0 泄露了从民主党全国委员会窃取的文件。一周后，就在民主党全国代表大会召开前三天，维基解密公布了数千封被盗电子邮件，导致伯尼·桑德斯、希拉里·克林顿和民主党全国委员会主席黛比·沃瑟曼·舒尔茨之间出现裂痕，后者几乎当场辞职。当然，尼克斯最终在丽贝卡·默瑟的要求下开始四处打听克林顿的电子邮件，最终向维基解密提供剑桥分析公司的服务，以帮助传播被黑客入侵的材料。我从一位仍在该公司工作的前同事那里得知了这件事，当时他认为一切都失控了。

IN EARLY SUMMER OF 2016, the Russia narrative started bubbling up. In mid-June, Guccifer 2.0 leaked documents that had been stolen from the Democratic National Committee. A week later, just three days before the Democratic National Convention, WikiLeaks published thousands of stolen emails, opening rifts between Bernie Sanders, Hillary Clinton, and DNC chair Debbie Wasserman Schultz, who resigned almost immediately. And, of course, Nix eventually began asking around about Clinton’s emails at the behest of Rebekah Mercer, eventually offering Cambridge Analytica’s services to WikiLeaks to help disseminate the hacked material. I found out about this from a former colleague who was still with the firm and thought everything was getting out of hand.

就在民主党试图让大会重回正轨时，唐纳德·特朗普又向民主党投掷了一颗手榴弹。在 7 月 27 日的新闻发布会上，他随意地邀请俄罗斯继续干涉竞选活动。“俄罗斯，如果你在听，”他咆哮道，“我希望你能找到失踪的三万封电子邮件”——这是指克林顿认为是私人邮件并删除的邮件，而不是将它们交给调查她使用私人电子邮件服务器的调查人员。

As the Democrats tried to get their convention back on track, Donald Trump lobbed another metaphorical grenade at the party. At a news conference on July 27, he casually invited Russia to continue its interference in the campaign. “Russia, if you’re listening,” he blustered, “I hope you’re able to find the thirty thousand emails that are missing”—a reference to emails that Clinton had deemed personal and deleted, rather than turning them over to investigators looking into her use of a private email server.

从夏天到秋天，特朗普和普京互相赞赏，我开始回想起我在剑桥分析公司注意到的与俄罗斯的奇怪联系。科根与圣彼得堡的关系。与卢克石油公司高管的会面。萨姆·帕滕吹嘘与俄罗斯政府合作。剑桥分析公司的内部备忘录暗示俄罗斯情报机构。有关普京的问题莫名其妙地插入我们的研究中。甚至布列塔尼·凯泽与朱利安·阿桑奇和维基解密的明显联系。当时，我以为这些都是奇怪的事件，每个事件都是偶然发生的。但现在它们开始看起来更像一件大事。

Over the summer and into the fall, Trump and Putin exchanged admiring comments, and I started thinking back on the weird Russia connections I’d noticed at Cambridge Analytica. Kogan’s ties to St. Petersburg. The meeting with Lukoil executives. Sam Patten’s boasts about working with the Russian government. Cambridge Analytica’s internal memos alluding to Russian intelligence. The Putin questions inexplicably inserted into our research. And even Brittany Kaiser’s apparent connection to Julian Assange and WikiLeaks. At the time, I had thought these were strange events, each one incidental to the others. But now they began to seem like something more.

特朗普于 7 月 19 日在共和党全国大会上成为共和党候选人。如果我的直觉没错，剑桥分析公司不仅利用我开发的数据工具操纵美国选民支持他，还可能有意或无意地与俄罗斯合作影响选举。现在我站在剑桥分析公司外面，仿佛拥有透视眼一样。我知道这家公司愿意涉足的深度，以及其核心的道德空白。我感到恶心。我知道我必须告诉某人——拉响警报。

Trump became the GOP nominee at the Republican National Convention on July 19. If my hunch was correct, Cambridge Analytica was not only using the data tool I had worked on to manipulate American voters into supporting him, it may have been knowingly or unknowingly working with Russians to sway the election. Now that I was outside Cambridge Analytica looking in, it was as if I had X-ray vision. I knew the depths this company was willing to plumb, and the moral void at its core. I felt sick to my stomach. And I knew I had to tell someone—to raise the alarm.

我联系了特鲁多政府的某个人——我称他为“艾伦”——并告诉他我的担忧。我开始描述俄罗斯、维基解密和剑桥分析公司之间的所有联系。我告诉他，我开始相信剑桥分析公司是俄罗斯事件的一部分，并建议我们与美国政府的某个人分享细节。

I approached someone in the Trudeau government—I’ll call him “Alan”—and told him about my concerns. I started describing all the connections between Russia, WikiLeaks, and Cambridge Analytica. I told him I had come to believe that Cambridge Analytica was a part of the Russia story and suggested that we share the details with someone in the U.S. government.

我们不想越界，我们希望尊重美国大选。我们担心，尽管我们只是想警告美国潜在的安全威胁，特别是来自俄罗斯的威胁，但站出来可能会被误解为外国势力试图干涉选举——我们绝对没有干涉。我们决定采取另一种计划——去伯克利参加一个以数据和民主为重点的会议，在那里我们可以与我们知道会出席的几位白宫官员进行一次秘密交谈。

We didn’t want to cross a line, and we wanted to stay respectful of the U.S. election. We were concerned that even though we only wanted to warn the United States about potential security threats, particularly from Russia, coming forward could be misinterpreted as a case of foreign actors attempting to interfere in the election—which we definitely were not. We settled on an alternative plan—a trip to Berkeley for a conference focused on data and democracy, where we could aim for a discreet chat with a couple of White House officials who we knew would be there.

另一个与我深入讨论过此事的人是奥巴马的前目标定位主管肯·斯特拉斯马。我曾在纽约与斯特拉斯马会面，并向他介绍了剑桥分析公司的数据定位。由于他的公司刚刚为伯尼·桑德斯的 2016 年竞选活动提供了微目标定位服务，他自然对此很感兴趣。

The other person I had talked to extensively about all this was Ken Strasma, Obama’s former targeting director. I had met with Strasma in New York and told him about Cambridge Analytica’s data targeting. Since his firm had just provided microtargeting services for Bernie Sanders’s 2016 campaign, naturally he was interested.

克林顿赢得提名后，7 月底，斯特拉斯玛打电话给我说：“既然我们输了，我想看看能否与希拉里的数据团队谈谈。”他问我是否有兴趣与他们见面，概述我对特朗普竞选团队发生的事情的怀疑。当然，我告诉他是的。不幸的是，我们始终无法与克林顿团队取得联系。

After Clinton clinched the nomination, in late July, Strasma called me and said, “Now that we’ve lost, I’m going to see if I can talk with Hillary’s data team.” He asked whether I’d be interested in meeting with them to outline my suspicions about what was happening with the Trump campaign. Yes, of course, I told him. Unfortunately, we were never able to connect with the Clinton team.

—

8 月，我和贾斯汀·特鲁多办公室的一些顾问一起前往伯克利参加会议。我们只会在那里呆几天，所以我请另一位来自硅谷的朋友（我称他为“凯拉尼”）帮我们安排会议。最重要的一次会议是与白宫工作人员的会面。

IN AUGUST, I TRAVELED to Berkeley for a conference with some advisers from Justin Trudeau’s office. We would be there for only a few days, so I asked another friend from Silicon Valley, whom I will call “Kehlani,” to help us arrange meetings. The most important one would be with the White House staffers.

我知道与白宫官员的会面会很短，这意味着我们只有一次机会来表达我们的观点。由于我的听众可能不熟悉剑桥分析公司，他们很可能不明白我们在说什么，从而忽略其重要性。所以我请凯拉尼找一个隐蔽的场所，我们可以在那里安顿下来并计划我们的会面。

I knew the meeting with the White House officials would be short, which meant we would have one shot to get our point across. And since it was likely that my audience would not be familiar with Cambridge Analytica, there was a good chance they wouldn’t understand what we were talking about and would miss its significance. So I asked Kehlani to find a discreet setting where we could set up base and plan our meeting.

“你想把它藏得多隐蔽？”她回答道。“我可以帮你找一个没有手机信号的地方。”

“How discreet do you want it?” she replied. “I can get you a place that doesn’t have cellphone reception.”

“有点没必要，不过没关系，”我笑着说。她给了我们一个地址。

“A little unnecessary, but okay,” I said with a laugh. She gave us an address.

第二天下午，我们开车来到 GPS 指引的地方，结果发现那里是造船厂的中央。凯拉尼正在等我们。她带我们经过一个仓库，沿着码头走下去。事情变得越来越奇怪，而当我们不得不绕过巨大的海豹时，情况就变得更加奇怪了。经过它们，我们遇到了一艘 135 英尺长的挪威渡轮，部分地方已经生锈——它肯定不会通过检查。这艘曾经白色的船已经变成了灰色，整个船底都粘满了藤壶。有人扔下梯子，这样我们就可以爬上在水中上下摇晃的船。

The following afternoon, we drove to where the GPS pointed us, which turned out to be the middle of a shipyard. Kehlani was waiting. She led us past a warehouse, down the dock. Things were getting weird, and they got even weirder when we had to step around giant harbor seals. Past them, we came upon a 135-foot Norwegian ferry, rusting in parts—it definitely wouldn’t have passed inspection. The once-white ship had become gray, with barnacles stuck along its entire base. Someone threw down a ladder so we could climb up to the ship as it bobbed and swayed in the water.

凯拉尼找到了最安全的环境：一艘黑客船。这艘船停泊在旧金山附近，船上有几名从事创业和其他不确定技术活动的程序员。我们没有问。考虑到正在发生的一切，这一切都感觉恰到好处。我们整个旅程都以这艘船为基地。

Kehlani had found the most secure environment imaginable: a hacker ship. Anchored near San Francisco, the vessel was home to a handful of coders engaged in startups and other indeterminate tech activities. We didn’t ask. In light of everything that was going on, it all felt perfectly apropos. We based ourselves on this ship throughout the trip.

第二天到达会场后，我们开始安排非正式会谈。艾伦尤其希望我们强调，我们是以个人身份进行此次对话，而不是以特鲁多的代表身份。此次会谈将把不代表加拿大政府的加拿大政府雇员介绍给不代表白宫的白宫工作人员。会谈的主题是美国大选，以及共和党在剑桥分析公司问题上的最新进展，包括其庞大的监控数据库及其与外国情报机构的潜在关系。

Arriving at the conference the next day, we made arrangements for our unofficial meeting. Alan, in particular, was eager for us to emphasize that we were having this conversation in a personal capacity, not as representatives of Trudeau. The meeting would introduce employees of the Canadian government who were not representing that government to White House staffers who were not representing the White House. The topic was the U.S. election and what was happening in the Republican Party with respect to Cambridge Analytica, including its massive surveillance database and its potential relationships with foreign intelligence agencies.

白宫小组的某个人问我们是否可以到外面聊聊，因为他们在会议上整天都被关在屋子里。于是，我们看到了一幅相当奇怪的画面：一群高级政府顾问挤在加州大学伯克利分校附近的一张野餐桌旁，谈论剑桥分析公司和俄罗斯参与美国总统大选——与此同时，一群抽着大麻、背着背包的学生从旁边走过。

Someone from the White House group asked if we could talk outside, as they’d been cooped up all day at the conference. Which is how we ended up in a rather bizarre tableau: a group of high-level government advisers, crowded around a picnic table near the UC Berkeley campus, talking about Cambridge Analytica and Russian involvement in the U.S. presidential election—all while weed-smoking, backpack-wearing students strolled past.

我直奔主题，警告美国人剑桥分析公司可能参与俄罗斯干预。“我们知道，特朗普竞选团队中有人与外国情报机构有联系，”我说。“他们建立了一个庞大的社交媒体数据库，并正在美国选民身上部署。”

I got right to the point, warning the Americans about Cambridge Analytica’s likely involvement in Russian interference. “We know that there are individuals working on Trump’s campaign who have ties to foreign intelligence services,” I said. “They have built up a massive social media database which is being deployed on American voters.”

我详细介绍了剑桥分析公司与俄罗斯的关系，并描述了尼克斯向卢克石油公司所做的介绍。我告诉他们该公司正在破坏人们对选举过程的信心。

I detailed Cambridge Analytica’s Russia connections and described the presentation Nix had made to Lukoil. I told them about the company’s work to undermine people’s confidence in the electoral process.

他们的回答是……乏味的。其中一位美国人说，他们无能为力，因为担心被指控利用联邦政府的力量来影响选举。（我清楚地记得“操纵选举”这个词。）奥巴马团队似乎非常担心不要玷污他们认为几乎肯定会获胜的克林顿。现在看来这很荒谬，但当时有传言称，在特朗普不可避免地失败后，他打算推出特朗普电视台来与福克斯新闻竞争。他还预计会声称选举被操纵了——深层政府影响了选举，或者克林顿作弊了，或者两者兼而有之。奥巴马政府担心特朗普会利用任何违规行为来使选举非法化，因此希望确保他没有任何具体的理由可以抱怨。

Their reply was…ho-hum. One of the Americans said they couldn’t do much, for fear of being accused of using the weight of the federal government to influence a vote. (I distinctly remember the phrase “move the dial.”) The Obama group seemed extremely concerned about not tainting what they believed was a near-certain Clinton win. It seems ridiculous now, but at the time, the rumor was that, after his inevitable loss, Trump intended to launch Trump TV as a rival to Fox News. He was also expected to claim that the election had been rigged—that the deep state had influenced it, or Clinton had cheated, or both. Worried that Trump would use any irregularity to delegitimize the election, the Obama administration wanted to make sure it gave him nothing concrete to complain about.

当白宫的人告诉我特朗普电视台的事情时，我明白了。我想他们知道自己在做什么——毕竟，这件事发生在他们的国家，不是我的国家。我们握手言和，各奔东西。这种反应并非独一无二。2016 年初，Facebook 高管发现俄罗斯黑客已在该平台上调查与总统竞选有关的个人，但他们选择不向公众或当局发出警告，因为这会给公司带来声誉问题。（Facebook 于 2017 年 9 月首次公开概述了俄罗斯在其平台上进行信息操作的程度，当时距离它首次发现该问题已过去一年多，距离它开始调查其网站上传播的所谓“五级火灾”虚假信息已过去七个月。）最终，由于民主党对威胁漠不关心，而硅谷无法理解如何在不制造另一个“ X的 Uber ”的情况下解决问题，我警告美国人的努力毫无进展。当你试图敲响警钟，而人们却不断告诉你“别担心”或“别惹麻烦”时，你开始怀疑自己是不是反应过度了。我既没有参加克林顿竞选，也没有在白宫任职。我只是一个在加拿大对着风大喊大叫的人。

When the White House guys told me about Trump TV, it made sense. I figured they knew what they were doing—and, after all, this was happening in their country, not mine. We all shook hands and went our separate ways. And this response was not unique. In early 2016, senior Facebook executives had identified that Russian hackers had probed the platform for individuals connected to the presidential campaigns, but chose not to warn the public or the authorities, as it would cause reputational issues for the company. (Facebook first publicly outlined the extent of the Russian information operations on its platform in September 2017, more than a year after it first identified the issue, and seven months after beginning to investigate what was called a “five-alarm fire” of disinformation spreading on its site.) Ultimately, between the Democrats’ indifference to the threat and Silicon Valley’s inability to understand how to solve a problem without creating another “Uber of X,” my efforts to warn the Americans went nowhere. When you try to sound an alarm and people keep telling you “Don’t worry about it” or “Don’t rock the boat,” you start to wonder if maybe you’re overreacting. I wasn’t in the Clinton campaign or in the White House. I was just a guy in Canada, shouting into the wind.

当然，最不好笑的笑点在于，在克林顿和奥巴马团队极度不愿“干预”选举之后，联邦调查局局长詹姆斯·科米却在最后一刻决定重启对克林顿电子邮件的调查，让一切都变得一团糟。当时，在加拿大，我感觉自己正在目睹一个自我毁灭的朋友终于跌入悬崖。你只能惊恐地站在那里，想着，我试图告诉你！但在这种情况下，这位朋友不只是烧毁了自己的房子。他烧毁了整个街区。

The unfunny punch line, of course, is that, following the supreme reluctance of the Clinton and Obama teams to “interfere” in the election, FBI director James Comey would sashay in and blow everything out of the water with his eleventh-hour decision to reopen the Clinton email investigation. At that point, back in Canada, I felt like I was watching a self-destructive friend finally tip over the edge. You can only stand there in horror, thinking, I tried to tell you! But in this case, the friend wasn’t just burning down his own house. He was burning down the whole neighborhood.

—

8 月底，参议员哈里·里德公开敦促联邦调查局调查俄罗斯干预大选。但当时，大多数人仍然认为希拉里·克林顿注定会输。与此同时，剑桥分析公司正式宣布与特朗普竞选团队合作。这让渥太华人感到紧张，因为我很清楚剑桥分析公司数据的力量和影响力。该公司为特朗普所做的工作已经够令人担忧了，但当你把俄罗斯的关系也算进去时，整个情况似乎非常令人担忧。

IN LATE AUGUST, Senator Harry Reid publicly urged the FBI to investigate Russian interference in the election. But at that time, most people still thought the race was Clinton’s to lose. At the same time, Cambridge Analytica officially announced that it was working with the Trump campaign. This put nerves on edge in Ottawa, because I had been clear about the power and reach of Cambridge Analytica’s data. The firm’s work on behalf of Trump was worrying enough, but when you added the Russian connections into the equation, the whole situation seemed very alarming.

特朗普获胜的可能性是特鲁多办公室热议的话题，尽管这仍然只是个笑话。从难以想象到难以想象再到令人恐惧，这到底有多难以想象？我们有一次开会时，有几个人取笑特朗普。天哪，这些美国人！他们每次都超越自己！然后每个人都笑了。好吧，几乎每个人都笑了。我没有笑，因为我明白心理战的威力。

The possibility of a Trump win was the talk of Trudeau’s office, though it was still mostly a laughing matter. On a scale of unimaginable to unthinkable to terrifying, just how unimaginable was it? We had one meeting where a couple of people were making fun of Trump. God, these Americans! They outdo themselves every time! And everybody laughed. Well, almost everyone. I wasn’t laughing, because I understood the power of psychological warfare at scale.

德国人有句俗语叫“ Mauer im Kopf”，翻译过来就是“心灵的墙”。1990年东西德统一后，两德之间的法定边界消失。检查站消失了，铁丝网被拆除了，柏林墙也终于被推倒了。但即使在统一 15 年后，许多德国人仍然高估了东西德城市之间的距离。似乎存在着一种挥之不去的心理距离，它暴露了国家的地理位置，在人们的脑海中形成了一条虚拟的边界。虽然那堵钢筋水泥的墙早已倒塌，但它的影子却依然存在，铭刻在德国人的心灵中。当这位新候选人突然出现，要求美国修建这堵墙时，我知道这不是字面上的要求。民主党和共和党似乎都不知道该如何应对如此荒谬的竞选纲领。但与这匹新黑马不同，他们无法洞悉美国人的内心想法。他们看不到这些人不仅仅是在要求修建一堵实体的墙。这并不是要建一堵字面上的墙——建墙的想法本身就足以开始实现班农的目标。他们要求建立美国自己的“毛里求斯”。

The Germans have an expression called Mauer im Kopf, which translates roughly as “the wall in the mind.” After the East and the West reunified in 1990, the legal border between the two Germanys was dissolved. The checkpoints disappeared, the barbed wire was ripped away, and the Berlin Wall was finally taken down. But even fifteen years after reunification, many Germans still overestimated the distances between cities in the East and the West. There was, it seems, a lingering psychological distance that betrayed the nation’s geography, creating a virtual border in people’s minds. Although that wall of concrete and steel had long since crumbled, its shadow lived on, etched into the psyches of the German people. When this new candidate came out of nowhere, demanding that America build the wall, I knew that this was not a literal demand. Democrats and Republicans alike seemed at a loss for how to react to such an absurd campaign platform. But, unlike this new dark horse, they could not peer into what was happening in the minds of America. They could not see that those people were not merely demanding a physical wall. It was not about building a literal wall—the very idea of the wall itself was enough to begin to achieve Bannon’s aims. They were demanding the creation of America’s very own Mauer im Kopf.

艾伦也没有笑。在一次会议上，他说：“我真的认为特朗普能赢。”人们看着他，翻了个白眼，有人说：“得了吧。”然后他看着我，我说：“是的，我也认为他能赢。”那一刻，我真正意识到，令我极度恐惧的是，我帮助建立的工具可能会在唐纳德·特朗普成为美国下一任总统的过程中发挥关键作用。

Alan wasn’t laughing, either. In one meeting he said, “I actually think Trump can win.” People looked at him and rolled their eyes, and someone said, “Come on.” Then he looked at me, and I said, “Yeah, I think he can win, too.” That was the moment when I truly grasped, to my utter horror, that the tools I had helped build might play a pivotal role in making Donald Trump the next president of the United States.

几周后，我父母家收到了 Facebook 的一封信。我不知道 Facebook 是如何得到他们的地址的。我母亲把信转发给了我。这封信是由 Facebook 聘请的一家律师事务所 Perkins Coie 寄出的，克林顿竞选团队正是通过这家律师事务所资助对后来成为特朗普-俄罗斯档案的私人调查。Facebook 的律师试图证实剑桥分析公司获得的数据仅用于学术目的，并且已被删除。现在剑桥分析公司正式为特朗普竞选团队工作，Facebook 显然认为，让数百万用户的个人资料被窃取以谋取政治利益是不光彩的，更不用说剑桥分析公司惊人的商业财富了。这封信没有提到利用公司数据颠覆世界。当然，这封信是荒谬的，是一种软弱的姿态，因为 Facebook明确授权剑桥分析公司使用的数据收集应用程序将数据用于非学术用途——这是我在与 Kogan 合作时专门向该公司提出的请求。我对 Facebook 假装的惊愕反应更加困惑，因为在 2015 年 11 月左右，Facebook 聘请了 Kogan 的商业伙伴 Joseph Chancellor 担任“量化研究员”。据 Kogan 说，Facebook 决定聘请 Chancellor 是在公司被告知性格分析项目之后。后来，当故事公开时，Facebook 扮演了震惊受害者的角色。但它没有明确表示，它愿意聘请一位曾与 Kogan 共事的人。然而，Facebook 后来在一份声明中表示，“他之前所做的工作与他在 Facebook 的工作无关。”

A couple of weeks later, a letter from Facebook arrived at my parents’ house. How Facebook got their address, I had no idea. My mother forwarded the letter to me. It had been sent by a law firm Facebook had hired, Perkins Coie, which was the same firm that the Clinton campaign was using to fund the private investigation into what later became the Trump-Russia dossier. Facebook’s lawyers sought to confirm that the data Cambridge Analytica had obtained was used only for academic purposes, and that it had been deleted. Now that Cambridge Analytica was officially working on the Trump campaign, Facebook had apparently decided it would be bad optics to have millions of its users’ personal profiles raided for political gain, not to mention Cambridge Analytica’s astonishing commercial enrichment. The letter made no mention of using company data to turn the world inside out. And, of course, the letter was preposterous, a feeble gesture, because Facebook had given the data-harvesting application used by Cambridge Analytica express permission to use the data for non-academic purposes—a request I had made specifically to the company while working with Kogan. I was even more confused at Facebook’s feigned pearl-clutching reaction, as in or around November 2015 Facebook hired Kogan’s business partner Joseph Chancellor to work as a “quantitative researcher.” According to Kogan, Facebook’s decision to hire Chancellor came after the company was told about the personality profiling project. Later, when the story became public, Facebook played the role of shocked victim. But what it did not make clear was that it was content to hire someone who had actually worked with Kogan. However, in a statement Facebook later said, “The work that he did previously has no bearing on the work that he does at Facebook.”

当然，剑桥分析公司不可能删除 Facebook 数据。但我一年多前就离开了公司，还被他们起诉过，我绝对不想为他们说话。我回复说，我不再拥有这些数据，但我不知道这些数据在哪里，还有谁拿到了这些数据，也不知道剑桥分析公司会用这些数据做什么——Facebook 也不知道。但我非常担心自己与剑桥分析公司有任何关联，所以我没有直接把这封信塞进加拿大议会的寄出邮件里，而是走到市中心把它寄出去。我不希望剑桥分析公司的污点出现在我为特鲁多工作的地方。

There was no way Cambridge Analytica had deleted the Facebook data, of course. But I had left the firm more than a year earlier, and had been sued by them, and wanted absolutely no part of speaking for them. I replied, saying that I no longer had the data in question, but I had no idea where the data was, who else got ahold of it, or what Cambridge Analytica was doing with it—and neither did Facebook. But I was paranoid enough about being connected to Cambridge Analytica in any way that, instead of just popping the letter into the outgoing mail from the Canadian Parliament, I walked downtown to mail it. I didn’t want the taint of Cambridge Analytica anywhere near my work for Trudeau.

2016 年 9 月 22 日，参议员黛安·范斯坦和众议员亚当·希夫发表声明称，俄罗斯正试图破坏选举。而在 9 月 26 日的首场总统辩论中，希拉里·克林顿敲响了警钟。“我知道唐纳德非常赞赏弗拉基米尔·普京，”她说。普京“放任网络攻击者入侵政府文件、个人文件、民主党全国委员会。我们最近了解到，这是他们试图制造混乱和收集信息的首选方法之一。”

On September 22, 2016, Senator Dianne Feinstein and Congressman Adam Schiff released a statement saying that Russia was attempting to undermine the election. And in the first presidential debate, on September 26, Hillary Clinton sounded the alarm. “I know Donald is very praiseworthy of Vladimir Putin,” she said. Putin had “let loose cyber attackers to hack into government files, to hack into personal files, hack into the Democratic National Committee. And we recently have learned that this is one of their preferred methods of trying to wreak havoc and collect information.”

“我认为没有人知道是俄罗斯入侵了民主党全国委员会，”特朗普回应道。“她说俄罗斯、俄罗斯、俄罗斯。也许是。我的意思是，可能是俄罗斯，但也可能是中国，也可能是其他很多人。也可能是坐在床上的某个重达 400 磅的人，好吗？”

“I don’t think anybody knows it was Russia that broke into the DNC,” Trump responded. “She’s saying Russia, Russia, Russia. Maybe it was. I mean, it could be Russia, but it could also be China, could also be lots of other people. It also could be someone sitting on their bed that weighs four hundred pounds, okay?”

10 月 7 日，在特朗普说“抓住他们的阴部”的Access Hollywood录音带公开后不到一小时，维基解密开始发布从克林顿竞选主席约翰·波德斯塔的账户中窃取的电子邮件。他们将继续一点一点地发布电子邮件，直到选举日，这对民主党来说是灾难性的后果。克林顿对华尔街演讲的细节以及其他披露的内容引发了丑闻，另类右翼的极端分子利用这些电子邮件来支持一种疯狂的理论，即克林顿竞选团队的最高层参与了华盛顿特区一家披萨店的儿童色情团伙。我的脑海里不断浮现出剑桥分析公司、俄罗斯政府和阿桑奇之间的联系。剑桥分析公司似乎在这场竞选的每个肮脏部分都沾染了它的肮脏手。

On October 7, less than an hour after the Access Hollywood tape of Trump saying “grab ’em by the pussy” became public, WikiLeaks began publishing emails hacked from the account of Clinton campaign chair John Podesta. They would continue to release emails, bit by bit, until Election Day, and the fallout for the Democrats was disastrous. Scandals erupted over details of Clinton’s speeches to Wall Street, among other revelations, and the lunatic fringe of the alt-right used the emails to fuel the deranged theory that the Clinton campaign, at the highest levels, was involved in a child sex ring being run out of a Washington, D.C., pizza parlor. My mind kept returning to the connections among Cambridge Analytica, the Russian government, and Assange. Cambridge Analytica seemed to have its dirty hands in every dirty part of this campaign.

—

大选当晚，我在温哥华参加了一个观选派对。我们在一块大屏幕上收看 CNN 的节目，在小屏幕上收看其他新闻频道的节目，同时我还在和来自设得兰群岛的议员阿利斯泰尔·卡迈克尔通电话，我在伦敦期间和他关系很亲密。随着数据对克林顿来说越来越糟糕，我实时了解了美国、加拿大和英国的反应。当 CNN 预测特朗普将获胜时，震惊的气氛笼罩了整个房间。

ON THE NIGHT OF the election, I was at a watch party in Vancouver. We had CNN on one giant screen, and other news channels on smaller screens, and at the same time I was on the phone with Alistair Carmichael, the MP from the Shetlands, whom I’d grown close to during my time in London. I was getting the U.S., Canadian, and British reactions in real time as the numbers started looking more and more dire for Clinton. The moment CNN projected Trump as the winner, a shocked pall fell over the room.
