我以为此时我作为告密者的大部分工作已经结束，但接下来发生的事情让我获得了非常敏感的信息，以至于我与众议院情报委员会的会议必须在 2018 年 6 月那天在美国国会大厦下面的 SCIF 进行。在那次秘密听证会之前的两个月里，我在伦敦各地的几个随机地点见到了这个人，很明显他可以访问 Leave.EU 联合创始人 Arron Banks 和通讯主管 Andy Wigmore 的文件。这些文件记录了 Leave.EU（一个主要的另类右翼支持英国脱欧运动）与俄罗斯驻伦敦大使馆在英国脱欧运动期间的大量通信。在确信其真实性后，Allen 和我联系了军情五处和国家犯罪局。

I had thought most of my work as a whistleblower was over by this point, but what transpired next led me to information so sensitive that my meetings with the House Intelligence Committee that day in June 2018 had to be conducted in the SCIF, underneath the United States Capitol. In the two months before that secret hearing, I met the man in several random locations scattered across London, and it became clear that he had access to files belonging to Leave.EU co-founder Arron Banks and communications director Andy Wigmore. The documents constituted a record of extensive communications between Leave.EU, a major alt-right pro-Brexit campaign, and the Russian embassy in London during the Brexit campaign. Once we were assured of their authenticity, Allen and I contacted MI5 and the National Crime Agency.

4 月，艾伦在伦敦一个主要火车站内的一个没有标记的办公室里会见了一名 NCA 官员，代表我向他们通报情况，因为我们不能确定我没有被跟踪。我们都很担心，因为我们得知这名男子带着这些文件在乌克兰和东欧各地旅行，这些文件可能包含俄罗斯情报行动的证据。NCA 将这一情况通知了英国驻基辅大使馆。然后我们就失去了他的踪迹，他的电话也断线了。我们都对他的安全深感担忧。

In April, Allen met with an NCA officer in one of their unmarked offices inside a major London train station to update them on my behalf, as we couldn’t be sure that I wasn’t being followed. We were both worried because we’d learned that the man was traveling with these documents, which potentially contained evidence of a Russian intelligence operation, throughout Ukraine and Eastern Europe. The NCA notified the British embassy in Kiev about the situation. Then we lost track of him and his phone was disconnected. We were all deeply concerned about his safety.

几周后，那名男子再次出现，并希望再次见面。艾伦和我决定秘密记录我与那名男子的会面。我们将录音副本和文件截图交给了英国当局。我们还通知了美国人，因为我们看到证据表明俄罗斯人在剑桥分析公司客户与特朗普竞选团队会面前后与他们进行了交谈。我们最终在国会大厦南希·佩洛西的办公室与时任众议院情报委员会高级成员的加州众议员亚当·希夫会面。艾伦和我告诉了希夫众议员这些文件的存在。我同意带着这些文件返回华盛顿，这些文件被安全地保存在国会卡迈克尔的保险箱中。

Several weeks later, the man reemerged and wanted to meet again. Allen and I decided that I would secretly record my meetings with the man. We handed over copies of the recordings and screenshots of the documents to the British authorities. We also notified the Americans, because we saw evidence that the Russians were speaking with Cambridge Analytica clients immediately before and after the clients met with the Trump campaign. We eventually had a meeting with California congressman Adam Schiff, then the ranking member of the House Intelligence Committee, in Nancy Pelosi’s office in the Capitol. Allen and I told Congressman Schiff about the existence of these documents. I agreed to return to D.C. with the documents, which were kept secure in Carmichael’s safe at Parliament.

在华盛顿特区的这次会议结束后不久，我接到了 Fusion GPS 的联系，这家私人情报公司整理了克里斯托弗·斯蒂尔撰写的特朗普-俄罗斯档案。斯蒂尔的公司通过一位英国消息人士了解到我拥有的文件和录音，Fusion GPS 告诉我们，他们有自己的文件和信息，可以阐明同一套联系——俄罗斯、英国脱欧和特朗普竞选活动之间的联系。我们都同意在 DCMS 委员会主席达米安·柯林斯的办公室见面。就像拼图一样，柯林斯、Fusion GPS 和我各自获得了关于同一事件的不同文件集，我们开始将所有文件拼凑在一起。艾伦再次联系了 NCA，但他们拒绝采取行动，所以我们将所有内容交给了美国众议院情报委员会，该委员会同意将其传递给适当的美国情报渠道。如果英国当局不打算擅自触碰我们掌握的有关英国脱欧和俄罗斯大使馆的证据，我们希望，当美国机构获得这些文件时，他们会向英国同事施加压力，要求他们采取行动。

Soon after this D.C. meeting, I was contacted by Fusion GPS, the private intelligence firm that had put together the Trump-Russia dossier authored by Christopher Steele. Steele’s firm had learned about the documents and recordings I had through a British source, and Fusion GPS told us they had documents and information of their own that illuminated the same set of connections—between the Russians, Brexit, and Trump’s campaign. We all agreed to meet in the office of DCMS committee chair Damian Collins. Like a jigsaw, Collins, Fusion GPS, and I had each acquired different sets of documents about the same events, and we began piecing everything together. Allen approached the NCA again, but they declined to take action, so we instead handed everything over to the U.S. House Intelligence Committee, which agreed to pass it on to the appropriate American intelligence channels. If the U.K. authorities were not going to touch the evidence we had about Brexit and the Russian embassy on their own, we hoped that when the American agencies got access to the documents they would put pressure on their British colleagues to take action.

—

这些文件讲述了一个非凡的故事。2015 年，在我离开剑桥分析公司后不久，英国独立党支持的 Leave.EU 运动聘请了这家公司，正如 Leave.EU 在其竞选活动启动时所说的那样，“绘制英国选民及其信仰的地图，使我们能够更好地与选民互动。” CA-UKIP 关系是由史蒂夫·班农 (Steve Bannon) 促成的。班克斯和威格莫尔与班农谈论剑桥分析公司后，奈杰尔·法拉奇 (Nigel Farage) 将他们介绍给了他的朋友罗伯特·默瑟 (Robert Mercer)。默瑟热衷于帮助他们萌芽中的另类右翼运动，但这位美国亿万富翁和所有外国人一样，在法律上被禁止捐款或实质性干预英国的政治运动。因此，这位亿万富翁告诉脱欧派，剑桥分析公司的数据和服务可能会有用，班农主动提出提供帮助。法拉奇、班克斯和公司接受了班农的提议，通过数据库和算法完成了新兴的英美另类右翼联盟。

THE DOCUMENTS TELL A remarkable story. In 2015, not long after I left Cambridge Analytica, the U.K. Independence Party–backed Leave.EU campaign retained the firm to, as Leave.EU stated at its campaign launch, “map the British electorate and what they believe in, enabling us to better engage with voters.” The CA-UKIP relationship was one that was fostered by Steve Bannon. Once Banks and Wigmore had been speaking to Bannon about Cambridge Analytica, Nigel Farage introduced them to his friend Robert Mercer. Mercer was keen to help their budding alt-right movement, but the American billionaire, like all foreigners, was legally barred from donating or substantively interfering in British political campaigns. So the Brexiteers were told by the billionaire that the data and services of Cambridge Analytica could be useful, and Bannon offered to help. Farage, Banks, and company accepted Bannon’s offer, consummating the emerging Anglo-American alt-right alliance with databases and algorithms.

正是这种关系成为众议院情报委员会关注的焦点，因为俄罗斯大使馆似乎利用这种关系作为秘密手段参与特朗普竞选活动。2015 年 11 月，Leave.EU 公开与布列塔尼·凯泽一起启动了公投活动，凯泽除了在剑桥分析公司工作外，还被任命为 Leave.EU 的新运营总监。在竞选活动中，凯泽将特别关注部署 CA 的微目标算法。

It was this relationship that became a focal point of interest for the House Intelligence Committee, as it appeared that this relationship was exploited by the Russian embassy as a discreet vehicle into the Trump campaign. In November 2015, Leave.EU publicly launched its referendum campaign with Brittany Kaiser, who, in addition to working at Cambridge Analytica, was appointed as Leave.EU’s new director of operations. On the campaign, Kaiser was to have a special focus on deploying CA’s microtargeting algorithms.

在剑桥分析公司公开发布之前不久，英国独立党和 Leave.EU 的最大捐助者——阿隆·班克斯和安迪·威格莫尔——开始与俄罗斯政府调情。一切始于 2015 年在唐卡斯特举行的英国独立党大会，当时两人与俄罗斯外交官亚历山大·乌多德会面，后者邀请他们到俄罗斯大使馆会见他的大使。几周后，在与俄罗斯驻伦敦大使亚历山大·弗拉基米罗维奇·雅科文科共进了“六个小时的醉酒午餐”后，班克斯和威格莫尔第二次会见了大使，并得到了一个诱人的提议，班克斯随后将这个提议扩展到几位同事，包括著名投资者和英国脱欧支持者吉姆·梅隆。俄罗斯大使馆有意促成一些可能有利可图的交易，以投资班克斯在一封电子邮件中所说的“俄罗斯黄金游戏”。大使向这些人进行了宣传，大使将他们介绍给了俄罗斯商人西曼·波瓦连金 (Siman Povarenkin)。波瓦连金表示，俄罗斯的几家金矿和钻石矿即将合并并部分私有化。大使馆明确表示，这笔交易将得到俄罗斯国家银行 Sberbank 的支持，该银行受到美国和欧盟的制裁。英国独立党的捐助者被告知，通过大使馆和 Sberbank 合作的优势在于“可以带来其他人无法获得的某些机会”。

Shortly before the public launch with Cambridge Analytica, the top donors to UKIP and Leave.EU—Arron Banks and Andy Wigmore—began their flirtations with the Russian government. It all started at the 2015 UKIP conference, in Doncaster, with a meeting between the two and Alexander Udod, a Russian diplomat who invited them to meet his ambassador at the Russian embassy. A few weeks later, after what was described in correspondence as a “boozy six-hour lunch” with Alexander Vladimirovich Yakovenko, the Russian ambassador in London, Banks and Wigmore met the ambassador a second time and were given an enticing offer, which Banks then extended to several associates, including Jim Mellon, a prominent investor and Brexit backer. The Russian embassy was interested in facilitating introductions for some potentially lucrative deals to invest in what Banks referred to in an email as “The Russian Gold Play.” The pitch to the men was made through the ambassador, who introduced them to Siman Povarenkin, a Russian businessman. Povarenkin suggested that several Russian gold and diamond mines were about to be consolidated and partially privatized. The embassy made clear that the deal would be backed by Sberbank, a Russian state bank, subject to U.S. and EU sanctions. The advantage of working through the embassy and Sberbank, the UKIP donors were told, was that it “leads to certain opportunities not available to others.”

在剑桥分析公司宣布将参与 Leave.EU 活动之前，他们与俄罗斯大使馆的联系一直在持续。在回复俄罗斯官员的会面邀请的电子邮件中，班克斯写信给大使馆说：“谢谢你，安迪，我很乐意参加 11 月 6 日的午餐会，向大使汇报情况。美国对这场公投也很感兴趣，我们很快就会去华盛顿，向大使汇报活动情况。”2015 年 11 月 16 日，也就是宣布的第二天，班克斯和威格摩尔被邀请回到大使馆参加更多会议。我们不知道那天大使馆里到底发生了什么，但我们知道脱欧派随后飞往美国与共和党同行会面，而俄罗斯大使馆知道这些行程。我们还知道，班克斯和威格莫尔热衷于让雅科文科大使了解最新情况，他们在 2016 年 1 月给大使的一条短信中说：“安迪和我很乐意过来向您通报竞选的最新情况。一切都在进行中。祝你一切顺利，阿隆。”

In the time leading up to the announcement that Cambridge Analytica would be working on Leave.EU’s campaign, the contact with the Russian embassy continued. In an email responding to a meeting invitation from a Russian official, Banks wrote the embassy to say, “Thank you Andy and myself will be delighted to attend lunch to brief the Ambassador on the 6th November. There is massive interest in this referendum in the USA as well, and we are shortly visiting Washington to brief key [sic] on the campaign.” On November 16, 2015, the day after the announcement, Banks and Wigmore were invited back to the embassy for more meetings. We do not know exactly what transpired in the embassy that day, but we do know that the Brexiteers then flew to America to meet with their Republican counterparts and that the Russian embassy was aware of these trips. We also know that Banks and Wigmore were keen on keeping Ambassador Yakovenko updated, saying in one text message to the ambassador in January 2016, “Andy and myself would love to come and update you on the campaign. It’s all happening. All the best, Arron.”

目前尚不清楚，如果班克斯只是在与俄罗斯人做生意，他为何会向俄罗斯大使透露自己在美国政界的联系或英国脱欧公投活动，但这些会面肯定对脱欧派产生了影响。在一连串的通信中，其中一名男子讨论了帮助在乌克兰创建一场英国脱欧式运动，目的是打击俄罗斯长期以来一直努力将其控制在其势力范围内的乌克兰的亲欧盟言论。他们后来决定不进军乌克兰，甚至在一封电子邮件中讨论了新闻稿草稿中的一句话是否会被视为“过于亲俄”，但威格莫尔还是回复说“向大使发送一份支持信”。

Why Banks would tell the Russian ambassador about his American political contacts or the Brexit referendum campaign if he was strictly dealing with the Russians on business is unclear, but the meetings certainly had an effect on the Brexiteers. In one chain of correspondence, one of the men discussed helping to create a Brexit-style movement in Ukraine, with the goal of fighting pro-EU narratives in a country Russia has long fought to keep inside its sphere of influence. They later decided against a foray into Ukraine and in one email even discussed whether a sentence in a draft of a press release might be seen as “too overtly Russophile,” but Wigmore nonetheless responded with the suggestion to “send a note of support to the Ambassador.”

班克斯和威格莫尔与俄罗斯大使馆保持联系；威格莫尔写信邀请俄罗斯外交官参加 Leave.EU 活动——包括 2016 年 6 月的英国脱欧胜利派对。据报道，尽管班克斯就俄罗斯金矿和钻石矿投资提议咨询了专家，但他告诉记者，他最终拒绝了所有提议。威格莫尔还决定“不再继续”投资。但据报道，脱欧运动结束后不久，英国独立党主要捐助者之一吉姆·梅隆旗下的一个投资基金对俄罗斯国有钻石公司 Alrosa 进行了投资，该公司已部分私有化。然而，该公司的一位代表表示，投资细节是在梅隆不知情的情况下进行的，该基金早在 2013 年首次公开发行股票时就对 Alrosa 进行了投资。2016 年 7 月下旬，英国脱欧后一个月，俄罗斯情报部门窃取民主党全国委员会文件和电子邮件的事件发生几周后，亚历山大·尼克斯 (Alexander Nix) 去看了一场马球比赛，并被拍到与大使雅科文科一起喝了一瓶俄罗斯伏特加。巧合的是，当时尼克斯也在试图获取维基解密为特朗普竞选提供的信息。

Banks and Wigmore kept in contact with the Russian embassy; Wigmore wrote to invite Russian diplomats to attend Leave.EU events—including their Brexit victory party in June 2016. Though Banks reportedly consulted experts about the Russian gold and diamond mine investment offers, he told reporters he ultimately turned all of them down. Wigmore had also decided “not to proceed further” with an investment. But shortly after the Brexit campaign concluded, an investment fund associated with Jim Mellon, one of UKIP’s major donors, reportedly made an investment in Alrosa, the Russian state-owned diamond company, which was partially privatized. However, a representative of the firm said that the specifics of the investment were made without Mellon’s knowledge and that the fund had made an earlier investment in Alrosa when public shares were first offered in 2013. In late July 2016, a month after Brexit was won and just weeks after the Russian intelligence hack of the Democratic National Committee’s files and emails was leaked, Alexander Nix went to a polo match and was photographed with Ambassador Yakovenko sharing a bottle of Russian vodka. Coincidentally, this was also around the time that Nix was seeking to get access to WikiLeaks’s information for the Trump campaign.

随着英国脱欧的胜利，法拉奇和班克斯将目光投向了美国，而美国目前正处于 2016 年大选的激烈竞争之中。2016 年，这些英国人为特朗普大力助选，法拉奇参加了这位共和党候选人的无数公开活动。当时的候选人特朗普自称是“脱欧先生”，邀请英国独立党领袖参加集会，这在当时的旁观者看来很正常。但许多美国人不明白，另类右翼有多么紧密的联系。这是一个协调一致的全球运动。2016 年，它成为了一个巨大的安全风险。

With Brexit won, Farage and Banks set their sights on America, now deep in the midst of the 2016 campaign. Over the course of 2016, these Brits campaigned vigorously for Trump, with Farage attending a myriad of public events for the Republican candidate. It seemed normal to casual observers at the time that then-candidate Trump, declaring himself “Mr. Brexit,” would invite the lead figures of UKIP to his rallies. But what many Americans don’t understand is how connected the alt-right is. It is a coordinated global movement. And it became a massive security risk in 2016.

2016 年 8 月 20 日，俄罗斯大使馆三等秘书谢尔盖·费迪奇金收到安迪·威格莫尔发送的一封电子邮件，主题为“转发科特雷尔文件——仅供阅读”。邮件中有几个附件和一行神秘的信息：“祝您玩得开心。”附件包含美国联邦特工逮捕乔治·科特雷尔的法律文件。当时，科特雷尔是奈杰尔·法拉奇的幕僚长，也是英国独立党筹款负责人。法拉奇后来说，他对科特雷尔的非法活动一无所知。科特雷尔和法拉奇飞往美国庆祝他们最近的英国脱欧胜利，以便在 2016 年共和党全国代表大会上举行大型特朗普集会，之后他们抵达芝加哥奥黑尔机场，准备返回英国。飞机起飞前，几名特工登上飞机，以多项共谋洗钱和电信欺诈罪名逮捕了科特雷尔。他还与摩尔多瓦银行 Moldindconbank 有联系，据称该银行是“俄罗斯洗钱”计划的关键参与者。我从联系人那里获得的电子邮件记录显示，威格莫尔曾向俄罗斯外交官发送美国司法部指控的副本。在达成认罪协议后，科特雷尔承认犯有电信欺诈罪。

On August 20, 2016, Sergey Fedichkin, the Third Secretary of the Russian embassy, was sent an email by Andy Wigmore, with the subject line “Fwd Cottrell docs—Eyes Only.” There were a couple of attachments and a cryptic one-line message: “Have fun with this.” The attachments contained legal documents pertaining to George Cottrell’s arrest by U.S. federal agents. At the time, Cottrell was the chief of staff to Nigel Farage and the head of fundraising for UKIP. Farage said later that he knew nothing of Cottrell’s illegal activities. After flying to America to celebrate their recent Brexit victory before a large Trump rally at the 2016 Republican National Convention, Cottrell and Farage were at Chicago O’Hare airport, about to return to England. Before takeoff, several agents boarded the plane and arrested Cottrell on multiple counts of conspiracy to commit money laundering and wire fraud. He had also been linked to Moldindconbank, the Moldovan bank alleged to be a key player in the “Russian Laundromat” money-laundering scheme. Wigmore is recorded, in emails I obtained from my contact, sending Russian diplomats copies of the U.S. Justice Department’s charges. Following a plea agreement, Cottrell pleaded guilty to wire fraud.

俄罗斯大使馆清楚地知道英国脱欧运动中的关键人物与特朗普竞选团队的关系有多紧密，大使馆一直在培养他们的关系，甚至从威格莫尔那里得到了有关其英国独立党同僚被联邦调查局逮捕的文件。美国人为什么要关心俄罗斯在英国的所作所为？因为这些脱欧派共用同一个数据公司剑桥分析公司，共用同一个顾问史蒂夫·班农，他们显然在每一步都向俄罗斯通报情况。这些脱欧派是特朗普意外获胜后第一批受邀前往特朗普大厦的人之一。美国当选总统会见了定期向俄罗斯政府汇报情况的英国公民。

The Russian embassy clearly knew how tightly connected key figures in the Brexit movement were to the Trump campaign, and the embassy kept cultivating their relationship to the point where they received documents from Wigmore about their UKIP associate’s FBI arrests. Why should Americans care about what Russia was doing in Britain? Because these Brexiteers shared the same data firm, in Cambridge Analytica, and the same adviser, in Steve Bannon, and they were clearly keeping the Russians informed at each step of the way. And these same Brexiteers were some of the very first people invited to Trump Tower after his surprise victory. The president-elect of the United States met with British citizens who were regularly briefing the Russian government.

当记者们庆祝揭露剑桥分析公司并导致顽固的 Facebook 股价暴跌时，我却没有感到高兴。我麻木了。感觉就像看着一个死期已到的人死去。这是我经历过的最残酷、最艰难的事情。几个月后，肾上腺素消退后，我才开始处理发生的事情。我意识到我经历了多少创伤，我允许自己感受这种经历的痛苦，这种痛苦因我在这场灾难中扮演的角色而变得更加剧烈。当我看到特朗普上台，看着他禁止穆斯林国家的公民进入美国并为白人至上主义运动辩护时，我不禁觉得我为这一切埋下了祸根。我玩火了，现在我看着世界在燃烧。我去国会，不仅仅是去那里作证。我是在参加自己的忏悔。

As the journalists celebrated having exposed Cambridge Analytica and plunged the stock of an intransigent Facebook, I did not feel joyous. I was numb. It felt like watching the death of someone whose time has come. It was the most grueling and arduous thing I have ever been through. I only began to process what had happened months later, after the adrenaline subsided. I realized how much trauma I had endured and I allowed myself to feel the pain of the experience, a pain made all the more acute by the role I had played in this disaster. As I saw Trump rise to power and watched as he banned citizens of Muslim states from entering the United States and gave justifications for white supremacist movements, I couldn’t help feeling that I had laid the seeds for this to happen. I had played with fire, and now I watched as the world was burning. In heading to Congress, I was not simply going there to give my testimony. I was attending my own confessional.

第十二章

CHAPTER 12

启示

REVELATIONS

-

我不会告诉你我住在哪里。它位于伦敦东区的肖尔迪奇和达尔斯顿之间。我是住在顶层的那个粉红色头发的家伙，但我并不显眼。这个社区的根源是工人阶级，这里的许多建筑都曾是伦敦工业时代的工厂。烟熏砖墙上褪色的油漆宣传着一个世纪前早已消失的产品。在上一波英联邦移民潮中搬到这里的印度、巴基斯坦和加勒比社区与新一波艺术家、同性恋、学生和邋遢的怪人之间关系有所缓和，他们被生活成本赶出了伦敦市中心。这里有装饰艺术电影院、屋顶花园，还有每个周末喝着 Red Stripe 罐装啤酒直到凌晨 4 点的醉酒俱乐部常客的喧闹声。人们经常看到全身蒙面的穆斯林妇女和头发不对称、满身纹身的俱乐部孩子在同一家卖蔬菜水果店购物。它仍然是一个我可以相对匿名地外出散步的地方。

I won’t tell you where I live, exactly. It’s somewhere between Shoreditch and Dalston, in the East End of London. I am the pink-haired guy who lives on the top floor, but I don’t really stand out much. The neighborhood is working class in its roots, and many buildings here were once factories in London’s industrial age. Faded paint on smoke-stained brickwork advertises long-gone products from a century ago. There is a détente between the Indian, Pakistani, and Caribbean communities that moved here in the last wave of Commonwealth immigration and the new wave of artists, gays, students, and grungy weirdos who are being pushed out of central London by the cost of living. There are art deco cinemas, roof gardens, and the restless cacophony of intoxicated clubgoers drinking cans of Red Stripe until 4 A.M. every weekend. One often sees completely veiled Muslim women shopping in the same off-license greengrocer as tattoo-clad club kids with asymmetrical hair. It is still a place where I can walk outside in relative anonymity.

我住的楼很旧，建于互联网还未出现、室内管道还很新奇的时代。地板是木质的，很结实，但走几步就会发出吱吱声。门上加了螺栓，在我公开身份的一周后，一群男人不断来敲门，于是就装上了螺栓。我的邻居们开始抱怨，直到他们意识到我是谁。现在，只要看到有人在附近闲逛，他们就会通知我。

My building is old, built in a time before the Internet was even imaginable and when indoor plumbing was still a novelty. The floor is wooden and solid, but every so often it creaks as you take a step. There are extra bolts on the door, installed after a group of men kept coming to the door the week after I went public. My neighbors started complaining, until they realized who I was. Now they let me know anytime they see people loitering nearby.

我住的地方缺少了很多东西。在我的客厅里，曾经放着一台电视机的角落里现在有一个架子。电线仍然从墙上垂下来。这是一台连接到我的 Netflix 和社交媒体账户的智能电视，它还配有麦克风和摄像头。在我的房间里，有一个床头柜，抽屉里衬着一种特殊的金属织物，可以防止抽屉里的任何设备发送或接收电子信号。作为睡前习惯的一部分，我会把我的设备放在那里。房间另一边的衣柜里放着我以前​​生活中的旧电子产品。一台拔掉电源的亚马逊 Alexa 孤零零地放在一堆其他电子垃圾中——平板电脑、手机、智能手表——我还没有妥善处理它们。另一个盒子里放着硬盘的残余物，在硬盘上的证据被交给当局后，它们被消磁、砸碎或用酸漂白。数据已经永远消失了，我不妨把它们扔掉，但我对它们却感到一种奇怪的伤感。

There are many things missing where I live. In my living room, there’s a stand in the far corner where there used to be a television. Wires still dangle from the walls there. It was a smart TV that connected to my Netflix and social media accounts, and it had a microphone and camera. In my room, there is a nightstand with a drawer that is lined with a special metallic fabric that prevents any devices in the drawer from sending or receiving electronic signals. As part of my bedtime ritual, I leave my devices in there. Across the room in my closet are my old electronics from my life before. An unplugged Amazon Alexa sits alone, buried among a pile of other electronic rubbish—tablets, phones, a smartwatch—that I have yet to dispose of properly. In another box sit the remnants of hard drives, degaussed, smashed up, or acid-bleached after the evidence on them was handed over to the authorities. The data is gone forever, and I might as well throw them out, but I feel oddly sentimental about them.

客厅里有一张来自旧工厂的古董木桌，上面放着一台从未连接过互联网的隔离笔记本电脑。我用它处理移交给众议院情报委员会的证据。抽屉里是我旅行时使用的空白笔记本电脑，以防在边境被搜查。我的个人电脑放在客厅里，用物理 U2F 密钥加密和锁定。摄像头被胶带封住了，不过你对内置麦克风几乎无能为力。地板上有一台连接到墙上的私人 VPN 服务器，它又连接到其他服务器。

In the living room, I have an antique wooden desk from an old factory, and on it sits an air-gapped laptop that has never been connected to the Internet. I used it to work through evidence handed over to the House Intelligence Committee. In the drawer is the blank laptop I use for traveling, in case it is searched at the border. My personal computer sits in the living room, encrypted and locked down with a physical U2F key. The cameras are taped, although there is little you can do about the built-in microphone. On the floor, there is a private VPN server connected to the wall, which in turn connects onward onto other servers.

我住的大楼入口处有一个安全摄像头，它会将数据转发给一家安全公司。我不知道其中是否有加密数据，所以谁知道谁在监视我。我出门时会带一个便携式紧急按钮，但我还没有用到它。NCA 将我列入了监视名单，该名单与我的一部手机相连。如果我打电话，他们会优先回复，即使我没有对接线员说任何话。我的背包里总是装着一个便携式硬件 VPN 路由器，以防我需要连接到不安全的 Wi-Fi，还有几个法拉第外壳，我买的是粉色的，因为它很可爱。我经常戴帽子，但即使一年后，人们仍然会认出我。几乎每天，我都会被问到“你是……告密者吗？”

There is a security camera at the entrance of my building that relays data to a security company. I have no idea if any of it is encrypted, so who knows who is watching. When I leave my house, I bring a portable panic button, but I have not yet needed to use it. The NCA put me on a watch list connected to one of my phones. If I call, they will prioritize a response, even if I say nothing to the operator. My backpack always has a portable hardware VPN router in case I need to connect to insecure Wi-Fi, as well as several Faraday cases that I got in pink because it was cute. I often wear a hat, but people will still recognize me, even a year later. Almost daily, I get the question “Are you…the whistleblower?”

我现在的生活看起来就像一个偏执狂，但在经历了街头袭击、收到流氓私人保安公司的威胁、深夜在我睡觉时闯入酒店房间、以及在过去十二个月内两次尝试黑客入侵我的电子邮件之后，谨慎才是明智的做法。当我检查公寓的安全风险时，电视被视为一种风险，因为它可能会在我不知情的情况下被用来观看或监听我。当我们拆开它时，我对一台监视你的电视的讽刺意味不禁一笑置之。

My life now looks like that of a paranoid man, but after being assaulted in the street, receiving threats from rogue private security firms, having my hotel room broken in to late at night as I was sleeping, and experiencing two hacking attempts on my email in the past twelve months, it is only sensible to be cautious. When I had my flat checked for security risks, the TV was deemed a risk, as it could be used to watch or listen to me without my ever knowing. As we dismantled it, I smiled at the irony of a TV that watches you.

在报道发表前几天，Facebook 开始向我发出法律威胁，并将我的案件上报给副法律总顾问和副总裁，我的律师意识到，该公司将我的举报视为对其业务的重大威胁。我的律师有处理其他黑客案件的经验，知道被逼入绝境的公司愿意做什么。但 Facebook 不同。他们不需要攻击我；他们只需通过我手机上的应用程序就可以随时随地跟踪我——我在哪里，我的联系人是谁，我在和谁见面。

In the days leading up to the story’s publication, when Facebook began sending me legal threats and escalated my case up to its deputy general counsel and vice president, my lawyers realized that the company saw my whistleblowing as a major threat to its business. Having experience on other hacking cases, my lawyers knew what companies backed into a corner were willing to do. But Facebook was different. They did not need to hack me; they could simply track me everywhere because of the apps on my phone—where I was, who my contacts were, who I was meeting.

我处理掉了我的手机，我的律师买了新的干净手机，这些手机从未使用过 Facebook、Instagram 或 WhatsApp。Facebook 移动应用程序的条款和条件要求访问麦克风和摄像头。尽管该公司竭力否认提取用户音频数据用于定向广告，但我们的手机上仍然有技术权限允许访问音频功能。而且我不是普通用户：我是该公司当时最大的声誉威胁。至少在理论上，音频可以被激活，我的律师担心公司可以监听我与他们或警察的对话。Facebook 已经可以访问我的照片和相机，这使他们不仅可以监听我，还可以查看我的位置。即使我独自在浴室洗澡，我也从来都不是孤独的。如果我的手机在那里，Facebook 也在那里。无处可逃。

I disposed of my phone, and my lawyers bought new clean phones that have never touched Facebook, Instagram, or WhatsApp. The terms and conditions of Facebook’s mobile app asked for microphone and camera access. Although the company is at pains to deny pulling user audio data for targeted advertising, there is nonetheless a technical permission sitting on our phones that allows access to audio capabilities. And I was not an average user: I was the company’s biggest reputational threat at the time. At least in theory, audio could be activated, and my lawyers were concerned that the company could listen in on my conversations with them or the police. Facebook already had access to my photos and my camera, which put them in a position to not just listen to me but also to see where I was. Even if I was alone in the bathroom taking a shower, I wasn’t really ever alone. If my phone was there, so was Facebook. There was no escape.

但扔掉手机还不够。出于同样的原因，我的父母和姐妹们都不得不从手机中删除 Facebook、Instagram 和 WhatsApp。但 Facebook 还知道我所有的朋友是谁，他们知道我们喜欢去哪里，我们在信息中写了什么，他们知道我们都住在哪里。甚至和朋友一起出去玩也是一种风险，因为 Facebook 可以访问他们的手机。如果一个朋友拍了一张照片，Facebook 就可以访问它，它的面部识别算法至少在理论上可以在其他人手机上的照片中检测到我的脸，即使他们是陌生人。

But getting rid of my phone was not going to be enough. My mom, dad, and sisters all had to remove Facebook, Instagram, and WhatsApp from their phones for the same reason. But Facebook also knew who all my friends were, they knew where we liked to go out, what we wrote about in messages, and they knew where we all lived. Even hanging out with my friends became a risk, as Facebook had access to their phones. If a friend took a photo, Facebook could access it, and its facial recognition algorithms could, at least in theory, detect my face in the photos sitting on other people’s phones, even if they were strangers to me.

当我处理掉旧电子产品时，朋友们开玩笑说，这就像我在驱除机器里的恶魔，一位朋友甚至带了一些鼠尾草来燃烧以防万一。当然，这是一个有趣的举动，但在某种程度上，这确实是一次驱魔。我们现在生活在一个由代码和数据组成的隐形灵魂的世界里，它们有能力观察我们、倾听我们、思考我们。我希望这些幽灵从我的生活中消失。

As I was getting rid of my old electronics, my friends joked that it was as if I was exorcising the demons inside the machines, and one friend even brought over some sage to burn just in case. A funny gesture, of course, but in a way it really was an exorcism. We now live in a world where there are invisible spirits made of code and data that have the power to watch us, listen to us, and think about us. And I wanted these specters gone from my life.

—

2018 年 3 月 16 日，即《卫报》和《纽约时报》发表我的故事的前一天，Facebook 宣布不仅禁止我使用 Facebook，还禁止我使用 Instagram。Facebook 拒绝禁止白人至上主义者、新纳粹分子和其他仇恨大军，但它选择禁止我。该公司要求我交出我的手机和个人电脑，并表示恢复我的唯一方法是向他们提供我向当局提供的相同信息。Facebook 的行为就像是一个民族国家，而不是一家公司。该公司似乎不明白我不是调查对象——他们才是。我的律师建议我拒绝他们的要求，以免干扰合法的警察和监管调查。后来，当我与当局合作时，这项禁令使交出我 Facebook 账户中的证据变得更加困难，对英国脱欧公投期间发生的事情的调查也因此受到影响。

ON MARCH 16, 2018, a day before The Guardian and The New York Times published my story, Facebook announced that it was banning me from not only Facebook but also Instagram. Facebook had refused to ban white supremacists, neo-Nazis, and other armies of hate, but it chose to ban me. The company demanded that I hand over my phone and personal computer and said that the only way for me to be reinstated was, in effect, to give them the same information I was providing the authorities. Facebook behaved as if it were a nation-state, rather than a company. The firm did not seem to understand that I was not the subject of investigation—they were. My lawyers advised me to refuse their demands, so as not to interfere with a lawful police and regulatory investigation. Later, when I was working with the authorities, the ban made it far more difficult to hand over evidence that was sitting in my Facebook account, and the investigation into what happened during the Brexit referendum suffered as a result.

人们说，只有失去才会珍惜，直到我被 Facebook 删除账号后，我才真正意识到我的生活与这个平台的接触频率有多高。我手机上的几个应用程序都停止工作了——一个约会应用程序、一个出租车应用程序、一个消息应用程序——因为它们使用了 Facebook 身份验证。我在网站上的订阅和账户也因同样的原因而失效。人们经常谈论二元论：网络世界和我们的“现实生活”。但在我的大部分数字身份被没收后，我可以告诉你，它们并不是分开的。当你从社交媒体上删除账号后，你就失去了与人的联系。我不再被邀请参加派对——这不是故意的，而是因为这些邀请总是在 Facebook 上或 Instagram 上发布。没有我的新电话号码的朋友几乎不可能联系到我，除非试着给我的律师发电子邮件。当我熬过举报过程时，只有在俱乐部或酒吧的偶然相遇中，我才会与几个月没见过的人取得联系。

They say you appreciate something only when it’s gone, and it was only when I was erased from Facebook that I truly realized how frequently my life touched their platform. Several of my phone’s apps stopped working—a dating app, a taxi app, a messaging app—because they used Facebook authentication. Subscriptions and accounts I had on websites failed for the same reason. People often talk about a dualism: the cyber world and our “real lives.” But after having most of my digital identity confiscated, I can tell you they are not separate. When you are erased from social media, you lose touch with people. I stopped getting invited to parties—not intentionally, but because those invites always happened on Facebook or were posted on Instagram. Friends who did not have my new phone number found it nearly impossible to get hold of me, except by trying to send an email to my lawyers. When I got through the thick of the whistleblowing, it would only be in coincidental encounters at clubs or bars that I would make contact with people I had not seen in months.

现在，当约会应用上的男生要求查看我的 Instagram 个人资料时，我就会尴尬地解释我是如何被封禁的——我保证我不是在钓鱼。就好像我的身份被没收了，人们不再相信我就是那个人。有时我会被认出是那个人，人们担心如果他们决定和我见面，有人可能会开始监视他们。我总是告诉他们不用担心，因为这些公司已经在 24/7 全天候跟踪他们了。这项禁令只不过是 Facebook 的卑鄙举动，感觉就像是被受惊的恶霸们戏弄。对我来说，它最多造成了令人讨厌的个人麻烦，对我的生活的影响远不及其他举报人所经历的报复。 （更不用说该平台已经对现代社会造成的破坏程度了。）但它向我展示了我的网络身份对我生活的方方面面有多么重要——而且我的身份没有得到正当程序权利或公正裁决。在我被封禁四天后，在议会的一次紧急辩论中，英国文化大臣表示，Facebook 单方面封禁举报人的能力“令人震惊”，因为它引发了人们对一家公司是否应该拥有这种不受制约的权力的严重质疑。

And now, when guys on dating apps ask to check out my Instagram profile, it starts an awkward explanation about how I was banned—and that I’m not catfishing, I promise. It’s as if my identity has been confiscated and people no longer believe that I am who I say I am. Sometimes I get recognized as that guy, and people worry that someone might start watching them if they decide to meet me. I always tell them that they needn’t worry, because these companies are already tracking them 24/7. This ban was nothing more than a dick move by Facebook, and it felt like trolling by frightened bullies. For me, it created at most an annoying personal hassle and was not nearly as consequential to my life as the kinds of retaliation that other whistleblowers have experienced. (Not to mention the degree of damage to modern society that the platform had already aided and abetted.) But it showed me just how integral my online identity had become to so many facets of my life—and that my identity was afforded no due process rights or an impartial adjudication. Four days after my ban, during an emergency debate in Parliament, the British secretary of state for culture said that Facebook’s ability to unilaterally ban whistleblowers was “shocking,” because it raised serious questions about whether a company should be able to wield this kind of unchecked power.

数亿美国人进入了 Facebook 的隐形架构，以为这是一个分享照片和关注他们最喜欢的名人的无害场所。他们被与朋友联系的便利以及通过游戏和应用程序抵御无聊的能力所吸引。Facebook 告诉用户，该企业旨在将人们聚集在一起。但 Facebook 的“社区”正在为与他们相似的人建立单独的社区。当平台观察他们、阅读他们的帖子并研究他们如何与朋友互动时，它的算法就会决定如何将用户分类到他们同类的数字社区中——Facebook 称之为他们的“相似者”。这样做的原因当然是允许广告商针对这些同质的相似者，为他们同类的人提供单独的叙述。大多数用户不知道他们的分类，因为其他与他们长得不一样的人的社区将保持不可见状态。毫不奇怪，相似者的细分使同胞之间的距离越来越远。它创造了我们现在生活的氛围。

Hundreds of millions of Americans have entered into Facebook’s invisible architecture thinking it was an innocuous place to share pics and follow their favorite celebrities. They were drawn into the convenience of connecting with friends and the ability to fend off boredom with games and apps. Users were told by Facebook that the enterprise was about bringing people together. But Facebook’s “community” was building separate neighborhoods just for people who look like them. As the platform watched them, read their posts, and studied how they interacted with their friends, its algorithms would then make decisions about how to classify users into digital neighborhoods of their kind—what Facebook called their “Lookalikes.” The reason for this, of course, was to allow advertisers to target these homogeneous Lookalikes with separate narratives just for people of their kind. Most users would not know their classification, as the other neighborhoods of people who did not look like them would remain unseen. The segmentation of Lookalikes, not surprisingly, pushed fellow citizens further and further apart. It created the atmosphere we are all living in now.

作为社交媒体的发源地，美国逐渐进入了新闻推送、关注者、点赞和分享等新的数字公共领域。而且，正如气候变化对我们的海岸线、森林和野生动物的渐进影响一样，我们很难完全想象我们所处事物变化的规模。但在某些情况下，我们可以看到社交媒体的明显影响，即社交媒体突然全面袭击一个国家。2010 年代中期，Facebook 进入缅甸并迅速发展，迅速在这个拥有 5300 万人口的国家拥有 2000 万用户。Facebook 的应用程序预装在该国销售的许多智能手机上，市场研究表明该网站是缅甸公民的主要新闻来源之一。

As the birthplace of social media, America was eased into the new digital commons of newsfeeds, followers, likes, and shares. And, as with the incremental effects of climate change on our shorelines, forests, and wildlife, it can be hard to fully picture the scale of change of something that envelops us. But there are cases where we can see the stark effects of social media, cases where it suddenly hits a country in full force. In the mid-2010s, Facebook entered into Myanmar and grew rapidly, quickly reaching 20 million users in a country of 53 million people. Facebook’s app came preinstalled on many smartphones sold in the country, and market research identified the site as one of the primary sources of news for Burmese citizens.

2017 年 8 月，Facebook 上针对缅甸以穆斯林为主的少数民族罗兴亚人的仇恨言论激增，其中“穆斯林自由”缅甸的言论和对该地区进行种族清洗的呼吁迅速传播。这些言论大部分是由执行信息行动的军事人员制作和传播的宣传。在罗兴亚武装分子对警察发动协同攻击后，缅甸军方利用他们在网上获得的支持激增，开始有计划地杀害、强奸和致残数万名罗兴亚人。其他团体也加入了屠杀，Facebook 上继续呼吁采取行动杀害罗兴亚人。罗兴亚村庄被烧毁，70 多万罗兴亚难民被迫越过边境进入孟加拉国。国际和当地组织多次向 Facebook 发出有关缅甸局势的警告。该公司禁止罗兴亚抵抗组织使用该平台，但允许军方和亲政府组织使用该平台，这让他们得以继续传播仇恨宣传。尽管联合国官员称这是“种族清洗的典型例子”，但该公司的做法却没有改变。

In August 2017, hate speech surged on Facebook targeting the Rohingya, a predominantly Muslim minority group in Myanmar, with narratives of a “Muslim-free” Myanmar and calls for ethnic cleansing of the region going viral. Much of this was propaganda created and disseminated by military personnel conducting information operations. After Rohingya militants launched a coordinated attack on the police, the Burmese military capitalized on a surge in support they received online and proceeded to systematically kill, rape, and maim tens of thousands of Rohingya. Other groups joined in the slaughter, and calls to action to murder Rohingya continued to go out on Facebook. Rohingya villages were burned and more than 700,000 Rohingya refugees were forced across the border into Bangladesh. Facebook was warned repeatedly by international and local organizations about the situation in Myanmar. The company banned a Rohingya resistance group from the platform but left the military and pro-government groups on the site, which enabled them to continue spreading hate propaganda. This was despite what United Nations officials called a “textbook example of ethnic cleansing.”

2018 年 3 月，联合国得出结论，Facebook 在罗兴亚人种族清洗中扮演了“决定性角色”。Facebook 的无摩擦架构助长了暴力行为，以前所未有的速度在人群中传播仇恨言论。Facebook 的冷漠回应绝对是奥威尔式的。“Facebook 上没有仇恨言论或宣扬暴力的内容，我们会努力将其从我们的平台上清除，”Facebook 在关于其在四万人种族清洗中扮演的促进角色的声明中写道。对于全世界来说，如果你想维持一个压迫性政权，Facebook 将是一家值得求助的绝佳公司。

In March 2018, the U.N. concluded that Facebook had played a “determining role” in the ethnic cleansing of the Rohingya people. Violence was enabled by Facebook’s frictionless architecture, propelling hate speech through a population at a velocity previously unimaginable. Facebook’s apathetic response was positively Orwellian. “There is no place for hate speech or content that promotes violence on Facebook, and we work hard to keep it off our platform,” read Facebook’s statement about its facilitating role in the ethnic cleansing of forty thousand human beings. It seemed for all the world that if you wanted to maintain an oppressive regime, Facebook would be an excellent company to turn to.

互联网的辉煌之处在于，人们突然间能够打破所有障碍，随时随地与任何人交谈。但实际上，这种趋势在一个国家的物理空间中得到了放大。人们在社交媒体上花费数小时，关注与他们类似的人，阅读由算法为他们“策划”的新闻文章，而算法唯一的道德标准就是点击率——这些文章除了强化单一的观点，并将用户推向极端以吸引他们点击之外，什么也没做。我们看到的是一种认知隔离，人们生活在自己的信息贫民窟中。我们看到了现实的隔离。如果 Facebook 是一个“社区”，那么它就是一个封闭的社区。

What was supposed to be so brilliant about the Internet was that people would suddenly be able to erode all those barriers and talk to anyone, anywhere. But what actually happened was an amplification of the same trends that took hold of a country’s physical spaces. People spend hours on social media, following people like them, reading news articles “curated” for them by algorithms whose only morality is click-through rates—articles that do nothing but reinforce a unidimensional point of view and take users to extremes to keep them clicking. What we’re seeing is a cognitive segregation, where people exist in their own informational ghettos. We are seeing the segregation of our realities. If Facebook is a “community,” it is a gated one.

共同的经历是现代多元民主中公民团结的基本基础，而民权运动的故事在某种程度上就是能够共享空间的故事：在电影院的同一区域，使用同一个饮水机或浴室。美国的种族隔离一直以阴险平凡的方式表现出来——通过单独的公交车座位、饮水机、学校、剧院门票和公园长椅。也许现在在社交媒体上。对于罗莎·帕克斯来说，被命令让出公交车座位只是白人美国系统地确保她的黑皮肤被隔离和看不见的无数方式之一——她仍然是异类，而不是他们美国的一部分。尽管我们不再允许建筑物根据客人的种族来隔离入口，但种族隔离是互联网架构的核心。

Shared experience is the fundamental basis for solidarity among citizens in a modern pluralistic democracy, and the story of the civil rights movement is, in part, the story of being able to share space together: being in the same part of the movie theater or using the same water fountain or bathroom. Segregation in America has always manifested itself in insidiously mundane ways—through separate bus seats, water fountains, schools, theater tickets, and park benches. And perhaps now on social media. For Rosa Parks, being ordered to give up her bus seat was just one of the countless ways white America systematically ensured that her dark skin was separated and unseen—that she remained the other, not part of their America. And although we no longer allow buildings to segregate their entrances based on a guest’s race, segregation rests at the heart of the architectures of the Internet.

社会孤立产生了阴谋论和民粹主义的原材料：不信任。剑桥分析公司是这种网络空间分裂的必然产物。该公司之所以能够让其攻击目标沉迷于愤怒，只是因为没有什么可以阻止它这样做——因此，该公司在畅通无阻的情况下将他们淹没在虚假信息的漩涡中，后果可想而知是灾难性的。但仅仅阻止剑桥分析公司是不够的。除非我们解决导致我们陷入困境的根本架构，否则美国新发现的认知危机只会继续恶化。不作为的后果将是可怕的。破坏共同体验是将其视为异类、否认成为我们中的一员的另一种视角的必要第一步。

From social isolation comes the raw material of both conspiracism and populism: mistrust. Cambridge Analytica was the inevitable product of this balkanized cyberspace. The company was able to get its targets addicted to rage only because there was nothing to prevent it from doing so—and so, unimpeded, the company drowned them in a maelstrom of disinformation, with predictably disastrous results. But simply stopping CA is not enough. America’s newfound crisis of perception will only continue to worsen until we address the underlying architectures that got us here. And the consequences of inaction would be dire. The destruction of mutual experience is the essential first step to othering, to denying another perspective on what it means to be one of us.

史蒂夫·班农 (Steve Bannon) 承认，互联网的“虚拟”世界比大多数人意识到的要真实得多。美国人平均每天查看手机 52 次。现在许多人睡觉时手机都放在身边充电——他们和手机一起睡觉的时间比和别人一起睡觉的时间还多。他们醒着时看到的第一件和最后一件东西就是屏幕。人们在屏幕上看到的内容会促使他们实施仇恨行为，在某些情况下，甚至实施极端暴力行为。现在不再有“只是上网”这回事了，网上信息（或虚假信息）如果能吸引目标用户，就会导致可怕的悲剧。作为回应，Facebook 和美国步枪协会 (NRA) 一样，通过援引同样的“枪不杀人”论点来逃避其道德责任。他们举手投降，声称他们无法控制用户如何滥用他们的产品，即使导致大规模谋杀。如果种族清洗还不足以让他们采取行动，那还有什么能让他们采取行动呢？当 Facebook 再次进行道歉之旅，高声宣称“我们会更加努力”时，其空洞的言辞只不过是一家满足于从无所作为的现状中获利的科技公司的想法和祈祷。对于 Facebook 来说，受害者的生命已经成为他们不断追求快速行动和打破常规的外部因素。

Steve Bannon recognized that the “virtual” worlds of the Internet are so much more real than most people realize. Americans check their phones on average fifty-two times per day. Many now sleep with their phones charging beside them—they sleep with their phones more than they sleep with people. The first and last thing they see in their waking hours is a screen. And what people see on that screen can motivate them to commit acts of hatred and, in some cases, acts of extreme violence. There is no such thing as “just online” anymore, and online information—or disinformation—that engages its targets can lead to horrific tragedies. In response, Facebook, like the NRA, evades its moral responsibility by invoking the same kind of “Guns don’t kill people” argument. They throw up their hands and claim they can’t control how their users abuse their products, even when mass murder results. If ethnic cleansing is not enough for them to act, what is? When Facebook goes on yet another apology tour, loudly professing that “we will try harder,” its empty rhetoric is nothing more than the thoughts and prayers of a technology company content to profit from a status quo of inaction. For Facebook, the lives of victims have become an externality of their continued quest to move fast and break things.

当我以告密者的身份站出来时，另类右翼的数字愤怒机器将目光转向了我。在伦敦，愤怒的脱欧派把我推到迎面而来的车流中。另类右翼跟踪者跟踪我，我和朋友在俱乐部的照片被发布在另类右翼网站上，并附上在哪里可以找到我的信息。到了在欧洲议会作证的时候，关于 Facebook 批评者的阴谋论开始在另类右翼的论坛上流传。当我作证时，后面传来“索罗斯，索罗斯，索罗斯”的呼喊声。当我离开欧洲议会时，一个男人在街上向我走来，喊着“犹太人的钱！”当时，这些叙述似乎是凭空而来的。后来，Facebook 因公关危机而惊慌失措，聘请了秘密通讯公司 Definers Public Affairs，该公司随后泄露了充满反犹太主义言论的虚假故事，称其批评者是乔治·索罗斯资助的阴谋的一部分。谣言在互联网上传播，正如我亲眼所见，其目标人物将此视为自己采取行动的线索。

When I came out as a whistleblower, the alt-right’s digital rage machine turned its sights to me. In London, enraged Brexiteers pushed me into oncoming traffic. I was followed around by alt-right stalkers and had photos of me at clubs with my friends published on alt-right websites with information about where to find me. When it came time to testify at the European Parliament, conspiracies about Facebook’s critics were beginning to percolate through forums of the alt-right. As I testified, there were chants of “Soros, Soros, Soros” in the back. As I was leaving the European Parliament, a man came up to me on the street, shouting “Jew money!” At the time, these narratives seemed to come out of nowhere. Later, it emerged that Facebook, in a panic about its PR crisis, had hired the secret communications firm Definers Public Affairs, which subsequently leaked out fake narratives filled with anti-Semitic tropes about its critics being part of a George Soros–funded conspiracy. Rumors were seeded on the Internet and, as I discovered personally, its targets took it as a cue to take matters into their own hands.

—

2013 年 2 月，俄罗斯军事将领瓦列里·格拉西莫夫写了一篇文章，对当时盛行的战争观念提出挑战。格拉西莫夫曾任俄罗斯总参谋长（大致相当于美国参谋长联席会议主席），他在《军工信使报》上发表了自己的看法，题为《科学的价值在于远见卓识》——后来有人将这套思想称为格拉西莫夫主义。格拉西莫夫写道，“‘战争规则’已经改变”，“非军事手段在实现政治和战略目标方面的作用已经增强。”他谈到了人工智能和信息在战争中的应用：“信息空间，”他写道，“为降低敌人的战斗力提供了广泛的非对称可能性。”从本质上讲，格拉西莫夫吸取了阿拉伯之春起义的教训，这些起义是由社交媒体上的信息共享推动的，他敦促军事战略家们加以借鉴。 “最简单的说法是，‘阿拉伯之春’事件不是战争，因此我们军人没有教训可学。但事实可能恰恰相反——这些事件恰恰是 21 世纪战争的典型特征。”

IN FEBRUARY 2013, a Russian military general named Valery Gerasimov wrote an article challenging the prevailing notions of warfare. Gerasimov, who was Russia’s chief of the general staff (roughly equivalent to chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff), penned his thoughts in the Military-Industrial Kurier under the title “The Value of Science Is in the Foresight”—a set of ideas that some would later dub the Gerasimov Doctrine. Gerasimov wrote that the “ ‘rules of war’ have changed” and that “the role of nonmilitary means of achieving political and strategic goals has grown.” He addressed the uses of artificial intelligence and information in warfare: “The information space,” he wrote, “opens wide asymmetrical possibilities for reducing the fighting potential of the enemy.” Essentially, Gerasimov took the lessons of the Arab Spring uprisings, which were propelled by information sharing on social media, and urged military strategists to adapt them. “It would be easiest of all to say that the events of the ‘Arab Spring’ are not war, and so there are no lessons for us—military men—to learn. But maybe the opposite is true—that precisely these events are typical of warfare in the twenty-first century.”

格拉西莫夫的文章发表后，俄罗斯又发表了另一份军事战略文件，由上校 SG 切基诺夫和中将 SA 波格丹诺夫撰写。他们的论文进一步推进了格拉西莫夫的想法：作者写道，可以通过“从 Facebook 和 Twitter 公共网络的服务器获取信息进行宣传”来攻击对手，并且利用这些“强大的信息技术，侵略者将努力让其打算攻击的国家的所有公共机构参与其中，主要是大众媒体和宗教组织、文化机构、非政府组织、由国外资助的公众运动以及从事外国资助研究的学者。”在当时，这是一个激进的新想法。今天读来，这是俄罗斯干预 2016 年大选的精确蓝图。

Gerasimov’s article was followed by another Russian military strategy paper, this one written by Colonel S. G. Chekinov and Lieutenant General S. A. Bogdanov. Their paper took Gerasimov’s idea even further: The authors wrote that it would be possible to attack an adversary by “obtain[ing] information to engage in propaganda from servers of the Facebook and [T]witter public networks” and that, with these “powerful information technologies at its disposal, the aggressor will make an effort to involve all public institutions in the country it intends to attack, primarily the mass media and religious organizations, cultural institutions, non-governmental organizations, public movements financed from abroad, and scholars engaged in research on foreign grants.” At the time, it was a radical new idea. Read today, it is a precise blueprint for Russia’s interference in the 2016 election.

战争史就是新发明和新战略的历史，其中许多都是出于必要而诞生的。按照大多数指标衡量，俄罗斯的军事实力都明显弱于美国。美国的军事预算为 7160 亿美元，是俄罗斯的 10 倍多。美国现役军人 128 万，而俄罗斯只有 100 万；美国共有 13000 多架飞机，而俄罗斯只有 4000 架；美国有 20 艘航空母舰，而俄罗斯只有一艘。按照现有的所有常规衡量标准，莫斯科在“大国”战争中再也无法与美国竞争，普京很清楚这一点。因此，俄罗斯人必须想出另一种方法来重新获得优势——一种与物理战场无关的方法。

The history of warfare is the history of new inventions and strategies, many of which were born out of necessity. By most metrics, Russia’s military is significantly weaker than that of the United States. The U.S. military budget, at $716 billion, is more than ten times that of Russia. The United States has 1.28 million active military personnel, as compared with Russia’s 1 million; has more than 13,000 total aircraft, as compared with Russia’s 4,000; and has twenty aircraft carriers, whereas Russia has one. By all existing conventional measures, Moscow would never again be competitive with the United States in terms of “great powers” warfare, and Vladimir Putin knew it. So the Russians had to devise another way to regain the advantage—one that had nothing to do with the physical battlespace.

当军事战略家专注于眼前的战斗时，他们很难设想新的战斗形式。在飞行出现之前，军事指挥官只关心如何在陆地或海上进行战斗。直到 1915 年，法国飞行员罗兰·加洛斯驾驶一架装有机关枪的飞机时，军事战略家才意识到战争实际上可以从空中发动。然后，一旦飞机开始发动攻击，地面上的军队也会随之转变，制造出紧凑、快速射击的高射炮。战争的演变就这样继续着。

It’s difficult for military strategists to envision new forms of battle when they’re focused on those at hand. Before the advent of flight, military commanders cared only about how to wage combat on land or at sea. It wasn’t until 1915, when the French pilot Roland Garros flew a plane jerry-rigged with a machine gun, that military strategists realized that war could actually be waged from the skies. Then, once aircraft began engaging in attacks, army units on the ground pivoted as well, creating compact, rapid-fire antiaircraft guns. And so the evolution of war continued.

信息战的发展方式也类似。起初，没人能想象 Facebook 或 Twitter 会成为战场工具；战争在地面、空中、海上甚至太空展开。但事实证明，第五个领域——网络空间——对于那些有想象力和远见的人而言，是一个富有成果的战场，他们设想利用社交媒体进行信息战。你可以从格拉西莫夫、切基诺夫和波格丹诺夫奠定的基础，到剑桥分析公司的行动，再到英国脱欧和特朗普竞选活动的胜利，画出一条直线。仅用五年左右的时间，俄罗斯军方和政府就成功开发出 21 世纪第一种具有毁灭性的新武器。

Information warfare has evolved in similar fashion. At first, no one could have imagined that Facebook or Twitter could be battlefield tools; warfare was waged on the ground, in the air, at sea, and potentially in space. But the fifth domain—cyberspace—has proved to be a fruitful battleground for those who had the imagination and foresight to envision using social media for information warfare. You can draw a straight line from the groundwork laid by Gerasimov, Chekinov, and Bogdanov, right through the actions of Cambridge Analytica, to the victories of the Brexit and Trump campaigns. In only five or so years, the Russian military and state have managed to develop the first devastatingly effective new weapon of the twenty-first century.

他们知道这个办法会奏效，因为 Facebook 这样的公司永远不会采取“非美国”的手段来控制用户。因此俄罗斯无需传播宣传。他们只需让美国人自己点击、点赞和分享即可。Facebook 上的美国人替俄罗斯人做了工作，利用《第一修正案》来洗白他们的宣传。

They knew it would work, because companies such as Facebook would never take the “un-American” step of reining in their users. So Russia didn’t have to disseminate propaganda. They could just get the Americans to do it themselves, by clicking, liking, and sharing. Americans on Facebook did the Russians’ work for them, laundering their propaganda through the First Amendment.

但这个大规模虚假信息的新时代并不局限于政治领域。星巴克、耐克等时尚品牌已成为俄罗斯资助的虚假信息行动的目标。当品牌发表涉足现有社会或种族紧张局势的言论时，已有几个已发现的案例表明，俄罗斯资助的虚假新闻网站、僵尸网络和社交媒体行动已启动，将这些言论武器化并挑起社会冲突。2016 年 8 月，足球运动员科林·卡佩尼克拒绝在美国国歌演奏时起立，以抗议美国系统性种族主义和警察对非裔美国人和其他少数族裔的暴行。卡佩尼克的赞助商时尚品牌耐克支持这位运动员，耐克的回应引发了争议。但当时许多人不知道，在丑闻爆发后的几个小时内，与俄罗斯有关的社交媒体账户开始传播并扩大现有的标签，呼吁抵制耐克。其中一些被俄罗斯放大的内容最终进入了主流媒体新闻，这有助于将抵制耐克的说辞合法化为纯粹的本土抗议。网络安全公司还发现了来自另类右翼团体的假耐克优惠券，这些团体针对非裔美国社交媒体用户提供“有色人种所有鞋子 75% 折扣”等优惠。这些优惠券的目的是创造这样的场景：不知情的非裔美国顾客会试图在耐克商店使用这些优惠券，但遭到拒绝。在病毒式视频时代，这种情况反过来可以创造出“真实”的镜头，展示一个“愤怒的黑人”在商店里索要免费物品的种族主义比喻。那么，为什么这些虚假信息行动会针对一家时装公司并试图将其品牌武器化呢？因为这种敌对宣传的目的不仅仅是干涉我们的政治，甚至不是损害我们的公司。其目的是撕裂我们的社会结构。他们想让我们互相憎恨。当这些叙述污染了我们日常生活中关心的事物（我们穿的衣服、我们看的运动、我们听的音乐、甚至我们喝的咖啡）时，这种分歧会造成更严重的打击。

But this new era of scaled disinformation is not confined to the realm of politics. Companies like Starbucks, Nike, and other fashion brands have found themselves targets of Russian-sponsored disinformation operations. When brands make statements that wade into existing social or racial tensions, there have been several identified instances in which Russian-sponsored fake news sites, botnets, and social media operations have activated to weaponize these narratives and provoke social conflict. In August 2016, the football player Colin Kaepernick refused to stand for the American national anthem to protest systemic racism and police brutality toward African Americans and other minorities in the United States. The fashion brand Nike, Kaepernick’s sponsor, stood behind the athlete, and a controversy ensued about Nike’s response. But unknown to many at the time, Russian-linked social media accounts began to spread and amplify existing hashtags promoting a Nike boycott within hours of the scandal emerging. Some of this Russian-amplified content eventually made it into mainstream news, which helped legitimize the Nike boycott narrative as a purely homegrown protest. Cybersecurity firms also identified fake Nike coupons originating from alt-right groups that targeted African American social media users with offers like “75% off all shoes for people of color.” The coupons were intended to create scenarios in which unwitting African American customers would try to use the coupons in a Nike store, where they would be refused. In the age of viral videos, this scenario could in turn create “real” footage showcasing a racist trope of an “angry black man” demanding free stuff in a store. So why would these disinformation operations target a fashion company and attempt to weaponize its brand? Because the objective of this hostile propaganda is not simply to interfere with our politics, or even to damage our companies. The objective is to tear apart our social fabric. They want us to hate one another. And that division can hit so much harder when these narratives contaminate the things we care about in our everyday lives—the clothes we wear, the sports we watch, the music we listen to, or the even coffee we drink.

我们都容易受到操纵。我们根据可获得的信息做出判断，但当我们获取信息的渠道被中介化时，我们都容易受到操纵。随着时间的推移，我们的偏见会在我们不知不觉中被放大。我们中的许多人都忘记了，我们在新闻源和搜索引擎中看到的内容已经受到算法的调节，算法的唯一动机是选择那些能吸引我们而不是通知我们的东西。由于大多数知名新闻来源现在都处于付费墙之下，我们已经看到信息在假新闻总是免费的市场上逐渐成为奢侈品。

We are all vulnerable to manipulation. We make judgments based on the information available to us, but we are all susceptible to manipulation when our access to that information becomes mediated. Over time, our biases can become amplified without our even realizing it. Many of us forget that what we see in our newsfeeds and our search engines is already moderated by algorithms whose sole motivation is to select what will engage us, not inform us. With most reputable news sources now behind paywalls, we are already seeing information inch toward becoming a luxury product in a marketplace where fake news is always free.

在上一次经济革命中，工业资本主义试图开发我们周围的自然世界。只是随着气候变化的出现，我们才开始接受其生态外部性。但在资本主义的下一次迭代中，原材料不再是石油或矿物，而是商品化的注意力和行为。在这个监控资本主义的新经济中，我们就是原材料。这意味着，存在一种新的经济激励，即在平台和用户之间制造巨大的信息不对称。为了能够将用户行为转化为利润，平台需要了解用户的所有行为，而用户对平台的行为一无所知。正如剑桥分析公司发现的那样，这成为了孵化宣传的完美环境。

In the last economic revolution, industrial capitalism sought to exploit the natural world around us. It is only with the advent of climate change that we are now coming to terms with its ecological externalities. But in this next iteration of capitalism, the raw materials are no longer oil or minerals but rather commodified attention and behavior. In this new economy of surveillance capitalism, we are the raw materials. What this means is that there is a new economic incentive to create substantial informational asymmetries between platforms and users. In order to be able to convert user behavior into profit, platforms need to know everything about their users’ behavior, while their users know nothing of the platform’s behavior. As Cambridge Analytica discovered, this becomes the perfect environment to incubate propaganda.

随着亚马逊 Alexa 和 Google Home 等家庭自动化中心的出现，我们正朝着网络空间与暂时的物理现实最终融合的方向迈出第一步。第五代 (5G) 移动和下一代 Wi-Fi 已经推出，为“物联网”(IoT) 成为新常态奠定了基础，大大小小的家用电器将连接到高速且无处不在的互联网网络。这些普通设备，无论是冰箱、牙刷还是镜子，都有望使用传感器开始跟踪用户在家中的行为，并将数据传回服务提供商。亚马逊、谷歌和 Facebook 已经申请专利，以创建将家庭物联网传感器与在线市场、广告网络和社交资料相结合的“联网家庭”。在未来，亚马逊会知道你什么时候吃阿司匹林，而 Facebook 会监视你的孩子在客厅玩耍。

With the advent of home automation hubs such as Amazon Alexa and Google Home, we are seeing the first step toward the eventual integration of cyberspace with our temporal physical reality. Fifth-generation (5G) mobile and next-generation Wi-Fi are already being rolled out, laying the foundations for the “Internet of Things” (IoT) to become the new norm, where household appliances big and small will become connected to high-speed and ubiquitous Internet networks. These mundane devices, whether they are a refrigerator, a toothbrush, or a mirror, are envisaged to use sensors to begin tracking users’ behavior inside their own homes, relaying the data back to service providers. Amazon, Google, and Facebook have already applied for patents to create “networked homes” that integrate in-home IoT sensors with online marketplaces, ad networks, and social profiles. In this future, Amazon will know when you pop an aspirin, and Facebook will watch your kids play in the living room.

这个新环境与智能信息网络完全融合，能够观察我们、思考我们、评判我们，并通过调解我们对信息的访问来影响我们——“它”可以看到我们，但我们看不到“它”。在人类历史上，我们将首次沉浸在受我们自己创造的硅精灵影响的激励空间中。我们的环境不再是被动或无害的；它将有意图、观点和议程。我们的家不再是外界的避难所，因为环境将在每个相连的房间中持续存在。我们正在创造一个未来，我们的家会思考我们。我们的汽车和办公室会评判我们。门将成为看门人。我们创造了未来的恶魔和天使。

Fully integrated with intelligent information networks, this new environment will be able to watch us, think about us, judge us, and seek to influence us by mediating our access to information—where “it” can see us, but we cannot see “it.” For the first time in human history, we will immerse ourselves in motivated spaces influenced by these silicon spirits of our making. No longer will our environment be passive or benign; it will have intentions, opinions, and agendas. No longer will our homes be a sanctuary from the outside world, for an ambient presence will persist throughout each connected room. We are creating a future where our homes will think about us. Where our cars and offices will judge us. Where doors become the doormen. Where we have created the demons and angels of the future.

这是硅谷为我们所有人设定的梦想——随时随地包围我们。剑桥分析公司在寻求信息主导权的过程中，绝不会满足于仅仅拥有社交数据集，它已经开始与卫星和数字电视提供商建立关系。在进入联网电视领域后，剑桥分析公司计划找到一种方法，与人们家中的传感器和智能设备进行整合。想象一下，未来像剑桥分析公司这样的公司可以编辑你的电视节目，与你的孩子交谈，甚至在你睡觉时对你低语。

This is the dream that Silicon Valley has for us all—to surround us at every minute and everywhere. In Cambridge Analytica’s quest for informational dominance, it was never going to be satisfied with just social data sets and had already begun to build relationships with satellite and digital TV providers. After tapping into connected televisions, Cambridge Analytica planned to find a way to integrate with sensors and smart devices in people’s homes. Imagine a future where a company like Cambridge Analytica could edit your television, talk to your children, and whisper to you in your sleep.

—

我们法律体系的基础建立在这样一个概念上：我们的环境是被动的、无生命的。我们周围的世界可能会被动地影响我们的决定，但这种影响是无动机的。自然或天堂不会选择影响我们。几个世纪以来，法律已经形成了关于人性的几个基本假设。其中最重要的是人类能动性的概念，这是法律中一个不可辩驳的假设——人类有能力自行做出理性和独立的选择。由此可见，世界不会为人类做决定，而是人类在世界内部做决定。

THE FOUNDATION OF OUR legal system is contingent upon the notion that our environment is passive and inanimate. The world surrounding us may passively influence our decisions, but such influence is not motivated. Nature or the heavens do not choose to influence us. Over centuries, the law has developed several fundamental presumptions about human nature. The most important of these is the notion of human agency as an irrefutable presumption in the law—that humans have the capacity to make rational and independent choices on their own accord. It follows that the world does not make decisions for humans, but that humans make decisions inside of that world.

这种人类主体性的概念是刑事责任的哲学基础，我们惩罚违法者，理由是他们做出了应受谴责的选择。一栋燃烧的建筑物确实可能会伤害到人们，但法律不会惩罚那栋建筑物，因为它没有主体性。因此，人类法律规范的是人类行为，而不是周围环境的动机或行为。由此得出的推论就是我们的基本权利。在启蒙运动时期，人们的基本权利被阐述为保护人类主体性行使的核心权利。生命权、自由权、结社权、言论权、投票权和良知权都以主体性推定为基础，因为它们是主体性的结果。但主体性本身并没有被阐述为一项权利，因为它一直被推定为仅仅凭借我们的人格而存在。因此，我们没有明确的主体性权利，即对环境本身可行使的主体性权利。我们没有权利对抗天堂或有动机和有思想的空间的不当影响来调解我们行动的行使。在美国建国之时，我们的行动可能被有动机和有思想的环境操纵，这种可能性从未被考虑过。对于开国元勋们来说，这是一种只有上帝才知道的力量。

This notion of human agency serves as the philosophical basis for criminal culpability, and we punish transgressors of the law on the grounds that they made a condemnable choice. A burning building may indeed harm people, but the law does not punish that building, as it has no agency. And so human laws regulate human acts, and not the motivations or behaviors of their surroundings. The corollaries to this are the fundamental rights we have. During the Enlightenment, the fundamental rights of people were articulated as core entitlements to protect the exercise of human agency. The rights to life, liberty, association, speech, vote, and conscience are all underpinned with a presumption of agency, as they are outputs of that agency. But agency itself has not been articulated as a right per se, as it has always been presumed to exist simply by virtue of our personhood. As such, we do not have an express right to agency that is contra mundum—that is, a right to agency that is exercisable against the environment itself. We do not have a right against the heavens or the undue influence of motivated and thinking spaces to mediate the exercise of our agency. At the time of America’s founding, a situation where our agency could be manipulated by a motivated and thinking environment was never contemplated as a possibility. For the Founding Fathers, this would have been a power known only to God.

我们已经看到，算法竞相吸引我们的注意力，不仅能够改变文化，还能重新定义生存体验。算法强化的“参与度”是我们愤怒政治、呼吁文化、自拍引发的虚荣心、技术成瘾和心理健康衰退的核心。目标用户沉浸在内容中，以保持点击。我们喜欢认为自己不受影响或认知偏见的影响，因为我们想感觉自己处于控制之中，但酒精、烟草、快餐和游戏等行业都知道，我们是容易受到认知和情感脆弱性的生物。科技已经通过对“用户体验”、“游戏化”、“增长黑客”和“参与度”的研究抓住了这一点，通过像老虎机一样激活游戏循环和强化计划。到目前为止，这种游戏化仅限于社交媒体和数字平台，但当我们将我们的生活与旨在利用我们认知进化缺陷的网络信息架构进一步融合时，会发生什么？我们真的想生活在一个“游戏化”的环境中吗？这个环境操控着我们的痴迷，玩弄我们的生活，仿佛我们身处游戏之中？

We can already see how algorithms competing to maximize our attention have the capacity to not only transform cultures but redefine the experience of existence. Algorithmically reinforced “engagement” lies at the heart of our outrage politics, call-out culture, selfie-induced vanity, tech addiction, and eroding mental well-being. Targeted users are soaked in content to keep them clicking. We like to think of ourselves as immune from influence or our cognitive biases, because we want to feel like we are in control, but industries like alcohol, tobacco, fast food, and gaming all know we are creatures that are subject to cognitive and emotional vulnerabilities. And tech has caught on to this with its research into “user experience,” “gamification,” “growth hacking,” and “engagement” by activating ludic loops and reinforcement schedules in the same way slot machines do. So far, this gamification has been contained to social media and digital platforms, but what will happen as we further integrate our lives with networked information architectures designed to exploit evolutionary flaws in our cognition? Do we really want to live in a “gamified” environment that engineers our obsessions and plays with our lives as if we are inside its game?

社交媒体的根本理念不是增强选择或自主权，而是缩小、过滤和减少选择，以使创作者和广告商受益。社交媒体将公民聚集到受监视的空间中，在那里，策划者可以跟踪和分类他们，并利用这种理解来影响他们的行为。如果民主和资本主义建立在可访问的信息和自由选择的基础上，那么我们正在目睹它们从内部被颠覆。

The underlying ideology within social media is not to enhance choice or agency, but rather to narrow, filter, and reduce choice to benefit creators and advertisers. Social media herds the citizenry into surveilled spaces where the architects can track and classify them and use this understanding to influence their behavior. If democracy and capitalism are based on accessible information and free choice, what we are witnessing is their subversion from the inside.

我们冒着创造一个痴迷于记忆的社会的风险，我们可能忽视了遗忘、前进或未知的价值。人类成长需要私人庇护所和自由空间，在那里我们可以实验、玩耍、涉猎、保守秘密、违反禁忌、违背诺言，思考未来的自己，而不会对我们的公共生活产生影响，直到我们决定在公共场合改变。历史告诉我们，个人和社会解放始于私下。如果我们无法控制自己的隐私和个人发展，我们就无法摆脱童年、过去的关系、错误、旧观点、旧身体或以前的偏见。如果我们的选择受到监控和过滤，我们就无法自由选择。如果我们被束缚在曾经的自己、我们认为的自己或曾经的自我表现上，我们就无法成长和改变。如果我们生活在一个总是根据我们无法控制或意识到的条件或价值观监视、记住和标记我们的环境中，那么我们的数据自我可能会将我们束缚在我们更愿意摆脱的历史中。隐私是我们决定自己是谁、想成为怎样的人的权力的本质。隐私不是隐藏，而是关乎人类的成长和自主权。

We risk creating a society obsessive about remembering, and we may have overlooked the value of forgetting, moving on, or being unknown. Human growth requires private sanctuaries and free spaces where we can experiment, play, dabble, keep secrets, transgress taboos, break our promises, and contemplate our future selves without consequence to our public lives until we decide to change in public. History shows us that personal and social liberation begins in private. We cannot move on from our childhoods, past relationships, mistakes, old perspectives, old bodies, or former prejudices if we are not in control of our privacy and personal development. We cannot be free to choose if our choices are monitored and filtered for us. We cannot grow and change if we are shackled to who we once were or who we thought we were or how we once presented ourselves. If we exist in an environment that always watches, remembers, and labels us, according to conditions or values outside our control or awareness, then our data selves may shackle us to histories that we prefer to move on from. Privacy is the very essence of our power to decide who and how we want to be. Privacy is not about hiding—privacy is about human growth and agency.

但这不仅仅关乎隐私或同意。这关乎谁能影响我们的真相以及我们周围人的真相。这关乎我们在社会周围构建的操纵架构。剑桥分析公司的教训就在于此。要了解社交媒体的危害，我们必须首先了解它是什么。Facebook可能称自己为用户的“社区”，或称监管机构的“平台”，但它不是一项服务，就像建筑物不是一项服务一样。即使你不完全了解网络空间的工作原理，也必须了解它现在围绕着你。每个连接的设备和计算机都是互连信息架构的一部分——并塑造了你对世界的体验。大多数硅谷公司最常见的职位是工程师和建筑师，而不是服务经理或客户关系经理。但与其他行业的工程不同，科技公司在发布产品之前不必进行安全测试以符合任何建筑规范。相反，平台被允许采用暗黑模式设计，故意误导用户继续使用并泄露更多数据。技术工程师们故意在他们的平台上设计令人困惑的迷宫，让人们越来越深入这些架构，而没有任何明确的出口。当人们不断地点击穿过迷宫时，这些建筑师们会为“参与度”的增加而感到高兴。

But this is not merely about privacy or consent. This is about who gets to influence our truths and the truths of those around us. This is about the architectures of manipulation we are constructing around our society. And herein lies the lesson of Cambridge Analytica. To understand the harms of social media, we have to first understand what it is. Facebook may call itself a “community” to its users, or a “platform” to regulators, but it is not a service, in the same way a building is not a service. Even if you don’t understand exactly how cyberspace works, it is important to understand that it now surrounds you. Every connected device and computer is part of an interconnected information architecture—and shapes your experience of the world. The most common job titles in most Silicon Valley companies are engineer and architect, not service manager or client relations. But unlike engineering in other sectors, tech companies do not have to perform safety tests to conform to any building codes before releasing their products. Instead, platforms are allowed to adopt dark pattern designs that deliberately mislead users into continual use and giving up more data. Tech engineers intentionally design confounding mazes on their platforms that keep people moving deeper and deeper into these architectures, without any clear exit. And when people keep clicking their way through their maze, these architects delight in the increase in “engagement.”

社交媒体和互联网平台不是服务，而是架构和基础设施。通过将架构标记为“服务”，他们试图通过消费者的“同意”将责任推到消费者身上。但在其他任何领域，我们都不会以这种方式给消费者增加负担。航空乘客不会被要求“接受”飞机的工程设计，酒店客人不会被要求“接受”建筑物出口的数量，人们也不会被要求“接受”饮用水的纯度水平。作为一名前俱乐部成员，我可以告诉你，当酒吧或音乐会超员并挤满狂欢者时，如果情况明显不安全，消防检查员会命令那些同意的顾客离开建筑物。

Social media and Internet platforms are not services; they are architectures and infrastructures. By labeling their architectures as “services,” they are trying to make responsibility lie with the consumer, through their “consent.” But in no other sector do we burden consumers in this way. Airline passengers are not asked to “accept” the engineering of planes, hotel guests are not asked to “accept” the number of exits in the building, and people are not asked to “accept” the purity levels of their drinking water. And as a former club kid, I can tell you that when bars or concerts are over capacity and heaving with ravers, fire inspectors will order those consenting customers to leave a building if the conditions become manifestly unsafe.

Facebook 可能会说：如果你不喜欢它，就不要用它。但是，互联网上没有可以与这些主导者相媲美的替代品，就像没有可以替代电力、电信或水务公司的替代品一样。拒绝使用 Google、Facebook、LinkedIn 和 Amazon 等平台就等于脱离现代社会。你怎么找工作？你怎么获取信息？你怎么与人交往？这些公司喜欢谈论消费者的选择，因为他们知道，他们已经尽其所能成为大多数人生活中必不可少的一部分。在向用户展示一本厚厚的法律术语（Facebook 的案例接近一万两千字）后让他们点击“接受”，这无异于洗白同意。这些平台专为将用户同意纳入考量而构建。没有人会选择退出这些平台，因为用户别无选择，只能接受。

Facebook may say: If you don’t like it, don’t use it. But there are no comparable alternatives to the dominant players on the Internet, just as there are no alternatives to electric, telecommunications, or water companies. To reject the use of platforms like Google, Facebook, LinkedIn, and Amazon would be to remove oneself from modern society. How are you going to get a job? How are you going to get information? How are you going to socialize with people? These companies love to talk about consumer choice, when they know that they have done everything in their power to become a necessary part of most people’s lives. Getting users to click “accept” after presenting them with a novella’s worth of dense legalese (almost twelve thousand words in Facebook’s case) is nothing but consent-washing. These platforms are purpose-built to run user consent through a blender. No one opts out of these platforms, because users have no other choice but to accept.

当 Facebook 封禁我时，他们并不是简单地停用了我的账户，而是抹去了我在 Facebook 和 Instagram 上的所有信息。当我的朋友们试图查找我发送的旧消息时，什么都没有出现：我的名字、我的文字——一切都消失了。我成了一个影子。流放是一种古老的惩罚，目的是将社会中的罪犯、异教徒和危害国家或教会权力的政治激进分子驱逐出去。在古雅典，人们可以因任何原因被驱逐出社会十年，没有上诉的机会。在苏联斯大林时期，国家的敌人不会就此消失；他们存在的所有残余——照片、信件、新闻参考——都会从官方历史记录中被抹去和清除。纵观历史，当权者一直将社会记忆和集体遗忘作为一种强大的武器来压制异议，纠正他们偏爱的历史，以塑造当下的现实。如果我们想了解这些科技公司为何如此行事，我们应该听听那些创建它们的人的话。 Facebook、Palantir 和 PayPal 背后的风险投资家彼得·蒂尔 (Peter Thiel) 详细阐述了他不再相信“自由和民主是相容的”。在阐述他对科技公司的看法时，他阐述了首席执行官是如何成为技术封建治理体系中的新君主。他说，我们只是不会在公开场合称他们为君主制，因为“任何不民主的东西都会让人感到不舒服。”

When Facebook banned me, they did not simply deactivate my account; they erased my entire presence on Facebook and Instagram. When my friends tried to look up old messages I had sent, nothing came up: My name, my words—everything—had disappeared. I became a shadow. Banishment is an ancient punishment to rid a society of its criminals, heretics, and political radicals who jeopardized the power of the state or church. In ancient Athens, people could be banished from society for ten years for any reason with no opportunity for appeal. In the Stalinist period of the Soviet Union, enemies of the state would not just disappear; all remnants of their existence—photos, letters, news references—would be erased and cleansed from the annals of official history. Throughout history, the powerful have used social memory and collective forgetting as a powerful weapon to crush dissent and correct their preferred histories to shape the realities of the present. And if we want to understand why these technology companies behave this way, we should listen to the words of those who built them. Peter Thiel, the venture capitalist behind Facebook, Palantir, and PayPal, spoke at length about how he no longer believes “that freedom and democracy are compatible.” And in elaborating his views on technology companies, he expounded on how CEOs are the new monarchs in a techno-feudal system of governance. We just don’t call them monarchies in public, he said, because “anything that’s not democracy makes people uncomfortable.”

威权主义的哲学基础在于在社会中创造绝对的确定性。确定性政治重新定位了自由的概念，其中免于的自由取代了寻求的自由。严格的规则和法律被强制执行，以管理和塑造政体的行为、思想和行动。威权政权的首要工具始终是信息控制——无论是通过监视收集公众信息，还是通过自有媒体向公众过滤信息。在早期，互联网似乎对威权政权构成了挑战，但随着社交媒体的出现，我们正在目睹满足每个威权政权需求的架构的构建：监视和信息控制。只有当公众习惯并麻木于新常态时，威权运动才有可能实现。

The philosophical basis of authoritarianism rests in the creation of total certainty within society. The politics of certainty repositions the notion of freedom, where freedoms from replace freedoms to. Strict rules and laws are coercively enforced to govern and shape the behavior, thoughts, and actions of the polity. And the first tool of authoritarian regimes is always informational control—both in the gathering of information on the public through surveillance and the filtration of information to the public through owned media. In its early days, the Internet seemed to pose a challenge to authoritarian regimes, but with the advent of social media, we are watching the construction of architectures that fulfill the needs of every authoritarian regime: surveillance and information control. Authoritarian movements are possible only when the general public becomes habituated to—and numbed by—a new normal.

—

互联网颠覆了人们对法律和其所管辖的政体的旧有假设。互联网无处不在，又无处不在——它在物理上依赖于服务器和电缆，但它的存在并不依赖于一个主要居住地。这意味着一个数字行为可能同时在无数个物理位置部分发生，或者一个地方的行为可能会在另一个地方产生影响。这是因为互联网是一种超对象——就像我们的气候和生物圈一样，互联网围绕着我们，我们也生活在其中。科技界通常将他们的平台称为“数字生态系统”，隐含地承认他们的构建是一个数字容器或领域，至少是我们生活的一部分存在于其中。我们看不见也摸不着，但我们通过它的影响知道它存在于我们身边。

THE INTERNET HAS FRUSTRATED these old assumptions about the law and the polity that it governs. The Internet is both everywhere and nowhere—it is physically dependent on servers and cables, but it exists without a single location of primary residence. This means that a single digital act could partially occur in countless physical locations simultaneously, or an action in one place could result in effects in another place. This is because the Internet is a type of hyperobject—like our climate and biosphere, the Internet surrounds us and we live within it. The tech community often call their platforms “digital ecosystems,” with an implicit recognition that their construction is a digital container or realm for at least part of our lives to exist within. We cannot see it or touch it, but we know it exists around us by its effects.

我经常遇到不熟悉数据犯罪的警察调查员使用错误的类比来解释找到“凶器”、“尸体位置”和线性的“因果关系链”。但数据犯罪通常不会发生在某个特定的地方。数据犯罪往往表现得像污染——通常无处不在，但没有具体到某个地方。数据是完全可替代和无形的，因为它仅仅是信息的一种表现形式。它可以同时存储在世界各地的分布式服务器中；即使它在某个地方，也不会完全在那个地方。位于 A 国处理 B 国数据主体的服务器可以被 C 国的人访问，并在收到来自 E 国公司（由 F 国资助）的指令后部署在 D 国的平台上。这就是剑桥分析公司复杂设置的本质。即使确实发生了严重危害，如黑客攻击、数据盗窃、威胁或欺骗，也不明确谁应该承担责任，而我们已知的评估责任的系统完全无法胜任这项工作。

Often I encountered police investigators unfamiliar with data crime using false analogies about finding the “murder weapon,” the “location of the body,” and linear “chains of causation.” But data crimes are crimes that usually don’t happen in one specific place. Data crime can often behave like pollution—it’s everywhere generally, but nowhere specifically. Data is completely fungible and intangible, as it is merely a representation of information. It can be stored simultaneously in distributed servers around the world; where even when it’s in a place, it’s never entirely in that place. Servers based in country A handling data subjects in country B could be accessed by a person in country C and deployed on a platform in country D after receiving instructions from a company in country E with financing from country F. This was the nature of Cambridge Analytica’s complex setup. Even if serious harms were clearly incurred, such as hacking, data theft, menacing threats, or deception, it would be unclear who could be held responsible, and our known systems for assessing culpability were entirely incapable of the job.

我们喜欢把政府想象成这艘船的船长，但当大海本身发生变化时，我们的船长可能会发现自己毫无准备，无法航行。2018 年 7 月，英国选举委员会发现脱欧派运动违反了法律，非法与脱欧派合作。2019 年 3 月 30 日——脱欧举报故事曝光一年后——脱欧派正式放弃对欧盟委员会调查结果和罚款的上诉，实质上承认了其所作所为。有人问：我们为什么要在意区区 70 万英镑？让我们明确一点：脱欧派的计划是英国历史上已知的最大一起违反竞选财务法的案件。但即使不是，选举也像奥运会的百米短跑一样，是零和游戏，赢家通吃。谁先获胜，哪怕只领先几票或几毫秒，谁就能赢得整个竞选：他们可以担任公职。他们可以赢得金牌。他们可以任命你的最高法院法官。他们可以带领你的国家脱离欧盟。

We like to imagine our government as the captain of the ship, but when the ocean itself changes, our captains may find themselves unprepared and unable to navigate. In July 2018, Britain’s Electoral Commission found that the Vote Leave campaign had broken the law, illegally coordinating with BeLeave. On March 30, 2019—one year after the Brexit whistleblowing stories broke—the Vote Leave campaign officially dropped its appeal of the EC’s findings and fines, essentially admitting to what it had done. Some have asked: Why should we care so much about a mere £700,000? Let’s be clear on this point: Vote Leave’s scheme was the largest known breach of campaign finance law in British history. But even if it wasn’t, elections, like a 100-meter sprint in the Olympics, are zero-sum games, where the winner takes all. Whoever comes first, even if it’s by just a few votes or milliseconds, wins the whole race: They get to sit in the public office. They get the gold medal. They get to name your Supreme Court justices. They get to take your country out of the European Union.

当然，唯一的区别是，如果你在奥运会上被发现作弊，你将被取消资格并失去奖牌。没有人讨论服用兴奋剂的运动员“是否无论如何都会获胜”——体育运动的公正性要求比赛干净利落。但在政治上，我们并不认为诚信是民主的必要先决条件。对在体育比赛中作弊的运动员的惩罚比对在选举中作弊的竞选活动更严厉。尽管脱欧派只以 3.78% 的优势获胜，但他们宣称完全符合“人民的意愿”——即使特朗普在普选中输了2.1%，他也宣称自己获胜了。尽管被证明作弊，但脱欧派并没有被剥夺脱欧奖牌。没有人被取消未来竞选的资格，脱欧派的两位领导人鲍里斯·约翰逊和迈克尔·戈夫都被允许竞选首相。政治阶层并不认为针对我们民主的犯罪是“真正的犯罪”。许多人认为这些违法行为与停车罚款不相上下，尽管我们面临的危害非常严重，因为我们的公民机构很容易被犯罪分子和敌对外国政府破坏，这些国家试图对我们的社会发动选举恐怖主义。当然，英国和美国最有权势的人认为这些罪行根本就没有发生过——相反，它们是“骗局”，是他们击败的对手的杜撰。而这一切，都与曾经被称为“事实”和“现实”的东西背道而驰。

The only difference, of course, is that if you are caught cheating in the Olympics, you get disqualified and lose your medal. There are no discussions of whether the doped athlete “would have won anyway”—the integrity of the sport demands a clean race. But in politics, we do not presume integrity as a necessary prerequisite to our democracy. There are harsher punishments for athletes who cheat in sport than for campaigns that cheat in elections. Though they won by only 3.78 percent, the Brexiteers claimed the entire “will of the people” for themselves––and even when Trump lost the popular vote by 2.1 percent, he too claimed victory. Despite proven cheating, Vote Leave did not have its Brexit medal taken away. No one was disqualified from running in future campaigns, and Vote Leave’s two leaders, Boris Johnson and Michael Gove, were both allowed to run for prime minister. Crimes waged against our democracy were not considered by the political class to be “real crime.” Many framed these transgressions as being on par with a parking fine, despite the very real harm we face when our civic institutions can be so easily undermined by criminals and hostile foreign states seeking to wage electoral terrorism on our society. And, of course, the most powerful people in Britain and America took the position that these crimes didn’t even happen—rather, they were a “hoax,” the invention of the bitter opponents they had vanquished. This, in the face of what were once known as “facts” and “reality.”

你可能会认为，在密谋入侵世界领导人的私人电子邮件和医疗记录、贿赂部长、勒索目标以及向选民提供可怕的谋杀和威胁视频后，肯定会产生某种法律后果。但剑桥分析公司非洲项目的任何参与者都没有受到任何惩罚。要确定管辖权太难了——是否“足够多”的犯罪行为发生在英国，足以在英国法庭上起诉。他们的服务器遍布世界各地，会议在不同的国家举行，黑客的基地在另一个国家，而剑桥分析公司只在伦敦收到了被黑客入侵的材料，但没有在英国请求获取被黑客入侵的材料。尽管有几位目击者目睹了整个事件，但剑桥分析公司还是逃脱了惩罚。事实上，尼日利亚项目的一位经理最终升任英国内阁办公室的高级职位，负责外交事务项目，位居英国政府最高层。

You’d think that after pulling off a conspiracy to hack a world leader’s private emails and medical records, bribe ministers, blackmail targets, and shower voters with menacing videos of gruesome murders and threats, there would be some kind of legal consequence. But there were no consequences for anyone involved in Cambridge Analytica’s African projects. It was too difficult to establish jurisdictionality—whether or not “enough” of the crime happened in Britain to warrant prosecution in the English courts. Their servers were all over the world, the meetings happened in different countries, the hackers were based in yet another country, and Cambridge Analytica only received the hacked material in London but did not request the hacked material in the U.K. Even though there were several witnesses to what happened, Cambridge Analytica simply got away with it. In fact, one of the managers from the Nigeria project eventually moved on to work in a senior position at the U.K. Cabinet Office on foreign affairs projects, sitting in the highest levels of the British government.

在美国，剑桥分析公司也没有受到任何惩罚。该公司明知故犯地违反了《外国代理人登记法》。它采取行动压制非裔美国选民。它欺骗 Facebook 用户并用令人作呕的内容威胁他们。它向敌对的外国政府曝光了数亿美国公民的私人记录。然而什么也没发生，因为剑桥分析公司是为了司法套利而设立的。逃税通常涉及在世界各地的热带岛屿上设立空壳公司，试图通过一个足够复杂的国家和公司链来洗钱，每个国家和公司都有自己独特的规则，以至于当局无法追踪这些钱的去向。这是可能的，因为钱和数据一样，是一种完全可替代的资产，可以立即在全球金融系统中转移。剑桥分析公司所做的是利用跨司法管辖区的复杂公司设置，不仅洗钱，还洗钱一些同样有价值的东西：你的数据。

In America there were no consequences for Cambridge Analytica, either. The company knowingly and willfully violated the Foreign Agents Registration Act. It conducted operations to suppress African American voters. It defrauded Facebook users and menaced them with disgusting content. It exposed hundreds of millions of private records of American citizens to hostile foreign states. And yet nothing happened, because Cambridge Analytica was set up for jurisdictional arbitrage. Tax evasion frequently involves setting up shell companies on tropical islands all around the world in an attempt to launder money through a complex enough chain of countries and companies, each with its own unique rules, that authorities lose track of where the money is. This is possible because money, like data, is a completely fungible asset and can be instantly moved through a global finance system. What Cambridge Analytica did was use complex corporate setups across jurisdictions not only to launder money but to launder something that was becoming just as valuable: your data.

在英国，AIQ 也没有受到影响。在桑尼和我揭露了脱欧派通过 AIQ 非法超支并将其作为剑桥分析公司定位能力的隐藏代理的证据后，这件事成为了英国脱欧辩论中的一大争议。英国已经正式提交了退出欧盟的通知。英国脱欧结果可能受到系统性作弊、数据泄露和外国干涉的影响，这一观点被故意忽视，因为后果难以想象。如果同样的事件发生在肯尼亚或尼日利亚，英国观察员会立即呼吁举行新的投票。

In Britain, there were no consequences for AIQ either. After Sanni and I revealed proof of Vote Leave’s unlawful scheme to overspend through AIQ and use it as a hidden proxy for Cambridge Analytica’s targeting capabilities, it became the elephant in the room for the Brexit debate. Britain had already formally submitted its notice to exit the European Union. The notion that the wafer-thin Brexit result could have been affected by systematic cheating, data breaches, and foreign interference was willfully ignored because the ramifications were unimaginable. If the same events had happened in Kenya or Nigeria, there would have been prompt calls from British observers to hold a new vote.

其他英国机构也未能如愿。BBC 高管在报道发表前几周就得到了《卫报》的简报，并获得了全部证据，但他们决定在报道公开前几天放弃报道——因为这会引起太大的争议。相反，BBC 在第四频道的曝光报道播出之前采访了亚历山大·尼克斯，并且没有包括举报人的任何评论。当我后来出现在BBC 的旗舰晚间新闻节目《新闻之夜》中时，主持人费尽心思不断插话说，脱欧派违法行为（涉及使用非法资金在 Facebook 上投放数十亿定向广告）只是我的另一项“指控”。尽管这已经是选举委员会的既定结论。我感到沮丧和困惑，然后开始争论“事实”的含义，以及即使英国司法当局已经公布了裁决，BBC 仍然不允许我说脱欧派违法或非法活动发生在 Facebook 的监视下，这是多么奇怪啊。
