Other British institutions failed as well. BBC executives, who were briefed by The Guardian on the story and given the entire corpus of evidence weeks in advance of publication, decided to drop the story days before it went public—it would have been too controversial. Instead the BBC interviewed Alexander Nix before the Channel 4 exposé was aired and did not include any comment from the whistleblower. When I later appeared on Newsnight, the BBC’s flagship evening news program, the host was at pains to keep interjecting that Vote Leave’s law-breaking, which involved using unlawful money for billions of targeted Facebook ads, was merely another one of my “allegations.” This was despite the fact that this was already an established finding of the Electoral Commission. Frustrated and confused, I then got into an argument about the meaning of a “fact” and how bizarre it was that even with the published rulings of British legal authorities, the BBC still would not let me say that Vote Leave broke the law or that unlawful activity occurred on Facebook’s watch.

NCA 突然放弃对俄罗斯干涉的调查，即使在收到俄罗斯大使馆与 Leave.EU 交易的证据后也是如此。后来，首相拒绝否认她已停止对英国脱欧的调查。英国议会并未对英国脱欧公投期间发生的作弊行为展开调查，我在美国国会作证时回答有关英国脱欧的问题所花的时间比在英国议会作证时所花的时间还多。尽管英国没有展开调查，但加拿大议会还是对 AIQ 在英国脱欧中的作用展开了调查，以帮助英国当局迫使 AIQ 作出答复，因为该公司通过留在加拿大成功避开了英国的管辖。

The NCA suddenly dropped its investigation of Russian interference, even after it received evidence of the Russian embassy’s dealings with Leave.EU. Later, the prime minister refused to deny that she had halted the investigation into Brexit. There was no parliamentary inquiry launched into the cheating that occurred during the Brexit referendum, and I ended up spending more time answering questions about Brexit in testimony before the United States Congress than in the British Parliament. Despite the lack of an inquiry in Britain, the Canadian Parliament opened its own inquiry into AIQ’s role in Brexit, to help the U.K. authorities compel answers from AIQ after the firm had successfully avoided its jurisdiction by remaining in Canada.

事实证明，作弊是一种很好的获胜策略，因为几乎没有什么后果。选举委员会后来承认，即使选举是利用非法数据或非法融资赢得的，结果仍然有效。Facebook 拒绝交出英国脱欧期间其平台上发生的事情的全部细节，也拒绝交出被非法活动分析和定位的选民数量或类型。马克·扎克伯格拒绝了三次在英国议会作证的请求，当代表六大洲近 10 亿公民的 15 个国家议会联合要求采访扎克伯格时，即使是通过电话，他仍然拒绝了——两次。似乎扎克伯格的时间比代表人类近七分之一的立法机构的时间更宝贵。Facebook 了解到，尽管媒体风暴肆虐，但仅仅无视世界议会实际上不会产生什么后果——该公司了解到它可以像一个主权国家一样行事，不受他们的审查。 Facebook 最终派其首席技术官迈克·斯科洛普夫 (Mike Schroepfer) 参加英国议会调查，但根据委员会随后的声明，他未能完全回答 40 个问题。但最能说明问题的或许是该公司缺乏悔意。当斯科洛普夫被问及 Facebook 向记者发出法律威胁的第一反应是否是欺凌行为时，这位 Facebook 首席技术官回答说：“我的理解是，这在英国很常见。”在议员们的质疑下，斯科洛普夫最终妥协并道歉，他说他“很抱歉记者们觉得我们试图阻止真相的曝光。”

It turns out cheating is a pretty good strategy to win, as there are very few consequences. The Electoral Commission later conceded that even if the vote was won with the benefit of illegal data or illegal financing, the result still stands. Facebook refused to hand over the full details of what happened on its platform during Brexit or the number or types of voters who were profiled and targeted by illegal campaigns. Mark Zuckerberg defied three requests to testify before the British Parliament, and when fifteen national parliaments, collectively representing almost one billion citizens across six continents, banded together in a joint request to interview Zuckerberg, even over the phone, he still turned them down—twice. It seemed that Zuckerberg’s time was more valuable than that of legislatures representing almost one seventh of the human race. Facebook learned that, despite the wrath of the media storm, there were actually very few consequences for simply ignoring the parliaments of the world—the company learned that it could behave like a sovereign state, immune from their scrutiny. Facebook eventually sent its chief technology officer, Mike Schroepfer, to the British parliamentary inquiry, but he failed to fully answer forty questions according to a subsequent statement by the committee. But what was perhaps most revealing about the performance was the lack of contrition on the part of the company. When Schroepfer was asked if Facebook’s first instinct to send journalists legal threats was bullying behavior, the Facebook CTO replied that “my understanding is that this is common practice in the U.K.” After being pressed by the incredulous MPs, Schroepfer acquiesced and finally apologized, saying that he was “sorry that journalists feel we are attempting to prevent the truth coming out.”

在所有可能在这一事件中受到正式惩罚的人中，令我难过的是，唯一受到制裁的人是 22 岁的脱欧派实习生达伦·格莱姆斯。尽管他的处境令人沮丧，但过时的立法意味着他个人要对选举违法行为负责。委员会对他个人处以 20,000 英镑的罚款，并将他的案件提交警方。他随后成功上诉，反对这一裁决，尽管选举委员会可能还会提出进一步上诉。脱欧派运动被罚款 61,000 英镑，其中一部分反映了他们拒绝与监管机构合作。脱欧派撤回了上诉，至少这项制裁仍然存在。

Of all the individuals who could have been formally punished in this saga, it was sad for me to see that one of the only people to face a sanction was Darren Grimes, the twenty-two-year old Vote Leave intern. As frustrating as his situation was, the archaic legislation meant that he was personally liable for electoral offenses. The commission levied a £20,000 fine against him personally and referred his case to the police. He subsequently succeeded in an appeal against that finding, although further appeals may yet be brought by the Electoral Commission. The campaign, Vote Leave, was fined £61,000, part of which reflected their refusal to cooperate with the regulator. Vote Leave dropped their appeal and that sanction, at least, remains.

看到格莱姆斯的遭遇令人难以置信，他的生活被别人策划的阴谋所摧毁。我们曾希望他能向桑尼、盖特森和我站出来，但格莱姆斯直到最后都为这个阴谋辩护。每次桑尼提起这个话题，他都会惊慌失措，崩溃不已，不愿接受自己被他信任的人利用的事实。格莱姆斯被设计成为他们的替罪羊，而脱欧派不可能要求比他更好的候选人了。尽管他为前任的行为辩护，但格莱姆斯是他们的俘虏。他们把他从一个有才华、自由​​、有艺术气质的学生变成了另类右翼事业的公众代言人，以换取他们支付法律费用。

It was incredibly hard to watch what happened to Grimes, who had his life torn up over a scheme that others had orchestrated. We had hoped that he would come forward with Sanni, Gettleson, and me, but Grimes defended the scheme until the very end. He panicked and broke down every time Sanni broached the topic, and did not want to accept that he had been used by the people he trusted. Grimes was set up to become their fall guy, and Vote Leave could not have asked for a better candidate. As much as he defended his old bosses’ actions, Grimes was their captive victim. They transformed him from a talented, liberal, and artistic student into a public shill for their alt-right causes, in exchange for help with legal fees.

报道公开几周后，在保守党顾问的压力下，沙米尔·桑尼被智库纳税人联盟解雇。该联盟后来向他的律师承认，他们非法解雇桑尼，以报复他所谓的“对英国民主神圣性的哲学信仰”。尽管帕金森在唐宁街 10 号的职位问题在议会中被多次提出，但帕金森保住了工作，没有因为利用首相新闻办公室曝光他的前实习生是同性恋而受到任何惩罚。而向大西洋两岸当局提供证据的马克·盖特森因对其举报的声誉担忧而被赶出了一家移动应用公司的新工作。

Several weeks after the story went public, Shahmir Sanni was terminated from his job at the TaxPayers’ Alliance, a think tank, after pressure from Conservative Party advisers. The alliance later admitted to his lawyers that they unlawfully fired Sanni in retaliation for what they called his “philosophical belief in the sanctity of British democracy.” Although the question of Parkinson’s job at 10 Downing Street was raised several times in Parliament, Parkinson kept his job and faced no consequences for using the press office of the prime minister to out his former intern as being gay. And Mark Gettleson, who provided evidence to authorities on both sides of the Atlantic, was pushed out of his new job at a mobile app company over reputational concerns about his whistleblowing.

2018 年 3 月，就在剑桥分析公司员工得知公司即将倒闭之前，亚历山大·尼克斯据称从公司账户中取出了 600 万英镑，阻止向其前员工发放遣散费。他后来在议会否认了这一点，称提取的资金是“用于交换未预订的服务”，他打算偿还部分资金。尼克斯被他的许多前商业伙伴和 Pall Mall 私人俱乐部的同行们所排斥，但作为一个超级富豪，他可以继续靠继承的遗产在伦敦荷兰公园的豪宅里生活。除了在议会举行的一些令人尴尬的公开听证会上，他指责“全球自由媒体”导致了公司的倒闭，他没有发生什么大事。

In March 2018, just before the staff at Cambridge Analytica learned about the impending demise of their firm, Alexander Nix allegedly emptied £6 million from company accounts, preventing severance pay from being issued to its former staff. He later denied this at Parliament, saying that the withdrawn money was “in exchange for unbooked services” and that he intended on paying some of it back. Nix was shunned by many of his former business partners and peers in the private clubs of Pall Mall, but, as a man of exceptional wealth, he could continue living off his inheritance in his mansion in London’s Holland Park. Nothing much happened to him beyond some cringeworthy public hearings in Parliament in which he blamed the “global liberal media” for his company’s demise.

在我揭露剑桥分析公司的故事后，布列塔尼·凯泽将自己重新定位为告密者，并聘请了一位公关经理开始安排采访。她参加了一次议会听证会，承认参与了尼日利亚项目，称剑桥分析公司可能保留了 Facebook 数据，并概述了她与朱利安·阿桑奇的关系。（后来，她曾到伦敦厄瓜多尔大使馆拜访过阿桑奇。）凯泽的证词结束后，尼克斯立即给她发短信说：“干得好，布列塔尼，这看起来相当艰难，但你做得还不错。;-)。”第二天，她飞往纽约，召开新闻发布会，宣传她的新数据项目，该项目推出了一种名为“价值互联网全账本”的东西，显然是为了释放我们的“数据自由”。

After I came forward with the Cambridge Analytica story, Brittany Kaiser rebranded herself as a whistleblower and hired a PR manager to start booking interviews. She attended a parliamentary hearing in which she admitted to being involved in the Nigeria project, said that Cambridge Analytica likely retained Facebook data, and outlined her relationship with Julian Assange. (Later, it would emerge that she visited Assange in the Ecuadorian embassy in London.) Immediately after Kaiser’s testimony concluded, Nix texted her, “Well done Britt, it looked quite tough and you did ok. ;-).” The next day, she flew to New York and held a press conference to plug her new data project, which launched something called the Internet of Value Omniledger, apparently intended to unleash our “data freedom.”

和凯撒一样，剑桥分析公司的其他几位前高管也创办了自己的数据公司。CA 前产品主管马特·奥茨科夫斯基 (Matt Oczkowski) 创立了一家名为 Data Propria（拉丁语意为“个人数据”）的公司，并带来了 CA 的首席数据科学家大卫·威尔金森 (David Wilkinson)。该公司表示，它将专注于针对“动机行为触发因素”，并已开始为唐纳德·特朗普 (Donald Trump) 的 2020 年美国总统竞选工作。剑桥分析公司前董事总经理马克·特恩布尔 (Mark Turnbull) 与该公司的前合伙人之一艾哈迈德·阿尔哈提卜 (Ahmad Al-Khatib) 联手成立了 Auspex International，他们将其描述为一家“以道德为基础”的“精品地缘政治咨询公司”。

Like Kaiser, several other former executives from Cambridge Analytica went on to found their own data companies. CA’s former head of product Matt Oczkowski founded a firm called Data Propria (Latin for “Personal Data”) and brought CA’s chief data scientist David Wilkinson with him. The firm has stated that it will focus on targeting “motivational behavioral triggers” and had already started work for the 2020 U.S. presidential campaign of Donald Trump. Mark Turnbull, the former managing director of Cambridge Analytica, joined up with one of the firm’s former associates, Ahmad Al-Khatib, to set up Auspex International, which they described as an “ethically based” and “boutique geopolitical consultancy.”

我最大的遗憾是杰夫·西尔维斯特。我甚至无法用语言形容，当我得知他和 AIQ 所做的事情时，我是多么的恼火和沮丧。他是我十几岁时的导师，也是一开始帮助我进入政界的人。他支持我、鼓励我，培养我的才能，让我成长。我仍然无法理解他怎么能让自己继续为如此错误、如此殖民、如此非法、如此邪恶的事情工作。我试图和他谈谈，我告诉他要对《卫报》坦诚相待，但我失败了。他本可以坦白。他本可以配合调查。他知道 AIQ 所做的事情是错的。他知道他的工作对整个国家的未来和数百万人的权利有着深远的影响。在深厚的友谊和举报犯罪之间做出选择是一种折磨，因为无论你选择什么，你都会感到深深的悔恨。但我别无选择，只能背叛他。在《卫报》向所有被告方发出答辩权信函的那天，我整天都在为发生的事情而苦恼，等待着任何消息。当西尔维斯特收到信时，他终于知道了我的选择，他开始意识到即将发生在他身上的事情。他给我发的最后一条短信只是“哇”。

My biggest regret was Jeff Silvester. I can’t even begin to put into words how maddening and disheartening it was for me to sit with the knowledge about what he and AIQ had done. He was my mentor when I was a teenager and the man who helped me enter politics in the first place. He had supported me, encouraged me, and nurtured my talents so I could grow. And I just still cannot understand how he could have let himself continue working for something so wrong, so colonial, so illegal, and so evil. I tried to talk to him, and I told him to be open with The Guardian, but I failed. He could have come clean. He could have cooperated with the investigations. He knew what AIQ had done was wrong. He knew that the effects of his work had profound consequences for the future of an entire nation and the rights of millions of people. Having to choose between a deep friendship and reporting a crime is torture, because no matter what you choose, you’ll feel profound regret. But I had no choice but to betray him. On the day The Guardian sent out the right-to-reply letters to all of the accused parties, I agonized over what was happening the entire day, waiting to hear anything. When he received his letter, Silvester finally learned of the choice I had made, and he began to realize what was about to happen to him. His final text message to me was simply “Wow.”

走进我第一次参加的议会听证会，听着相机快速按下快门的声音和大声提问的声音，我感到意外的轻松。艾伦坐在我身后，偶尔递给我一些法律建议。我们准备了几个小时，仔细审查了证据，我享有议会特权的特殊保护——这意味着我说的任何话都不能用于民事或刑事诉讼。听证会引起了全世界立法界的关注，DCMS 委员会主席达米安·柯林斯开始组织 15 个国家议会举行国际联合听证会。下议院进行了辩论，跨党派支持监管社交媒体。几个月来，英国似乎在挑战硅谷的权力方面处于领先地位。

Walking into my first parliamentary hearing, to the sound of rapidly clicking cameras and shouted questions, I felt unexpectedly at ease. Allen sat behind me, occasionally passing me notes of legal advice. We had prepared for hours, going through the evidence, and I had the special protection of parliamentary privilege—meaning that nothing I said could be used in civil or criminal proceedings. The hearing caused a wave of legislative attention around the world, and the DCMS committee chair, Damian Collins, began organizing international joint hearings among fifteen national parliaments. There were debates on the floor of the House of Commons and cross-party support for regulating social media. For a couple of months, it seemed as if Britain was leading the way in challenging the power of Silicon Valley.

但随后，在 2018 年 10 月，剑桥分析公司丑闻震惊 Facebook 七个月后，该公司宣布将进行一项重大招聘：为世界各国政府任命一位新的首席辩护人。Facebook 的新任全球公关专家将是前自由民主党领袖和英国副首相尼克·克莱格——我在 LDHQ 工作期间曾为他工作。讽刺的是，克莱格曾发誓宁愿入狱也不愿在试点国家身份数据库中登记。但他也是在担任副首相期间，在联合政府中违背了一系列关键承诺后，实际上成为了五年道歉之旅的人。我越想越觉得，这对搭档简直是天作之合。扎克伯格和克莱格的职业生涯都是在违背原则的基础上建立起来的，他们都在忽视对用户或选民的承诺后，遭受了公众信任的灾难性打击，而且两人都在 2010 年失去了风采。克莱格的任命宣布后，第四频道要求我在镜头前发表评论，我当时唯一能想到的就是“这简直是胡说八道”。他们播出了这番评论，尽管声音有点刺耳。

But then, in October 2018, seven months after the Cambridge Analytica scandal rocked Facebook, the company announced that it was making a major hire: a new apologist in chief to world governments. Facebook’s new global spin doctor was going to be Nick Clegg, the former leader of the Liberal Democrats and deputy prime minister of the United Kingdom—the same man I used to work for in my days at LDHQ. Ironically, it was Clegg who had once vowed that he would go to prison before registering in a pilot national identity database. But he was also the guy whose tenure as deputy prime minister became in effect a five-year apology tour after he broke a host of key promises in the coalition government. And the more I thought about it, the more the pairing seemed to be a match made in heaven. Both Zuckerberg and Clegg had built their careers on compromising their principles, both suffered catastrophic blows of public confidence after they ignored their promises to users or voters, and both stopped being cool in 2010. When Channel 4 asked me for comment on camera after Clegg’s appointment was announced, all I could think to say was “This is bullshit.” They aired the comment, albeit with a bleep.

2019年5月24日，英国首相特雷莎·梅宣布辞职，保守党内部由此展开领导人角逐。英国首相中期辞职的惯例是，女王陛下无需举行大选，直接任命执政党新领导人为新首相。这意味着，保守党内部的幕后人员、捐款人和有偿党员可以绕过选举，在他们之间选择谁来领导英国。7月23日，保守党党内投票通过，决定新首相人选为前外交大臣、无协议脱欧（通常称为“硬脱欧”）的主要倡导者鲍里斯·约翰逊。在组建新政府时，约翰逊任命其前脱欧派同事多姆·卡明斯成为其在唐宁街10号的新任高级顾问之一。卡明斯是公投作弊运动的负责人，而约翰逊现在正利用公投作为不惜一切代价脱欧的“民主”基础。但这一事实似乎并不重要。就在卡明斯被任命的几个月前，他无视议会命令，拒绝出庭回答有关欧盟公投作弊和传播虚假新闻的问题，因此被判藐视议会。尽管卡明斯是极少数被下议院一致投票正式谴责的人之一，但议会权力的界限受到了考验，因为卡明斯似乎没有受到什么惩罚。在新的约翰逊政府中，将与卡明斯一起担任英国财政部新任特别顾问的是马修·埃利奥特，他曾是脱欧投票组织的首席执行官，也是纳税人联盟的联合创始人，该游说团体因桑尼的举报而解雇了他。这看起来像是脱欧派接管了英国政府。在下议院的第一次首相问答环节中，反对党成员问约翰逊 2016 年 12 月与剑桥分析公司首席执行官亚历山大·尼克斯会面时讨论了什么，当时他担任英国外交大臣。他的回答很简单：“我不知道。”

On May 24, 2019, Prime Minister Theresa May announced her intention to resign, triggering an internal leadership race within the Conservative Party. In the United Kingdom, if a prime minister resigns mid-term, the convention is that Her Majesty the Queen appoints the new leader of the governing party as the new prime minister without a general election. This means that the internal party back-roomers, donors, and paid members of the party can bypass an election and choose among themselves who shall lead Britain. On July 23, the members of the Conservative Party decided that the new prime minister would be Boris Johnson, the former foreign secretary and lead advocate for leaving the European Union without any negotiated exit deal (often referred to as a “hard Brexit”). When forming his new government, Johnson appointed Dom Cummings, his former colleague from Vote Leave, to become one of his new senior advisers in 10 Downing Street. It did not seem to matter that Cummings was the director of a campaign that cheated during the very referendum Johnson was now using as the “democratic” basis for leaving the European Union at almost any cost. Only a few months prior to his appointment, Cummings was found to be in contempt of Parliament after ignoring an order to appear before Parliament to answer questions about cheating and the dissemination of fake news in the EU referendum. Although Cummings is one of only a handful of people ever to be formally admonished by a unanimous vote of the House of Commons, the limits of parliamentary authority were tested, at it appears there were very few consequences for Cummings. And slated to join Cummings in the new Johnson government as a new special adviser to Her Majesty’s Treasury was Matthew Elliott, the former chief executive of Vote Leave and co-founder of the TaxPayers’ Alliance, the lobbying group that fired Sanni in retaliation for his whistleblowing. It looked like a Vote Leave takeover of the British government. During his first Prime Minister’s Questions session in the House of Commons, Johnson was asked by opposition members about what was discussed in December 2016, when he met with Cambridge Analytica’s CEO, Alexander Nix, when he was Britain’s foreign secretary. His response was simply “I have no idea.”

在剑桥分析公司内部，我近距离目睹了贪婪、权力、种族主义和殖民主义。我看到了亿万富翁在想要按照自己的形象塑造世界时会做出什么行为。我看到了我们社会中最怪异、最黑暗的角落。作为一名告密者，我看到了大公司会采取什么措施来保护自己的利润。我看到了人们为了方便的叙述不惜一切代价掩盖他人犯下的罪行。我看到挥舞着旗帜的“爱国者”对一代人最重要的宪法问题上法治的破坏视而不见。但我也看到了所有关心并反击失败体系的人。我看到《卫报》、 《纽约时报》和第四频道的记者都在努力见证剑桥分析公司犯下的罪行和 Facebook 的无能。我看到我出色的律师克服了对我发出的每一个威胁。我看到了那些来支持我而不求回报的人们的善良。我看到位于英格兰威姆斯洛教区小镇的小型信息专员办公室利用其所能的权力对付一家美国科技巨头——最终对 Facebook 处以法律允许的最高数据泄露罚款。

Inside Cambridge Analytica, I saw what greed, power, racism, and colonialism looks like up close. I saw how billionaires behave when they want to shape the world in their image. I saw the most bizarre, dark niches of our society. As a whistleblower, I saw what big companies will do to protect their profits. I saw the lengths to which people will go to cover up crimes that others committed for the sake of a convenient narrative. I saw flag-waving “patriots” turn a blind eye to the defacement of the rule of law on the most important constitutional question of a generation. But I also saw all the people who cared and who fought back against a failing system. I saw journalists at The Guardian, The New York Times, and Channel 4 all working to bear witness to the crimes committed by Cambridge Analytica and the incompetence of Facebook. I saw my brilliant lawyers outmaneuver every threat that was thrown my way. I saw the kindness of people who came to support me and asked for nothing in return. I saw the tiny Information Commissioner’s Office, based in the parish town of Wilmslow, England, use what powers it could to take on an American technology giant––eventually issuing Facebook the maximum fine allowable in law for data breaches.

我看到国会议员们都很关心并渴望了解我们现在所处的美好新世界。当我离开众议院情报委员会听证会时，我和我的律师以及桑尼走出 SCIF，与委员会成员握手，然后由众议员亚当·希夫和他的助手护送到安全入口。他们很客气，感谢我飞到美国帮助他们了解剑桥分析公司以及社交媒体平台对美国选举带来的新风险。这将是我在美国最后一次作证，但一切似乎都远未解决。

And I saw members of Congress who were concerned and eager to learn about the brave new world we now find ourselves in. As I left the House Intelligence Committee hearing, emerging from the SCIF with my lawyers and Sanni, I shook hands with the members of the committee and was walked to the security entrance by Congressman Adam Schiff and his aides. They were gracious, and they thanked me for flying to America to help them understand not only Cambridge Analytica but the emerging risks to American elections posed by social media platforms. It would be the last of my testimonies in the United States, but everything felt far from resolved.

2019年7月24日，美国联邦贸易委员会对Facebook处以创纪录的50亿美元民事罚款，同一天美国证券交易委员会也发布通知，将对其处以1亿美元额外罚款。监管机构发现，Facebook不仅未能保护用户隐私，还通过发布虚假声明误导公众和记者，声称没有发现任何不当行为的证据，而事实上确实有。这笔罚款是美国政府对任何违法行为开出的最高罚款之一。事实上，这是有史以来对一家美国公司因侵犯消费者隐私权开出的最高罚款，是全球有史以来最高隐私或数据安全罚款的20倍。然而，投资者仍将此视为好消息。这一消息实际上使Facebook的股价上涨了3.6%，市场心照不宣地承认，即使是法律也无法阻止这些科技巨头的成长。

On July 24, 2019, the Federal Trade Commission levied a record $5 billion civil penalty against Facebook, and the same day the Securities and Exchange Commission issued notice of an additional $100 million fine. The regulators found that not only did Facebook fail to protect users’ privacy, the company misled the public and journalists by issuing false statements that it had seen no evidence of wrongdoing when it in fact had. The fine was one of the largest imposed by the U.S. government for any violation. In fact, this was the largest ever fine issued to an American company for violating consumers’ privacy rights, and was twenty times greater than the largest privacy or data security penalty ever imposed worldwide. However, it was nonetheless seen by investors as good news. The news actually increased Facebook’s share value by 3.6 percent, with the market tacitly recognizing that even the law cannot stop the growth of these technology giants.

如果我不承认我现在比开始这段旅程之前更加愤世嫉俗，那我就是在撒谎。但这并没有让我更加听天由命。如果说有什么不同的话，那就是它让我变得更加激进。我曾经相信我们现有的系统大体上是有效的。我曾经认为有人拿着一个计划等着解决剑桥分析公司这样的问题。我错了。我们的系统已经崩溃，我们的法律不起作用，我们的监管机构很弱，我们的政府不了解正在发生的事情，我们的技术正在篡夺我们的民主。

I would be lying if I didn’t admit that I am far more cynical now than before I started this journey. But it hasn’t made me more resigned. If anything, it has made me even more radical. I used to believe that the systems we have broadly work. I used to think that there was someone waiting with a plan who could solve a problem like Cambridge Analytica. I was wrong. Our system is broken, our laws don’t work, our regulators are weak, our governments don’t understand what’s happening, and our technology is usurping our democracy.

所以我必须学会找到自己的声音，以便说出我所看到的事情。我充满希望，因为我已经看到了当我们找到自己的声音时会发生什么。当《卫报》报道这个故事时，许多记者将其视为一系列阴谋论。硅谷的科技兄弟们嘲笑他们应该受到任何审查的想法。华盛顿特区和威斯敏斯特的政客们称这个故事为小众。这需要《卫报》艺术与文化版块和其周日报纸《观察家》的一群女性的坚持，这篇轰动一时的报道就刊登在那里。它引起了信息专员办公室和选举委员会调查女性的注意。它需要两名移民同性恋告密者和一位坚定的女律师支持。这个故事需要敬业的女性、移民和同性恋者的领导，才能点燃公众对硅谷谨慎的殖民力量以及他们创造的包围我们的数字技术的觉醒。我们都坚持发出自己的声音，直到世界最终能够看到我们所看到的一切。

So I had to learn to find my voice in order to speak up about what I saw was happening. I am hopeful, because I have seen what happens when we find our voices. When The Guardian took on this story, many journalists saw it as a series of conspiracy theories. The tech bros of Silicon Valley laughed at the notion that they should be subjected to any scrutiny. Politicos in D.C. and Westminster called the story niche. It took the persistence of a team of women at The Guardian’s Arts & Culture section and its Sunday paper, The Observer, where the blockbuster story appeared. It took the attention of the women who led the investigations at the Information Commissioner’s Office and the Electoral Commission. And it took two immigrant queer whistleblowers backed by a steadfast woman lawyer. This story took the leadership of dedicated women, immigrants, and queers to ignite a public awakening about the discreet colonizing power of Silicon Valley and the digital technologies they have created to surround us. We all persisted in raising our voices until the world could finally see what we saw.

作为同性恋者，你从小就知道自己的存在不符合常态。我们将自己隐藏在柜子里，保持不为人知的身份，并隐藏自己的真相，直到无法忍受。生活在柜子里是痛苦的。这是一种对自己施加的情感暴力，我们这样做是为了不让周围的人感到不舒服。同性恋者深知权力体系，而出柜是我们讲真话的变革行为。在出柜的过程中，我们意识到向那些可能不想听的人说出真相的力量。我们拒绝他们的安慰，让他们倾听。为什么这么多同性恋者在 Pride 上吹口哨？为了引起你的注意。为了宣布我们将不再隐藏自己。为了反抗强权的霸权。而且，就像许多在我之前出现的同性恋者一样，我不得不接受自己的真相，并接受我永远无法成为社会所认为的完美男人这一不可避免的失败。

Growing up queer, you learn early in life that your existence is outside the norm. We incubate ourselves inside a closet, remaining unknown, and hide our truth until it becomes unbearable. Living in a closet is painful. It is an act of emotional violence we inflict upon ourselves so as not to discomfort those around us. Queers understand systems of power intimately, and coming out is our transformative act of truth telling. In coming out, we realize the power of speaking our truth to those who may not want to hear it. We reject their comfort and make them listen. Why do so many gays blow whistles at Pride? To get your attention. To announce that we will no longer hide ourselves. To defy hegemonies of the powerful. And, like so many queers who came before me, I had to accept my own truth and come to terms with my inevitable failure to ever become society’s notion of a perfect man.

我是一名同性恋告密者，这是我第二次出柜。他们让我遵守保密协议，迫使我躲进一个新的秘密柜子，过着隐瞒自己不舒服的知识和令人反感的真相的生活。两年来，我的生活一直遵循着大公司强加给我的个性化“不问不说”政策。如果我希望避免任何后果，我就被禁止向他人透露自己的身份，而我成了他们的小秘密。但和其他出柜的同性恋者一样，我是一个真相揭露者，我选择直言不讳地揭露这些不舒服的真相，不再隐瞒，不再成为他们的秘密，面对摆在我面前的后果，向全世界大声说出我所知道的一切。

I am a queer whistleblower, and this was my second coming out. Subjecting me to covenants of nondisclosure, I was forced into a new closet, to live in hiding with my uncomfortable knowledge and objectionable truths. I lived my life for two years with a personalized don’t ask, don’t tell policy imposed upon me by powerful companies. If I hoped to avoid any consequences, I was forbidden to reveal myself to others, and I became their little secret. But like other out queers, I am a truth teller, and I chose to be indiscreet with those uncomfortable truths, to stop hiding, to stop being their secret, to face the consequences before me, and to shout out to the world what I know.

衣柜不是一个实际的空间；而是我们作为酷儿内化并遵守的社会结构。衣柜是一个容器，它的界限是由想要控制你的行为和自我表现的其他人强加的。衣柜是看不见的，它是默认的，而不是自愿的，它是为了让别人创造出一个更容易接受的你——为他们的利益，而不是你的利益。在衣柜里长大意味着逐渐学习如何在社会中生存——哪些动作、语气、表情、观点或表达的愿望超越了强加给你的社会界限的规范。酷儿孩子们一点一点地学习如何约束自己的行为，直到它几乎成为第二天性，直到他们摆脱困境。这些变化是如此缓慢，以至于有时你甚至没有注意到你的行为发生了多大的改变，直到有一天，你决定离开衣柜。而出柜的一部分就是接受这个柜子里为你构建的很多东西，意识到你曾经的很多东西都是在你不知情或不同意的情况下强加给你的，这可能会很痛苦。柜子是一个默许社会以换取通过的地方，但它也是一个愤怒不断积累的地方，因为那些界限和定义会慢慢让你窒息，直到你无法忍受留在监狱里。

The closet is not a literal space; it is a social structure that we as queer people internalize and conform to. The closet is a container whose boundaries are imposed by others who want to control how you behave and present yourself. The closet is invisible, and it is placed upon you by default, never by choice, for others to create a more palatable version of who you are—for their benefit, not yours. Growing up in a closet means incrementally learning how to pass in society—which movements, tones, expressions, perspectives, or uttered desires transgress the norms of those social boundaries imposed upon you. Queer kids learn, little by little, how to restrain their behavior until it becomes almost second nature, until they pass. So incremental are these changes that sometimes you do not even notice how much you have changed your behavior until, one day, you decide to leave that closet. And part of coming out is coming to terms with how much of you has been constructed for you inside that closet, and it can be painful to realize how much of who you once were was imposed upon you without your awareness or consent. The closet is a place of acquiescing to society in exchange for passing, but it is also a place where rage builds as those boundaries and definitions slowly suffocate you until you cannot bear to remain inside that prison.

出柜意味着拒绝别人强加给我们的定义。定义我们身份的能力非常强大，无论对这种权力的威胁是以社交壁橱还是算法壁橱的形式出现，我们都必须抵制任何人或任何事物，它们试图为自己的利益定义或划分我们的身份。硅谷通过为每个人构建这些个性化空间，冒着创造新的身份霸权的风险。这些空间只不过是定义我们身份、表达和行为的新壁橱。在收集和处理你的数据自我时，算法会决定如何定义你、如何对你进行分类、你应该注意什么以及谁应该注意你。但是，在算法定义你以代表你真正是谁和算法定义你以创造一个它认为你应该成为谁的自我实现预言之间，有一条细线。

Coming out is our rejection of the definitions that have been imposed upon us by someone else. The ability to define our identities is extremely powerful, and whether the threats to that power take the form of a social closet or an algorithmic one, we must resist anyone or anything that seeks the power to define or classify who we are for their benefit. Silicon Valley risks creating a new hegemony of identity through its construction of these personalized spaces for each person. And these spaces are nothing but a new closet to define our identities, expressions, and behaviors. In harvesting and processing your data self, algorithms make decisions on how to define you, how to classify you, what you should notice, and who should notice you. But there is a fine line between an algorithm defining you in order to represent who you really are and an algorithm defining you to create a self-fulfilling prophecy of who it thinks you should become.

人们已经开始改变自己，以适应机器对他们应该成为什么样的人的印象。我们中的一些人在社交媒体上精心策划自己，以增加粉丝的参与度，以至于我们的真实身份和我们在网上的表现变得混乱和混杂。当这些粉丝看到足够多的这些精心策划的身份时，他们中的一些人开始讨厌自己是谁或自己的长相，他们节食以符合现在围绕着他们的新标准。其他人点击算法推荐给他们的链接，参与其中，并越来越深地陷入个性化的兔子洞，直到他们的世界观在不知不觉中发生了变化。我们在网上购买的东西现在是基于我们的个人资料策划的，而这个个人资料是由其他东西定义的 。我们作为工作、保险、信贷或抵押贷款申请人的价值现在是基于我们的个人资料，而这个个人资料是由其他东西定义的。我们观看的节目和我们发现的音乐现在都是根据我们的个人资料预先选择的，而这个个人资料是由其他东西定义的。随着我们走向物理世界和数字世界不可避免的融合，我们的生活将越来越多地不再由我们自己而是由其他东西来定义。因此，如果我们要抵制未来的生活被其他东西所定义，我们可能都需要走出自己的小圈子，否则就会有人或某物把我们关在里面。

People are already morphing themselves to fit a machine’s idea of who they should be. Some of us are curating ourselves on social media to increase our follower engagement, to the point that who we really are and how we present online become confused and conflated. And when those followers see enough of these curated identities, some of them begin to hate who they are or how they look, and they starve their bodies to conform to a new standard that now surrounds them. Others click on links recommended to them by algorithms, engaging with that content, and get drawn further and further down the rabbit hole of personalization until their worldview changes without their realizing it. What we buy online is now curated based on a profile of us, defined by something else. Our worthiness as job, insurance, credit, or mortgage applicants is now based on a profile of us, defined by something else. The shows we watch and the music we discover are now preselected based on a profile of us, defined by something else. As we move toward the inevitable merger of our physical and digital worlds, more and more of our lives will start to become defined not by us but by something else. And so, if we are ever to resist our future lives being defined by something else, we may all need to come out of our closets before someone or something locks us inside.

—

2019 年 5 月 23 日，我早上6 点就醒了，这对我来说早得有些过分。房间明亮温暖，朝阳透过窗帘照进来。我不喜欢早起，所以我盯着天花板看了一会儿，然后瞥了一眼窗外，看到街上开始有了人。一个我约会的男人留宿了一夜，所以我不得不小心翼翼地从床上溜下来，以免发出声音。那天是英国的投票日，可能是有史以来最后一次欧洲议会选举。我的投票卡上写着投票站将于早上7 点开放，所以我想偷偷溜出去，跑到当地的社区中心，我所在选区的投票正在那里进行。

ON MAY 23, 2019, I woke up at 6 A.M., unusually early for me. My room was bright and warming up, the sunrise peeking through my curtains. I hate getting up early, so I stared at the ceiling for a bit before glancing out the window to see life emerging on the street. A guy I had been seeing stayed the night, so I had to slip out of bed carefully in order not to make a sound. It was polling day in Britain, in what was potentially the last-ever European Parliament election. My polling card said polls would open at 7 A.M., so I wanted to sneak out to run to the local community center where voting in my local ward was taking place.

我迈着略显夸张的步伐，悄无声息地走到梳妆台前，抓起牛仔裤和一件 T 恤，它们堆在地板上。这件 T 恤是英国设计师凯瑟琳·哈姆内特送给我的礼物。柔软的黑色棉布上印着醒目的白色字母，上面写着：现在进行第二次公投！ 如果今天我要穿什么，那应该是这件 T 恤，我想。我伸手到抽屉里拿出手机，手机一恢复信号，就开始嗡嗡作响，有消息传来。

Taking slightly exaggerated steps to silently glide over to my dresser, I grabbed my jeans and a T-shirt, lying in a heap on the floor. The shirt was a gift from the English designer Katharine Hamnett. Soft black cotton with bold white letters, it simply read, SECOND REFERENDUM NOW! If I wear anything today, it should be this T-shirt, I thought. I reached over into my drawer to pull out my phone, and once it regained signal, it began buzzing with messages.

哦，该死，我心想。我转过身，发现我吵醒了他。他趴在枕头上呻吟着，问我为什么这么早起床，我只是说因为我想去投票。他坐起来，笑着翻了个白眼，问今天对我这样的人来说是不是像圣诞节一样。我告诉他不，我想早点去，在党派投票观察员出现并开始统计谁在投票之前。我不想再与英国独立党或脱欧派发生争执。我被称为叛徒并被推上街头，但我不想被阻止投票。

Oh shit, I thought. I turned back to see I had woken him up. Groaning into a pillow, he asked why I was up so early and I simply said because I want to go vote. He sat up and smirked, rolling his eyes, asking if today was like Christmas for people like me. I told him no, that I wanted to go early, before the party poll watchers show up and start tallying who is voting. I didn’t want to get into another fight with UKIP or Brexiteers. I have been called a traitor and pushed into the streets, but I did not want to be stopped from voting.

这感觉不像圣诞节，一点也不令人兴奋。这是悲伤的一天，因为我心里知道，我不会参加真正的选举——这只是英国退出欧盟前的最后一场演出。尽管选举委员会裁定脱欧公投失败，国家犯罪局正在进行调查，议会有证词，《卫报》连续数周揭露唐宁街内部的掩盖行为，但政府仍然决心通过欺骗和欺诈赢得授权退出欧盟。

It did not feel like Christmas, and it wasn’t exciting at all. It was a sad day, because I knew in my heart that I wasn’t going to be taking part in a real election—it was all part of a final performance before Britain was scheduled to leave the European Union. Despite the Electoral Commission’s ruling against Vote Leave, an ongoing National Crime Agency investigation, testimonies at Parliament, and a weeks-long exposé in The Guardian about the cover-up inside Downing Street, the government was nonetheless determined to exit the European Union with a mandate won through cheating and fraud.

我的邮箱里堆满了传单和宣传资料。我几乎以为会收到来自 Arron Banks 或 Leave.EU 的疯狂传单，比如卷在俄罗斯伏特加酒瓶里的脱欧传单，因为他们非常喜欢戏弄我和《卫报》记者 Carole Cadwalladr。但不是，那只是普通的传单。绿党。自由民主党。英国独立党。出于某种原因，没有来自保守党或工党的传单。我打开了自由民主党的传单，想着他们现在正在使用什么数据，以及他们是否向我发送了信息。看起来不像。那只是另一张垃圾传单。

My postbox was filled with leaflets and literature. I was half expecting to receive something mad from Arron Banks or Leave.EU, like a Brexit leaflet rolled into a Russian vodka bottle, as they were so fond of trolling me and Guardian journalist Carole Cadwalladr. But no, it was just regular leaflets. Greens. Lib Dems. UKIP. Nothing from the Tories or Labour, for some reason. I opened up the Lib Dem one and I thought about what data they were using now and whether they had targeted me with a message. It didn’t look like it. It was just another crap leaflet.

我抬头看了看大厅里监视我的安全摄像头，然后离开了。我出发了，走过我家附近的几条街道。古老的乔治亚式排屋散布着偶尔出现的公寓楼。天气格外明亮和阳光明媚。早晨的空气清新而令人精神振奋。我拐进一条大街，那里的商店还没有开门，只有一家当地的咖啡店。我走进去，点了一杯加了一点豆奶的咖啡。在等待的时候，我看着咖啡馆里的每个人，都站着看着他们的手机，都在滚动、关注和浏览内容。我站在他们旁边，但他们都沉浸在自己的数字世界中。说实话，在我被禁止之前，我也做过同样的事情。但是没有社交媒体，除了我几乎不使用的推特账户外，我发现自己滚动得更少，发帖更少，拍照也更少了。我不再花几个小时和其他人一起通过我的屏幕。我可能生活在这些数字世界之外，但至少我已经更多地活在这个世界里了。拿了咖啡后，我离开，沿着一条绿树成荫的街道走到社区中心。树上挂着一块巨大的白色标语牌，上面用黑色字母写着“投票站”。我保持距离，四处张望，但还没有哪个政党的人在外面闲逛。于是，我走进去，沿着标语牌穿过走廊，走进一个简朴的房间，里面散落着纸板投票亭和没有橡皮擦的小铅笔。

I looked up at the security camera watching me in the lobby and left. I set out, walking through a couple of streets in my neighborhood. Old Georgian row houses interspersed with the occasional block of flats. It was extremely bright and sunny. The morning air was fresh and invigorating. I turned onto a high street, where the shops were not yet open, save for a local coffee shop. I walked in and ordered a coffee with a splash of soy milk. As I waited, I looked at everyone in the café, standing and looking at their phones, all scrolling, following and engaging with content. I stood beside them, but they were all off in their own digital worlds. To be honest, I used to do the same thing before my ban. But without social media, aside from a Twitter account I barely use, I have found myself scrolling less, posting less, and taking fewer photos of things. I no longer spend hours being alone together with other people through my screen. I may live outside these digital worlds, but at least I have come to be more present in this world. After grabbing my coffee, I left and walked down a tree-lined street before reaching the community center. Tied to the trees were large white placards with black letters that read POLLING STATION. I kept my distance and peered around, but no one from any of the parties was loitering outside yet. So I walked inside and followed the signs down a corridor and into a simple, unadorned room scattered with cardboard voting booths and tiny pencils without erasers.

投票站工作人员看了看我，问了我的名字。她翻看纸质名单，拿起铅笔划掉。就这样——没有身份证，没有电子设备。她递给我一张一米长的选票，用于选举伦敦欧洲议会议员代表团。这张纸只比报纸厚一点，但当我拿着它时，我想到投票看起来是多么的体力活，然而网上有如此多复杂的活动，最终却变成了在薄纸上划一个X 的简单动作。我把选票扔进了投票箱，希望这不是最后一次。

The polling station clerk looked at me and asked for my name. She flipped through the paper list and took a pencil to cross it out. That was it—no IDs, no electronics. She handed me what seemed like a meter-long ballot for the election of London’s delegation of members of the European Parliament. The paper was only slightly thicker than newspaper, but as I held it, I thought about how physical the act of voting seems, and yet so much sophisticated activity online leads up to this simple act of crossing an X on a thin piece of paper. I dropped the ballot into the ballot box and hoped it would not be the last time.

结语

关于监管：致立法者的一封信​​

ON REGULATION: A NOTE TO LEGISLATORS

如果我们要防止另一个剑桥分析公司攻击我们的民间机构，我们必须设法解决它孵化的有缺陷的环境。长期以来，世界各国的国会和议会都陷入了一种错误的观点，即“法律无法跟上技术的步伐”。科技界喜欢重复这种观点，因为它往往会让立法者感到自己太愚蠢或与时代脱节，无法挑战他们的权力。但法律可以跟上技术的步伐，就像它跟上医药、土木工程、食品标准、能源和无数其他高科技领域的步伐一样。立法者不需要了解新抗癌药物中分子异构体的化学性质来创建有效的药物审查流程，也不需要了解高压电线中铜的导电性来制定有效的绝缘安全标准。我们不期望我们的立法者拥有任何其他领域的专业技术知识，因为我们将技术监督责任下放给了监管机构。监管之所以有效，是因为我们信任那些比我们更了解的人，他们会以公共安全的守护者的身份来调查行业和创新。 “监管”可能是最不吸引人的词语之一，它让人联想到那些拿着珍贵清单的无名公务员，我们总是会争论他们不完善的规则的细节，但尽管如此，安全监管通常还是有效的。当你在杂货店买食物、去看医生或登上飞机在数千英尺的高空飞行时，你感到安全吗？大多数人会说是的。你是否觉得你需要考虑其中的化学或工程问题？可能不需要。

If we are to prevent another Cambridge Analytica from attacking our civil institutions, we must seek to address the flawed environment in which it incubated. For too long the congresses and parliaments of the world have fallen for a mistaken view that somehow “the law cannot keep up with technology.” The technology sector loves to parrot this idea, as it tends to make legislators feel too stupid or out of touch to challenge their power. But the law can keep up with technology, just as it has with medicines, civil engineering, food standards, energy, and countless other highly technical fields. Legislators do not need to understand the chemistry of molecular isomers inside a new cancer drug to create effective drug review processes, nor do they need to know about the conductivity of copper in high-voltage wiring to create effective insulation safety standards. We do not expect our legislators to have expert technical knowledge in any other sector because we devolve technical oversight responsibility to regulators. Regulation works because we trust people who know better than we do to investigate industries and innovations as the guardians of public safety. “Regulation” may be one of the least sexy words, evoking an image of faceless jobsworths with their treasured checklists, and we will always argue about the details of their imperfect rules, but nonetheless safety regulation generally works. When you buy food in the grocery store or visit your doctor or step onto an airplane and hurtle thousands of feet in the air, do you feel safe? Most would say yes. Do you ever feel like you need to think about the chemistry or engineering of any of it? Probably not.

科技公司不应该被允许快速发展和破坏现状。道路限速是有原因的：为了人们的安全而放慢速度。制药实验室或航空航天公司在未通过安全和功效标准的情况下无法将新创新推向市场，那么为什么数字系统可以在未经任何审查的情况下发布呢？为什么我们应该允许大型科技公司进行大规模人体实验，直到发现它们变成了一个难以管理的大问题？我们已经看到激进化、大规模枪击、种族清洗、饮食失调、睡眠模式的改变以及对我们民主的大规模攻击，所有这些都直接受到社交媒体的影响。这些可能是无形的生态系统，但对受害者的伤害却是有形的。

Tech companies should not be allowed to move fast and break things. Roads have speed limits for a reason: to slow things down for the safety of people. A pharmaceutical lab or an aerospace company cannot bring new innovations to market without first passing safety and efficacy standards, so why should digital systems be released without any scrutiny? Why should we allow Big Tech to conduct scaled human experiments, only to realize that they become too big a problem to manage? We have seen radicalization, mass shootings, ethnic cleansing, eating disorders, changes in sleep patterns, and scaled assaults on our democracy, all directly influenced by social media. These may be intangible ecosystems, but the harms are not intangible for victims.

规模是显而易见的问题。当硅谷高管为自己辩解说他们的平台规模太大，很难阻止大规模枪击事件被直播或种族清洗在他们的平台上被煽动时，这并不是借口——他们含蓄地承认，他们所创造的东西太大了，他们无法独自管理。然而，他们也含蓄地认为，他们从这些系统中获利的权利超过了其他人承担的社会成本。因此，当像 Facebook 这样的公司说“我们听到反馈说我们必须做更多”，就像他们的平台被用来直播新西兰大规模枪击事件时他们所做的那样，我们应该问他们一个问题：如果这些问题太大，你无法即时解决，那么为什么在你了解它们对社会的潜在影响之前，你应该被允许发布未经测试的产品？

Scale is the elephant in the room. When Silicon Valley executives excuse themselves and say their platform’s scale is so big that it’s really hard to prevent mass shootings from being broadcast or ethnic cleansing from being incited on their platforms, this is not an excuse—they are implicitly acknowledging that what they have created is too big for them to manage on their own. And yet, they also implicitly believe that their right to profit from these systems outweighs the social costs others bear. So when companies like Facebook say, “We have heard feedback that we must do more,” as they did when their platform was used to live-broadcast mass shootings in New Zealand, we should ask them a question: If these problems are too big for you to solve on the fly, why should you be allowed to release untested products before you understand their potential consequences for society?

我们需要新的规则来帮助在互联网上创造健康的摩擦，就像减速带一样，以确保新技术和生态系统的安全。我不是监管专家，也不自称知道所有答案，所以不要把这些话当作真理。这应该是一场更广泛的社区参与的对话。但我想提供一些想法供大家考虑——至少能引发思考。其中一些想法可能有效，其他可能无效，但我们必须开始思考这个难题。技术是强大的，它有潜力以多种方式提升人类。但这种力量需要集中在建设性的努力上。有鉴于此，以下是一些想法，可帮助您考虑如何前进：

We need new rules to help create a healthy friction on the Internet, like speed bumps, to ensure safety in new technologies and ecosystems. I am not an expert on regulation, nor do I profess to know all the answers, so do not take these words as gospel. This should be a conversation that the wider community takes part in. But I would like to offer some ideas for consideration—at the very least to provoke thought. Some of these ideas may work, others may not, but we have got to start thinking about this hard problem. Technology is powerful, and it has the potential to lift up humanity in so many ways. But that power needs to be focused on constructive endeavors. With that, here are some ideas to help you consider how to move forward:

1.互联网的 构建代码​​​

1. A BUILDING CODE FOR THE INTERNET

建筑规范的历史可以追溯到公元64 年，当时一场毁灭性的大火肆虐了罗马九天，之后尼禄开始限制房屋高度、街道宽度和公共供水。尽管 1631 年的一场大火促使波士顿禁止使用木制烟囱和茅草屋顶，但第一部现代建筑规范还是在 1666 年伦敦大火的惨烈屠杀中诞生的。和波士顿一样，伦敦的房屋密集地用木材和茅草建造，这使得火势在四天内迅速蔓延。它摧毁了 13,200 所房屋、84 座教堂和几乎所有的城市政府建筑。之后，查理二世国王宣布“任何人不得建造任何房屋或建筑，无论大小，都必须用砖或石头建造”。他的声明还拓宽了道路，以防止未来火势从街道的一侧蔓延到另一侧。在 19 世纪发生其他历史性火灾之后，许多城市纷纷效仿，最终公共测量员负责检查并确保私人财产的建设对居民和广大公众都是安全的。新的规则出现了，最终公共安全的概念成为一项总体原则，可以推翻不安全或未经证实的建筑设计，无论业主的意愿或居民的同意如何。像 Facebook 这样的平台多年来一直饱受灾难——剑桥分析公司、俄罗斯干涉、缅甸种族清洗、新西兰大规模枪击事件——正如大火后的改革一样，我们必须开始超越政策，关注威胁我们社会和谐和公民福祉的根本建筑问题。

The history of building codes stretches back to the year 64 C.E., when Nero restricted housing height, street width, and public water supplies after a devastating fire ravaged Rome for nine days. Though a fire in 1631 prompted Boston to ban wooden chimneys and thatched roofs, the first modern building code emerged out of the devastating carnage of the Great Fire of London, in 1666. As in Boston, London houses had been densely constructed from timber and thatch, which allowed the fire to spread rapidly over four days. It destroyed 13,200 homes, eighty-four churches, and nearly all of the city’s government buildings. Afterward, King Charles II declared that no one shall “erect any House or Building, great or small, but of Brick, or Stone.” His declaration also widened thoroughfares to stop future fires from spreading from one side of the street to the other. After other historic fires in the nineteenth century, many cities followed suit, and eventually public surveyors were tasked with inspections and ensuring that the construction of private property was safe for the inhabitants and for the public at large. New rules emerged, and eventually the notion of public safety became an overarching principle that could override unsafe or unproven building designs, regardless of the desires of property owners or even the consent of inhabitants. A platform like Facebook has been burning for years with its own disasters—Cambridge Analytica, Russian interference, Myanmar’s ethnic cleansing, New Zealand’s mass shootings—and, as with the reforms after the Great Fire, we must begin to look beyond policy, to the underlying architectural issues that threaten our social harmony and citizens’ well-being.

互联网包含无数种类型的架构，人们每天甚至每小时都在与之互动。随着数字世界与物理世界的融合，这些数字架构将越来越影响我们的生活。隐私是一项基本人权，应该得到重视。然而，隐私往往被简单地点击“接受”一组难以理解的条款和条件的行为所破坏。这种“同意洗白”行为不断让大型科技平台通过“消费者选择”这种虚伪的语言为其操纵行为辩护。这使我们的思维框架远离了这些有缺陷的架构的设计——以及设计者——而转向了对系统设计没有理解或控制的用户的活动的无益关注。我们不会让人们“选择”进入有故障线路或没有消防出口的建筑物。那样是不安全的——而且贴在门上的条款和条件不会让任何建筑师逃脱建造危险空间的惩罚。软件和在线平台的工程师和架构师又有什么不同呢？

The Internet contains countless types of architectures that people interact with on a daily and sometimes hourly basis. And as we merge the digital world with the physical world, these digital architectures will impact our lives more and more. Privacy is a fundamental human right and should be valued as such. However, too often privacy is eviscerated through the bare performance of clicking “accept” to an indecipherable set of terms and conditions. This consent-washing has continually allowed large tech platforms to defend their manipulative practices through the disingenuous language of “consumer choice.” This positions our frame of thinking away from the design—and the designers—of these flawed architectures, and toward an unhelpful focus on the activity of a user who does not have understanding or control over the system’s design. We do not let people “opt in” to buildings that have faulty wiring or lack fire exits. That would be unsafe—and no terms and conditions pasted on a door would let any architect get away with building dangerous spaces. Why should the engineers and architects of software and online platforms be any different?

从这个角度来看，同意不应成为平台运行涉及用户基本权利的功能的唯一基础。遵循加拿大和欧洲将隐私视为工程和设计问题的方法——一个称为“设计隐私”的框架——我们应该扩展这一原则，以创建一整套工程规范：互联网的建筑规范。这将包括隐私之外的新原则，包括尊重最终用户的代理权和诚信。这样的代码将创建一个新的原则——设计代理——要求平台使用增强选择的设计。这一原则还将禁止暗黑模式设计，这是一种常见的设计模式，故意混淆、欺骗或操纵用户同意某项功能或以某种方式行事。设计代理还要求效果成比例，即技术对用户的影响与用户的目的和利益成比例。换句话说，在平台设计中，如果存在持久和不成比例的影响，例如令人上瘾的设计或随之而来的心理健康问题，则禁止不当影响。

In this light, consent should not be the sole basis of a platform’s ability to operate a feature that engages the fundamental rights of users. In following the Canadian and European approach of treating privacy as an engineering and design issue—a framework called “privacy by design”—we should extend this principle to create an entire engineering code: a building code for the Internet. This would include new principles beyond privacy, to include respect for the agency and integrity of end users. Such a code would create a new principle—agency by design—to require that platforms use choice-enhancing design. This principle would also ban dark pattern designs, which are common design patterns that deliberately confuse, deceive, or manipulate users into agreeing to a feature or behaving in a certain way. Agency by design would also require proportionality of effects, wherein the effect of the technology on the user is proportional to the purpose and benefit to the user. In other words, there would be a prohibition on undue influence in platform design, where there are enduring and disproportionate effects, such as addictive designs or consequential mental health issues.

与传统建筑规范一样，危害避免原则将成为此类数字建筑规范的核心特征。这将要求平台和应用程序在发布或扩展产品或功能之前进行可滥用性审计和安全测试。科技公司将承担证明其产品在公众中大规模使用是安全的负担。因此，禁止在公众中对未经测试的新功能进行实时规模实验，公民也不能再被当作实验对象。这将有助于防止缅甸出现类似情况，Facebook 事先没有考虑过其功能如何在种族冲突地区引发暴力事件。

As with traditional building codes, the harm avoidance principle would be a central feature in such a digital building code. This would require platforms and applications to conduct abusability audits and safety testing prior to releasing or scaling a product or feature. The burden would rest with tech companies to prove that their products are safe for scaled use in the public. As such, using the public in live scaled experiments with untested new features would be prohibited, and citizens could no longer be used as guinea pigs. This would help prevent cases like Myanmar, where there was no prior consideration from Facebook on how features could ignite violence in regions of ethnic conflict.

2.软件工程师的道德规范 ​​​​​

2. A CODE OF ETHICS FOR SOFTWARE ENGINEERS

如果您的孩子迷路了，需要帮助，您希望他们向谁求助？也许是医生？也许是老师？加密货币交易员或游戏应用程序开发人员呢？我们的社会尊重某些具有可信赖地位的职业——医生、律师、护士、教师、建筑师等——很大程度上是因为他们的工作要求他们遵守道德规范和管理安全的法律。这些职业在社会中的特殊地位意味着我们要求更高的职业行为标准和注意义务。因此，许多国家的法定机构对这些职业的道德行为进行监管和执行。为了使社会正常运转，我们必须能够相信我们的医生或律师始终为我们的利益行事，并且我们每天使用的桥梁和建筑物都是按照规范和能力建造的。在这些受监管的行业中，不道德的行为会给那些超越行业界限的人带来可怕的后果——从罚款和公开羞辱到暂时停职，甚至对更恶劣的违法者永久禁止。

If your child was lost and needed help, whom would you want them to turn to for help? Perhaps a doctor? Or maybe a teacher? What about a cryptocurrency trader or gaming app developer? Our society esteems certain professions with a trustworthy status—doctors, lawyers, nurses, teachers, architects, and the like—in large part because their work requires them to follow codes of ethics and laws that govern safety. The special place these professions have in our society means that we demand a higher standard of professional conduct and duties of care. As a result, statutory bodies in many countries regulate and enforce ethical conduct of these professions. For society to function, we must be able to trust our doctors or lawyers to always act in our interests, and that the bridges and buildings we use every day have been constructed to code and with competence. In these regulated professions, unethical behavior can bring dire consequences for those who transgress boundaries set by the profession—ranging from fines and public shaming to temporary suspensions or even permanent bans for more egregious offenders.

软件、人工智能和数字生态系统如今已渗透到我们的生活，然而，任何联邦法规或可执行法规均未要求那些制造我们每天使用的设备和程序的人充分考虑其对用户或整个社会造成的道德影响。作为一门职业，软件工程存在着严重的道德问题需要解决。科技公司不会凭空创造出有问题或危险的平台——这些公司内部有人在构建这些技术。但有一个明显的问题是：软件工程师和数据科学家与此无关。如果工程师的雇主指示其创建具有操纵性、道德上可疑或鲁莽实施的系统，而不考虑用户安全，则没有拒绝的要求。目前，这种拒绝不道德行为的行为会给受雇工程师带来报复或被解雇的风险。即使不道德的设计后来被发现违反了法规，公司也可以承担责任并支付罚款，而开发该技术的工程师不会受到职业影响，而医生或律师严重违反职业道德则需要承担职业影响。这是一种其他职业不存在的反常激励。如果雇主要求律师或护士做出不道德的行为，他们有义务拒绝，否则将面临失去职业执照的风险。换句话说，他们有义务挑战雇主。

Software, AI, and digital ecosystems now permeate our lives, and yet those who make the devices and programs we use every single day are not obligated by any federal statute or enforceable code to give due consideration to the ethical impacts to users or society at large. As a profession, software engineering has a serious ethics problem that needs to be addressed. Tech companies do not magically create problematic or dangerous platforms out of thin air—there are people inside these companies who build these technologies. But there is an obvious problem: Software engineers and data scientists do not have any skin in the game. If an engineer’s employer instructs her or him to create systems that are manipulative, ethically dubious, or recklessly implemented, without consideration for user safety, there are no requirements to refuse. Currently, such a refusal to act unethically creates a risk to the employed engineer of repercussions or termination. Even if the unethical design later is found to run afoul of a regulation, the company can absorb liability and pay fines, and there are no professional consequences for the engineers who built the technology, as there would be in the case of a doctor or lawyer who commits a serious breach of professional ethics. This is a perverse incentive that does not exist in other professions. If an employer asked a lawyer or nurse to act unethically, they would be obligated to refuse or face losing their professional license. In other words, they have skin in the game to challenge their employer.

如果我们作为软件工程师和数据科学家，要称自己为值得尊敬和高薪的专业人士，那么我们必须有相应的责任以道德的方式行事。如果我们不从让这些公司内部的人参与进来，那么针对科技公司的监管将不会发挥应有的作用。我们需要让工程师开始关心他们所创造的东西。一个下午的员工研讨会或一个学期的道德课程对于解决我们现在面临的新兴技术问题来说完全是不够的。我们不能继续走我们现在的道路，在这条道路上，技术家长制和硅谷与世隔绝的乌托邦造就了一批危险的大师，他们不考虑他们的工作可能造成的危害。

If we as software engineers and data scientists are to call ourselves professionals worthy of the esteem and high salaries we command, there must be a corresponding duty for us to act ethically. Regulations on tech companies will not be nearly as effective as they could be if we do not start by putting skin in the game for people inside these companies. We need to put the onus on engineers to start giving a damn about what they build. An afternoon employee workshop or a semester course on ethics is a wholly insufficient solution for addressing the problems we now face from emerging technologies. We cannot continue down the path we are on, in which technological paternalism and the insulated bro-topias of Silicon Valley create a breed of dangerous masters who do not consider the harm that their work has the potential to inflict.

我们需要一套由法定机构支持的专业准则，就像许多司法管辖区的土木工程师和建筑师一样，软件工程师或数据科学家如果利用自己的才能和专业知识构建危险、操纵性或其他不道德的技术，就会受到实际后果。这种准则不应使用松散的理想语言；相反，应该以清晰、具体和明确的方式阐明什么是可以接受的，什么是不可接受的。应该要求尊重用户的自主权，识别和记录风险，并对代码进行审查和审核。这样的准则还应包括一项要求，即考虑他们的工作对弱势群体的影响，包括对不同种族、性别、能力、性取向或其他受保护群体的用户的任何不成比例的影响。如果经过适当考虑，工程师认为雇主提出的建造某项设施的要求是不道德的，则应有拒绝和报告的义务，否则将导致严重的职业后果。那些拒绝并举报的人也必须受到法律保护，以免遭到雇主的报复。

We need a professional code that is backed by a statutory body, as is the case with civil engineers and architects in many jurisdictions, where there are actual consequences for software engineers or data scientists who use their talents and know-how to construct dangerous, manipulative, or otherwise unethical technologies. This code should not have loose aspirational language; rather, what is acceptable and unacceptable should be articulated in a clear, specific, and definitive way. There should be a requirement to respect the autonomy of users, to identify and document risks, and to subject code to scrutiny and review. Such a code should also include a requirement to consider the impact of their work on vulnerable populations, including any disproportionate impact on users of different races, genders, abilities, sexualities, or other protected groups. And if, upon due consideration, an employer’s request to build a feature is deemed to be unethical by the engineer, there should be a duty to refuse and a duty to report, where failure to do so would result in serious professional consequences. Those who refuse and report must also be protected by law from retaliation from their employer.

在所有可能的监管类型中，为软件工程师制定法律规范可能是最能防止伤害的，因为它会迫使开发人员在向公众发布任何内容之前考虑自己的工作，而不是仅仅通过服从命令来逃避道德责任。技术往往体现了我们的价值观，因此，如果我们作为一个社会要越来越依赖软件工程师的创造，那么灌输道德文化至关重要。如果能适当追究软件工程师的责任，他们将成为我们抵御未来技术滥用的最佳防线。而且，作为软件工程师，我们都应该努力在构建社会新架构时赢得公众对我们工作的信任。

Out of all the possible types of regulation, a statutory code for software engineers is probably what would prevent the most harm, as it would force the builders themselves to consider their work before anything is released to the public and not shirk moral responsibility by simply following orders. Technology often reflects an embodiment of our values, so instilling a culture of ethics is vital if we as a society are to increasingly depend on the creations of software engineers. If held properly accountable, software engineers could become our best line of defense against the future abuses of technology. And, as software engineers, we should all aspire to earn the public’s trust in our work as we build the new architectures of our societies.

3.互联网公用事业和公共利益​​​

3. INTERNET UTILITIES AND THE PUBLIC INTEREST

公用事业传统上是物理网络，据说“受公共利益影响”。它们在市场上的存在是独一无二的，因为它们的基础设施对于商业和社会的运作至关重要，因此我们允许它们以不同于普通公司的运营方式运营。公用事业往往必然是一种自然垄断。在市场上，平衡竞争通常会带来创新、更好的质量和更低的消费者价格。但在某些领域，如能源、水或道路，在同一地点修建相互竞争的电力线、管道或地铁是没有意义的，因为这会导致大量冗余和增加消费者承担的成本。随着单一服务供应商效率的提高，也带来了不当影响和权力的风险——无法切换到新电力线、管道或地铁的消费者可能会被无良公司挟持。

Utilities are traditionally physical networks said to be “affected with the public interest.” Their existence is unique in the marketplace in that their infrastructure is so elemental to the functioning of commerce and society that we allow them to operate differently from typical companies. Utilities are often by necessity a form of natural monopoly. In a marketplace, balanced competition typically results in innovation, better quality, and reduced prices for consumers. But in certain sectors, such as energy, water, or roads, it makes no sense to build competing power lines, pipelines, or subways to the same places, as it would result in massive redundancy and increased costs borne by consumers. With the increased efficiencies of a single supplier of a service comes the risk of undue influence and power—consumers unable to switch to new power lines, pipelines, or subways could be held hostage by unscrupulous firms.

在互联网上，显然存在着极其占主导地位的市场参与者。谷歌占据了所有搜索流量的 90% 以上，近 70% 活跃在社交媒体上的成年人使用 Facebook。但这并不意味着它们本身就是通用基础设施。当科技平台遭遇停电时，我们可以生存下来并应对更长时间（尽管不是无限期），而同样的情况发生在电力上时则不会发生。在谷歌搜索引擎偶尔出现故障的情况下，用户会通过转向其他不太知名的搜索引擎来应对，直到谷歌修复其问题。大型互联网参与者的受欢迎程度也存在物理基础设施所没有的周期。MySpace 曾经是首屈一指的社交媒体平台，后来被 Facebook 击败，而我们很少甚至从未遇到过水务或电力公司的市场周期。

On the Internet, there are clearly extremely dominant market players. Google accounts for more than 90 percent of all search traffic, and almost 70 percent of adults active on social media use Facebook. But this does not make them universal infrastructure per se. When tech platforms suffer an outage, we can survive and cope for longer (albeit not indefinitely) than we would if the same thing happened with electricity. On the infrequent occasions when Google’s search engine has failed, users coped by moving to other, lesser-known search engines until Google patched its problem. There are also cycles of popularity for large Internet players that are not found in physical infrastructure. MySpace was once the preeminent social media platform, before Facebook crushed it, whereas we rarely if ever encounter market cycles with water or electric companies.

尽管如此，互联网的主导者确实与实体设施有着共同之处。与实体设施一样，这些架构通常充当着商业和社会的事实上的支柱，它们的存在已成为日常生活的必然。例如，企业已经开始被动地依赖谷歌搜索引擎来为其员工提供服务。这并不是一件坏事。搜索引擎和社交媒体受益于网络效应，使用服务的人越多，服务就越有用。与实体设施一样，规模可以为消费者带来巨大的利益，我们不想阻碍这种公共利益。然而，与其他自然垄断一样，同样的风险也威胁着消费者。我们必须在一套新规则中考虑到这些潜在的危害。

That said, the Internet’s dominant players do share things in common with physical utilities. Like physical utilities, these architectures often serve as a de facto backbone of commerce and society, where their existence has become a given of day-to-day life. Businesses have come to passively rely upon the existence of Google’s search engine for their workforces, for example. And this is not a bad thing. Search engines and social media benefit from network effects, where the more people use the service, the more useful the service becomes. As with physical utilities, scale can create a huge benefit to the consumer, and we do not want to impede this public benefit. However, as with other natural monopolies, the same kinds of risks threaten consumers. And it is these potential harms that we must account for in a new set of rules.

因此，在充分认识到互联网与物理基础设施之间存在本质区别的情况下，我将使用“互联网公用事业”这一方便术语来表示与传统公用事业类似但又不同的事物：“互联网公用事业”是 一种服务、应用程序或平台，其存在在互联网上已经占据主导地位，以至于其自身规模的性质会受到公众利益的影响。对互联网公用事业的监管应承认其在社会和商业中的特殊地位，并对用户施加更高的标准。这些监管应采取法定职责的形式，以年利润为基准进行处罚，以制止当前的情况，即监管违规行为被协商并计入经营成本。

So, in full recognition that there are essential differences between the Internet and physical infrastructure, I will use “Internet utilities” as a term of convenience to mean something similar to but different from a traditional utility: An “Internet utility” is a service, application, or platform whose presence has become so dominant on the Internet that it becomes affected with the public interest by the very nature of its own scale. The regulation of Internet utilities should recognize the special place they hold in society and commerce and impose a higher standard of care toward users. These regulations should take the form of statutory duties, with penalties benchmarked to annual profits as a way to stop the current situation, in which regulatory infractions are negotiated and accounted for as a cost of doing business.

正如我们不会因为电力公司的规模而受到惩罚一样，如果互联网公用事业的网络效应具有真正的社会效益，那么它们也不应该因为规模而受到惩罚。换句话说，这并不是要拆分大型科技公司，而是要让它们承担责任。然而，作为保持规模的交换，互联网公用事业应该被要求积极主动地成为最终演变成我们数字公共资源的负责任的管理者。必须让它们明白，规模会唤起内在的公共利益，在某些情况下，这种利益必然会取代它们在盈利方面的私人利益。与其他公用事业一样，这必须包括遵守针对软件应用程序的更高的用户安全标准和新的数字消费者权利准则。这些新的数字消费者权利应该成为普遍条款和条件的基础，在科技公司不断失败的领域，互联网用户的利益应该得到适当的考虑。

In the same way we do not penalize the scale of electric companies, the scale of Internet utilities should not be penalized where there are network effects of genuine social benefit. In other words, this is not about breaking up large technology companies; this is about making them accountable. However, in exchange for maintaining their scale, Internet utilities should be required to act proactively as responsible stewards of what eventually evolve into our digital commons. They must be made to understand that scale evokes innate public interests that in some cases will, by necessity, supersede their private interests in making profit. As with other utilities, this must include compliance with higher user safety standards specific to software applications and a new code of digital consumer rights. These new digital consumer rights should serve as the basis of universal terms and conditions, in that the interests of Internet users are properly accounted for in areas where technology companies have continuously failed.

4.数字公共资源的公共管理​​

4. PUBLIC STEWARDSHIP OF THE DIGITAL COMMONS

这些互联网公用事业公司对我们的公共话语、社会凝聚力和心理健康产生的影响是不受限制的，无论是有意还是无能或疏忽，也必须接受公共问责。应建立一个新的数字监管机构，以法定的制裁权来执行这一新的数字监管框架。特别是，这些机构应包括技术上胜任的监察员，并有权代表公众对平台进行主动技术审计。我们还应该使用基于市场的强化机制，例如要求互联网公用事业公司对数据滥用造成的损害投保。通过要求对数据泄露投保，并与数据的市场价值挂钩，我们可以创造纠正性的财务压力，以使其做得更好。

The unrestricted power of these Internet utilities to impact our public discourse, social cohesion, and mental health, whether intentionally or through incompetence and neglect, must also be subject to public accountability. A new digital regulatory agency should be established to enforce this new digital regulatory framework with statutory sanctioning powers. In particular, these agencies should contain technically competent ombudsmen empowered with rights to conduct proactive technical audits of platforms on behalf of the public. We should also use market-based reinforcement mechanisms, such as the requirement of Internet utilities to hold insurance for harms incurred from data misuse. In requiring insurance for data breaches, linked to the market-rate value of that data, we could create corrective financial pressure to do better.

我们已经看到个人数据的价值为社交媒体公司创造了全新的商业模式和巨额利润。Facebook 等平台极力辩称，它们提供的是“免费”服务，如果消费者不必为服务付费，那么平台就不能算作反竞争行为的同谋。然而，这一论点要求人们接受这样一个事实：用个人数据换取平台使用权并不是价值交换，而事实显然如此。有整个市场对个人数据进行估价、出售和许可。目前针对大型科技公司的反垄断方法的缺陷在于，监管机构没有正确考虑消费者数据的价值。

We have seen the value of personal data create entirely new business models and huge profits for social media companies. Platforms such as Facebook have vigorously argued that they are a “free” service, and if consumers do not have to pay for the service, the platform cannot be complicit in anticompetitive practice. However, this argument requires one to accept that the exchange of personal data for use of a platform is not an exchange of value, when it plainly is. There are entire marketplaces that valuate, sell, and license personal data. The flaw in current antitrust approaches for large tech companies is that the value of the consumer’s data has not been properly accounted for by regulators.

如果我们真的考虑到消费者向平台提供的个人数据价值不断上升，我们就会得出结论，消费者一直在被这些公司欺骗，而这些公司并没有相应提高其平台对消费者的价值。从这个角度来看，消费者通过他们的数据为这些占主导地位的平台提供了更多的价值，却没有得到相应的回报。美国现行的反垄断法可能认为，基于此，数据交换让消费者付出了更多代价。然而，即使情况确实如此，这也是一个过于狭隘的测试，以判断什么是公平和对消费者有利的。相反，如果我们要创建一个新的互联网公用事业分类，我们可以对这些公司的运营、增长和并购活动进行更广泛的公共利益测试。

If we actually considered the rising value in the personal data provided by consumers to platforms, we’d conclude that consumers have continuously been ripped off by these companies, which are not proportionately increasing their platform’s value to consumers. In this light, consumers are giving more value via their data to these dominant platforms without receiving reciprocal benefits. There may be an argument in America’s current antitrust laws that on this basis, the data exchange has been costing consumers more. However, even if this were the case, this is an overly narrow test of what is fair and right for consumers. Instead, were we to create a new classification of Internet utilities, we could use a broader public interest test for the operation, growth, and mergers-and-acquisitions activity of these firms.

然而，与实体公用事业不同，社交媒体和搜索引擎并非不可替代，因此监管也应考虑到行业发展的健康效益。我们希望避免制定以牺牲更新更好的产品为代价来巩固当前占主导地位的互联网公用事业地位的法规。但我们也需要拒绝这样一种观点，即对规模庞大的巨头的任何监管都会以某种方式阻碍新的挑战者。按照这种逻辑，石油行业的安全和环境监管将抑制未来可再生能源的出现，这是没有道理的。如果我们担心市场发展的受阻，那么我们可以要求互联网公用事业与规模较小的竞争挑战者共享其主导基础设施，以改善消费者的选择，就像占主导地位的电信公司与规模较小的参与者共享通信基础设施一样。现有大型参与者的安全和行为标准与技术发展的延续并不相互矛盾。从这个角度来看，应该制定基于原则而非基于技术的监管，以便我们小心不要将旧技术或过时的商业模式嵌入监管准则中。

However, unlike physical utilities, social media and search engines are not so essential as to be irreplaceable, so regulations should also account for the healthy benefits of industry evolution. We want to avoid regulations that entrench the position of currently dominant Internet utilities at the expense of newer and better offerings. But we also need to reject the notion that any regulation of scaled giants would somehow impede new challengers. To follow this logic would mean that safety and environmental regulation of the oil sector would inhibit the emergence of renewable energy in the future, which makes no sense. And if we are concerned about the inhibition of market evolution, then we could require Internet utilities to share their dominant infrastructure with smaller, competing challengers, to improve consumer choice in the same way dominant telecom companies share communications infrastructure with smaller players. Safety and conduct standards of existing large players are not mutually incompatible with the continuation of technological evolution. In this light, principle-based rather than technology-based regulation should be created so that we are careful not to embed old technologies or outdated business models into regulatory codes.

谢谢。祝你好运。

Thanks. And good luck.

感谢我的父母 Kevin 和 Joan，他们教会我要勇敢，要为自己挺身而出，要做正确的事

To my parents, Kevin and Joan, who taught me to be brave, to stand up for myself, and to do the right thing

Second, literally nothing else seems to faze you. 告密者​​

THE JOURNALISTS

Carole Cadwalladr，谢谢你相信我，也谢谢你对我的信任。从我见到你的那一刻起，我就知道你是少数几个能够以一种让人们关注的方式向世界讲述这个故事的人之一。你唤醒了世界，震撼了巨人。我可能有一头粉红色的头发，但你才是挥舞笔的人。尽管受到另类右翼、私人情报公司和硅谷科技兄弟们的无情辱骂和威胁，你仍坚持不懈。你接受我采访的唯一原因就是真诚地致力于造福大众，你出色的新闻报道值得所有赞誉。

Carole Cadwalladr, thank you for believing me—and for believing in me. I knew from the moment I met you that you were one of the few people who could tell this story to the world in a way that makes people take note. You woke up the world and shook giants. I may have had the pink hair, but you were the one who wielded the pen. You kept going despite an unrelenting stream of abuse and threats from the alt-right, private intelligence firms, and Silicon Valley tech bros. You took me on for no other reason than a sincere dedication to the greater good and you deserve every accolade for your brilliant journalism.

莎拉·唐纳森 (Sarah Donaldson) 和艾玛·格雷厄姆-哈里森 (Emma Graham-Harrison)，感谢你们在向世界讲述这个故事中所发挥的关键作用。你们和卡罗尔所做的工作在很大程度上让我能够如此自信地说，如果没有这些女性的参与，我不会取得今天的成就。《卫报》和《观察家报》很幸运有你们两位。当然，还要感谢保罗·韦伯斯特、约翰·穆赫兰和吉莉安·菲利普斯，感谢你们在亿万富翁、科技巨头、愤怒的白宫官员、情报机构和几乎每天都在出现的大量法律威胁面前坚定地捍卫这个故事。马修·罗森伯格、尼古拉斯·康菲索尔、加布里埃尔·丹斯、丹尼·哈基姆、大卫·柯克帕特里克和《纽约时报》，感谢你们以一种其他人无法做到的方式将这个故事带到美国，感谢你们在要求 Facebook 和其他硅谷巨头承担责任方面发挥的巨大影响。乔布·拉布金、本·德·皮尔和第四频道新闻，感谢你们冒着巨大风险勇敢地进行卧底调查，并在其他人不愿意的情况下向电视观众揭露这个故事。你们的镜头用剑桥分析公司自己令人不寒而栗的话语向全世界展示了该公司邪恶行动的真正深度。

Sarah Donaldson and Emma Graham-Harrison, thank you for your pivotal role in telling this story to the world. Your work alongside Carole’s is largely why I can so confidently claim that I would not be where I am today without the women involved. The Guardian and The Observer are lucky to have you both. And of course, thank you, Paul Webster, John Mulholland, and Gillian Phillips, for steadfastly defending this story in the face of billionaires, tech giants, angry White House officials, intelligence agencies, and a cornucopia of almost daily legal threats. Matthew Rosenberg, Nicholas Confessore, Gabriel Dance, Danny Hakim, David Kirkpatrick, and The New York Times, thank you for bringing this story to America in a way no one else could, and for the huge impact of your role in holding Facebook and other Silicon Valley giants to account. Job Rabkin, Ben de Pear, and Channel 4 News, thank you for daring to go undercover at huge risk, and for breaking this story to a television audience when others would not. Your footage showed the world the true depth of Cambridge Analytica’s nefarious operation in the firm’s own chilling words.

议员们​​

THE PARLIAMENTARIANS

国会议员阿利斯泰尔·卡迈克尔，感谢您多年来坚定不移的支持和建议，感谢您在办公室里深夜谈话，感谢您在压力大的时候培养我对苏格兰威士忌的品味。在这个故事公开之前，您的帮助非常宝贵。您不求回报地冒着风险，利用您对议会的详细了解来保护我和其他几位告密者。这使得涉及重大公共利益的证据得以保存和公布。国会议员达米安·柯林斯和英国议会的整个数字、文化、媒体和体育委员会，感谢你们成为要求硅谷承担责任的最响亮的声音。你们在对虚假信息和“假新闻”的调查中的无党派合作将公众利益放在首位，你们都为如何进行政治活动树立了光辉的榜样。通过共同努力，您的委员会对抗了硅谷巨头，并汇集了来自世界各地的立法行动支持。达米安，作为一个心肠软弱的自由主义者，我从没想过我会说出这样的话，但你向我证明了——也许——一些保守党人真的可以很酷。

Alistair Carmichael MP, thank you for your unwavering allyship and counsel over the years, for the late-night talks in your office, and for cultivating my palate for Scotch whisky during a stressful time. Your help before this story went public was invaluable. For nothing in return, you took risks and used your detailed knowledge of Parliament to help protect me and several other whistleblowers. This allowed evidence of significant public interest to be preserved and published. Damian Collins MP and the entire Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Committee at the British Parliament, thank you for being some of the loudest voices for holding Silicon Valley to account. Your nonpartisan collaboration on the inquiry into disinformation and “fake news” put the public interest first, and you all set a shining example of how politics should be done. By working together, your committee took on the giants of Silicon Valley and pulled together support for legislative action from around the world. And Damian, as a bleeding-heart liberal I never thought I would ever say this, but you showed me that—maybe—some Tories really can be cool.

无名英雄​​​​​

THE UNSUNG HEROES

感谢我的父母 Kevin 和 Joan，感谢你们无条件的爱、鼓励和智慧，感谢我的两个姐姐 Jaimie 和 Lauren，感谢她们在事情变得混乱时放下一切来帮助我，让我发泄压力，并让我的冰箱里储备了食物。同时感谢所有帮助揭露和讲述这个故事的人。我特别要感谢斯特拉斯堡勋爵（感谢你在幕后提供的谨慎但不可估量的帮助）；Peter Jukes（感谢你所有的鼓励和对故事的精彩介绍）；Marc Silver（感谢你令人惊叹的电影和长达数小时的鼓舞人心的谈话）；Jess Search（感谢你明智的建议和对我性取向的培养）；Kyle Taylor（感谢你热情的活动）；Elizabeth Denham、Michael McEvoy 和整个英国信息专员办公室（感谢他们让数据权利得到重视）；众议员 Adam Schiff 和美国众议院情报委员会的工作人员（感谢你们所做的所有默默工作）； Glenn Simpson 和 Fusion GPS（感谢你们出色的调查工作）；Ken Strasma（激发了我对数据的兴趣）；Keith Martin PC 博士（培养了我的独立精神）；Jeff Silvester（尽管后来发生了一切，但依然指导了我年轻时的自己）；Tom Brookes（感谢你们自始至终的支持）；David Carroll 和 Paul-Olivier Dehaye（感谢你们坚持捍卫我们的数据权利）；Emma Briant 博士（发现关键证据）；Harry Davies、Ann Marlowe 和 Wendy Siegelman（感谢你们早期的调查工作）；我的前任学术导师 Carolyn Mair 博士（审阅本书并教会我很多关于心理学、数据和文化的知识）；以及 Shoshana Zuboff 教授（她关于监控资本主义的工作帮助我完善了很多想法）。或许最重要的是，我想感谢成千上万分享这个故事、打电话给他们的代表、游行抗议、举着标语牌并向我发送鼓励信息的人——有很多我从未见过的人在整个旅程中一直热情地支持着我。

Thank you to my parents, Kevin and Joan, for your unconditional love, encouragement, and wisdom, and to my two sisters, Jaimie and Lauren, for dropping everything to help when things got chaotic, for letting me vent my stress, and for keeping my fridge stocked with food. And thank you to everyone else who helped uncover and tell this story. In particular, I would like to thank Lord Strasburger (for your discreet but immeasurable assistance behind the scenes); Peter Jukes (for all your encouragement and a brilliant launch for the story); Marc Silver (for your stunning film and hours-long inspiring conversations); Jess Search (for your sage advice and nurturing my queerness); Kyle Taylor (for your passionate campaigning); Elizabeth Denham, Michael McEvoy, and the entire U.K. Information Commissioner’s Office (for putting data rights on the map); Representative Adam Schiff and the staff of the U.S. House Intelligence Committee (for all the unseen work you do); Glenn Simpson and Fusion GPS (for your brilliant investigative work); Ken Strasma (for sparking my interest in data); Dr. Keith Martin PC (for nurturing my independent spirit); Jeff Silvester (for mentoring my younger self, despite everything that happened later); Tom Brookes (for your support throughout); David Carroll and Paul-Olivier Dehaye (for your persistence in defending our data rights); Dr. Emma Briant (for uncovering critical evidence); Harry Davies, Ann Marlowe, and Wendy Siegelman (for your early investigative work); my former academic supervisor Dr. Carolyn Mair (for reviewing this book and teaching me so much about psychology, data, and culture); and Professor Shoshana Zuboff (whose work on surveillance capitalism helped me refine so many ideas). Perhaps most important, I want to recognize the hundreds of thousands of people who shared this story, called their representatives, marched in protests, held up placards, and sent me encouraging messages—there are so many people I have never even met who have passionately had my back throughout this journey.

这本书​​

THIS BOOK

最后，我要感谢我的两位杰出的书籍合作者，Lisa Dickey 和 Gareth Cook；兰登书屋的编辑 Mark Warren；威廉莫里斯奋进出版社的文学经纪人 Jay Mandel 和 Jennifer Rudolph Walsh；负责核实本书事实的 Kelsey Kudak；以及我的娱乐律师 Jared Bloch。你们都指导我写第一本书，鼓励我动笔写作，帮助我提炼这个故事的精髓，删去我的胡言乱语，并抑制我散漫的倾向。

And last, I would like to thank my two brilliant book collaborators, Lisa Dickey and Gareth Cook; my editor at Random House, Mark Warren; my literary agents at William Morris Endeavor, Jay Mandel and Jennifer Rudolph Walsh; Kelsey Kudak for fact-checking this book; and my entertainment lawyer, Jared Bloch. You all guided me through writing my first book, pushed me to put pen to paper, helped me distill the essence of this story, edited out my nonsense, and curbed my more discursive tendencies.

关于作者

ABOUT THE AUTHOR

克里斯托弗·怀利被称为“千禧一代的第一位伟大的告密者”和“来自未来的粉红色头发、戴着鼻环的先知”。他因在建立剑桥分析公司（然后将其取缔）中发挥的作用而闻名。他揭露了猖獗的数据滥用行为，震惊了硅谷，并引发了有史以来规模最大的跨国数据犯罪调查。他出生于加拿大不列颠哥伦比亚省，在伦敦经济学院学习法律，之后进入文化数据科学和时尚趋势预测领域。他现居英国伦敦。

CHRISTOPHER WYLIE has been called “the millennials’ first great whistleblower” and “a pink-haired, nose-ringed oracle sent from the future.” He is known for his role in setting up—and then taking down—Cambridge Analytica. His revelations exposing the rampant misuse of data rocked Silicon Valley and led to some of the largest multinational investigations into data crime ever. Born in British Columbia, Canada, he studied law at the London School of Economics before moving into cultural data science and fashion trend forecasting. He lives in London, England.
